553	74	\N	2	SuccessStoryDetailComponent	"body"=>"<p>By Gretchen Joyce, Chief Operating Officer,&nbsp;MaxPoint<br />\r\n<em>This article first appeared on CMO.COM</em>.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>October 12, 2012</strong>&nbsp;<strong>&ndash;</strong> Every retail and brand marketer is looking for new ways to generate extra revenue during major shopping seasons, especially during the winter holidays and events like back-to-school. It&rsquo;s natural to assume that such high-traffic events will automatically result in increased sales, but that&rsquo;s not always the case. Take, for instance, an electronics retailer that we recently worked with for its back-to-school campaign. As summer came to an end, the retailer knew it had to kick its marketing into high gear to promote the fact that its stores had the best deals on electronics, especially computers. Like many other brands and retailers, it was competing to be on every parent&rsquo;s back-to-school list.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAs many CMOs know, there is an inevitable and continuous inventory imbalance during major shopping periods. With the economy in flux, it&rsquo;s hard to predict which consumers are going to be spending their hard-earned money, especially around the holidays. So for the back-to-school shopping season, the retailer used a hyperlocal digital advertising approach to complement its traditional marketing tactics. It was able to target households living within a six- to eight-mile radius of a store location with kids ages 17 to 24 who are going to college for the first time or going back to college.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nBy targeting specific household types at the neighborhood level, the retailer was able to create demand for inventory in specific locations that needed to move product. As a result, it didn&rsquo;t have to worry about major markdowns and discounts once school started. Now it can apply a similar strategy to the holiday season using the following lessons learned during its successful back-to-school campaign:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n\t<li><strong>Don&rsquo;t solely rely on national carpet-bombing campaigns:&nbsp;</strong>These massive campaigns are excessive. They might raise broad awareness, but oftentimes your ad dollars are reaching an irrelevant audience&ndash;especially when you just want to reach relevant customers around very specific geographic locations.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Be timelier:&nbsp;</strong>Traditional ad campaigns require a lot of preparation. These planned promotions are useful in some instances, but going digital changes the timeline from weeks and months of presale mailings, TV spots, and print ads to being able to launch a hyperlocal campaign in a matter of hours. In addition, you can reuse those traditional assets in a digital, hyperlocal format to maximize and extend the reach of your effort and ad dollars.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Go beyond DMA targeting:&nbsp;</strong>You may be accustomed to targeting a demographic within a DMA, but it&rsquo;s time to get more specific (focused) to move products off of the shelves. To move holiday inventory, you need to know which consumers are interested in those products and close enough to actually shop at that store within a certain mile radius of your stores. It might seem impossible, but by leveraging technology that analyzes billions of offline and online data points, including POS data, you can react to that data analysis and create just-in-time demand that drives sales at the neighborhood level, across the country.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Customize your messaging:&nbsp;</strong>Once you have access to such robust and precise data, you can use national campaign assets that speak to each neighborhood with localized messages, and even include store addresses for locations closest to the customer. In order to maximize your ad spend, look for ways to combine national assets with personalized experiences, ensuring that each consumer gets consistent but targeted ads on the media most appropriate and convenient for them.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Incent in-store shopping:</strong>&nbsp;If you are seeing a lot of catalog, phone, and online shopping, but in-store sales are slow, then repurpose assets and quickly encourage your shoppers to visit the store with sales and special offers.It&rsquo;s not too late to rethink your digital ad strategy before the holiday season. Getting hyperlocal with your ads&ndash;by leveraging actionable offline and online data&ndash;will drive those sales before the holidays are over, easing the typical pain associated with inventory management during this hectic time.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nIt&rsquo;s not too late to rethink your digital ad strategy before the holiday season. Getting hyperlocal with your ads&ndash;by leveraging actionable offline and online data&ndash;will drive those sales before the holidays are over, easing the typical pain associated with inventory management during this hectic time.</p>\r\n", "title"=>"5 Back-to-School Lessons for the Holiday Shopping Season", "sidebar_text"=>"", "sidebar_image_uid"=>NULL, "sidebar_image_name"=>NULL, "sidebar_image_link_target"=>"_blank", "sidebar_image_link_page_id"=>"", "sidebar_image_link_external_url"=>"http://cmo.com/"	\N	2013-05-14 23:34:57.815303	2013-08-27 19:46:35.267551
