1062	146	\N	3	SuccessStoryDetailComponent	"body"=>"<p><strong>Raleigh, N.C.</strong> <strong>&ndash; June 25, 2013 </strong>&ndash;<strong> </strong>School is just letting out for the summer across most of the U.S., but it&rsquo;s never too early for retailers and brands to start preparing for the back-to-school shopping season. <a href=\\"http://www.maxpoint.com\\" rel=\\"nofollow\\" target=\\"_blank\\"><u>MaxPoint</u></a>, the company that helps retailers and brands drive local in-store sales with its innovative Digital Zip<sup>&reg;</sup> technology, has identified U.S. cities with the neighborhoods that over-index for back-to-school clothing shopping. The company found that there were two distinct groups of buyers that purchase kid&rsquo;s apparel: seasonal spenders and year-round spenders.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAccording to the National Retail Federation&rsquo;s (NRF) back-to-school spending survey, parents spent an average of $688 on new backpacks, fall sweaters, footwear and electronics.[1] But it&rsquo;s not just school supplies that sell&mdash;kids&rsquo; apparel and accessories are also big sellers. In fact, on clothing and accessories alone, the NRF reported that back-to-school spending totaled $10.8 billion. &nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>The Profile of a Seasonal Spender</strong><br />\r\nMaxPoint found that seasonal spenders purchase children&rsquo;s clothing in large quantities during the back-to-school season, but don&rsquo;t purchase children&rsquo;s apparel throughout the rest of the year in the same capacity. Based on the research, MaxPoint found that the typical seasonal spender makes $60,000 a year or less, is over the age of 55, owns their home and is married. They trend high in interest on topics such as food and drink trends, allergy relief, NASCAR, home improvement and retirement planning. Seasonal-spender families most often spend their money at value grocery stores, sporting goods and apparel stores and office supply chains. Given the demographics, this audience is likely made up of grandparents and other family members purchasing gifts and clothing for children specifically for the back-to-school season. The U.S. cities that had the highest percentage of neighborhoods on the seasonal spender index were:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>Charleston, WV</li>\r\n\t<li>Eureka, CA</li>\r\n\t<li>Madison, WI</li>\r\n\t<li>Shreveport, LA</li>\r\n\t<li>Oklahoma City, OK &nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<strong>The Profile of a Year-Round Spender</strong><br />\r\nUnlike their seasonal spender counterparts, the year-round spenders purchased high quantities of children&rsquo;s clothing both during the back-to-school season and throughout the rest of the year. MaxPoint found that the typical year-round spender makes more than $100,000 per year, has a college degree and is typically between the ages of 35 and 44. This group trends high on interest in topics such as the economy, business and finance, weddings and fashion. They tend to shop most often at women&rsquo;s apparel stores, department stores and drug stores. The U.S. cities that had the highest percentage of neighborhoods on the year-round spender index were:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>Baltimore, MD</li>\r\n\t<li>Huntsville, AL</li>\r\n\t<li>Savannah, GA</li>\r\n\t<li>Terre Haute, IN</li>\r\n\t<li>Flagstaff, AZ</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nMaxPoint found that, even within the top cities, certain neighborhoods indexed higher than others for seasonal versus year-round shopping for children&rsquo;s clothes. For instance, within Oklahoma City, the neighborhoods of Covington, Douglas and Hayward trended high for having the most seasonal shoppers. While the Equestrian Estates, Pine Del and Railroad Springs sections of Flagstaff, AZ were among the most likely to spend year round.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;Back-to-school is hugely profitable for brands and retailers alike. However, it&rsquo;s critical for these advertisers to be able to sustain high sales activity throughout the rest of the year, and targeted advertising plays a big role in that process,&rdquo; said Gretchen Joyce, COO of MaxPoint. &ldquo;We help advertisers understand who is buying, when they are buying, what they are buying and where they are buying &ndash; which enables them to personalize and deliver their messages based on the specific audience.&nbsp; Advertisers that capitalize by using offline and online data to better understand consumers will be the most profitable during the upcoming back-to-school season.&rdquo;&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Interest Data in Action</strong><br />\r\nMaxPoint used its Digital Zip technology to run hyperlocal digital advertising campaigns for several retailers&rsquo; back-to-school promotions including: &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>An electronics retailer that wanted to build awareness of its brands and products, while driving in-store sales at its various locations during back-to-school shopping months. To help them, MaxPoint targeted households with kids between the ages of 18 and 24 and with interests in college and college living. MaxPoint helped the company focus its campaign on a tight six to eight mile radius of the store. The campaign resulted in a CTR that was more than four times the industry average.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>An arts and crafts retailer that wanted to drive customers to its stores for several back-to-school promotions. MaxPoint helped by targeting two audiences: teachers and mothers. The teacher audience was primarily made up of women between the ages of 25 and 55, while the mother audience was made up of women between 35 and 55 with purchase histories of craft supplies. The campaign targeted neighborhoods within 10 miles of the retailer&rsquo;s locations and resulted in a CTR that was three times the industry average.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>About the MaxPoint Interest Index</strong><br />\r\nUsing its unique <a href=\\"http://www.maxpoint.com\\" rel=\\"nofollow\\" target=\\"_blank\\"><u>Digital Zip</u></a> technology, MaxPoint analyzes billions of data points consumed by neighborhoods across the United States such as offline point-of-sale data, credit card purchase data, social media, videos, music, local Web pages and online magazines. For the June Interest Index, the company scored each neighborhood across hundreds of online topics related to consumers&rsquo; interest in terms such as children&rsquo;s clothing, children&rsquo;s shoes and back-to-school sales. &nbsp; <strong>&nbsp;</strong><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>About MaxPoint </strong><br />\r\nMaxPoint&rsquo;s retail advertising platform drives in-store traffic for retailers and brands. The company&rsquo;s Digital Zip<sup>&reg; </sup>technology delivers the most effective and scalable hyperlocal neighborhood-level online campaigns. MaxPoint can pinpoint qualified customers interested in purchasing a product with more precision than using traditional zip codes, ultimately offering accurate neighborhood-level targeting with national reach and local results. Founded in 2007, MaxPoint has offices in New York, Chicago, Los Angeles, Atlanta, Austin, Bentonville, Cincinnati, and Raleigh. For more information visit <a href=\\"http://www.maxpoint.com\\" rel=\\"nofollow\\" target=\\"_blank\\"><u>www.maxpoint.com</u></a>, follow us on Twitter <a href=\\"http://twitter.com/maxpoint_int\\" rel=\\"nofollow\\" target=\\"_blank\\">@maxpoint_int</a>, and subscribe to the <a href=\\"http://www.maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/onpoint-blog\\" rel=\\"nofollow\\" target=\\"_blank\\">OnPoint Blog</a>. <strong>&nbsp;</strong><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Contact:</strong><br />\r\nAmy Peterson<br />\r\nfama PR<br />\r\n617-986-5026<br />\r\n<a href=\\"mailto:maxpoint@famapr.com \\">maxpoint@famapr.com </a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>1. <a href=\\"http://www.nrf.com/backtoschool\\" rel=\\"nofollow\\" target=\\"_blank\\">www.nrf.com/backtoschool</a></p>\r\n", "title"=>" MaxPoint Consumer Interest Index Finds Two Distinct Types of Spenders When It Comes to Back-to-School Shopping", "sidebar_text"=>"", "sidebar_image_uid"=>"2013/09/05/18_01_58_714_school_apparel.png", "sidebar_image_name"=>"school-apparel.png", "sidebar_image_link_target"=>"", "sidebar_image_link_page_id"=>"", "sidebar_image_link_external_url"=>""	\N	2013-06-25 16:09:51.860186	2013-11-13 15:05:08.222956
