587	91	\N	2	SuccessStoryDetailComponent	"body"=>"<p>By: David Ranii<br />\r\n<em>This article first appeared in</em> The News &amp; Observer.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>May 14,&nbsp;2012 &ndash;</strong> As consumers have steadily shifted away from traditional media to the Internet, businesses seeking to reach them online have run into a problem.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAlthough great at reaching specific demographic groups nationwide, the Internet falls short of old-school advertising vehicles such as direct mail and newspaper inserts when it comes to being hyper-local.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nA Morrisville startup is focused on changing that.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nUsing a two-step process that combines the computer-processing power of &ldquo;big data&rdquo; with a 21st-century adaptation of old-school ZIP codes, MaxPoint Interactive is competing with pinpoint print advertising as well as national Web-based services from companies such as Yahoo.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAnd unlike Yahoo and similar services that rely on &ldquo;cookies&rdquo; &ndash; small data files created when you visit a website &ndash; MaxPoint&rsquo;s technology is cookie-free. That makes it less objectionable to those worried about consumer privacy issues as well as increasing its reach at the neighborhood level.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&ldquo;They are going after a market opportunity that is a multibillion-dollar opportunity,&rdquo; said Gus Tai of Trinity Ventures, a Silicon Valley venture capital firm that has invested in MaxPoint. &ldquo;&hellip; MaxPoint has cracked that code of how to do it efficiently.&rdquo;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMaxPoint, which until now has maintained a low profile locally, ranks among the Triangle&rsquo;s fastest-growing young technology companies. It has blossomed from a half-dozen employees at the end of 2009 to 60 at the end of last year. Today it has 83 workers &ndash; more than half of whom are based in Morrisville &ndash; and new hires that are coming on board will swell its ranks to more than 90 by June 1.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&ldquo;And we continue to hire,&rdquo; said Joe Epperson, 41, the former eBay executive who is MaxPoint&rsquo;s founder and CEO. He expects the company will have 120 employees by the end of the year.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMaxPoint has created the digital equivalent of ZIP codes by dividing the nation into 34,000 neighborhoods, which it calls Digital Zips. By analyzing billions of data points &ndash; including sales data from more than 80,000 brick-and-mortar stores nationwide as well as a wealth of online and social media data &ndash; it can identify neighborhoods that are fertile grounds for a particular product or service. Equally important, it can specify which retailers have stores nearby.None of the data identifies individual consumers.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Cutting waste</strong><br />\r\nMaxPoint has coupled that mother lode of data with its real-time analysis of how best to reach consumers in a particular neighborhood through online ads.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&ldquo;So literally, as a page on your Web browser is rendering, we are deciding whether or not to purchase that ad,&rdquo; Epperson said. &ldquo;We make about 12 billion decisions a day.&rdquo; Each automated decisions is made in between 8 and 12 milliseconds.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn the end, said Epperson, MaxPoint&rsquo;s technology can deliver ads within a particular neighborhood to 80 percent to 90 percent of the targeted consumers that are online.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMaxPoint, which was founded in 2007, has reported raising $12.2 million from outside investors to date. Like many privately held companies, it&rsquo;s tight-lipped about its revenue. Epperson said the company, which only started generating revenue in 2009, has generated &ldquo;multiple tens of millions of dollars&rdquo; in sales over the past 12 months.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nCalifornia Olive Ranch, an olive oil company, tested MaxPoint&rsquo;s ability to deliver its ads to the consumers most likely to buy its product &ndash; educated women who live in larger cities and like to cook.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&ldquo;They helped us find the websites they&rsquo;ll be on and they overlaid that with our store network, because people tend to shop at grocery stores close to home,&rdquo; said Mike Forbes, vice president of sales and marketing. &ldquo;It cuts out the waste from our (advertising) budget and makes sure we are talking to the right people.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&rdquo;Sales in Boston rose 20 percent as a result, he said.&ldquo;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nJust as importantly, we actually ran a test and noticed our brand awareness and consumers&rsquo; willingness to buy us went up rather dramatically as well,&rdquo; Forbes said.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Scaling up</strong><br />\r\nCalifornia Olive is working with MaxPoint as it rolls out its olive oil to markets in North Carolina.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&ldquo;You&rsquo;ll actually probably be seeing our ads in Raleigh,&rdquo; Forbes said.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nCalifornia Olive Ranch is the only customer MaxPoint has publicly disclosed. But Lynn Vitello, vice president of marketing, said the company works with 10 of the nation&rsquo;s top 15 advertisers &ndash; a group that includes Proctor &amp; Gamble, AT&amp;T and General Motors.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMaxPoint typically charges $4 to $5 for every 1,000 online ads purchased. Monthly payments by customers range from $5,000 to more than $500,000.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nEpperson credits customer satisfaction for fueling much of the company&rsquo;s growth. Nearly four out of five first-time customers, he said, become repeat customers.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe company&rsquo;s biggest challenge, said Trinity Ventures&rsquo; Tai, is to maintain the quality of its hires given its rapid-fire expansion.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&ldquo;And scaling (up), by the way, isn&rsquo;t easy,&rdquo; Tai added.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nEpperson previously worked in Silicon Valley when he was at eBay, but he and his wife are from Ohio. They wanted to return to the east coast when he decided to start MaxPoint. The two locations that made the most sense were Boston and the Triangle, because both are home to workers with the necessary business intelligence and analytics skills.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&ldquo;It came down to this very hard-core fact that after being in California seven-plus years, my wife is like, &lsquo;Boston&rsquo;s too cold,&rsquo;&rdquo; Epperson said.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAlthough Epperson has been delighted with the talent MaxPoint has been able to hire here, he stressed that the company isn&rsquo;t getting them on the cheap.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&ldquo;We have a Silicon Valley mentality,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;We have compensation packages that are equivalent to Silicon Valley because the people we hire from Duke and UNC, their alternatives are Yahoo, Google. That&rsquo;s who we compete with for employees.&rdquo;</p>\r\n", "title"=>"MaxPoint’s ad technology fuels growth ", "sidebar_text"=>"", "sidebar_image_uid"=>NULL, "sidebar_image_name"=>NULL, "sidebar_image_link_target"=>"_blank", "sidebar_image_link_page_id"=>"-1", "sidebar_image_link_external_url"=>"http://www.newsobserver.com/"	\N	2013-05-15 00:04:24.659062	2013-12-05 14:59:12.164552
