1353	165	\N	3	SuccessStoryDetailComponent	"body"=>"<p><strong>Raleigh, N.C. &ndash; August 28, 2013 &ndash; </strong>To help advertisers target customers preparing for retirement, MaxPoint leveraged its proprietary Digital Zip<sup>&reg;</sup> technology to develop two customer profiles: those who prepare for retirement by searching online for resources about more stable investments, debt elimination and Social Security and those who spend on financial services and make riskier investments to grow their nest eggs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>MaxPoint&rsquo;s Interest Index comes at a time when consumers are increasingly concerned about their retirement. A recent report from the Pew Research Center claims that, for survey respondents between 36 and 40, &ldquo;53% say they are either &lsquo;not too&rsquo; or &lsquo;not at all&rsquo; confident that their income and assets will last through retirement.&rdquo; But it&rsquo;s not just 36&ndash;40 year olds&mdash;34% of respondents between 60 and 64 also lacked confidence in the size of their retirement nest eggs. The profiles uncovered by MaxPoint help financial services companies capitalize on an existing trend, while also making their customers feel more secure about the future.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>The Conservative Retirement Planners</strong><br />\r\nUsing its Digital Zip technology, including credit card purchase data, MaxPoint was able to pinpoint the top neighborhoods in the country where consumer interest trended highest for stable or conservative retirement planning, such as savings rather than wealth generation. Based on research, MaxPoint found that typical planners tend to be 55 or older, own their homes and are less likely to have children in the house. The group trends high for interest in topics such as organic living, elderly care and the economy. Additionally, planners&rsquo; purchases include video rentals, communication services (such as cell phones and Internet services), meals at quick service restaurants and items from office supply chains.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The following cities have neighborhoods that scored the highest when it comes to conservative retirement planners:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>Columbus, OH</li>\r\n\t<li>Denver, CO</li>\r\n\t<li>Los Angeles, CA</li>\r\n\t<li>New York, NY</li>\r\n\t<li>Orlando, FL</li>\r\n\t<li>Phoenix, AZ</li>\r\n\t<li>St. Louis, MO</li>\r\n\t<li>San Francisco, CA</li>\r\n\t<li>Seattle, WA</li>\r\n\t<li>Washington, DC</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<strong>The Financial Services Spenders</strong><br />\r\nAdditionally, MaxPoint identified shoppers who spend on financial services, including investment services, tax preparation, and other financial and accounting services. They found that the average spenders are older than 45, hold college degrees and are less likely to have children in the house. They trend high on interest in topics such as interior design, foreign policy, eco-friendly living and products, and health and fitness. In addition to their financial services spending, they also spend their incomes at general merchandise stores (typically home goods stores), at home furnishing stores, and on consumer appliances and electronics.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The following cities have neighborhoods that score the highest on financial services spenders:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>Chicago, IL</li>\r\n\t<li>Dallas, TX</li>\r\n\t<li>Houston, TX</li>\r\n\t<li>Las Vegas, NV</li>\r\n\t<li>Los Angeles, CA</li>\r\n\t<li>Miami, FL</li>\r\n\t<li>New York, NY</li>\r\n\t<li>Phoenix, AZ</li>\r\n\t<li>San Diego, CA</li>\r\n\t<li>San Francisco, CA</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nAlthough four cities appear on both lists, the two groups reside in different neighborhoods within those cities. For example, within the Los Angeles DMA, planners reside most heavily in Seal Beach while financial spenders live in Manhattan Beach. This demonstrates the importance of looking beyond the DMA to target customers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;Retirement is such a personal matter, so it&rsquo;s key that financial advertisers target the right people with the right message,&rdquo; said Gretchen Joyce, COO at MaxPoint. &ldquo;These profiles demonstrate how retirement planners are different from financial services consumers from demographics and interests to purchase behaviors. Advertisers can use this data to target the right audience and ultimately achieve higher campaign response rates while reducing impressions wasted on the wrong audience.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Interest Data in Action</strong><br />\r\nUsing the data gleaned from the Interest Index, MaxPoint has run several campaigns for retirement planners and for financial services spenders, including:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>A National Non-Profit&rsquo;s Financial Planning Campaign&mdash;A national non-profit wanted to drive awareness of a financial planning and services program for African Americans and Hispanics. The program provided information and education on investing, debt elimination and budgeting. To help, MaxPoint targeted Digital Zips around the nation that over-indexed for African Americans and Hispanics more than 40 years old, with annual incomes between $25,000 and $75,000. The ad campaign produced a response rate that was 78% higher than the industry average.</li>\r\n\t<li>National Private Banking Company&mdash;A private banking company wanted to build awareness of its programs and offerings. MaxPoint served ads in Digital Zips that over-indexed for married adults with annual household incomes above $100,000 and between $1 and $5 million in investible assets. The campaign resulted in a response rate that was more than three times the industry average.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<strong>About the MaxPoint Interest Index</strong><br />\r\nUsing its unique <a href=\\"http://maxpoint.com/solution/\\" target=\\"_blank\\">Digital Zip</a> technology, MaxPoint analyzes billions of data points consumed by neighborhoods across the United States such as offline point-of-sale data, credit card purchase data, social media, videos, music, local Web pages and online magazines.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>About MaxPoint </strong><br />\r\nMaxPoint&rsquo;s retail advertising platform drives in-store traffic for retailers and brands. The company&rsquo;s Digital Zip<sup>&reg;</sup> technology delivers the most effective and scalable hyperlocal neighborhood-level online campaigns. MaxPoint can pinpoint qualified customers interested in purchasing a product with more precision than using traditional zip codes, ultimately offering accurate neighborhood-level targeting with national reach and local results. For more information visit <a href=\\"http://www.maxpoint.com/\\" target=\\"_blank\\">www.maxpoint.com</a>, follow us on Twitter <a href=\\"https://twitter.com/maxpoint_int\\" target=\\"_blank\\">@maxpoint_int</a>, and subscribe to the <a href=\\"http://maxpoint.com/onpoint-blog/\\" target=\\"_blank\\">OnPoint Blog</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Contact:</strong><br />\r\nAmy Peterson<br />\r\nfama PR<br />\r\n617-986-5026<br />\r\n<a href=\\"mailto:maxpoint@famapr.com\\">maxpoint@famapr.com</a></p>\r\n", "title"=>" MaxPoint Interest Index Finds Two Distinct Profiles for  Consumers Focused on Retirement", "sidebar_text"=>"", "sidebar_image_uid"=>"2013/08/28/17_40_10_522_Golden_Years.png", "sidebar_image_name"=>"Golden-Years.png", "sidebar_image_link_target"=>"", "sidebar_image_link_page_id"=>"", "sidebar_image_link_external_url"=>""	\N	2013-08-27 21:27:54.046436	2013-09-03 15:58:52.407136
