654	1	15	tips-for-designing-effective-campaign-landing-pages	Tips for Designing Effective Campaign Landing Pages	<p>When developing a digital campaign, we all know you also need a landing page, right? Landing pages provide a non-generic point of entry to your website and your audience reaches that page with a specific intention in mind, such as downloading a coupon for example. Once you have gotten your audience to your landing page then go ahead and give yourself a pat on the back &ndash; your ad captured enough of their attention to click for more information!</p>\r\n	<p>When developing a digital campaign, we all know you also need a landing page, right? Landing pages provide a non-generic point of entry to your website and your audience reaches that page with a specific intention in mind, such as downloading a coupon for example. Once you have gotten your audience to your landing page then go ahead and give yourself a pat on the back &ndash; your ad captured enough of their attention to click for more information! <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nHowever, driving your audience to your landing page is not the last step; you also need to keep them engaged once they get there. That being said, the design of your campaign landing page will do the rest of the work. Below are a few guidelines to keep in mind.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Keep it Consistent</strong><br />\r\nFirst and foremost, make sure your messages match.&nbsp; Your digital ad and corresponding landing page should have the same call to action. It ensures your audience that they&rsquo;re in the right place to find the deal, offer, signup, etc. and it also tells them that you aren&rsquo;t pulling the &lsquo;ol bait-and-switch. Inspiring trust increases the likelihood of conversion.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhile the visual design of your landing page should be geared towards the message of your campaign, it should stylistically feel like part of your greater online presence. The design should be similar to what people have experienced in the past from your brand&ndash; this helps to create a strong <a href="http://www.businessdictionary.com/definition/brand-image.html" target="_blank">brand image</a>. Match the colors of your brand and use some subtle, or perhaps not-so-subtle, nods to the graphical elements on your main website.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Keep It Simple</strong><br />\r\nClear and concise headlines should compel your audience to take a closer look but don&rsquo;t make them hunt for that call to action. Call to action buttons should stand out. Make it big, make it bright, and make it above the fold. Label the button with the exact action you hope for &ndash; Sign Up, Download, etc. For example, Mozilla saw a 3% increase in downloads from their Firefox browser landing page just by changing the button text from &ldquo;Try Firefox 3&rdquo; to &ldquo;Download Now &ndash; Free&rdquo;.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nDon&rsquo;t confuse your audience by offering too many options for navigation. Remember, you want them to stick around. A link to items relevant to the offer and one to the main website should suffice. Also, minimize the number of clicks required for response. Each additional and unnecessary click is an opportunity to lose your audience. As a best practice, capture what you need on the first page. That being said, there&rsquo;s no better way to turn your audience away than to present them with a giant <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/onpoint-blog/2011/8/29/best-practices-for-website-form-design" target="_blank">form</a>. Ask only for what you need and plan other ways to get the nice-to-haves late.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Keep It Interesting</strong><br />\r\nCustomer testimonials, product images, or an engaging video are great ways to pull your audience in. Think of each item as a tool for persuading them to take the next step. And, all of these should be curated with the goal of conversion in mind. Graphics for the sake of graphics are not going to help convince your audience, and they may dilute your message &ndash; so take a giant step back from the stock art.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Keep Measuring It</strong><br />\r\nIn addition to delivering a targeted message, your landing page allows you to measure your digital campaign.&nbsp; Using web analytics will allow you to help calculate the ROI at the end of a campaign and can be used to unlock some clues on where you can improve an active campaign as well. For example, if your audiences drop off after hitting your landing page, you might examine your message and/or call to action. If people are dropping off midway through conversion, you might need to ask for less information or minimize the number of steps. Don&rsquo;t hesitate to make tweaks along the way. It&rsquo;s a great way to see what resonates best with your visitors.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhat works well for one campaign may not work well for all campaigns, but following these basic guidelines should help you to deliver a focused experience on your landing page and get you well on your way to accomplishing your conversion goal. For more ideas about what makes a great landing page, check out these articles:<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<a href="http://www.tripwiremagazine.com/2011/06/showcase-and-tips-how-to-create-effective-landing-page-designs.html" target="_blank">How To Create Effective Landing Page Design</a>, via Tripwire<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<a href="http://www.businessweek.com/smallbiz/tips/archives/2011/01/create_landing_pages_that_deliver_sales.html" target="_blank">Create Landing Pages That Deliver Sales</a>, via Businessweek</p>\r\n	t	2011-09-06 14:25:48	\N	2011-09-06 14:25:48	2013-10-23 18:00:06.175914	49	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, Lora Edwards, landing pages, digital campaigns, campaigns, landing page design tips, Tripwire, Businessweek  
653	1	20	eliminating-checkout-choices-can-hurt-in-store-sales	Eliminating Checkout Choices Can Hurt In-Store Sales	<p>I am one of the 35% of shoppers who love the self-checkout.&nbsp; Maybe love is strong word.&nbsp; I prefer self-checkouts when it comes to smaller orders.&nbsp; For me, larger orders belong with a full-service checkout, especially with a lot of produce, alcohol (since you need to show ID), bulky items or coupons.&nbsp; Self-checkouts should be fast and convenient and for 20 items or fewer.&nbsp;</p>\r\n	<p>I am one of the 35% of shoppers who love the self-checkout.&nbsp; Maybe love is strong word.&nbsp; I prefer self-checkouts when it comes to smaller orders.&nbsp; For me, larger orders belong with a full-service checkout, especially with a lot of produce, alcohol (since you need to show ID), bulky items or coupons.&nbsp; Self-checkouts should be fast and convenient and for 20 items or fewer.&nbsp;<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nThere is nothing worse than a self-checkout line being held up by a full cartload.&nbsp; The reason I prefer them rather than like or love them is all in the functionality.&nbsp; If the self-checkout would allow you to scan items at the same rate as a full-service, manned register, allow for quantity entry instead of scanning identical items one at a time, have a hand scanner for larger, bulky items and perhaps incorporate a larger &ldquo;staging area&rdquo; like a conveyor (rather than the paltry 2&rsquo;x2&rsquo; space to put a hand basket), I would love them.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nRegardless if you love them or hate them, it gives shoppers choices.&nbsp; According to an <a href="http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/43729757/ns/today-today_news/t/welcome-valued-customer-more-self-checkouts/" target="_blank">MSNBC report</a>, 35% of shoppers love self-checkouts and 37% hate them.&nbsp; The 37% that hate them, need not use them, but what about the 35% who love them?&nbsp; Is a store willing to lose out on a chunk of that 35% to a local competitor down the road that still offers self-checkouts?&nbsp; It doesn&rsquo;t really make good business sense.&nbsp; At first glance, the math in this article points to a higher cost of self-checkouts vs. purchasing a regular cash register.&nbsp; However, what the numbers fail to show are the added costs of the standard register.&nbsp; For one, they need to be manned.&nbsp; That hits payroll.&nbsp; Second, they take up more space in the store that can be used for prime display space.&nbsp; Over the course of 5 years, the cost comparison would likely be negligible.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThat said, I have to commend Albertsons supermarket for thinking of the customer!&nbsp; Their decision to eliminate self-checkouts was based on the desire to have more interaction with the customer &ndash; how refreshing &ndash; a store that cares.&nbsp; Unfortunately, there is not an Albertson&rsquo;s in my area or I would visit to experience this customer friendly store.&nbsp; Of course, the proof is in the pudding.&nbsp; Will this decision affect Albertsons bottom line, one way or the other?<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAs for the not-to-distant future of the in-aisle smart phone shopping experience mentioned in the article, bring it on!&nbsp; Think Amazon.com functionality (people who bought this, also bought&hellip;) on steroids.&nbsp; The amount of opportunity for retailers to highly target shoppers right at the individual store level while they are actually in the store with promos, add-ons, up-sells, recipe ideas, alternative choice recommendations and the like could be a huge boon for market leaders and thought leaders alike.</p>\r\n	t	2011-08-31 13:46:04	\N	2011-08-31 13:46:04	2013-10-23 18:01:29.846149	49	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, Lynn Vitello, OnPoint, self-checkout, grocery stores, MSNBC, shoppers, Albertsons 
649	1	15	display-video-advertising-targeting-solution-another-channel-to-reach-your-audience	Display Video Advertising Targeting Solution: Another Channel to Reach Your Audience	<p>Video advertising has quickly become a highly engaging way for retailers and brands to reach their audiences, driving in-store sales. And, this applies for all retailers and brands (regional &amp; national).</p>\r\n	<p>In the past year in particular, online video advertising adoption has begun to grow at a rapidly increasing rate. According to a recent survey by BrightRoll, &quot;28% of media buyers expect to see the greatest increase in ad spending in the online video category for 2011.&quot; In addition, according to <a href="http://www.emarketer.com/Reports/All/Emarketer_2000713.aspx" target="_blank">eMarketer</a>, its unique interactivity helps marketers more accurately measure the relationship between video ads and their influence on consumers. This being said, video advertising has quickly become a highly engaging way for retailers and brands to reach their audiences, driving in-store sales. And, this applies for all retailers and brands (regional &amp; national).<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn June, we were pleased to announce our video targeting solution enabling digital advertisers to target their pre-roll video, reaching up to 90% of online users across high-quality and brand-safe content sites, including co-branded YouTube channels. Now able to target both pre-roll and in-banner video ads at a local level, marketers can ensure that the consumers most able to buy and interested in a product see the ad. Furthermore, <a href="http://dynamicvideoad.mixpo.com" target="_blank">Mixpo</a> has been a helpful partner throughout this process, enabling brands and retailers to easily leverage already existing investments in TV advertising or other creative into powerful, locally targeted online video ads. Click <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/online-advertising-news/health-care-video-ads" target="_blank">here</a> to read the press release.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nNew to video advertising? To ensure that the video advertisements are successful, two things need to happen:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n\t<li>The video ad must reach only the most qualified audience: Video advertisements need to be targeted to run only where an audience who matches a brand&rsquo;s customized neighborhood profile is spending time. If the customers targeted are not able or interested in purchasing a product then the video solution is not being optimized to its full effect.</li>\r\n\t<li>The video ad should take into consideration the following: Define the goal of the video ad, keep it short and simple (:15 to :30 second video clips are ideal), get to the point, use effective visuals, and test different formats/messages with an audience test group before launch.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nKeeping these in mind, you are on your way to video advertising success! Want to know more? Feel free to leave a comment or send us a tweet <a href="http://twitter.com/maxpoint_int" target="_blank">@maxpoint_int</a> prepending the hashtag #videotargetingsolution.</p>\r\n	t	2011-07-07 13:45:23	\N	2011-07-07 13:45:23	2013-10-09 18:19:03.219451	51	\N
652	1	15	best-practices-for-website-form-design	Best Practices for Website Form Design	<p>You&rsquo;re just about finished with your website or landing page for your digital campaign, and now all you need to do is add a web form. Forms can be an important element to your digital campaign &ndash; requiring your audience to fill out a form for access to certain campaign collateral or maybe even digital coupons.</p>\r\n	<p>You&rsquo;re just about finished with your website or landing page for your digital campaign, and now all you need to do is add a web form. Forms can be an important element to your digital campaign &ndash; requiring your audience to fill out a form for access to certain campaign collateral or maybe even digital coupons. It&rsquo;s often the element standing between you and the information you want from your audience. Their uses range from sign up and payment, all the way to help and contact us. We all know forms and we all use them (at one point or another).<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nWeb forms are great because they not only let you collect information without giving your direct e-mail out but they can also collect the information you want, having the capability to set specific boundaries. However, while forms are an incredibly useful tool for tracking your audience&rsquo;s information, they also represent a big risk. Badly designed forms are one of the biggest reasons for site drop off (one of the last things you want to see when collecting web metrics).<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn order to avoid this, here are some tips to help you get the most out of your forms:<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Keep it Short</strong><br />\r\nThere&rsquo;s nothing that will make your audience close their browser window faster than encountering a really long form. Ask yourself if you really need all the information you are requesting. Just like designing a campaign, make it short, sweet and to the point.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIf you&rsquo;ve taken out all the &ldquo;nice-to-knows&rdquo; and you still have a lot on your hands, consider breaking the form into separate chunks of related fields or even into multiple pages, similar to a wizard. Your audience should be able to see their progress - specifically, how much they have to go - on each page.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Be Clear About What You Want</strong><br />\r\nUse field labels that your audience will understand. Your labels should be clear and descriptive &ndash; but also, short. If extra clarification is needed, use contextual help rather than a long, wordy label.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAlso, make sure to distinguish between required and optional fields. An asterisk placed to the right of the label is an accepted standard. If your optional fields are by far the minority, it may make sense to indicate those instead of the required fields.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Implement with Care</strong><br />\r\nTry not to be too picky about the formats you accept. For example, if you are asking for a date, ideally the form should accept all versions (ex. 11/5/2011, 11/05/2011, 11-5-11, 11-05-2011 and November 5, 2011).<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIf there is an intelligent default value for an element, go ahead and select it. For instance, it&rsquo;s a good idea to select &ldquo;United States&rdquo; for country, when the vast majority of your users live in the US.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAlso, allowing your audience to advance from one field to the next using the tab key is an absolute must.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Give Meaningful Feedback</strong><br />\r\nOnce your audience successfully submits the form, they should receive a success message. This message should confirm that their information has been submitted along with any available information about what to expect next. For example, &ldquo;You can now check your email for your login to the research study&rdquo; or &ldquo;A representative will contact you in the next 24 hours.&rdquo; This message can add a humanistic element that forms usually lack. It&rsquo;s important your audience leaves feeling that they have reached you.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nEvery form has the possibility for error and you will want to plan for that. Helpful error handling will be specific about which field has the error and what is expected.&nbsp; The error text should appear at the top of the form and the problematic field should be indicated in some way. An icon or highlighted fields are popular and effective options.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOnce your form is ready to use on your website or campaign landing page, you&rsquo;ll want to track its performance. Performance indicators like conversion and dropout rates are clear indicators about how you&rsquo;re doing. It&rsquo;s also helpful to capture submission errors. These can be really telling about any misunderstandings your audience is having. Don&rsquo;t be afraid to tweak your form until you&rsquo;re getting the results you want. It may even be helpful to have a friend walk through the form while you watch and listen.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nFor more information about designing great forms, check out these articles:<br />\r\n<a href="http://www.uxforthemasses.com/forms-usability/" target="_blank">How to Improve the Usability of Your Forms</a>, via UX for the Masses<br />\r\n<a href="http://uxdesign.smashingmagazine.com/2008/07/04/web-form-design-patterns-sign-up-forms/" target="_blank">Web Form Design Patterns: Sign-Up Forms</a>, via Smashing Magazine<br />\r\n<br />\r\nReally interested in form design? Check out this <a href="http://www.lukew.com/resources/web_form_design.asp" target="_blank">book</a>.</p>\r\n	t	2011-08-29 13:26:27	\N	2011-08-29 13:26:27	2013-10-23 18:02:51.651226	49	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, forms, digital campaign, website form design, web form, website tips  
650	1	20	refreshing-inventory-leads-to-more-repeat-in-store-sales	Refreshing Inventory Leads to More Repeat In-Store Sales	<p>It is difficult for retail stores to compete with pricing in an online world, but the one advantage they have is the ability to cycle fresh merchandise more quickly and frequently, which is critical as the Web makes it harder for stores to compete on price. Surprises also create suspense and encourage repeat visits.</p>\r\n	<p>It is difficult for retail stores to compete with pricing in an online world, but the one advantage they have is the ability to cycle fresh merchandise more quickly and frequently, which is critical as the Web makes it harder for stores to compete on price. Surprises also create suspense and encourage repeat visits.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nCostco, for example, uses the term &quot;treasure hunt&quot; to explain why up to a fifth of its stock is limited-quantity items that are in the store for as little as a week.&nbsp; Some of that inventory is seasonal such as patio furniture and pool toys in summer. Some high end products such as bargain-priced Hunter rain boots, sold almost exclusively in the U.S. by Nordstrom are a top find for those hunting for the next great Costco deal.&nbsp; But you have to be quick&mdash;the inventory moves fast and is unlikely to return.&nbsp; The merchandise may not return but bargain hunters will.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAccording to an article in the Sun Herald in Mississippi, the wholesale chain shows that the treasure hunt strategy can pay. Revenue at U.S. Costco stores open at least a year was up 10 percent last quarter from last year, with strong growth in non-essentials like jewelry and home and garden.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This goes to show that once you get someone into their neighborhood store to grab the next best bargain, they will also stay and possibly purchase impulse items or consider other items they would normally buy online since they are already in the store.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOn the flipside to continually adding and changing inventory, some retailers have tried the approach of paring down their inventory to the basics and removing many competing products.&nbsp; While this is a bold move in attempting to gain more market share, it unfortunately does not always prove to be successful.&nbsp; Not all ideas will work, but kudos for trying innovative strategies and seeing them through.&nbsp; Retailers should keep taking risks and trying new things to win the in-store sales race.</p>\r\n	t	2011-08-22 13:34:12	\N	2011-08-22 13:34:12	2013-10-23 18:09:49.889055	49	MaxPoint, Maxpoint Interactive, OnPoint, Lynn Vitello, inventory, retail inventory, in-store sales, pricing, Costco, Sun Herald  
651	1	15	as-hispanic-culture-has-gone-digital-why-have-hispanic-ad-dollars-stayed-traditional	As Hispanic Culture Has Gone Digital, Why Have Hispanic Ad Dollars Stayed Traditional?	<p>Lately, there has been a lot of discussion around the missed advertising opportunities within the Hispanic culture group. Missed opportunities being attributed to traditional advertising methods, despite the fact that the Hispanic culture group has gone digital.</p>\r\n	<p>In one of our recent posts, <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/onpoint-blog/2011/10/7/out-with-the-old-in-with-the-new-why-traditional-ad-budgets-should-be-allocated-for-digital-2" target="_blank">Out with the Old, In with the New: Why Traditional Ad Budgets Should be Allocated for Digital</a>, we discussed how advertisers and brands really need to re-think online advertising as a way to effectively reach their audiences. In the post, we quickly came to the conclusion that the digital advertising route is becoming the more effective way to reach audiences (arguing this based on online ad spending predictions and consumer preference). And, while we generally discussed some of the reasons to make the transition, we thought we would take it one step further and follow up with a direct example.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nLately, there has been a lot of discussion around the missed advertising opportunities within the Hispanic culture group. Missed opportunities being attributed to traditional advertising methods, despite the fact that the Hispanic culture group has gone digital.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn a recent Media Post <a href="http://www.mediapost.com/publications/?fa=Articles.showArticle&amp;art_aid=153564" target="_blank">article</a>, author Jose Villa, discusses how heavily advertisers &ldquo;play on and integrate&rdquo; digital themes in television advertisements directed towards the U.S. Hispanic culture. He focuses on pointing out the digital themes in TV ads to show that marketers do understand that digital media is a large part of the U.S. Hispanic reality. However, while advertisers are aware that Hispanics are heavy users of digital media, only 4.8% of all Hispanic media went to online media &ndash; shocking! And, this is ironic because clearly advertisers feel that the digital element is important to incorporate in traditional ad concepts&hellip;bringing Villa to the conclusion that it is clear there is some major inefficiency in how Hispanic advertising dollars are being spent. Quoting Villa, &ldquo;I would assume the account planners at the agencies that created the spots were looking at the same data we see all the time in writing their creative briefs&hellip;Hispanics are heavy users of all kinds of digital media.&rdquo;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn addition, a recent eMarketer <a href="http://www.emarketer.com/Article.aspx?R=1008524" target="_blank">post</a> also discussed how Hispanics are going digital, highlighting that they have the highest tablet/eReader adoption rate. After sharing some of these tablet/eReader adoption stats, eMarketer pointed out that this may be due to the &ldquo;tremendous&rdquo; buying power of Hispanic consumers &ndash; buying power projected to reach $1.3 trillion by 2015. Again, this brings us back to the question: if Hispanics are both active and early adopters of digital technology and media, and have the buying power&hellip;wouldn&rsquo;t you want to make sure to target digital advertisements to this group effectively?<br />\r\n<br />\r\nKnowing the above, marketers are potentially missing a huge untapped market and need to make the transition from traditional to digital when it comes to Hispanic consumers. At the end of the day, an advertisement&rsquo;s success is dependent on its ability to reach the target audience (i.e. if the target audience is online then that is where the ads should be)!</p>\r\n	t	2011-08-24 13:00:24	\N	2011-08-24 13:00:24	2013-10-23 18:06:38.325839	49	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, consumers, digital consumers, traditional advertising, digital advertising, ad spending, Hispanic, eMarketer, Media Post, Jose Villa, traditional vs. digital  
655	1	15	whats-the-scoop-with-hadoop	What's the Scoop with Hadoop?	<p>We live in a highly technical world, one where we can activate our house alarm from an airplane, receive coupons on our mobile as we walk past stores and access endless amounts of information in the cloud. Technology is at our fingertips and it is important to keep up with the latest technology trends. However, while it is easy to spot some of these trends, others are harder to find and conquer, which brings us to Hadoop.</p>\r\n	<p>We live in a highly technical world, one where we can activate our house alarm from an airplane, receive coupons on our mobile as we walk past stores and access endless amounts of information in the cloud. Technology is at our fingertips and it is important to keep up with the latest technology trends. However, while it is easy to spot some of these trends, others are harder to find and conquer, which brings us to Hadoop. <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn its simplest form, Hadoop is an open-source (free) Apache Software Foundation product used by companies for data mining. And, this is important to companies because data mining allows you to store and process large amounts of data in an array of computers (your internal or cloud based IT infrastructure). This would be data that allows for statistical sampling, such as, internet data (things you need to know to &ldquo;understand&rdquo; internet behavior &ndash; i.e. page views) or shopping data (in our case). Hadoop uses an array of computers to store this data and provides a software framework that allows you process it in parallel. With these features, Hadoop makes it easier to analyze very large datasets. For instance, you could download terabytes of weather data and write your own analysis to discover trends. This leaves you with an analysis of what you would think is interesting about the weather, highlighting a certain trend (such as certain weather patterns that may be important to identify when rolling out certain campaigns).<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSo, how does this work?<br />\r\n<br />\r\nYour data is stored as files broken into small blocks and replicated across multiple computers in your array. To perform an analysis, each computer in the array can process the blocks that it is storing. This allows all of the computers to analyze part of a large dataset simultaneously, in order to collect results faster (results being the data trends identified).&nbsp; For instance, 50 computers could process different portions of a data set simultaneously thus allowing the data to be processed much faster.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhy should you care?<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>It&rsquo;s different:</strong> Unlike most data mining services, Hadoop allows companies to process large amounts of data collected across an array of computers (commodity servers) as opposed to specialized hardware like a mainframe or supercomputer.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Easy Investment:</strong> Hadoop is a small up-front cost with predictable incremental growth as opposed to the costs associated with specialized hardware procuring and replacement.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Parallel/Fast:</strong> Several computers can process data from the same data set simultaneously.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Reliable:</strong> If one computer fails, its data files still exist on other computers and its processing tasks can be reassigned to another computer.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIf you need to process large amounts of data (because it would take a ridiculous amount of time to process the data and find trends manually), Hadoop is the right software for you. And, Hadoop is now taking a turn towards usability as it becomes more user-friendly. Read more <a href="http://www.networkworld.com/news/2011/072011-apache-hadoop-to-get-more.html" target="_blank">here</a>.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nFun fact: Hadoop was named after the creator&rsquo;s son&rsquo;s toy elephant.</p>\r\n	t	2011-09-08 13:49:38	\N	2011-09-08 13:49:38	2013-11-11 15:12:34.335049	52	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, Kimberly Burke, data storage, Hadoop, Apache, data mining, technology, data, commodity server, data analysis, NetworkWorld 
889	1	47	need-to-reach-hispanic-shoppers-go-mobile	Need to Reach Hispanic Shoppers? Go Mobile	<p>Did you know Hispanic shoppers use mobile devices more than almost any other group? In today&#39;s post, we cover some strategies to help you better reach this growing audience.</p>\r\n	<p>Hispanics are the most rapidly growing demographic in the United States. The group already brings a lot of purchasing power to the US economy&mdash;Hispanic shoppers are estimated to spend up to $1.5 trillion by 2015.<a href="#_ftn1" name="_ftnref1" title="">[1]</a> In short, advertisers know how important it will be to reach these shoppers now and over the next few years.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="Cell Phone" src="/system/editor/W1siZiIsIjIwMTMvMTEvMTMvMDdfMzJfMDVfNjc1X0NlbGxfUGhvbmUuanBnIl0sWyJwIiwidGh1bWIiLCI4MDB4ODAwPiJdXQ/Cell%20Phone.jpg" style="float:right; height:214px; margin:0px 15px; width:215px" />Recently, the Pew Research Center released some interesting intelligence about Hispanics. According to its report, Hispanic shoppers score higher than any other demographic (aside from young shoppers) when it comes to accessing the web via mobile device.<a href="#_ftn2" name="_ftnref2" title="">[2]</a> So, what does this mean for your advertising strategies for reaching Hispanic shoppers?</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>Devote More of Your Budget to Mobile&mdash;</strong>Since mobile is such a great way to reach this audience, you&rsquo;ll want to put more money toward mobile ads. But don&rsquo;t stop using desktop ads altogether&mdash;just work with your digital provider to find the right mix.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Think Mobile Responsive&mdash;</strong>Since Hispanic shoppers respond to ads on mobile devices, make sure that you support the full mobile experience with a mobile-responsive site or landing page. Mobile shoppers and visitors will likely bounce from a site with a subpar mobile experience. Your ads invite shoppers to your site&mdash;make sure it&rsquo;s hospitable once they get there.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Make Your Content and Deals Shareable&mdash;</strong>A report from the Interactive Advertising Bureau claimed that for Hispanics, word-of-mouth and sharing is key.<a href="#_ftn3" name="_ftnref3" title="">[3]</a> Many Hispanics see themselves as influencers and enjoy being the first to share deals and new products with their friends and family. Make it simple for them by offering easy sharing functionality on your content, ads, and promotions.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Support Multiple Languages on Your Mobile Site and Apps&mdash;</strong>If your company caters to a multicultural audience, then your website likely already supports multiple languages. But what about your mobile solutions? If you do have a mobile site, make sure to include multiple language support. If you have any apps or mobile loyalty programs, make sure you include versions in Spanish as well.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>Post Spanish Ads on English Sites&mdash;</strong>Even though you should include Spanish language support, don&rsquo;t overlook placements on English-written sites. Many Hispanic shoppers frequent sites in English, and often the Spanish ads cut through the clutter on the site. You should target Hispanic shoppers wherever they are on the Web, whether a Spanish site or an English site.<br />\r\n\t&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>As the size of the Hispanic audience continues to grow in the United States, smart advertisers will try to gain more market share. Work with your digital provider to get the right intelligence to power the mobile buys that will best help you reach your goals. There&rsquo;s a lot you can do to reach Hispanic shoppers&mdash;just make sure that you have mobile as a large part of your Hispanic advertising strategies.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Do you advertise to Hispanics or to a multicultural audience? If so, what tactics have you found effective? Let us know in the comments below.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="#_ftnref1" name="_ftn1" title="">[1]</a>. Selig Center for Economic Growth, <em>The Multicultural Economy: 2010</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="#_ftnref2" name="_ftn2" title="">[2]</a>. <a href="http://www.emarketer.com/Article/Hispanics-Lead-Web-Users-Who-Truly-Mobile-First/1010280" target="_blank">http://www.emarketer.com/Article/Hispanics-Lead-Web-Users-Who-Truly-Mobile-First/1010280</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="#_ftnref3" name="_ftn3" title="">[3]</a>. <a href="http://www.iab.net/media/file/Hispanic-Digital-Consumer.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.iab.net/media/file/Hispanic-Digital-Consumer.pdf</a></p>\r\n	t	2013-11-13 13:16:58	\N	2013-11-13 13:19:53.208999	2013-11-13 15:52:33.580721	59	\N
766	1	15	how-to-tap-video-advertisings-potential	How to Tap Video Advertising's Potential	<p>Nielsen recently found that half of U.S. consumers exposed to a TV ad featuring a sports sedan recalled viewing the advertisement. More importantly, when consumers were exposed to the ad across multiple screens (TV, computer, mobile phone, and tablet), that percentage jumped to 74 percent, a 48 percent increase in ad recall. For a brand or retailer looking to drive in-store traffic, these ads can have quite an effect on brand and product preferences.</p>\r\n	<p>Nielsen recently found that half of U.S. consumers exposed to a TV ad featuring a sports sedan recalled viewing the advertisement. More importantly, when consumers were exposed to the ad across multiple screens (TV, computer, mobile phone, and tablet), that percentage jumped to 74 percent, a 48 percent increase in ad recall. For a brand or retailer looking to drive in-store traffic, these ads can have quite an effect on brand and product preferences.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nHowever, with major broadcast events, such as, the elections and the 2012 Summer Olympic Games, traditional broadcast advertising spots will be priced at a premium, leaving little opportunity for regional and local retailers and brands to get the air time they may be used to. But, millions of consumers will be tuned into online video channels for updates and coverage of these major events -- making digital video advertising an especially lucrative opportunity for retailers and brands of all sizes.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAccording to Forrester Research, U.S. online video ad spend will reach $5.4 billion by 2016 &ndash; it&rsquo;s a rising digital force that advertisers are allocating more dollars to today. Whether it&#39;s a small retailer trying to gain visibility and drive in store traffic in a local market, or a large brand looking to complement a major national campaign with a digital video campaign that gives them additional reach, the medium provides a wealth of opportunities.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe next phase in online video&#39;s expansion is in obtaining reach and relevance among the audiences that matter most. This is done by applying &quot;big data&quot; analysis or knowledge derived from large offline data sets pulled from point-of-sale information, social media, videos, music, local web pages, and online magazines. Brands and retailers armed with this information can more efficiently reach households by executing digital video campaigns, while complementing their traditional offline media plans. This approach makes it far more effective to reach the right consumer at the right time -- especially if you are looking to drive in-store traffic and sales.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn addition, advertisers now have a way to make this data actionable for the benefit of their campaigns. For instance, if a car manufacturer was looking to drive sales of a higher-end luxury car, it&#39;s unlikely that it would want to target areas that house a high population of college students. There is no need to re-invent creative either -- it can simply tailor the video used in the national spot, and have it display in targeted areas where the consumers are most likely to purchase the product live. In the case of a smaller retailer or restaurant, digital video advertising campaigns not only make advertising more attainable, but they also help to eliminate wasteful advertising spending, which is often a large line item for a small business.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIf the exponential growth of online video advertising is telling us anything, it&#39;s that it&#39;s an ever-evolving and effective medium for retailers and brands of all sizes. Whether your goal is to complement traditional offline and broadcast campaigns or to dedicate the entire budget to online video, this growing medium is fast becoming one of the most cost-effective and influential ways to reach your relevant audience and drive in-store traffic.</p>\r\n	t	2012-04-2