657	1	15	pharma-goes-digital-a-big-opportunity-for-health-marketers	Pharma Goes Digital: A Big Opportunity for Health Marketers	<p>When I&rsquo;m sick, the first place I turn to is the Internet &ndash; researching symptoms on WebMd or searching for reviews on the best drug and regiment to treat my ailments. It&rsquo;s the only place to get the best research and I&rsquo;m not alone.</p>\r\n	<p>When I&rsquo;m sick, the first place I turn to is the Internet &ndash; researching symptoms on WebMd or searching for reviews on the best drug and regiment to treat my ailments. It&rsquo;s the only place to get the best research and I&rsquo;m not alone. According to a study by the <a href="http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/3077086/t/more-people-search-health-online/#.TmZ3ZGpAL2A" target="_blank">Pew Internet &amp; American Life Project</a>, 80% of Internet users research health-related topics online (34% of this research is dedicated to over-the-counter drugs searches). With this high level of activity around health-related topics on the Internet, it becomes clear that there is a big opportunity for health marketers here. &nbsp;<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nOver the next four years, pharma ad spend is predicted to see steady growth, rising from $1.3 billion in 2010 to $1.86 billion in 2015. This puts pharma closely in parallel to the increase in expected growth of ad spend by retail and the automotive industries &ndash; predicted to capture at least 4.2% of the overall total of online ad spend in 2015. Knowing this, it&rsquo;s especially important for health marketers to use all the possible resources to find their relevant audiences and optimize campaign goals.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe ideal health advertising solution combines multiple data sources to produce a highly relevant audience. It should not rely on aggressive computer targeting methods that put privacy concerns in question.&nbsp; It should provide national coverage and scale with ease of deployment.&nbsp; In addition, it&rsquo;s important to realize that not all health marketing is the same. OTC marketers and prescription drug marketers have different concerns and need to reach customers in different ways.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAnd, rest assured, it&rsquo;s possible to achieve the above. Now you can laser target your desired audience, execute your campaign quickly and easily at scale and without privacy concerns.&nbsp; At the end of the day, it&rsquo;s all about producing measurable and maximized ROI.&nbsp; Stay tuned on the OnPoint blog for upcoming posts on the different solutions for OTC and prescription drug marketers.</p>\r\n	t	2011-09-16 15:56:09	\N	2011-09-16 15:56:09	2013-10-23 17:54:19.947276	48	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, pharma, digital advertising, ideal health advertising solution, Pew Internet & American Life Project, OTC, health marketers, prescription drug marketers, pharma online ad spending, privacy
656	1	20	new-campbell-soup-study-shows-purchase-decisions-are-made-before-the-store	New Campbell Soup Study Shows Purchase Decisions Are Made Before the Store	<p>The long-held belief that shoppers make 70% of their buying decisions at the shelf has been challenged by new research from the Campbell Soup Company.&nbsp; The study proves instead that shoppers make 80% of their decisions to fill a specific food-consumption mission <em>before</em> they enter a supermarket.</p>\r\n	<p>My husband is one of those people who sits down over a cup of coffee on a Sunday morning and contemplates meals for the week ahead.&nbsp; He methodically types out the days of the week Monday-Friday on a list on his laptop and begins selecting main courses.&nbsp; We try to keep it varied.&nbsp;&nbsp; Chicken, pasta, seafood, pork, beef in some combination with an ethnic flair &ndash; Mexican, Italian, Mediterranean, American makes for endless combinations.&nbsp; After the main course is decided, he moves onto sides like rice, bread, salads, random veggies, legumes and potatoes.&nbsp;<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nLots of things can inspire the menu, like anything from the content he consumes on sites like foodandwine.com, a recent visit to a neighborhood restaurant, or word of mouth.&nbsp; Once that is hashed out, he begins the shopping list.&nbsp; Once the shopping list is complete, it is pretty much set in stone with little room for variation while in the store (aside from our 5 year old son begging for a new cereal or other food he&rsquo;s seen advertised during morning cartoon time!)<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThis personal scenario pretty much supports the recent Campbell Soup study summarized on <a href="http://www.cpgmatters.com/instoremarketing0811.html" target="_blank">CPG Matters</a>.&nbsp; The long-held belief that shoppers make 70% of their buying decisions at the shelf has been challenged by new research from the Campbell Soup Company.&nbsp; The study proves instead that shoppers make 80% of their decisions to fill a specific food-consumption mission <em>before</em> they enter a supermarket.&nbsp; Such data leads to further assumptions that non in-store advertising has even more of an effect as previously thought.&nbsp; Certainly there is a place for in-store advertising &ndash; it does work to an extent.&nbsp; But budget savvy shoppers likely have already laid out their mission, estimated their costs, and strive to beat or meet their food budget &ndash; meaning, they are not really paying attention to anything that is not on their list.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThis study strongly supports the argument to build out-of-store advertising budgets.&nbsp; But for companies with tight financials, it is impossible to simply add money to the advertising budget, so they must shift money away from other budgets.&nbsp; Companies should be shifting these dollars from traditional promotional budgets since their targeting abilities are so limited with these traditional channels.&nbsp; The logical venue to turn to is online advertising where organizations can more accurately target their consumers with more certainty and less cost.&nbsp; A beauty of building an online advertising campaign is within the metrics.&nbsp; You will quickly know if an ad is working and if not, you can quickly make adjustments to make it more effective &ndash; something you cannot quickly do with traditional methods.</p>\r\n	t	2011-09-12 13:27:32	\N	2011-09-12 13:27:32	2013-10-23 17:56:22.882304	50	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, Lynn Vitello, Campbell Soup, Campbell Soup study, online advertising, purchase behavior, purchase decisions, shopping, retail, shopping lists
890	1	37	in-flight-mobile-advertising-not-ready-for-takeoff	In-Flight Mobile Advertising: Not Ready for Takeoff	<p>New guidelines allow airline passengers to use mobile devices throughout the flight. But advertisers shouldn&#39;t get too excited...</p>\r\n	<p><img alt="mobile phone on plane" src="/system/editor/W1siZiIsIjIwMTMvMTEvMjcvMTNfMzVfMzFfMzI2X01vYmlsZV9waG9uZV9vbl9wbGFuZS5qcGciXSxbInAiLCJ0aHVtYiIsIjgwMHg4MDA%2BIl1d/Mobile%20phone%20on%20plane.jpg" style="border-style:solid; border-width:0px; float:right; height:250px; margin:5px 10px; width:377px" />Thanksgiving is just around the corner. People will be traveling all over the country, visiting family and friends in time for turkey. And for the first time, new guidelines from the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) will allow airline travelers to use approved electronic devices through the duration of the flight.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At first glance, some advertisers <a href="http://www.mobilemarketer.com/cms/news/strategy/16521.html" target="_blank">were excited at the possibility</a> of reaching more shoppers while they&rsquo;re on planes. However, the new guidelines offer more hype than hope for advertisers this holiday season.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>First, the new rules don&rsquo;t really add much to the current online environment. They won&rsquo;t make more people hop on the Wi-Fi on the planes, and they only add a few extra minutes for those who already surf the web while in the skies. The new rules might be more convenient for frequent fliers, but they&rsquo;ll make little difference for advertisers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Second, you won&rsquo;t reach enough shoppers to really make a large sales difference. The FAA guidelines still require that phones be placed on airplane mode, meaning that most travelers won&rsquo;t have web access while on the flight.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But what about Wi-Fi access provided by the airlines? Well, many planes aren&rsquo;t Wi-Fi enabled. However, even among those who fly on Wi-Fi planes, only 6% will pay the fee to use the service.<a href="#_ftn1" name="_ftnref1" title="">[1]</a> Many who do opt for in-flight wireless access could be focusing on work or checking email rather than shopping.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Third, you still need to consider the best practices for ad personalization and audience intelligence. Even though passengers are on the same plane, that doesn&rsquo;t necessarily mean they&rsquo;re interested in the same products and services. On any flight, you&rsquo;ll reach a broad audience with diverse tastes&mdash;for example, some prefer to eat fast food in the airport while others seek out a nice restaurant near their hotel. With so little insight into the passengers on a flight, you&rsquo;ll end up wasting a lot of your budget on the wrong target audience.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Your better bet when targeting customers is to focus on their points of origin. People who choose to live in a certain neighborhood share quite a bit in common&mdash;they often have similar demographics, share interests, shop at the same stores, and have overlapping purchases. Armed with the right neighborhood intelligence, you can reach the perfect customers at a scale that really makes a difference. Most airline passengers share little in common with their fellow travelers other than their destinations. You&rsquo;ll waste a lot of impressions trying to target any specific audience on a plane. When it comes to targeting the right customers, it doesn&rsquo;t matter where they currently are&mdash;it matters where they come from.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>One common example mentioned when talking about in-flight advertising is for rental car companies. This seems like an excellent use case&mdash;the rental company could advertise to a captive audience in the air that might need to book a rental car. However, this example breaks down upon closer examination.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Many travelers will be heading to places where transportation will already be provided by their families, friends, or employers. And those fliers who will rent cars at their destinations will often have already booked their reservations before they reach the airport. Once they&rsquo;re on the plane, they&rsquo;re unlikely to be strong prospects.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So if a rental car service really wants to personalize its message to the right shoppers, it should use neighborhood-level targeting to tailor its message based on its intended audience. For example, the company could promote SUVs and minivans to neighborhoods that over-index for the presence of children and it could advertise luxury cars to people living in high-income neighborhoods. By segmenting its ad buys, the rental car company can reach the perfect shoppers and keep its ad waste to a minimum.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For digital advertisers, the in-flight audience is just too broad to be an efficient media spend. And with so few passengers opting to use Wi-Fi, you&rsquo;ll have a hard time reaching customers at a meaningful scale. In short, if you want to really boost your sales, you should keep your digital advertising on the ground.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>1. <a href="http://www.businessinsider.com/the-new-faa-device-rules-for-mobile-marketing-2013-11" target="_blank">http://www.businessinsider.com/the-new-faa-device-rules-for-mobile-marketing-2013-11 </a></p>\r\n	t	2013-11-27 19:31:30	\N	2013-11-27 19:34:18.814007	2013-11-27 19:37:20.703266	59	\N
