669	1	15	where-have-all-the-cookies-gone-2	Where Have All the Cookies Gone?	<p>Where have all the cookies gone? Well, for starters, they haven&rsquo;t gone anywhere&hellip;yet.&nbsp; They are still sitting with those big companies whose main business is the reselling of cookie data to different online advertising companies, who utilize them when targeting consumers at that level. Problem? Potentially, yes.&nbsp; &nbsp;</p>\r\n	<p>Where have all the cookies gone? Well, for starters, they haven&rsquo;t gone anywhere&hellip;yet.&nbsp; They are still sitting with those big companies whose main business is the reselling of cookie data to different online advertising companies, who utilize them when targeting consumers at that level. Problem? Potentially, yes.&nbsp; &nbsp;<!--more--></p>\r\n\r\n<p>All of this new legislation coming down the pike may, in fact, pose a great problem for those digital advertising companies who rely so heavily upon cookie data.&nbsp; What&rsquo;s an advertiser to do, then, if their primary partners&rsquo; basic methodology for efficient targeting goes by the wayside?<br />\r\n<br />\r\nLong before the &ldquo;cookie issue&rdquo; was at the forefront of our industry, we have been targeting consumers at the neighborhood level, serving them ads that are relevant and actionable while, at the same time, respecting their privacy.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nJust recently AdAge had an article, <a href="http://adage.com/article/digitalnext/brands-win-respecting-online-privacy/228828/" target="_blank">How Brands Can Win By Respecting Your Online Privacy</a>, highlighting this very issue. One key takeaway&hellip; &ldquo;Ask [consumers] how they feel about the fact that their online activity is tracked by a series of companies they&#39;ve probably never heard of and have no direct relationship with, and then sold without their knowledge or consent to advertisers&rdquo; directly addresses this issue in a frank manner.&nbsp; We would doubt that the average person would be willing to share that information with a nameless third party without consent.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOur solution to this is to serve ads at the neighborhood level, thereby taking away the &ldquo;one to one&rdquo; advertising methodology that naturally lends itself to privacy concerns.&nbsp; In doing so, we take away the granular personal information that may be gleaned (or feared) when using cookies while still meeting and exceeding the metrics of success defined by our clients.</p>\r\n	t	2011-10-07 21:33:14	\N	2011-10-07 21:33:14	2013-11-06 19:45:05.123481	49	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, Andrea Berkman, cookies, neighborhood targeting, digital advertising, online privacy, AdAge, Digital Zip 
670	1	15	out-with-the-old-in-with-the-new-why-traditional-ad-budgets-should-be-allocated-for-digital-2	Out with the Old, In with the New: Why Traditional Ad Budgets Should be Allocated for Digital	<p>Change is sometimes difficult to accept, but change can be a good thing. Otherwise, we would still be carrying around 3 pound portable phones and wishing our dial-up connection would hurry up. But, if change is good, then why are marketers still relying heavily on&nbsp; traditional advertising methods when advertising has gone digital?</p>\r\n	<p>Change is sometimes difficult to accept, but change can be a good thing. Otherwise, we would still be carrying around 3 pound portable phones and wishing our dial-up connection would hurry up. But, if change is good, then why are marketers still relying heavily on&nbsp; traditional advertising methods when advertising has gone digital?<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nAdvertisers and brands really need to re-think online advertising as a way to effectively reach their audiences. Today, most consumers live in the digital space, receiving their news and connecting with friends online. In fact, digital is the number one way to reach a broad (and highly demanded) demographic: 18-54 year olds. Relying upon the Internet more and more to receive and gather information, consumers have indeed turned into &ldquo;digital consumers&rdquo;.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAccording to U.S. Census data, 75 percent of consumer spending occurs within 15 miles of the average American&#39;s home; meaning that 50 percent of the nation&#39;s GDP is dependent on consumers buying locally. With these statistics in mind, it&rsquo;s important for brick-and-mortar businesses and the brands within them to connect with consumers in order to drive in-store activity. Unfortunately, the standard methods of reaching local audiences through advertising for the last six decades &ndash; local newspaper, TV and radio ads, direct mail and/or Free Standing Inserts (FSIs) &ndash; just aren&#39;t as effective anymore.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nDespite the obvious reasons why traditional methods may not be as strong as they used to be, a significant imbalance still exists in terms of retailers&rsquo; and brands&rsquo; ad spending, with online still a distant third to TV and print. To highlight this issue more specifically, consider that consumers spend 12% of their time consuming print media; yet, 26% of the typical ad budget is still spent on print media. In addition, the budget currently spent online is actually not highly targeted enough to successfully drive people through the doors of a store. Spending that same budget online, with effective targeting, can drive traffic into stores where purchases are made. Consumers usually research a store online before visiting the store, so it is imperative to have the right presence online. Effectively reach consumers online; effectively drive in-store traffic.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThere are a few things advertising and brands should keep in mind when using online advertising. Specifically, it is the scale and reach, cost-effectiveness, speed and flexibility of digital that enables advertisers to accomplish goals print cannot. When you take into account the average CPM of digital (~$5) vs. print (~$17), you immediately see a huge cost and reach advantage. Plus, digital intrinsically offers greater flexibility for your campaign. You can start and stop it as needed. You can even target different ads to different neighborhoods around the country. And this all comes with much shorter insertion lead times (e.g., minutes vs. weeks).Furthermore, with print, advertisers have to guess what ads will work and what ads will not. With online, advertisers can change campaigns on the fly, better aligning with consumer interests and hot selling products in the store.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAvoid the same classic media mix of newspaper, radio and television advertising. Once you&rsquo;ve reconciled the imbalance in the media mix with the actual rates of digital media consumption by today&rsquo;s consumer, you can properly target your digital ads and see an immediate and measurable lift in product sales and increased engagement. See, change is good, so what are you waiting for?<br />\r\n<br />\r\nFor more stats on digital, check out these resources below:<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<a href="http://www.emarketer.com/Article.aspx?R=1008509" target="_blank">Options for Online Video Ad Viewers Lead to Greater Engagement</a>, via eMarketer<br />\r\n<a href="http://mashable.com/2011/07/05/online-ad-spending-50-bilion/" target="_blank">Online Ad Spending Set to Hit $50B in 2015</a>, via Mashable</p>\r\n	t	2011-10-07 21:45:45	\N	2011-10-07 21:45:45	2013-10-23 17:40:39.672405	50	digital advertising, traditional advertising, MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, ad spending, digital, digital consumers, in-store traffic, eMarketer, Mashable, digital vs. traditional
668	1	20	retailers-dont-limit-yourself-to-coupons-creative-online-strategies-to-drive-in-store-sales-2	Retailers, Don't Limit Yourself to Coupons! Creative Online Strategies to Drive In-Store Sales	<p>Don&rsquo;t get me wrong.&nbsp; I love coupons.&nbsp; Call it competitive, but if someone else is getting a lower price for the same product, then I want that same price too.&nbsp; In fact, coupons are one of the most effective methods of driving in-store sales. &nbsp;</p>\r\n	<p>Don&rsquo;t get me wrong.&nbsp; I love coupons.&nbsp; Call it competitive, but if someone else is getting a lower price for the same product, then I want that same price too.&nbsp; In fact, coupons are one of the most effective methods of driving in-store sales. &nbsp;<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nAccording to the Annual Topline U.S. <a href="http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/value-centric-shoppers-save-37-billion-in-2010-using-coupons-114281974.html" target="_blank">CPG Coupon Facts Report</a> for Year-end 2010, shoppers saved $3.7 billion with coupons in 2010. That is an impressive number indicating the state of our economy and how people are trying to get the most from their hard-earned dollar.&nbsp; However, value lies not only in coupon discounts.&nbsp; There is also a huge and underutilized opportunity for brick-and-mortar merchants to advertise promotional offers &ndash; especially offers that cannot be executed by &ldquo;etailers&rdquo;.&nbsp; Merchants need to focus on the unique experience they can provide in their physical location that etailers cannot.&nbsp; Strategic and creative thinking about other online advertising promotions beyond coupons to drive in-store sales can place you well ahead of your competitors.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nFor example, a local neighborhood gift boutique retailer launched an online ad campaign for a &ldquo;ladies night out.&rdquo;&nbsp; I discovered this as I was searching for things to do with my girlfriends this weekend in my local area.&nbsp; The ad promised free drinks, appetizers, entertainment and an invitation for a sneak preview of a new clothing store located next door to this gift boutique.&nbsp; They offered the opportunity to try on their new line of designer jeans and casual wear.&nbsp; Nothing beats a couple of drinks while trying on clothes with your girlfriends.&nbsp; Based on the turnout and number of bags being carried out of the stores, it was a win-win for both retailers.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAnother great promotion that recently caught my attention as a mom of a 5-year old was a neighborhood-area restaurant advertising Sundays as kids eat free and entertainment provided by a magician.&nbsp; I happened to be searching for &ldquo;kids eat free&rdquo; local coupons online when this ad showed up.&nbsp; No coupon needed AND free table-side entertainment for the family.&nbsp;&nbsp; It was a very enjoyable evening with my family.&nbsp; It worked out well for the magician too.&nbsp; He was so great with kids that we booked him for our son&rsquo;s birthday party!<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThese are just a couple of creative examples of online advertising promotions that drove in-store sales in specific neighborhoods without the use of coupons.&nbsp; Online advertisers who creatively go beyond print and digital coupons to get consumers to eat and shop locally really do win.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nBe creative.&nbsp; Be strategic.&nbsp; Be successful.</p>\r\n	t	2011-10-07 21:22:57	\N	2011-10-07 21:22:57	2013-10-23 17:45:04.543299	49	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, Lynn Vitello, Coupons, in-store sales, retailers, CPG Coupon Facts Report, brick-and-mortar, etailers
672	1	15	effective-online-advertising-consumer-privacy-can-both-be-achieved-without-sacrificing-the-other-2	Effective Online Advertising & Consumer Privacy: Can Both be Achieved Without Sacrificing the Other?	<p>The opportunity the digital world gives businesses to reach and connect with consumers is limitless. Brands have social media accounts that invite consumer engagement, digital coupons can be downloaded in an instant and the space to serve ads can be used for the most creative of campaigns. Unfortunately, this tremendous opportunity to connect with consumers is strained due to the issue of consumer privacy.</p>\r\n	<p>The opportunity the digital world gives businesses to reach and connect with consumers is limitless. Brands have social media accounts that invite consumer engagement, digital coupons can be downloaded in an instant and the space to serve ads can be used for the most creative of campaigns. Unfortunately, this tremendous opportunity to connect with consumers is strained due to the issue of consumer privacy.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nData is a fundamental part of marketing campaigns, and data tracking has been an even more fundamental part of how most online campaigns are executed. Take display ads for instance, data identifies who (consumers) visit certain sites most frequently, identifies trends and then uses data collected about consumer behavior (without the consumer knowing) to target more ads. According to a <a href="http://www.netmining.com/pdf/Netmining-Mapping-Digital-Display-Landscape.pdf" target="_blank">post</a> in Netmining, a marketer can target a consumer on a website who display certain behaviors when visiting that website &ndash; i.e. you ditch your shopping cart and then the marketer invites you to free shipping and to continue with your purchase. Third party data collected on consumers (demographic, psychographic, purchase history, etc) is also frequently used to compile &ldquo;cookie pools&rdquo; which then implements a cookie to follow and track a consumer online. Ultimately, once a consumer clicks on ad, they are finding less ways to opt out.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAnd, consumers are finally speaking up. Recently, the Federal Trade Commission started looking into potentially regulating online marketing. The issues surrounding consumer privacy are regarded as &ldquo;unfair or deceptive acts or practices&rdquo; and is suggested that companies, in particular high tech companies, do not take the FTC guidance about consumer privacy lightly.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nBut, if leveraging data helps marketers target the right customers to serve a relevant ad, what&rsquo;s a marketer to do? Fear not, at MaxPoint we serve relevant ads to the right consumers at the right time, while also supporting consumer privacy. How? Our technology does not collect personally identifiable information (PII) but yet still serves micro-targeted ads to relevant consumers that meet our client metrics. Read more about the solution <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/onpoint-blog/2011/10/7/where-have-all-the-cookies-gone-2" target="_blank">here</a>.</p>\r\n	t	2011-10-07 22:05:27	\N	2011-10-07 22:05:27	2013-11-01 21:35:46.312308	49	digital, online advertising, consumer privacy, data, campaigns, data tracking, display ads, Netmining, cookies, FTC, MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint
891	1	10	lets-get-real-about-real-time	Let’s Get Real about Real Time	<p>Real-time advertising is alive and well&mdash;learn why the criticisms of real-time advertising might just be myths.</p>\r\n	<p><img alt="Clock" src="/system/editor/W1siZiIsIjIwMTMvMTIvMDUvMTRfMjZfMDJfOTgxX2lTdG9ja18wMDAwMDc3MTk2MzZTbWFsbC5qcGciXSxbInAiLCJ0aHVtYiIsIjgwMHg4MDA%2BIl1d/iStock_000007719636Small.jpg" style="float:right; height:200px; margin-left:25px; margin-right:25px; width:300px" />At the 2013 Super Bowl, Oreo put real-time advertising on the map. When the lights went down and Oreo tweeted a relevant display ad within minutes, it set a new ideal for brands. As a result, many heralded 2013 as the year of real-time advertising.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, several recent articles (such as these from <a href="http://adage.com/article/special-report-advertising-week-2013/5-hyped-trends-big-hits-advertising-week/244410/" target="_blank">Advertising Age</a> and <a href="http://digiday.com/brands/brands-killed-real-time-marketing/?utm_source=Sailthru&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_term=Digiday%20Brands%20Newsletter&amp;utm_campaign=Brands_Sailthru_July2013" target="_blank">Digiday</a>) have highlighted some problems with real-time advertising. Some have gone so far as to say that the real-time advertising trend is dead. However, this pronouncement is premature. Today, I want to address two key myths about real-time advertising. &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Myth 1: Real-Time Advertising Is Too Resource Intensive</strong><br />\r\nMany believe that real-time advertising requires excessive planning and resources. The thought here is that to respond to a major cultural event such as the Oscars or the Super Bowl, a brand must have its creative agency on call to quickly cook up an advertisement and must have its executives at the ready to review and approve. However, this view of real-time misses the bigger picture.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For example, let&rsquo;s say that a major fast food chain wants to create a real-time ad to boost sales in the cities for teams in the MLB World Series. It could create two separate digital banner ads that congratulate each team for the win. Once the Series concludes, the advertiser could post its congratulations to the winning team and offer a special deal for anyone who comes into the restaurant wearing their team&rsquo;s hat. This would be a perfectly relevant real-time advertisement that would boost sales and improve the brand&rsquo;s perception among baseball fans, and it would only require a little prior planning. And with the right targeting technology, the chain can ensure that it reaches the right neighborhoods with the right fans. It&rsquo;s real-time advertising without the real-time headache.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Myth 2: Real-Time Ads Aren&rsquo;t Successful</strong><br />\r\nMany see Oreo&rsquo;s advertisement as a success because of the press it generated for the brand. But few know whether or not the advertisement increased brand perception or moved more cookies. Without this knowledge, it&rsquo;s difficult to say whether or not Oreo&rsquo;s ad was successful.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Real-time advertising campaigns don&rsquo;t need to get a lot of press or latch onto a major national event to produce strong sales for a retailer; they only need to be relevant. For example, a pharmacy selling allergy remedies can use weather data to serve ads in locations with higher pollen counts during allergy season. This won&rsquo;t generate the buzz that Oreo received around the Super Bowl, but it will certainly sell more remedies to allergy sufferers looking for relief.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Truth: Real-Time Advertising Can Be Easy and Successful</strong><br />\r\nThe truth is that real-time advertising can be both relatively easy to implement and extremely successful. For example, let&rsquo;s say that you&rsquo;re advertising for a restaurant. You can simply prep a few ads in advance and serve them based on weather patterns. In areas where the weather is cold or snowing, you could run an ad for chili or soup with the headline, &ldquo;Snowing? Warm up with a nice bowl of hot soup.&rdquo; Alternately, when the weather is extremely warm, you could appeal to shoppers with an ad that says, &ldquo;Cool off from this heat wave with a nice bowl of ice cream.&rdquo; All it takes is a little planning combined with the right technology that can help you adapt to local weather patterns.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You may not receive major press attention with this approach. But you&rsquo;ll get sales, and you&rsquo;ll improve your brand perception among your target audience. Real-time advertising fulfills the basic promise of advertising&mdash;to connect brands with the right customers in the right locations at the right time. That&rsquo;s every advertiser&rsquo;s dream, isn&rsquo;t it?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Have you tried any form of real-time or time-sensitive advertising? If so, tell us about it in the comments.</p>\r\n	t	2013-12-05 19:48:21	\N	2013-12-05 19:53:23.402102	2013-12-11 17:49:10.830048	63	\N
893	1	50	maxpoint-classes-up-classrooms-for-children-this-holiday-season	MaxPoint Classes Up Classrooms for Children This Holiday Season	<p>The MaxPoint team recently spiced up the classrooms at the John Avery Boys &amp; Girls Club of Durham. Read this post to see how it all turned out.&nbsp;</p>\r\n	<p>Every year, I look forward to the MaxPoint end-of-year party. After working hard for 12 months, the entire company comes together to relax, dance, and let loose with our co-workers. But over the past few years, we have also had the chance to give back to the community by volunteering for the John Avery Boys &amp; Girls Club of Durham. Last year, we assembled bikes as gifts for children; this year, we stepped it up a notch by helping them redesign their classrooms.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Now, if you&rsquo;ve ever met a MaxPointer, you&rsquo;ll realize how competitive we get. Whenever a few of us gather, it&rsquo;s simply a matter of time before someone decides to turn it into a competition. As a result, we decided to divide the company into teams that would compete for the award of the best-designed classroom (naturally, my team won).</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Planning the Event:</strong><br />\r\nA few weeks before the event, I traveled with a teammate to the Boys &amp; Girls Club to scope out the classrooms. The room was fairly well organized, but could definitely use some additional decorations to spice things up:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Surveying the classroom</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="Before Photo" src="/system/editor/W1siZiIsIjIwMTMvMTIvMTkvMDlfNTlfMDBfNjRfSU1HXzA2MjFfNTE4eDM0NS5wbmciXSxbInAiLCJ0aHVtYiIsIjgwMHg4MDA%2BIl1d/IMG_0621_518x345.png" style="float:left; height:266px; width:400px" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>When we returned, we called a meeting to walk the group through the space so we could develop our plan of attack. The entire team worked together to plan the space and purchase the decorations. One teammate even consulted with his teenaged daughter for some design ideas (she decided on a disco ball). After the meeting, we just had to order the supplies and wait for the big day.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Designing on a Dime:</strong><br />\r\nWhen we arrived, we gathered together in the gym. Because we were assigned to the teenager room, we named our team Smells Like Team Spirit:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Arriving in style</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="Arriving in Style" src="/system/editor/W1siZiIsIjIwMTMvMTIvMTkvMTBfMDFfMzdfMzIyX0lNR18wNzk2X1VwZGF0ZWRfMjY2eDMyOS5wbmciXSxbInAiLCJ0aHVtYiIsIjgwMHg4MDA%2BIl1d/IMG_0796-Updated_266x329.png" style="float:left; height:329px; width:266px" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Next, we went to our room and immediately rolled up our sleeves. My teammates put me on sweeping duty:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Cleaning the floors</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="Cleaning the floors" src="/system/editor/W1siZiIsIjIwMTMvMTIvMTkvMTBfMDJfNTVfMjE1X0lNR18wOTQ0X1VwZGF0ZWRfNDE0eDM0NS5wbmciXSxbInAiLCJ0aHVtYiIsIjgwMHg4MDA%2BIl1d/IMG_0944-Updated_414x345.png" style="float:left; height:292px; width:350px" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Others worked on hanging some lights or installing mirrors on the wall:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Hanging lights</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="Hanging the Lights" src="/system/editor/W1siZiIsIjIwMTMvMTIvMTkvMTBfMDNfNTZfMjkyX0lNR18wOTQ3XzM0Nng1MTkucG5nIl0sWyJwIiwidGh1bWIiLCI4MDB4ODAwPiJdXQ/IMG_0947_346x519.png" style="float:left; height:399px; width:266px" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Putting up mirrors</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="Hanging the Mirror" src="/system/editor/W1siZiIsIjIwMTMvMTIvMTkvMTBfMDVfMjhfNDAwX0lNR18xMDA5XzUxOHgzNDUucG5nIl0sWyJwIiwidGh1bWIiLCI4MDB4ODAwPiJdXQ/IMG_1009_518x345.png" style="float:left; height:233px; width:350px" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>We had a little help from Eric, the teacher from the Boys &amp; Girls Club. He gave us some great tips on what would resonate most with the kids. However, I think the best part of having him there was being able to see his reaction as the room began to come together.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The entire redesign took about only four hours, but the results were dramatic:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Our team gathers in the completed room</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="Team Photo" src="/system/editor/W1siZiIsIjIwMTMvMTIvMTkvMTBfMDZfMDlfODU1X0lNR18xMDUzXzUxOHgzNDUucG5nIl0sWyJwIiwidGh1bWIiLCI4MDB4ODAwPiJdXQ/IMG_1053_518x345.png" style="float:left; height:233px; width:350px" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Spending time with the kids</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="Spending time with the kids" src="/system/editor/W1siZiIsIjIwMTMvMTIvMTkvMTBfMDdfMzFfOTk1X0lNR18xMTQ1XzUxOHgzNDUucG5nIl0sWyJwIiwidGh1bWIiLCI4MDB4ODAwPiJdXQ/IMG_1145_518x345.png" style="float:left; height:233px; width:350px" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>I asked Monica Wood, one of my fellow team members, what she thought about the entire project. &ldquo;This was the best volunteer experience I&rsquo;ve ever had. It&rsquo;s rewarding to be able to see the difference you make when you volunteer. Frankly, I teared up a few times.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I share Monica&rsquo;s sentiments. It&rsquo;s always great to make a difference, but it&rsquo;s even better to be able to see the effect of your work. Of course, it&rsquo;s also fun to take a break and play some games with the kids:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Playing Connect Four</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="Connect Four" src="/system/editor/W1siZiIsIjIwMTMvMTIvMTkvMTBfMDhfNTBfNjA1X0lNR18xMDI2X1VwZGF0ZWRfNTE4eDM0NS5wbmciXSxbInAiLCJ0aHVtYiIsIjgwMHg4MDA%2BIl1d/IMG_1026-Updated_518x345.png" style="float:left; height:233px; width:350px" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>A Surprise Announcement:</strong><br />\r\nAt the end of the day, we gathered in the gym to find out which team won the contest. But Joe Epperson, MaxPoint&rsquo;s CEO, had a better surprise for us&mdash;he announced that MaxPoint would be sponsoring the <a href="http://bgca.org/ClubTech/ClubTech/Pages/ClubTech.aspx" target="_blank">Club Tech program</a> in 2014. Throughout the next year, MaxPoint will provide funds for equipment and field trips, and MaxPoint employees will donate their time to help the kids explore careers in technology. &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ultimately, I had a blast. I got a chance to work with fellow MaxPointers from across the nation who I don&rsquo;t frequently see, and I was able to see the effects of my work on the kids and the teachers at the club. And honestly, I can&rsquo;t wait to see what we get to do next year!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Visit our <a href="https://www.facebook.com/pages/MaxPoint-Interactive/275921092465603" target="_blank">Facebook page</a> to see more photos from the event.</p>\r\n	t	2013-12-19 14:17:53	\N	2013-12-19 14:20:10.812403	2013-12-19 16:22:39.574339	47	\N
692	1	15	maxpoints-top-ten-digital-resources	MaxPoint's Top Ten Digital Resources	<p>We love to share the latest digital advertising news with our blog subscribers and Twitter followers. But, where do we get our news? If it&rsquo;s not thought leadership from our Executive team, we often turn to these resources.</p>\r\n	<p>We love to share the latest digital advertising news with our blog subscribers and Twitter followers. But, where do we get our news? If it&rsquo;s not thought leadership from our Executive team, we often turn to these resources.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<a href="http://adage.com/" target="_blank"><strong>Advertising Age</strong></a><br />\r\nAdvertising Age is the leading global source of news, intelligence and conversation for marketing and media communities. The multiple blogs and columnists cover the latest industry trends and topics ranging from digital to marketing statistics and campaign news.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<a href="http://www.adweek.com/" target="_blank"><strong>AdWeek</strong></a><br />\r\nAdWeek is an insightful, forward-thinking magazine that appeals to consumers and advertising professional alike. It provides a regional focus on advertising industry&rsquo;s creative process, account changes, and decision makers.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<a href="http://allthingsd.com/" target="_blank"><strong>All Things D</strong></a><br />\r\nAllThingsD.com is a website devoted to news, analysis and opinion on technology, the Internet and media. It is a fusion of different media styles, different topics, different formats and different sources. The site offers lots of opinion and analysis, but plenty of industry facts as well.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<a href="http://www.cynopsis.com/" target="_blank"><strong>Cynopsis: Digital</strong></a><br />\r\nThe goal of Cynopsis: Digital is to help readers stay up-to-date with the rapidly ever-changing digital platform. It is a must read for people in content, distribution, technology, ad sales and creative services. Cynoposis: Digital helps make sense of this landscape, reporting on the latest trends and newest innovations in this space.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<a href="http://www.emarketer.com/" target="_blank"><strong>eMarketer</strong></a><br />\r\neMarketer publishes data, analysis and insights on digital marketing, media and commerce. eMarketer&#39;s analyst reports, articles, charts, case studies, interviews, comparative estimates and forecasts help you focus on what matters in the digital world, and equally important, what doesn&#39;t.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<a href="http://www.imediaconnection.com/" target="_blank"><strong>iMedia&nbsp; Connection</strong></a><br />\r\nThe iMedia Connection and ad:tech blog share news and features covering the online marketing sector.&nbsp; iMedia news inspires marketers of all types to explore and embrace interactive marketing strategies.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<a href="http://mashable.com/" target="_blank"><strong>Mashable</strong></a><br />\r\nMashable&rsquo;s mission is to empower and inspire people by spreading knowledge of social media and technology. It is the largest independent news source dedicated to covering digital culture, social media and technology.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<a href="http://www.mediapost.com/" target="_blank"><strong>MediaPost</strong></a><br />\r\nMediaPost Communications is an integrated publishing and content company whose mission is to provide a complete array of resources for media, marketing and advertising professionals. News and blogs help readers better plan both traditional and online advertising.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<a href="http://www.nytimes.com/pages/business/media/index.html" target="_blank"><strong>New York Times: Media &amp; Advertising</strong></a><br />\r\nThe New York Times: Media &amp; Advertising news section is devoted to sharing coverage on news from the advertising industry to industry transitions and insider reports/opinions on campaigns and the latest media trends.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<a href="http://online.wsj.com/public/page/news-media-marketing.html" target="_blank"><strong>Wall Street Journal: Media &amp; Marketing</strong></a><br />\r\nGet the latest media agency and marketing news on Wall Street Journal&rsquo;s online Media &amp; Marketing news section. Topics range from viral video ads and advertising promotions to marketing strategies and the latest web trends.</p>\r\n	t	2011-12-01 14:00:12	\N	2011-12-01 14:00:12	2013-10-03 00:12:15.024364	51	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, digital advertising, resources, news, digital advertising resources, top ten, digital, Advertising Age, AdWeek, All Things D, Cynopsis Digital, eMarketer, iMedia Connection, Mashable, MediaPost, New York Times: Media & Advertising, Wall Street Journal: Media & Marketing      
681	1	15	qr-codes-the-good-and-the-bad	QR Codes - The Good and The Bad	<p>Once you&rsquo;ve noticed them, you realize QR codes are nearly everywhere.&nbsp; Just today I&rsquo;ve seen them on business cards, the packaging for my shampoo, TV, the newspaper, and on billboards. These 2-dimensional barcodes are incredibly versatile - and, they are opening lots of doors for advertisers!</p>\r\n	<p>Once you&rsquo;ve noticed them, you realize QR codes are nearly everywhere.&nbsp; Just today I&rsquo;ve seen them on business cards, the packaging for my shampoo, TV, the newspaper, and on billboards. These 2-dimensional barcodes are incredibly versatile - and, they are opening lots of doors for advertisers! There are many ways to use QR codes to engage and connect with your audience.&nbsp; You can further your consumers&rsquo; brand experience by allowing them to access a website, make a phone call, or view a video right from the camera on their smart phone. <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhile QR codes have already made a name, they are still relatively new to the U.S. It&rsquo;s hard to say if they are around to stay but they certainly have lots of potential. This is what I&rsquo;ve observed so far.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>The Good</strong><br />\r\nQR codes relieve a lot of the hassle of real-time engagement &ndash; there&rsquo;s no more typing in a long URL or SMS code. They&rsquo;re a quick, error-free scan! Once consumers have a QR reader application downloaded to their phone, they can begin to learn more about what you have to offer, interact with you, or explore your products. QR codes provide trackable results. You can see how many people are engaging with your campaign/ brand in real-time.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMore importantly, QR codes can assist with in-store shopping, with the goal of driving in-store sales. For example, cooking stores use QR codes to assist shoppers in their purchase decisions. The barcode is placed on certain products for shoppers to scan and find relevant recipes they can make with the cooking product. According to an article in <a href="http://www.dmnews.com/qr-codes-enhance-the-in-store-experience/article/201338/">Direct Marketing News</a>, you can&rsquo;t always rely on a store employee to be right there to answer questions and sales displays do not say everything. QR codes can address this issue.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>The Bad</strong><br />\r\nQR codes do require an internet connection - and preferably a fast one. Many users may lose patience waiting for the scan to happen on a shaky 3G signal. However, the biggest downside to QR codes right now isn&rsquo;t the lack of signal, but the lack of people who are familiar with them. comScore estimates around 14 million people have scanned a QR code, but that&rsquo;s actually only about 6.2% of US mobile users.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWant to know more about creative ways to use QR codes? Click <a href="http://www.fastcompany.com/1720193/13-creative-ways-to-use-qr-codes-for-marketing" target="_blank">here</a>.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWant to make your own QR code? Try this <a href="http://quikqr.com/?p=qr-code-faq" target="_blank">generator</a>.</p>\r\n	t	2011-10-31 13:00:32	\N	2011-10-31 13:00:32	2013-10-23 16:57:31.516832	49	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, Lora Edwards, QR codes, Direct Marketing News, QR code advantages, QR code disadvantages, comScore, in-store shopping
683	1	20	guilt-humor-in-advertising-works-for-cvspharmacy	Guilt, Humor in Advertising Works for CVS/pharmacy	<p>Even when we are loyal to a specific retailer, we don&rsquo;t always redeem spending rewards before they expire.&nbsp; It happens with many retailer&rsquo;s rewards, but CVS/pharmacy is tackling the issue with guilt, humor and a little peer pressure.</p>\r\n	<p>We are inundated every day with offers to save money; coupons, e-offers, social media, reward cards, and direct mail to name a few.&nbsp; How many do you actually redeem?&nbsp; It depends on whether the sender&rsquo;s offer truly targets their audience.&nbsp; A lot of times, retailers blindly send mass offers in hopes it will hit someone, but most are discarded, deleted or ignored.&nbsp; Even when we are loyal to a specific retailer, we don&rsquo;t always redeem spending rewards before they expire.&nbsp; For example, my husband often gets $5 rewards from Ace Hardware, but if he doesn&rsquo;t need anything for a couple of weeks, he ends up not using it prior to its expiration.&nbsp; It happens with many retailer&rsquo;s rewards, but CVS/pharmacy is tackling the issue with guilt, humor and a little peer pressure.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn&nbsp;a Retailing Today article <a href="http://www.retailingtoday.com/article/cvspharmacy-continues-fight-against-money-trashing" target="_blank">CVS/pharmacy continues fight against &#39;money trashing&#39;</a>, CVS/pharmacy said that it is expanding its successful <a href="http://www.cvs.com/moneytrashers/" target="_blank">&quot;MoneyTrashers&quot;</a> campaign associated with the ExtraCare rewards card by adding new digital resources to CVS.com and the CVS/pharmacy Facebook page.&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhat is a &ldquo;MoneyTrasher&rdquo; you ask? They are people like my husband who throw away earned reward money by not using it in time. The drug store chain said that both sites now feature new humorous videos showing shoppers all the ways they can remember to not be a &quot;MoneyTrasher.&quot;&nbsp; To add to the success of the campaign, shoppers can declare their commitment against &quot;MoneyTrashing&quot; by taking a digital pledge to not be a MoneyTrasher. The first 500,000 pledge registrants will automatically receive $2 ExtraBucks rewards.&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIt won&rsquo;t end there.&nbsp; CVS/pharmacy customer relationship management VP Melissa Studzinski hinted at another phase of the campaign where customers are enlisted to teach their friends and family to stop &#39;trashing&#39; their ExtraBucks rewards, too.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nBy poking fun at MoneyTrashers, guilting them into using their earned rewards, and using peer pressure, I expect CVS/pharmacy&nbsp;sees a spike in store sales as people are reminded not to waste their hard earned dough.&nbsp; Further more, the campaign supports continued customer loyalty in a very competitive market with multiple drug stores in just about every neighborhood in the US.&nbsp; Kudos to CVS/pharmacy for the creativity!</p>\r\n	t	2011-11-07 14:40:34	\N	2011-11-07 14:40:34	2013-10-11 16:57:45.986288	49	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, Lynn Vitello, pharmacy, CVS, Money Trashers, campaign, digital campaign, advertising, rewards, Retailing Today, Melissa Studzinkski
682	1	15	maxpoint-interactive-encourages-retailers-and-brands-to-localize-digital-advertising-efforts-in-final-72-hours-of-holiday-shopping-season	MaxPoint Encourages Retailers and Brands to Localize Digital Advertising Efforts in Final 72 Hours of Holiday Shopping Season	<p>For retailers and brands, the holiday shopping season can amount up to 40% of retailer&rsquo;s annual sales. More importantly, it is the critical 72 hours before the end of the holiday shopping season where retailers and brands can drive high in-store sales with shoppers purchasing last minute gifts. Knowing this, it&rsquo;s important to practice and implement digital strategies for driving in-store sales.</p>\r\n	<p>For retailers and brands, the holiday shopping season can amount up to <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/onpoint-blog/2011/10/5/holiday-shopping-season-what-retailers-can-expect" target="_blank">40%</a> of retailer&rsquo;s annual sales. More importantly, it is the critical 72 hours before the end of the holiday shopping season where retailers and brands can drive high in-store sales with shoppers purchasing last minute gifts. Knowing this, it&rsquo;s important to practice and implement digital strategies for driving in-store sales. <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nHow can you drive in-store sales during this critical time period? We&rsquo;ve released our list of digital strategies for driving in-store sales, just in time for the holiday season. Here is a preview:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>Think local:</strong> According to NRF, US Census data indicates that approximately 75 percent of all US consumer spending occurs at retail locations within 15 miles of home. By reaching potential customers at the neighborhood level with digital campaigns, retailers can get much more targeted and serve the right ads to the right customers, driving traffic and sales.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Leverage highly relevant data to proactively move inventory:</strong> Retailers are often focused on selling excess &ldquo;holiday&rdquo; inventory before the New Year. Leverage digital campaigns and neighborhood targeting technology (such as our offering) to create highly-customized advertising that reaches qualified audiences to drive in-store sales of products that may create excess inventory. This approach also helps reach the last minute shoppers who have run out of time to purchase gifts online in the final 72 hours of the holiday shopping season.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Create &ldquo;just in time&rdquo; demand:</strong> Most advertising programs require brands and retailers to create campaigns weeks or months in advance of when they&rsquo;d like to drive traffic to stores. By creating a highly-localized digital campaign, brands, retailers and restaurants of any size can easily create and execute a campaign to drive &ldquo;just in time&rdquo; demand for their products or services.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nPractice these strategies and take some of the stress out of meeting revenue projections for the year. By developing highly-customized local digital advertising strategies, retailers and brands can effectively drive in-store sales.</p>\r\n	t	2011-11-02 13:33:27	\N	2011-11-02 13:33:27	2013-10-11 17:05:56.522902	49	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, press release, holiday shopping season, in-store sales, retailers, local advertising, local digital advertising, digital strategies, digital, local, NRF
680	1	20	in-store-man-caves-allow-women-to-shop-longer-happier-and-spend-more	In-Store Man Caves Allow Women to Shop Longer, Happier...and Spend More!	<p>Some men are shoppers.&nbsp; Many are not. My husband is in between.&nbsp; If he knows he is getting something for himself, then the amount of time before his patience runs out is significantly greater than if it was just shopping for items for our son or me.&nbsp; Sometimes I just want to try on 15 pairs of jeans to find the right one, but that won&rsquo;t happen with two &ldquo;boys&rdquo; on my heels.&nbsp; If only more retailers would follow IKEA&rsquo;s lead and create &ldquo;man-cave&rdquo; areas.</p>\r\n	<p>Some men are shoppers.&nbsp; Many are not. My husband is in between.&nbsp; If he knows he is getting something for himself, then the amount of time before his patience runs out is significantly greater than if it was just shopping for items for our son or me.&nbsp; Sometimes I just want to try on 15 pairs of jeans to find the right one, but that won&rsquo;t happen with two &ldquo;boys&rdquo; on my heels.&nbsp; If only more retailers would follow IKEA&rsquo;s lead and create &ldquo;man-cave&rdquo; areas.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn a recent Retail Wire article <a href="http://www.retailwire.com/discussion/15536/ikea-creates-in-store-man-cave" target="_blank">IKEA Creates In-Store Man Cave</a>, M&Auml;NLAND is IKEA&#39;s way of taking some of the dread out of going to its stores for guys. The concept is pretty simple: an in-store man cave with sports on the television, foosball and pinball machines, massages, free hot dogs, chips and drinks.&nbsp;&nbsp; What better way for retailers to increase the &ldquo;stickiness&rdquo; of a shopper than to remove the rush factor.&nbsp; Women can now browse, touch, design and imagine the furniture possibilities without being under the constraints of a short attention window of most men.&nbsp; Sort of&hellip; the down side, according to an <a href="http://www.adweek.com/" target="_blank">Adweek</a> report, M&Auml;NLAND is &quot;modeled off the actual IKEA toddler-care area -- and women are given a buzzer to remind them to collect their significant other after 30 minutes of shopping.&quot; I suppose that if IKEA is giving away food and drinks in this area, there needs to be some sort of limit, but maybe 60 minutes would be better.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAs I have said in many of my previous blogs, retailers have to keep one step ahead of their competition in order to survive.&nbsp; The M&Auml;NLAND idea is one of those tactics that drive in-store sales while increasing the likelihood of greater purchases. Now if IKEA would add a few Legos, Goldfish and TV&rsquo;s with cartoons all in the same area, then shopping would be perfect!</p>\r\n	t	2011-10-26 14:06:44	\N	2011-10-26 14:06:44	2013-10-23 16:59:09.591953	49	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, Lynn Vitello, IKEA, Manland, AdWeek, Retail Wire, retail, in-store sales, in-store sales tactics 
679	1	25	reaching-the-reach-affluent-americans-and-online-advertising	Reaching the Rich: Affluent Americans and Online Advertising	<p>The IAB partnered with research firm Ipsos Mendelsohn to evaluate how affluent Americans interact with digital media.&nbsp;</p>\r\n	<p>In July of this year, the IAB partnered with research firm Ipsos Mendelsohn to evaluate how affluent Americans interact with digital media.&nbsp; See the entire presentation <a href="http://www.iab.net/media/file/DigitalAffluentStudyFINAL1.pdf" target="_blank">here</a>. <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nFor the purposes of the study, Ipsos Mendelsohn considered the &ldquo;affluent&rdquo; as those households with an annual income greater than $100,000.&nbsp; Such households represent 21% of U.S. consumers and control 70% of total U.S. consumer wealth.&nbsp; According to the study, these consumers are 2x more likely to buy advertised goods and services and spend 3.2x more when they buy.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSo, what did the study show?<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe study is packed with interesting information and useful statistics.&nbsp; Here are my three major takeaways:<span id="cke_bm_337C" style="display:none">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>Online is the place to reach the affluent.&nbsp; 98% of those defined by the study as affluent use the Internet, and on average they spend 26.2 hours per week online. As significant as those numbers are, more impressive is how online stacks up against traditional media when it comes to the affluent.&nbsp; First, that group spends a relatively low 17.6 hours per week watching TV and 7.5 hours per week listening to the radio.&nbsp; Each of those numbers represents roughly half of the time spent by the population generally.&nbsp; Putting these numbers together illuminates one of the study&rsquo;s key findings:&nbsp; the difficulty of reaching the affluent with traditional media is completely reversed when advertisers leave the airways for the Internet.&nbsp; Of course, this insight does not even account for the increased ability to target specific markets online, which far exceeds any attempts to do the same using traditional media.</li>\r\n\t<li>Digital ads work on the affluent.&nbsp; Affluent users recalled seeing an average of 21.1 digital ads in the past seven days.&nbsp; Even more impressive, 55% of affluent users identified that digital ads had created an awareness of new products, compared to 49% of the general population.&nbsp; Affluent users particularly over-indexed for their awareness of banner ads, with 80% recalling exposure to a banner ad in the previous seven days.&nbsp; Importantly, 59% of users recalled taking action as a direct result of a digital ad in the past 6 months, including an impressive 17% of affluent users visiting brick-and-mortar retail locations in response to an advertisement seen online.</li>\r\n\t<li>Affluent users like seeing ads targeting them.&nbsp; Being &ldquo;too targeted&rdquo; is not a major concern among affluent users, who do not significantly over-index when asked if they have been made uncomfortable by advertising targeting them online.&nbsp; In fact, the affluent actually greatly over-index when asked if they would be willing to share some personal information.&nbsp; Finally, and perhaps most importantly, affluent users tend to value advertising relevant to them.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What does this mean for marketers?<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMarketing executives are always seeking ways to reach affluent consumers and their tremendous buying power.&nbsp; Using traditional media outlets and advertising methods, these wealthy consumers are notoriously hard to reach.&nbsp; However, in a reversal of their relative position in traditional media use, the affluent are online more and are more engaged with online activities than the general population.&nbsp; This represents a huge opportunity for marketers.&nbsp; By shifting traditional advertising dollars to online platforms and tailoring advertising campaigns to reach the affluent, advertisers can reach an elusive and highly desirable segment of the market like never before.</p>\r\n	t	2011-10-24 14:55:05	\N	2011-10-24 14:55:05	2013-10-23 17:01:24.692548	49	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, Morgan Mueller, online advertising, digital, traditional advertising, campaigns, Ipsos Mendelsohn, internet usage statistics
678	1	20	adding-local-brands-can-make-a-retailer-stand-out-but-letting-customers-know-is-key	Adding Local Brands Can Make a Retailer Stand Out...but letting customers know is key!	<p>Growing up, I remember going with my mom to the local butcher for meats, the baker for bread and the produce stand or farmer&rsquo;s market for fruits and vegetables.&nbsp; Chances are, the majority of what was bought then was locally sourced and grown.&nbsp; But, people got busy.&nbsp;</p>\r\n	<p>Growing up, I remember going with my mom to the local butcher for meats, the baker for bread and the produce stand or farmer&rsquo;s market for fruits and vegetables.&nbsp; Chances are, the majority of what was bought then was locally sourced and grown.&nbsp; But, people got busy.&nbsp; <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nAs a result, grocery stores expanded or added their own meat, bakery and produce sections out of customer demand for convenience.&nbsp; Now, you can go into just about any major grocery store chain and buy the exact same brands as any other.&nbsp; Where you buy them comes down to price and the convenience of store location.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhat if there was a compromise?&nbsp; What if stores began to carry more local brands to not only differentiate themselves from a nearby competitor, but also to give their customers a more diversified selection?<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<em>Frozen &amp; Dairy Buyer</em> broached these questions in a <a href="http://www.retailwire.com/discussion/15517/fd-buyer-more-smaller-regional-brands-at-grocery" target="_blank">recent survey</a> by asking a number of supermarket frozen and dairy retail executives to rank a variety of statements on a scale of one to 10, with one being &quot;disagree strongly&quot; and 10 being &quot;agree strongly.&quot; They explored whether an increasing amount of smaller, regional brands would be heading to the food channel.&nbsp; While specific to frozen and dairy products, the results could be similar for other local food niches.&nbsp; The survey found that few grocers were neutral on whether to stock local products &ndash; it was either a good idea or bad idea.&nbsp;&nbsp; The sticking point on the executives most opposed to carrying local brands came down to SKU rationalization.&nbsp; However, several experts made comments to the contrary:<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<em>&ldquo;SKU rationalization can certainly accommodate smaller/regional brands if they fill a role or niche in the category. The key in SKU rat is to reduce duplication and non-productive SKUs. No reason a more specialized product that is more local can&#39;t fill holes in an assortment mix.&rdquo;</em><br />\r\n<a href="http://www.retailwire.com/profile/62123/dr-stephen-needel" target="_blank">Dr. Stephen Needel, Managing Partner, Advanced Simulations</a><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<em>&ldquo;The usual metrics used in SKU rationalization often do not take into consideration the human element of the shopping experience. Not all consumers are so vanilla that all they want to buy are the top national branded SKUs in any given category. Consumers have a strong desire for variety, differentiation, specialty, and niche. In a bad economy you ask? Yes even more so! SKU rationalization frequently creates sameness among every retailer within a given channel and it creates a boring and disappointing shopping experience for the consumer.&rdquo;</em><br />\r\n<a href="http://www.retailwire.com/profile/25536/david-biernbaum" target="_blank">David Biernbaum, Senior Marketing and Business Development Consultant, David Biernbaum Associates</a><br />\r\n<br />\r\nLocal brands are necessary for differentiation in a competitive market place where national brands saturate the market.&nbsp; Certainly there is a huge need and desire for national brands, but local brands not only support the regional economy, they also provide greater choice for shoppers looking to buy in alignment with the current trends such as organics and the buy local/shop local initiatives.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhat cannot be forgotten however is that consumers need to know <em>which</em> neighborhood retailers carry local goods.&nbsp; This is where a targeted advertising strategy needs to be in place to successfully gain local market share from competitors.&nbsp; The cost effectiveness of online marketing far surpasses that of traditional print channels such as weekly circulars and advertisements.&nbsp; Not all online campaigns are created equal.&nbsp; Retailers need to work with leading technology companies like <em>Maxpoint Interactive</em> who can deliver the most effective and scalable neighborhood-level online campaigns for retailers and brands.</p>\r\n	t	2011-10-19 15:57:59	\N	2011-10-19 15:57:59	2013-10-23 17:03:24.512834	50	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, Lynn Vitello, local brands, grocery stores, Frozen & Dairy Buyer, SKU rationalization, Dr. Stephen Needel, David Biernbaum, local store, retailers, online campaigns  
677	1	15	breaking-down-the-scores-the-local-approach-the-state-of-localized-advertising-in-retail	Breaking Down the Scores - The Local Approach: The State of Localized Advertising in Retail	<p>In a recent Retail Systems Research (RSR) report, The Local Approach: The State of Localized Advertising in Retail, RSR evaluated 20 top retailers&rsquo; localization efforts. This report provides recommendations for retailers from various categories to create cohesive local campaigns that reach consumers at every touch point throughout the purchase path.</p>\r\n	<p>In a recent Retail Systems Research (RSR) <a href="http://maxpointinteractive.com/insights/rsrlocal/" target="_blank">report</a>, The Local Approach: The State of Localized Advertising in Retail, RSR evaluated 20 top retailers&rsquo; localization efforts. This report provides recommendations for retailers from various categories to create cohesive local campaigns that reach consumers at every touch point throughout the purchase path.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nWe&rsquo;re pleased to share a special glimpse of some of the insights from this report with you:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Overall Results</strong><span id="cke_bm_337C" style="display:none">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>The top five &ldquo;local&rdquo; advertisers were: Macy&rsquo;s, J.C. Penney, Sports Authority, Best Buy &amp; Kohl&rsquo;s</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ul><br />\r\n\t<li>Electronic retailers appear to be successfully leveraging across social networking channels, but have far to go in video, mobile and alternative social branding</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ul><br />\r\n\t<li>Sporting goods retailers are more likely to segment advertising by category (e.g. football, lacrosse) than other retailers</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ul><br />\r\n\t<li>Casual dining has the most difficulty with localized advertising, missing out on search and display advertising opportunities</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ul><br />\r\n\t<li>Retailers seem to be looking more to social and digital channels to provide localization opportunities, and not relying as heavily on traditional channels</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ul><br />\r\n\t<li>Despite some localization efforts, retailers have not implemented localization as a major part of their advertising strategy, particularly as it relates to driving in-store traffic</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nTo get RSR&rsquo;s specific tactics of how to boost local retail sales, click <a href="http://maxpoint.com/rsrreport" target="_blank">here</a> to download the full report.</p>\r\n	t	2011-10-17 14:11:44	\N	2011-10-17 14:11:44	2013-10-23 17:05:30.524061	49	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, retail sales, OnPoint, RSR, research report, Retail Systems Research, localized advertising, results, retail, localization efforts
690	1	15	embrace-digital-and-fill-just-in-time-demand-in-the-final-hours-of-the-holiday-shopping-season	Embrace Digital and Fill Just In-Time Demand in the Final Hours of the Holiday Shopping Season	<p>The final 72 hours of the holiday shopping season are the most critical when it comes to meeting revenue projections for the year. Fortunately, retailers and brands can now quickly and easily create &ldquo;just-in-time&rdquo; demand to help meet their revenue projections.</p>\r\n	<p>The final 72 hours of the holiday shopping season are the most critical when it comes to meeting revenue projections for the year. Fortunately, retailers and brands can now quickly and easily create &ldquo;just-in-time&rdquo; demand to help meet their revenue projections. The key here is flexibility &ndash; which you have with digital channels. Most advertising programs require brands and retailers to create campaigns weeks or months in advance of when they&rsquo;d like to drive traffic in stores. By creating a highly localized digital campaign, brands, retailers and restaurants of any size can easily create and execute a campaign to drive &ldquo;just-in-time&rdquo; demand for their products or services. Not only does this meet demand during the holiday season, but can be quickly executed at any time of the year (unlike non-digital options which require long lead times). <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nFor instance, if in-store sales are slow, organizations can create campaigns that incentivize local customers to come in and make purchases. Here are some examples:<span id="cke_bm_98C" style="display:none">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>Restaurants:</strong> In the case of a local restaurant, let&rsquo;s say they happen to have a surplus of seafood they need to use. They can quickly and easily &ldquo;turn on&rdquo; a local, digital ad campaign, advertising seafood specials to help drive traffic to their restaurant a specific day of the week.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ul><br />\r\n\t<li><strong>Retailers:</strong> If a retailer, say a sporting goods store, is having a slow week and they want to drive traffic to their store on a Tuesday, they can send out a digital promotion around a store event targeting neighborhoods around their store full of interested and qualified shoppers. For example, they can encourage shoppers to gear up for March Madness and let them know their favorite NCAA team apparel is on sale and there will be chances to win prizes.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ul><br />\r\n\t<li><strong>Brands:</strong> Now let&rsquo;s consider brands. For example, if a potato chip brand has extra inventory a particular week at a local store, they can launch a digital campaign with a coupon for that specific store to help boost sales of their chips.&nbsp; This can also be done on a national or regional scale.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nThe flexibility of the digital channel allows for unique, local customization that should be taken advantage of. You can create just-in-time demand every single week of the year quickly and effectively by using a highly localized digital campaign.</p>\r\n	t	2011-11-28 14:26:13	\N	2011-11-28 14:26:13	2013-10-03 00:21:09.855699	49	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, digital, digital campaigns, campaigns, holiday, holiday shopping, retail, local, local campaigns, "just-in-time" demand
687	1	20	coca-cola-drives-in-store-sales-with-innovative-soda-fountain	Coca-Cola Drives In-store Sales with Innovative Soda Fountain	<p>Your options have increased dramatically with Coke&rsquo;s latest innovation in soda fountains, the Freestyle.</p>\r\n	<p>You go to your local restaurant, order your food at the counter with a drink, then walk over to the soda fountain and choose from a handful of soft drinks.&nbsp; Truth be told, I look in advance and if the fountains do not serve <a href="http://www.coca-cola.com/en/index.html" target="_blank">Coca-Cola</a> products, I instead order water or iced tea.&nbsp; Yes, I am a huge fan of Coca-Cola (just check out my bottle collection in our home bar).&nbsp; However, if you like diet soda, you know there is not much of a choice.&nbsp; If you don&rsquo;t want caffeine,&nbsp; you are also limited.&nbsp; But now, your options have increased dramatically with Coke&rsquo;s latest innovation in soda fountains, <a href="http://www.coca-colafreestyle.com/" target="_blank">the Freestyle</a>.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe soda fountains, have up to 125 different soda choices, both carbonated and non-carbonated.&nbsp; That is a huge leap forward in and of itself.&nbsp; The real intriguing function of this machine lies in its ability to track usage data and send it back to Coca-Cola&rsquo;s HQ for analysis and market research.&nbsp; Now if that doesn&rsquo;t excite a marketing professional, I don&rsquo;t know what does.&nbsp; The implications are endless for targeted marketing.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAccording to preliminary research, 20% of consumers said they would be very likely to switch restaurants or convenience stores due to the presence of this Freestyle fountain machine.&nbsp; Restaurant management at the test locations were very happy as well. Results have been so impressive at Firehouse Subs that the chain announced it will be rolling Freestyle out to all of its 437 restaurants by year&#39;s end.&nbsp;&nbsp; The stores saw a double-digit increase in traffic and overall sales, as well as an increase in people buying a drink and sandwich, rather than just a sandwich. Those stores also saw increased numbers of families with kids coming in, as well as more people choosing to dine in the restaurants, versus just take out.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIt won&rsquo;t surprise me to see a huge jump in the on-boarding of the Freestyle in other chains over the next couple of years.&nbsp; The need for more and more &ldquo;smart&rdquo; technology to keep up with the demand of targeted advertising and shrinking budgets is rapidly growing, especially now that there is a technology infrastructure to deliver and analyze the incoming data.</p>\r\n	t	2011-11-16 15:15:16	\N	2011-11-16 15:15:16	2013-10-08 21:50:31.658884	49	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, Lynn Vitello, OnPoint, Firehouse Subs, Coca-Cola, soda fountain, the Freestyle, sales, targeted marketing, restaurants, data, consumers
688	1	15	retailers-get-creative-get-digital-and-drive-in-store-sales	Retailers: Get Creative, Get Digital and Drive In-store Sales	<p>With online ad spend hitting $26 billion in 2010 and predicted to have double-digit growth through 2015, more and more retailers are using digital to reach shoppers in order to drive in-store traffic. And, it doesn&rsquo;t stop there, once these shoppers are in store, retailers are coming up with more ways to enhance the in-store experience.</p>\r\n	<p>With online ad spend hitting $26 billion in 2010 and <a href="http://mashable.com/2011/07/05/online-ad-spending-50-bilion/" target="_blank">predicted</a> to have double-digit growth through 2015, more and more retailers are using digital to reach shoppers in order to drive in-store traffic. And, it doesn&rsquo;t stop there, once these shoppers are in store, retailers are coming up with more ways to enhance the in-store experience. Below are some creative ways retailers have used digital to engage with shoppers in the store: <!--more--></p>\r\n\r\n<ul><br />\r\n\t<li><strong>QR codes:</strong> Many retailers are using QR codes to engage with in-store shoppers. QR codes are placed next to displays to prompt shoppers to read more about the product or are used to provide suggestions for fun ways to use the product. <a href="http://www.jcpenney.com/jcp/default.aspx?&amp;cm_mmc=Google-_-G_JCP_Official_Site_Exact-_-G_JCP_Official_Site-_-jc%20penneys" target="_blank">J.C. Penney&rsquo;s</a>, for example, will use QR codes this holiday shopping season to add a personalized voice message to gifts purchased in-store. More <a href="http://mashable.com/2011/11/10/j-c-penney-qr-codes/" target="_blank">here</a>.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ul><br />\r\n\t<li><strong>Self-checkout:</strong> <a href="http://www.apple.com/" target="_blank">Apple</a> is testing a new self-checkout service where shoppers can use their iTunes account to make payments in-store. Simply enable the app., grab an item and check yourself out.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ul><br />\r\n\t<li><strong>Interactive displays:</strong> <a href="http://www.macys.com/?cm_mmc=GOOGLE_Trademark-_-Macys+Trademark+Exact+-+G_Macy%27s-_-7652215760_Exact-_-macys._mkwid_sD8ZWkSIK_7652215760|-|D8ZWkSIK" target="_blank">Macy&rsquo;s</a> is using augmented reality as part of its Believe campaign. Consumers mail their letters to Santa at Macy&rsquo;s &ldquo;Believe Stations&rdquo; in-store and can take pictures with the campaign&rsquo;s animated stars via augmented technology.&nbsp; Thinking of visiting a &ldquo;Believe Station&rdquo; near you? Find out more <a href="http://www.mobilemarketer.com/cms/news/software-technology/11417.html" target="_blank">here</a>.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ul><br />\r\n\t<li><strong>Interactive hangers:</strong> A radio frequency identification (RFID) chip is embedded in hangers at stores and when a hanger is removed from the rack, the chip sends a message to a store computer that is controlling video displays. When a shopper takes a clothing item off of the rack, a digital screen above the hanger will activate and provide the shopper with recommendations for matching items.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nAs you can see, more and more retailers are starting to embrace digital in order to engage with their customers and these strategies are both welcomed by and appealing to in-store shoppers! But, remember, while it is important to add digital elements to the in-store experience, it is also important to use digital advertising to drive your customers into your stores. How can you optimize your digital campaign? Find out more <a href="http://www.maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-solutions" target="_blank">here</a>.</p>\r\n	t	2011-11-17 14:51:27	\N	2011-11-17 14:51:27	2013-10-03 00:26:24.691772	51	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, retail, brands, digital, in-store, online ad spend, QR codes, J.C. Penney, Apple, Macy's, Believe Stations, digital campaign 
685	1	25	what-do-wwii-bombers-and-digital-advertising-have-in-common-approaches-data-critically	What do WWII Bombers and Digital Advertising Have in Common? Approaches Data Critically	<p>Critical analysis of data is vital in every business. Always try to think outside of the box when developing your digital strategy.</p>\r\n	<p>Dr. John D. Cook teaches courses in statistics at the University of Texas Graduate School of Biomedical Sciences and has a blog called <a href="http://www.johndcook.com/blog/" target="_blank">The Endeavour</a>.&nbsp; The blog is updated almost daily with interesting tidbits about math, science, and statistics. This is one of his many stories:<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nA couple of years ago, Dr. Cook told an interesting story about selection bias during World War II.&nbsp; You can check out the story <a href="http://www.johndcook.com/blog/2008/01/21/selection-bias-and-bombers/" target="_blank">here</a>, but the gist is that during the war, a statistician named Abraham Wald was asked to help the British determine where to add armor to their bomber planes.&nbsp; Wald looked at the bullet holes on all the planes the British had in their hangers, and then suggested that armor be added to the places where the planes had no damage.&nbsp; If you think this sounds counterintuitive, you&rsquo;re not alone.&nbsp; Wald&rsquo;s reasoning, however, was brilliant:&nbsp; he assumed that the distribution of bullet holes on the fleet of planes was relatively even.&nbsp; The only planes available for him to analyze were the ones that had made it back to England without being shot down, meaning that the planes could survive shots in the places where he saw bullet holes but were being shot down when hit elsewhere.&nbsp; So, armor should be added where it looked like the planes were not being hit.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThis anecdote&rsquo;s lesson is in approaching data critically, which is what we do at MaxPoint every day.&nbsp; A perfect example is a campaign we ran recently advertising a national consumer service.&nbsp; While working with the agency to develop a targeting strategy, MaxPoint was asked to identify the neighborhoods around service locations with the most households that matched who the brand believed its target audience should be&mdash;households with very low income and very low credit score.&nbsp; Both the agency and brand were convinced that this particular audience would respond best.&nbsp; In doing our own pre-campaign research, the data we analyzed gave us insight into who the consumer actually was.&nbsp; We discovered that neighborhoods with higher income, higher net worth and a higher concentration of Bachelor&rsquo;s and Master&rsquo;s degrees were actually the most relevant for this campaign &mdash;the exact opposite of the anticipated audience.&nbsp; Based on these insights, we worked with the brand and agency to design a successful campaign targeted to the most appropriate consumers for their service.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nCritical analysis of data is vital in every business.&nbsp; The brand&rsquo;s misconception about its target audience was an unscientific form of selection bias&mdash;they assumed, based on their knowledge of the service they offered, that a certain type of consumer would be the best target audience.&nbsp; Without taking a hard look at the actual data, and its real world implications, a campaign based on those assumptions would have been little better than re-armoring the already fortified portions of the planes - we would have gone with the obvious instead of digging deeper.&nbsp; Always try to think outside of the box when developing your digital strategy!</p>\r\n	t	2011-11-09 22:59:27	\N	2011-11-09 22:59:27	2013-11-06 19:42:05.451197	49	Dr. John Cook, The Endeavour, data, digital zip technology, critical analysis, campaign, digital strategy, MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, Morgan Mueller, OnPoint
686	1	15	leverage-highly-relevant-data-to-proactively-move-inventory-this-holiday-season	Leverage Highly Relevant Data to Proactively Move Inventory this Holiday Season	<p>The last 72 hours of the holiday shopping season is a critical time period retailers and brands can leverage to drive in-store sales and proactively move seasonal inventory. During this time, retailers can leverage highly relevant data to proactively move inventory and avoid having to discount items or return them to the manufacturer.</p>\r\n	<p>The last 72 hours of the holiday shopping season is a critical time period retailers and brands can leverage to drive in-store sales and proactively move seasonal inventory. Someone always procrastinates and shops the night before the holiday or forgets a gift for a last minute holiday party, and it is too late to purchase gifts online. Online stores cannot ship in time to meet last minute shopper demands, but brick-and-mortar stores allow shoppers the ease of purchasing last minute gifts in-store. During this time, retailers can leverage highly relevant data to proactively move inventory and avoid having to discount items or return them to the manufacturer. <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nHow?<br />\r\n<br />\r\nRetailers can use local digital advertising solutions to reach the last minute shoppers who have run out of time to purchase gifts online in the final hours of the holiday shopping season.&nbsp; By using a targeted digital solution (like MaxPoint&rsquo;s Digital Zip&trade; technology), retailers and brands can leverage a wide range of data sources, including demographic and interest data, purchase data and health data &ndash; among many others &ndash; to pinpoint neighborhoods where the qualified audience lives. From there, they can create highly-customized and localized advertising campaigns that reach a very specific audience and drive in-store sales of products that may create excess inventory (if not sold during a particular time frame - e.g. final 72 hours of the holiday shopping season).<br />\r\n<br />\r\nBy developing a highly-customized local digital advertising strategy, retailers and brands can effectively drive in-store sales that eliminate excess inventory along with helping to increase revenue and create more personal relationship with customers. For more digital strategies for retailers and brands this holiday season, click <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/advertising-tips-and-strategies/advertising-guides-and-reports/2012-guide-to-holiday-advertising" target="_blank">here</a>.</p>\r\n	t	2011-11-14 14:22:03	\N	2011-11-14 14:22:03	2013-11-11 15:19:08.156862	49	Maxpoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, local digital advertising, local, digital, digital advertising, holiday shopping season, inventory, retail, data, Digital Zip
699	1	20	even-grocery-stores-can-bundle-services-to-drive-in-store-sales	Even Grocery Stores Can Bundle Services to Drive In-Store Sales	<p>Service organizations have been doing it for years; bundling complementary, value-add offerings to attract more customers.&nbsp; Most people do it with their cable, Internet and phone but why not with your grocery store.</p>\r\n	<p>Service organizations have been doing it for years; bundling complementary, value-add offerings to attract more customers.&nbsp; Most people do it with their cable, Internet and phone but why not with your grocery store.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nJoin the <a href="http://www.wholefoodsmarket.com/wellnessclub/" target="_blank">Whole Foods Wellness Club</a> and reap 10% off of your grocery bill with the added value of a program developed for the company by two physicians and a registered dietitian.&nbsp; Extra offerings include a lifestyle evaluation, nutrition education, coaching, skill-building classes and Supper Clubs with healthy four-course meals.&nbsp; At $45 per month, people seeking that extra help in improving their nutritional lifestyle can&rsquo;t go wrong, especially if Whole Foods is your primary grocery store.&nbsp; You&rsquo;ll save that $45 with your 10% discount in no time!&nbsp; Also included are introductory nutrition classes, a four-week &quot;immersion&quot; period that is followed by a four-week &quot;experimental&quot; phase, emphasizing how members can lead healthier lives.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe Dedham, MA store is the first to offer Wellness Club with others planned in Chicago, New York City, Princeton, NJ and Oakland, CA.&nbsp; There are also plans to seek out local partners in areas such as yoga and fitness to offer lectures and classes on site.&nbsp; This shows a drive for even more value-add bundling to keep people shopping locally in support of their neighborhood businesses.&nbsp; I know that if I owned a health-related business near a Whole Foods Wellness Club, I would certainly jump on board to boost local sales!<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe grocery market is highly competitive, with competing stores a block away or right across the street.&nbsp; In order for these stores to remain in business, they need to differentiate themselves or find a niche unique to that neighborhood to draw a loyal customer base. John Mackey, founder and co-CEO of Whole Foods is no stranger to forward thinking and staying one step ahead of the competition.&nbsp; Whole Foods, by nature, is a unique niche in the neighborhood grocery market.&nbsp; In article, <a href="http://www.retailwire.com/discussion/15449/whole-foods-wellness-club-focuses-on-consumer-education" target="_blank">Whole Foods Wellness Club Focuses on Consumer Education</a> posted on <a href="http://www.retailwire.com/" target="_blank">Retail Wire</a>, Mackey said, &quot;This is like nothing the grocery world has ever seen before and we&#39;re thrilled to offer it to our communities and to be a pioneer in the effort of providing support for our shoppers.&quot;&nbsp; Pioneer is the key term.&nbsp; Retailers have to be willing to try new trends and ideas to stay fresh and competitive.</p>\r\n	t	2011-12-19 13:56:04	\N	2011-12-19 13:56:04	2013-10-02 23:53:10.31069	49	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, Lynn Vitello, grocery stores, retail, shoppers, deals, Whole Foods, Wellness Club, Whole Foods Wellness Club, John Mackey, Retail Wire, in-store sales
