702	1	15	maxpoint-interactives-2011-digital-look-back	MaxPoint Interactive's 2011 Digital Look Back	<p>This past year, the advertising industry saw tremendous growth as more dollars were allocated towards digital advertising solutions. Here&rsquo;s a look back at some of the major strides made in digital in 2011. &nbsp;</p>\r\n	<p>This past year, the advertising industry saw tremendous growth as more dollars were allocated towards digital advertising solutions. Here&rsquo;s a look back at some of the major strides made in digital in 2011. &nbsp;<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Digital became integral part of advertising strategies</strong>: In the beginning of 2011, <a href="http://www.emarketer.com/AboutUs/Bios.aspx" target="_blank">David Hallerman</a>, eMarketer principal analyst commented, &ldquo;as consumers continue to increase their time spent online and as the resurgent economy continues to bolster ad budgets, we&rsquo;re going to continue to see an influx of dollars toward the internet.&rdquo; And&hellip;we sure did! More advertisers and brands re-considered online advertising as a way to effectively reach consumers. In 2011, online ad spending was expected to reach $31.3 billion, a 20.2 % increase over 2010 spending. By 2015, online advertising is expected to make up nearly 28% of all US media ad spending. More <a href="http://www.emarketer.com/Article.aspx?R=1008431" target="_blank">here</a>.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Video:</strong> In the past year in particular, online video adoption has begun to grow at a rapidly increasing rate &ndash; 28% of media buyers expected to see the greatest increase in ad spending in the online video category for 2011. According to an <a href="http://www.emarketer.com/Welcome.aspx" target="_blank">eMarketer</a> report, the spending for US online video advertising spending grew 52.1% to $2.16 billion, up from $1.42 billion in 2010. Its unique interactivity helps marketers more accurately measure the relationship between video ads and their influence on consumers. In June, we were pleased to announce our video targeting solution enabling digital advertisers to target their pre-roll and in-banner video ads at a neighborhood level, reaching up to 90% of online users across high-quality and brand-safe content sites.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Mobile:</strong> Mobile web adoption began to pick up rapidly towards the end of 2011 with the continued advance of smartphones and tablet acquisition &ndash; US mobile ad spending already expected to grow 47% in 2012, reaching $1.8 billion. Search and display emerged as the dominant mobile ad formats. More stats <a href="http://www.emarketer.com/Article.aspx?R=1008666" target="_blank">here</a>.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Localized campaigns:</strong> This past year, there has been an increasing amount of buzz around local and localizing advertising campaigns to drive in-store traffic. As US Census data indicates that approximately 75 % of all US consumer spending occurs at retail locations within 15 miles of home, advertisers understand that localization needs to become a key part of the brand strategy. Just this past October, we released a <a href="http://maxpointinteractive.com/insights/rsrlocal/" target="_blank">study</a> that analyzed retailers&rsquo; localization efforts &ndash; Here are the top five &ldquo;local&rdquo; advertisers of 2011 &ndash; Macy&rsquo;s, J.C. Penney, Sports Authority, Best Buy &amp; Kohl&rsquo;s.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nJoin our conversation on Twitter (<a href="http://twitter.com/maxpoint_int" target="_blank">@maxpoint_int</a>) and share your 2011 digital memories and predictions for 2012 with the #digital11 or #digital12.</p>\r\n	t	2011-12-29 15:09:10	\N	2011-12-29 15:09:10	2013-10-02 14:36:01.628149	51	Macy's, J.C. Penney, Sports Authority, Best Buy, Kohl's, MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, digital, 2011, 2011 look back, online advertising, online advertising statistics, eMarketer, David Hallerman, maxpoint_in