714	1	15	emerging-technology-and-the-digital-advertising-industry	Emerging Technology and the Digital Advertising Industry	<p>As the digital advertising industry continues to grow, more advertising dollars are being allocated to digital, revealing how media and technology are intersecting in new ways. At this year&rsquo;s annual Consumer Electronics Show, it became clear that technology such as, tablets, smartphones, and notebooks &ndash; to name a few &ndash; are offering new advertising channels and creative ways to reach and engage with target audiences.</p>\r\n	<p>As the digital advertising industry continues to grow, more advertising dollars are being allocated to digital, revealing how media and technology are intersecting in new ways. At this year&rsquo;s annual <a href="http://www.cesweb.org/aboutces.asp" target="_blank">Consumer Electronics Show</a>, it became clear that technology such as, tablets, smartphones, and notebooks &ndash; to name a few &ndash; are offering new advertising channels and creative ways to reach and engage with target audiences. And, as advertisers explore these channels, they need to first understand the technology behind them. For instance, advertisers should take time to understand technology adoption rates, how technology is consumed and how new technology is being marketed. Below is a look at a few insights around the emerging technologies of 2012, referencing takeaways from the 2012 Consumer Electronics Show (CES). <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Smartphones:</strong> The key to new technology is understanding how content will be consumed. This year, smart mobile devices are predicted to become one of the leading media consumption platforms. With a wide variety of smart, interconnected mobile devices, consumers will expect content to be on-the-go and easy to access.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Tablets:</strong> <a href="http://www.forrester.com/rb/research/" target="_blank">Forrester Research</a> estimates that the current &ldquo;single digit penetration&rdquo; of tablets will increase 3-to-4 times by 2015 and with it, maturation of its usage expected. It is valued across all consumer groups, with Hispanics and Asian-Americans leading as the early adopters of the tablets. In addition, tablets are the first device that can easily travel with the shopper through the complete path to purchase.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Tech Audience:</strong> At the CES show this year, one of the panels addressed how technology marketing is distinct for each sex. According to James McQuivey, principal analyst at Forrester Research, &ldquo;tech marketers traditionally focus on 25 to 40 year old men.&rdquo; However, according to data compiled by retailer HSN, more women actually buy tech products than men. Understanding your true consumer can have tremendous consequences for how tech products are marketed.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhat can you take away from the above? With the emergence of new technology, advertising opportunities can extend throughout the entire path to purchase,&nbsp; engaging with your consumers in new and unique ways. If you understand the technology, keep in mind how content is consumed, who your audience really is, the best way to engage with your audience and how to optimize campaigns across these new formats; then you will be on your way to digital success this year.</p>\r\n	t	2012-01-30 15:12:03	\N	2012-01-30 15:12:03	2013-10-01 20:00:52.552941	50	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, Consumer Electronics Show, CES, digital, technology, advertising, digital advertising, 2012, smartphones, tablets, consumers, James McQuivey, Forrester Research 
713	1	15	local-matters-to-retailers-in-2012	Local Matters to Retailers in 2012	<p>In 2012, how can retailers localize their digital advertising campaigns to reach the right shoppers, serve relevant ads and still maintain a national brand look and feel?</p>\r\n	<p>As retailers rethink ways to drive in-store traffic in 2012, more are turning to local. According to a recent RSR (Retail Systems Research) <a href="http://maxpoint.com/rsrreport" target="_blank">research study</a>, retailers have struggled to create relevant, &ldquo;local&rdquo; experiences. Shoppers in different geographic locations have different consumer needs and retailers and brands have focused on maintaining a consistent national brand look and feel, neglecting localization efforts. In 2012, how can retailers localize their digital advertising campaigns to reach the right shoppers, serve relevant ads and still maintain a national brand look and feel? Below are a few things to keep in mind. <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Local matters:</strong> Retailers often struggle with engagement opportunities with consumers. According to Nikki Baird, managing partner at Retail Systems Research, &ldquo;retailers increasingly have to drive traffic across more channels with communication tools that reach smaller groups of consumers, albeit potentially in a more targeted way.&rdquo;&nbsp; By localizing advertising campaigns, ads can still have scale (reaching many consumers, not just a small group) at the local level, serving relevant ads to consumers who meet your local store&rsquo;s shopper profile.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Localized advertising solutions:</strong> Targeted campaigns result in more engaging and relevant experiences for your customers. At MaxPoint, we delve deep into a wide variety of data sources to pinpoint neighborhoods where your qualified audience lives. MaxPoint&rsquo;s Digital Zip&trade; technology takes localized ad campaigns to a new level, pinpointing neighborhoods at the most 