712	1	15	mobile-devices-better-suited-for-customer-acquisition-or-redemption	Mobile Devices: Better Suited for Customer Acquisition or Redemption?	<p>This is the first post in our Executive Team Talk series. MaxPoint Interactive&rsquo;s Executive Team Talk blog posts explore diverse topics, sharing insights from our CEO, Joe Epperson, COO, Gretchen Joyce, and CTO, Kurt Carlson. This blog post shares insight from Joyce and Carlson on mobile devices and whether or not they are better suited for customer acquisition or customer redemption.</p>\r\n	<p>This is the first post in our Executive Team Talk series. MaxPoint Interactive&rsquo;s Executive Team Talk blog posts explore diverse topics, sharing insights from our CEO, Joe Epperson, COO, Gretchen Joyce, and CTO, Kurt Carlson.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThis blog post shares insight from Joyce and Carlson on mobile devices and whether or not they are better suited for customer acquisition or customer redemption. <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nMobile gives retailers and brands an incredible opportunity to reach customers in a uniquely personal, targeted and cost-effective manner. Customers can redeem coupons instantly with targeted advertisements, gain rewards with mobile loyalty programs or sign-up for a store&rsquo;s e-newsletter. The opportunities are endless.&nbsp; And with mobile adoption rates on the rise, there&rsquo;s no denying that mobile is slowly making its way into the advertising plans of retailers and brands everywhere.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nHowever, before implementing an advertising plan, retailers and brands need to decide mobile&rsquo;s role in the advertising strategy. More specifically&hellip;will mobile devices be better suited for customer acquisition or customer redemption? Here is what Joyce and Carlson had to say on mobile&rsquo;s role with acquisition and redemption.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAccording to Joyce, mobile, in general, is a fairly new channel and sees its current benefits in helping create additional awareness for a brand with the ideal final state being redemption. However, the challenge to mobile is finding a way to make it work for redemption within stores. For example, when it comes to redeeming mobile coupons, stores are not yet equipped with systems that make it easy for redemption to truly work. Once this issue is addressed though, there lies a huge opportunity for mobile to reach already engaged customers and then prompt them to redeem something once in-store &ndash; becoming clear that mobile devices are better suited for customer redemption opposed to customer acquisition.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAs we just mentioned, retailers and brands have a huge opportunity to reach shoppers with mobile coupons.&nbsp; A recent Exposure2 report shows that mobile coupon redemption rates often exceed 50%, while paper coupons typically have a redemption rate of only .2 &ndash; 2%. Why? It is immediate redemption, in real-time. The print rate or cut-out rate might be high for print coupons but it&rsquo;s easy to leave these behind, often forgetting to go back to your printer to pick-up the coupons. This is where mobile comes in, because who doesn&rsquo;t have a phone everywhere they go? &ndash; Joyce comments. The phone is a convenient way to receive a coupon and provides easy access when it is time to redeem in-store. All you have to do is scan right at the register or simply show the cashier the coupon.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nBecause of mobile selectivity, mobile users had to have previous interaction with a retailer or brand to get a coupon on their phone. This is very compelling to advertisers because you can mail a coupon to anyone, but whether you can get them to do anything with it is hard &ndash; with mobile you can pick people who are most inclined to react, comments Carlson, greatly increasing the number of people who will actually redeem the coupon.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nFurthermore, where coupons end, offers exist.&nbsp; Joyce comments earlier that the challenge to redeeming coupons is the hardware needed in-store. Retailers and brands can use apps, emails and/or notifications to let shoppers know about offers or sales for the day. This catches shoppers en route to the store, in the store and is super easy! Today, most shoppers plan before heading in-store, using their mobile phone to look up daily deals, sales and offers. What&rsquo;s great about this is that smartphones allow shoppers to access the Internet anywhere, so shoppers can be reached at their homes, en-route to the store, or in-store. Utilize mobile to reach shoppers on the path-to-purchase by reaching them with offers when they begin the decision making online.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn addition, mobile users are selective. When it comes to receiving messages from retailers and brands, mobile users already know what will or will not interest them. A mobile user that is already a shopper and engaged with a retailer or brand, is most likely already headed in-store, and more likely to redeem an offer by that retailer or brand. According to Carlson, mobile allows retailers and brands to reach already acquired customers and then provide convenience for them to redeem something in-store.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nHowever, like any new channel, there are still questions to be answered. For instance, stores must train employees on mobile coupon redemption and have the hardware set up to redeem coupons via scanners. But one thing remains clear, wherever mobile is headed, it will be better suited for customer redemption as opposed to customer acquisition.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAgree? Disagree? We&rsquo;d love to hear your feedback. Tweet <a href="http://twitter.com/maxpoint_int" target="_blank">@maxpoint_int</a> with the hashtag (#mobile) and share your thoughts on this topic with us.</p>\r\n	t	2012-01-25 14:41:41	\N	2012-01-25 14:41:41	2013-10-01 20:06:54.28329	55	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, mobile, mobile devices, customer acquisition, customer redemption, Gretchen Joyce, Kurt Carlson, digital, digital advertising, coupons, offers, @maxpoint_int
711	1	20	retailers-shouldnt-put-all-eggs-in-the-online-shopping-basket	Retailers Shouldn't Put All Eggs in the Online Shopping Basket	<p>When news about the liquidation of Borders broke, industry reporters talked about the demise of these retail stores due to the ability to download/read online with new technology (eReaders, tablets, etc). However, to erroneously assume retail stores are going entirely by the way of digital books with the inevitable closing of brick-and-mortar stores, is a bit shortsighted.&nbsp;</p>\r\n	<p>When news about the liquidation of Borders broke, industry reporters talked about the demise of these retail stores due to the ability to download/read online with new technology (eReaders, tablets, etc). However, to erroneously assume retail stores are going entirely by the way of digital books with the inevitable closing of brick-and-mortar stores, is a bit shortsighted.&nbsp; With a little innovation, there is still a huge profit potential in their neighborhood retail locations without losing sight of the importance of the online market.&nbsp; They are, in fact, two very different yet important sales channels.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nBookstores such as Barnes &amp; Noble are more than just a place to buy books, they are a cultural phenomenon that goes beyond print material.&nbsp; The need to buy books for gifts or for reading to a group of children is still very real.&nbsp; I know this firsthand, as I received a last minute invitation to read at my son&rsquo;s preschool class as a mystery reader.&nbsp; I frantically shopped for a book to match their weekly theme. I did not have time to order it online.&nbsp; Not to mention some people will never give up the feel of a real book or magazine.&nbsp; And what about book signings?&nbsp; True, authors can &ldquo;digitally&rdquo; sign an eBook, but it is just not as meaningful.&nbsp; There is validity with a personal introduction to the author, to connect with them and to potentially buy more of their work.&nbsp; There is a human interaction that you simply cannot get online.&nbsp; Bookstores also provide a social scene as a meeting place for coffee, book clubs, study groups, budding musical artists and author lectures, all of which provide the brick-and-mortar store plenty of unique money making opportunities that cannot be made online.&nbsp; It is up to the company to think of their stores beyond a place to buy books and enhance the in-store experience to bolster profits and redefine a culture that spans the vast differences in the current generations.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThis is not to say that stores aren&rsquo;t making a wise choice to push eBooks.&nbsp; They make a lot of money and it is quickly becoming the preferred reading method for many age groups (and I am an avid eBook reader myself).&nbsp; Retailers are, in essence, wisely diversifying their potential customer portfolio.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThere is huge opportunity to drive in-store sales via digital kiosks where a visitor can purchase and download eBooks with perhaps an off-line only incentive to visit their neighborhood store.&nbsp; No one says customers can&rsquo;t bring their digital reader into a store and read in one of the cozy alcoves with oversized chairs.&nbsp; And, while they are there, it gives them an opportunity to browse other books and magazines and have a cup of coffee or tea.&nbsp; Who knows, if the store provides the opportunity, they may also catch a visiting author with whom they may not otherwise have been familiar, or a live acoustic soloist, or they may bump into a friend, or find a potential date.&nbsp; The opportunities could be endless and profitable if planned and marketed correctly.</p>\r\n	t	2012-01-23 16:31:44	\N	2012-01-23 16:31:44	2013-10-01 20:08:25.948445	49	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, Lynn Vitello, retail, in-store traffic, neighborhood, online shopping, bookstores, Barnes & Noble, Borders, sales channels, online, Ereader, tablet, book sales, digital kiosks
710	1	15	nrf-attendees-share-their-new-rules-for-retail	NRF Attendees Share Their New Rules for Retail	<p>This past week, MaxPoint attended the National Retail Federation&rsquo;s 101st Annual Convention &amp; Expo, also known as &ldquo;Retail&rsquo;s Big Show.&rdquo; Celebrating the show&rsquo;s theme, &ldquo;Retail&rsquo;s New Rules,&rdquo; MaxPoint hit the show floor to learn attendees&rsquo; &ldquo;new rules&rdquo; for retail in 2012. In honor of the show&rsquo;s 101st year, MaxPoint surveyed 101 retailers, technology vendors and consultants. Read about the common themes that were found.</p>\r\n	<p>This past week, MaxPoint attended the <a href="http://www.nrf.com/" target="_blank">National Retail Federation&rsquo;s</a> 101st Annual Convention &amp; Expo, also known as &ldquo;Retail&rsquo;s Big Show.&rdquo; Celebrating the show&rsquo;s theme, &ldquo;Retail&rsquo;s New Rules,&rdquo; MaxPoint hit the show floor to learn attendees&rsquo; &ldquo;new rules&rdquo; for retail in 2012. In honor of the show&rsquo;s 101st year, MaxPoint <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/advertising-tips-and-strategies/advertising-insights/101-rules" target="_blank">surveyed</a> 101 retailers, technology vendors and consultants. Below is a sneak preview to the common themes that were found. <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Mobile Adoption:</strong> Attendees placed great emphasis on the need for a mobile strategy in 2012. Needs ranged from wanting to launch a mobile shopper app to enabling mobile payments.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Creating a Seamless Cross-Channel Customer Experience:</strong>&nbsp; Attendees also placed emphasis on continuing to focus on providing a seamless cross-channel experience. According to one attendee, &ldquo;It shouldn&rsquo;t matter what channel my customer comes in through or whether they use multiple channels before ultimately making their purchase. They should receive the same experience at every touch point.&rdquo;<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Security:</strong> From PCI compliance to securing customer information, security is a top priority for many show attendees in 2012.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Customer Service:</strong> Last but not least, a number of attendees shared that they will be placing much more emphasis on customer service in 2012, satisfying the customer at every interaction. Why? Because &ldquo;people remember good service.&rdquo; According to our Vice President of Marketing, Lynn Vitello, &ldquo;our survey revealed the retailers and the vendors that serve them have reverted back to the very first rule of retail &ndash; put the customer first. Many of the rules attendees shared came back to creating the best possible experience for the consumer.&rdquo; Read more about why customer service is key for driving in-store traffic <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/onpoint-blog/2011/10/7/poor-customer-service-can-undo-retailers-efforts-to-drive-in-store-sales-2" target="_blank">here</a>.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nHow do these themes match up to your new rules for retail in 2012? To see the full list of 101 New Rules for Retail collected at &ldquo;Retail&rsquo;s Big Show&rdquo;, click <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/advertising-tips-and-strategies/advertising-insights/101-rules" target="_blank">here</a> and tweet us <a href="https://twitter.com/maxpoint_int" target="_blank">@maxpoint_int</a> to share your new rule for retail in 2012 using the #101retailrule.</p>\r\n	t	2012-01-19 18:03:37	\N	2012-01-19 18:03:37	2013-10-01 20:14:51.759415	49	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, press release, insight, retail, 101 retail rules, NRF, National Retail Federation, #nrf12, Retail's Big Show, Retail's New Rules, mobile, cross-channel, security, customer service, Lynn Vitello, @maxpoint_int, #101retailrule
