719	1	15	the-path-to-purchase-how-is-it-changing-in-2012	The Path-to-Purchase: How is it Changing in 2012?	<p>Retailers and brands are re-thinking marketing strategies this year and allocating more shopper marketing dollars for reaching shoppers at different touch points throughout the path.</p>\r\n	<p>With the emergence of new technologies and new digital channels to advertise on, retailers and brands are noticing the way to reach shoppers throughout the path-to-purchase is changing. In most cases, retailers and brands are re-thinking marketing strategies this year and allocating more shopper marketing dollars for reaching shoppers at different touch points throughout the path. <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nAccording to a survey completed by the <a href="http://p2pi.org/" target="_blank">Path to Purchase Institute</a> in the January 2012 issue of <a href="http://www.shoppermarketingmag.com/home/" target="_blank">Shopper Marketing Magazine</a>, more dollars are being allocated to the shopper marketing budget in 2012 &ndash; as high as a 10% lift from the previous year. Originally focused on in-store marketing, retailers and brands are realizing the opportunities to reach shoppers throughout the entire path-to-purchase - constantly reminding shoppers of a brand as close to the decision making point as possible.&nbsp; So, what has changed? Let&rsquo;s review:<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Smartphone/Tablet penetration:</strong>&nbsp; In the past year, adoption for smartphones and tablets has skyrocketed bringing great new features to users but new opportunities for advertisers as well. Smartphones and tablets are the first devices that can actually travel with the shopper through the complete path-to-purchase. For instance, shoppers can begin the path-to- purchase by researching for coupons and other items to pick up in-store with their smart devices before heading in-store. Shoppers can then travel the path with their devices, researching a product all the way to the store and there are even some applications that assist shoppers in-store &ndash; roughly half of all smartphone owners use devices in-store (<a href="http://www.internetretailer.com/2011/12/07/smartphones-are-transforming-consumers-path-purchase" target="_blank">21%</a> increase from a year ago).<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Pre-store planners:</strong> Most consumers prepare a list before shopping &ndash; it is rarely a spontaneous event, and includes much thought and planning in each trip. Nowadays, the path-to-purchase starts online with shoppers beginning their purchasing experience by completing online research to compare prices, quality and reviews from other shoppers. With shoppers headed online, retailers and brands can now reach these pre-store planners when they are beginning the decision making process. Understanding where to allocate money requires that marketers understand how and where purchase decisions are made, and purchase decisions now begin online &ndash; before heading in-store.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Satisfying shopper budgets:</strong> As more shoppers are mindful of their spending, especially at the start of a new year, retailers look to revise strategies to drive these shoppers in-store. Retailers and brands meet the needs of stressed shoppers by utilizing a strong marketing mix, with focus on shopper marketing activities that still delivers a solid return on investment. If shoppers are mindful of budgets, they may not make a trip in-store and fail to see in-store marketing. However, if shoppers are reached at different touch points throughout the entire path-to-purchase, a retailer can avoid this trap.&nbsp; For example, with digital advertising, retailers can promote in-store offers and/or discounts online that are more mindful to a shopper&rsquo;s budget. Retailers may spend more to drive purchase behavior, but with digital, they have vast opportunities to reach shoppers and get the return on investment.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn 2012, there&rsquo;s no need to guess where to spend your shopper marketing dollars &ndash; spread beyond in-store marketing and reach shoppers at every touch point on the path-to-purchase. How will you reach shoppers on the path-to-purchase this year? Tweet us <a href="https://twitter.com/maxpoint_int" target="_blank">@maxpoint_int</a> with the #mpasks.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n	t	2012-02-09 15:14:36	\N	2012-02-09 15:14:36	2013-10-01 19:43:36.781429	50	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, 2012, path to purchase, path-to-purchase, Shopper Marketing Magazine, shopper marketing, digital advertising, touch points, shoppers, digital, advertising, advertising spend, budget, shopper marketing budget, P2P Institute, smartphone, tablet, @maxpoint_int 
717	1	15	old-navys-team-sport-apparel-an-opportunity-to-take-national-ad-campaign-beyond-just-tv	Old Navy's Team Sport Apparel: An Opportunity to Take National Ad Campaign Beyond just TV	<p>The only problem with living in North Carolina as a Steelers fan, is that team apparel is difficult to find in local retail stores.&nbsp; Fortunately, Old Navy has solved that problem!</p>\r\n	<p>Even though the Super Bowl is over, football season at my house is always in full swing and always ready for some Pittsburgh Steelers action!&nbsp; The only problem with living in North Carolina as a Steelers fan, is that team apparel is difficult to find in local retail stores.&nbsp; Fortunately, Old Navy has solved that problem!<br />\r\n<br />\r\nRecently, <a href="http://www.oldnavy.com/browse/home.do?tid=ongobue8t&amp;kwid=1&amp;ap=7&amp;sem=true&amp;mkwid=6953Gbsh&amp;adid=byq+anil:&amp;creative=9557690643&amp;adpos=1t1" target="_blank">Old Navy</a> expanded its sports-apparel push, unveiling its <a href="http://www.marketwatch.com/story/old-navy-expands-sports-apparel-push-2011-08-13?link=mw_home_kiosk" target="_blank">Super Fan Nation stores-within-stores</a> at about 1,000 locations across the U.S.&nbsp; The stores sell branded goods of more than 70 Division I schools, as well as National Football League teams.&nbsp; In fact, we went to our neighborhood Old Navy store last weekend and bought one Steelers t-shirt for me, one for my husband and one for my son!<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOld Navy supported the effort with a unique, seven-figure marketing campaign that includes advertising at college stadiums and arenas, in-store appearances by college bands, cheerleaders and mascots, and a 10-day national television advertising campaign.&nbsp; This sounds like a great mix, but 10 days of TV ads doesn&rsquo;t really have a lasting effect.&nbsp; This is where they have a golden opportunity to expand their campaign online.&nbsp; They can easily leverage this TV creative and transform it into a video ad and reach more people for a much longer period of time for less money than TV.&nbsp; Companies such as <a href="http://dynamicvideoad.mixpo.com/" target="_blank">Mixpo</a>, can take existing TV commercials and create video display ads out of them, thus increasing the ROI from the original commercial production.&nbsp; Combine that with MaxPoint&rsquo;s ability to target digital ads at the neighborhood level, and you&rsquo;ve just created a truly well rounded ad campaign that will be more targeted and cost effective &ndash; and one that can run significantly longer with a smaller budget.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMy guess is that Old Navy hopes to see a spike in traffic at their in-store locations as a result of this campaign.&nbsp;&nbsp; Competition to draw customers into retail stores continues to heat up, so companies are looking for the next big idea to pull ahead of the race.&nbsp; Old Navy&rsquo;s leap into affordable team sports apparel displays their effort to leave competitors in the dust.&nbsp; Now they just need to take the campaign one step further with digital neighborhood advertising to claim a comfortable lead.</p>\r\n	t	2012-02-06 13:53:21	\N	2012-02-06 13:53:21	2013-10-01 19:53:38.287967	51	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, Lynn Vitello, Old Navy, digital, advertising, traditional advertising, digital advertising, neighborhood, in-store traffic, football, campaign, Mixpo, sports apparel
895	1	49	what-is-the-best-real-estate-in-mobile	What is the Best Real Estate in Mobile?	<p>When you run a mobile campaign, should you spend more on mobile web placements or in-app placements? Read today&#39;s blog post to find out.</p>\r\n	<p><img alt="cell phone" src="/system/editor/W1siZiIsIjIwMTMvMTIvMTEvMTNfMjhfNDdfNzUwX0NlbGxfUGhvbmVfaW5fSGFuZF82NzJ4NDQwLnBuZyJdLFsicCIsInRodW1iIiwiODAweDgwMD4iXV0/Cell-Phone-in-Hand_672x440.png" style="float:right; height:196px; width:300px" />When you think of mobile ads, you probably imagine seeing a banner ad when you go to a site like espn.com on your smartphone. And although that sort of ad is available and can be used to good effect, a lot of mobile power comes from putting relevant ads inside the apps people use on their phones.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you&rsquo;re already advertising on the mobile web, you should seriously consider complementing your efforts by purchasing in-app inventory. Some <a href="http://www.marketingcharts.com/wp/direct/mobile-ads-seeing-higher-click-rates-in-app-than-on-web-35283/" target="_blank">studies</a> have demonstrated that in-app placements tend to have higher click-through rates than mobile web placements. Application ads should not completely replace mobile web display, but they need to be a part of your mix. For starters:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>You&rsquo;ll Get Exclusive Placement with Little Competition&mdash;</strong>The small screen size of most smartphones provides little real estate in each app for advertisements. At first glance, this might seem like a limitation, but it actually provides some key advantages for advertisers. Because most apps can handle only a single banner, every impression is front and center. Your in-app ad will receive more attention than if it were on a mobile website, where it would have to compete with other ads for attention.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>You&rsquo;ll Reach More of Your Audience&mdash;</strong>According to <a href="http://www.comscore.com/Insights/Press_Releases/2012/5/Introducing_Mobile_Metrix_2_Insight_into_Mobile_Behavior" target="_blank">comScore</a>, mobile users spend up to 81.5% of their time using applications. Even though users still surf the mobile web, you&rsquo;ll miss out on a lot of valuable time with your prospects by limiting your ad buys.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>You&rsquo;ll Ensure a Positive Brand Experience&mdash;</strong>Despite the explosion of mobile devices, most companies still don&rsquo;t have mobile-optimized websites. This means you have to keep a vigilant eye on your mobile ad buys to avoid placing your ad on a site that might cause a negative experience for your customers. Because mobile apps are already built for the mobile experience, you know you&rsquo;ll provide your customers with an excellent user experience.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nDespite these advantages, don&rsquo;t drop mobile web impressions from your media plan yet. Some <a href="http://www.journalism.org/2012/10/01/future-mobile-news/" target="_blank">reports</a> show that app users still prefer the mobile browser as their primary way of getting content and news. A consumer reading a news report could be more likely to purchase a related product than they would if seeing an ad on an unrelated app.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ultimately, you want to make sure you have a good mix of both mobile web and application ads. Your perfect mix will depend on your audience, campaign, and current needs. The key is to test until you find the right ratio. Once you find the sweet spot, you&rsquo;ll be in the perfect position to profit from the fastest growing medium.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Have you used application-based mobile ads? If so, tell us about your experience in the comments below.</p>\r\n	t	2013-12-11 18:52:43	\N	2014-01-03 18:56:52.654811	2014-01-03 18:57:41.915427	59	\N
760	1	16	follow-the-data	Follow the Data	<p>My CEO is fond of the expression &ldquo;follow the data.&rdquo; The more I think about it, the more I realize that I&rsquo;ve always agreed. This has been true for every job I&rsquo;ve ever had&mdash;and here at Maxpoint Interactive, we follow this mantra in our continuous quest for better campaign performance and understanding.</p>\r\n	<p>My CEO is fond of the expression &ldquo;follow the data.&rdquo; The more I think about it, the more I realize that I&rsquo;ve always agreed. This has been true for every job I&rsquo;ve ever had&mdash;and here at Maxpoint Interactive, we follow this mantra in our continuous quest for better campaign performance and understanding. No matter what you&rsquo;re doing&mdash;whether you&rsquo;re debugging hardware or software code, performing analyses, whatever&mdash;if you look at the data and listen to what it tells you, you&rsquo;ll find your answer. The trick is trusting that the data doesn&rsquo;t lie, even when it doesn&rsquo;t tell you what you wanted to hear, or take you where you thought it would.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nI think &ldquo;following the data&rdquo; applies to all areas of business or technology. In everyday software engineering and analytics, it seems that often people follow part of the data and come to a conclusion that is almost, but not quite right. If they would look further into the data, look at all the data, they would find the right answer. Analyze it&mdash;what does it really mean? Data will pull you in the direction toward your conclusion, but you&rsquo;ve got to be willing to follow it.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIt&rsquo;s easy for previous views, opinions, or knowledge to lead you astray. It&rsquo;s human nature to get to a point and interpret the signs, to jump ahead to a conclusion. But did the data really tell you that? Be diligent at following through. If you think something is an issue or area of concern, get data around it to prove it. Don&rsquo;t get caught in the trap of following data to a certain point, but not all the way.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nUse the scientific method&mdash;look at the available information, and use it to home in on your hypothesis. Then confirm, deny, or adjust your hypothesis as needed. The quality of your original hypothesis may come from the experience you have in your field&mdash;but in the end, it&rsquo;s the data that will lead you to the correct, and most critical, answer. If you&rsquo;re not following the data&mdash;you&rsquo;re guessing.</p>\r\n	t	2012-04-20 13:00:43	\N	2012-04-20 13:00:43	2013-09-27 02:59:20.879844	52	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, data, data analysis, OnPoint, data trends
