726	1	15	understanding-the-mom-shopper-while-planning-for-the-back-to-school-season	Understanding the Mom Shopper While Planning for the Back-to-School Season	<p>One very popular target audience today is the Mom shopper. With back-to-school campaign planning beginning this month, many retailers and brands will be focusing advertising campaigns around the mom shopper. Today, we&rsquo;re here to share the following insights on the mom shopper.</p>\r\n	<p>In order to reach shoppers and drive in-store traffic, retailers need to first understand their shoppers, what they are looking for and how they are looking for it.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMarketers have several target audience groups today and they each vary based on several variables such as location, demographics, psychographics and more.&nbsp;&nbsp; And, many industry professionals spend time researching and sifting through data in order to understand and effectively reach their target audience. One very popular target audience today is the Mom shopper. With back-to-school campaign planning beginning this month, many retailers and brands will be focusing advertising campaigns around the mom shopper. Today, we&rsquo;re here to share the following insights on the mom shopper. <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Where Moms are looking:</strong> In 2012, meet the digital mom. Before heading in-store, <a href="http://www.socialmediaexaminer.com/social-media-differences-among-teens-boomers-and-moms-new-study-findings" target="_blank">moms head online</a> &ndash; did you know that 44% of moms use social media for word-of-mouth recommendations on products and 73% feel they find trustworthy information about brands and products online? A mother&rsquo;s time is valuable and in order to manage time, mom&rsquo;s put preparation into everything. Once online, moms complete store research, find the best deals and prepare a list &ndash; they never go shopping unprepared. And, as more mom shoppers head online, the gap between traditional and digital channels is closing quickly.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>How Moms are shopping:</strong> According to Advertising Age author, Tina Sharkey, &ldquo;Motherhood triggers big changes in how women spend their time, how they consume media. <strong>And how they shop</strong>.&rdquo; Research indicates that mom shoppers use every available resource to gain a competitive, budget-friendly edge when shopping. Today, more moms are equipped and using their mobile devices when shopping. Almost two-thirds of mom shoppers have a bar code scanner app on their mobile phone. And, moms use mobile devices in-store to look up product reviews, share discounts and post online reviews.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>What Moms are thinking:</strong> Whether it&rsquo;s the back-to-school shopping season or not, moms are looking for the best deals and offers a retailer has to give. In addition, when marketing to the mom shopper, keep their families in mind. Often times, moms keep their kids&rsquo; preferences in mind when heading in-store. According to a recent <a href="http://www.retailwire.com/discussion/14632/new-reality-of-marketing-to-older-moms" target="_blank">article</a> in Retail Wire, 42% of mom shoppers over the age of 35 agree that their children have a significant impact on the brands they choose.&nbsp; At the same time, 33% of these mom shoppers agreed that advertising helps them choose products as well, so really make sure you&rsquo;re marketing a product both moms and their families are interested in.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOnce you gain insight into how moms are shopping and what they are thinking, what will you do with the information? Use localized advertising to serve relevant online ads to Moms that live within a specific radius of a retail location and are interested in and/or have the purchasing power to buy a certain product.&nbsp; More on localized advertising <a href="http://maxpoint.com/rsrreport" target="_blank">here</a>.</p>\r\n	t	2012-02-21 16:14:55	\N	2012-02-21 16:14:55	2013-10-01 19:13:01.921425	49	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, mom, retailers, brands, advertising, back-to-school, back-to-school campaigns, campaign planning, insights, digital mom, digital, Advertising Age, Tina Sharkey, RetailWire, localized digital advertising, local 
873	1	15	measuring-your-digital-ad-campaigns	Measuring Your Digital Ad Campaigns: Do You Know Where Your Sales Are?	<p>Digital advertising works&mdash;but how well did a specific digital campaign work? Find out in the first post in our series on measuring the effects of your digital ad campaigns.</p>\r\n	<p>Digital advertising works. Even brands that have traditionally advertised offline are shifting more to digital advertising each year. They know it&rsquo;s cost-effective and that it produces strong returns (including offline sales).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The real question for today&rsquo;s advertiser, then, is not does digital advertising work, but how much did a <em>specific</em> digital campaign help? Does the ad&rsquo;s creative hit the mark with the intended audience? And does it really lift sales?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Answering these questions is paramount for any campaign&mdash;whether it&rsquo;s a branding campaign or a direct sales campaign.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="MaxPoint Measurement Guide" src="/system/editor/W1siZiIsIjIwMTMvMDkvMDkvMTBfNDlfMDhfMzg2X01lYXN1cmVtZW50XzM3NXgzMDAucG5nIl0sWyJwIiwidGh1bWIiLCI4MDB4ODAwPiJdXQ/Measurement_375x300.png" style="float:left; height:173px; margin:0px 10px; width:214px" />Over the next few weeks, we&rsquo;re going to review the different options you have for measuring your digital campaigns&rsquo; effects. There are several key types of studies that you can run, depending on your campaign goal and your budget. We&rsquo;ll cover the finer details later, but for now, here are the broad strokes:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>Sales Lift Studies&mdash;</strong>Wouldn&rsquo;t you love to put a dollar amount on your increase in sales? Sales lift studies help you do that. They measure how much your campaign boosted sales in an area or over a period of time, and then provide key insights to help you on your next digital campaign. And yes, these studies can get expensive&mdash;but they don&rsquo;t have to break your budget. In fact, there are three different styles of sales lift studies, each with their own price tags. We&rsquo;ll cover all three, including their pros and cons, so you know which one to pick for your situation.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Brand Lift Surveys&mdash;</strong>Advertising can&rsquo;t always be measured in direct dollars and cents. Building a strong brand is more a marathon than a sprint. Before the digital age, measuring such intangible, yet critical, variables as brand awareness and favorability was a matter of gathering people into a room for focus groups or paying for costly surveys from data researchers and professional interviewers. With digital advertising, a campaign&rsquo;s effect on brand perception can come into focus much more easily and cost-effectively. We&rsquo;ll cover brand lift surveys in-depth and even pull back the curtain on some of the questions MaxPoint typically asks after campaigns.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Audience Match Studies&mdash;</strong>Digital provides the biggest bang for the advertising buck by targeting audiences far more precisely than print or TV can. Because a campaign&rsquo;s success can be directly attributed to the customers reached, audience match studies measure the overall efficiency of a campaign&rsquo;s targeting.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nOver the next few weeks, you&rsquo;ll get the inside track on how each of these studies are run, how much they cost, and what the pros and cons are of each. We&rsquo;ll debunk a few myths while bringing the measurement landscape into crisper focus. We&rsquo;ll even draw back the curtain on some of our own campaigns and show you how we&rsquo;ve applied these studies and learned key insights.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Stay tuned for <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/onpoint-blog/2013/9/12/measuring-your-digital-ad-campaigns-the-conundrum-of-clicks" target="_blank">next week&rsquo;s post</a>, in which we debunk a few myths about online measurement and show you why click-through rates may tell only part of the story.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Don&rsquo;t Want to Wait?</strong><br />\r\n<a href="http://offers.maxpoint.com/measurement" target="_blank">Download our free measurement guide</a> now to learn more about putting your digital campaigns to the measurement test.</p>\r\n	t	2013-09-06 13:38:20	\N	2013-09-06 13:43:13.857252	2013-10-15 13:20:21.648355	62	\N
739	1	15	when-planning-a-shopper-marketing-strategy-keep-local-in-mind	When Planning a Shopper Marketing Strategy Keep Local in Mind	<p>Retailers today are constantly looking for ways to increase their shopper marketing initiatives to reach shoppers to drive traffic and move products off the shelves. How can you leverage local this year?</p>\r\n	<p>Retailers today are constantly looking for ways to increase their shopper marketing initiatives to reach shoppers to drive traffic and move products off the shelves. <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn 2012, localization is becoming a key part of brand strategies. Their goal is to drive local in-store traffic to move products off the shelves by reaching qualified shoppers with localized efforts. Below are a few ways you can leverage local this year:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>Make Room for Localized Advertising:</strong> Incorporate digital into a shopper marketing campaign with localized advertising and reach pre-store planners. According to Forrester Research, digital is the number one medium for ages 18-44 and by 2014 the Web will be influencing $1.4B worth of in-store sales. Shoppers spend their money close to home, yet increasingly spend more time online before going to the store. Take advantage of this and target your most valuable shoppers dynamically and easily, with all of the precision and none of the waste. Read more on localized advertising <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/onpoint-blog/2012/2/22/what-is-the-state-of-localized-advertising-in-retail" target="_blank">here</a>.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Leverage Mobile:</strong> Leverage mobile in 2012 to reach shoppers headed in-store and while in-store. For example, Hy-Vee Food Stores signed on with aisle411 to offer its mobile shoppers a way to find products in-store. The app accesses retail inventory data and floor maps to make the products available for shoppers searchable. In addition, other retailers encourage shoppers to re