738	1	15	san-francisco-residents-are-most-interested-in-new-consumer-technology	San Francisco Residents are Most Interested in New Consumer Technology	<p>As many of you already know, Apple released their newest iPad last week! Where are the U.S. neighborhoods most interested in being &ldquo;up&rdquo; on the newest consumer technology?</p>\r\n	<p>As many of you already know, Apple released their newest iPad last week! Surrounded by the chatter of the upcoming launch for weeks, we started wondering who exactly was most interested in the release of not just this product, but the latest technology products in general. Today, we released our monthly indexing study that analyzed billions of data points to determine the U.S. neighborhoods most interested in being &ldquo;up&rdquo; on the newest consumer technology. Using our unique Digital Zip&trade; technology, the data points analyzed help provide advertisers with insight into the U.S. neighborhoods most interested in consumer technology. <!--more--></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Fueled by the surge of activity surrounding Apple&rsquo;s iPad launch, San Francisco topped the list of cities with people who enjoy reading the latest technology rumors and staying ahead of the curve with tech industry knowledge. The top ten cities with neighborhoods that indexed the highest in the country for people most interested in the latest and greatest technology products include:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>San Francisco, CA</li>\r\n\t<li>Lafayette, IN</li>\r\n\t<li>West Palm Beach, FL</li>\r\n\t<li>Sacramento, CA</li>\r\n\t<li>Los Angeles, CA</li>\r\n\t<li>Honolulu, HI</li>\r\n\t<li>Miami, FL</li>\r\n\t<li>Chicago, IL</li>\r\n\t<li>New York, NY</li>\r\n\t<li>Tampa, FL</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nUsing the data gleamed from this index; we implemented highly targeted neighborhood-level digital ad campaigns for a variety of consumer technology retailers and brands, including:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>A major global technology company looking to raise awareness and drive sales in the U.S. of a new consumer pocket projector product launching later this year. MaxPoint helped the company drive traffic to a specific retail outlet and attract men within a 10 mile radius who had an average household income of $75K or higher.</li>\r\n\t<li>One of the world&rsquo;s most famous technology companies, interested in driving in-store traffic at its new U.S. retail locations. MaxPoint helped the company identify and target consumers between 30-45 years old, with an average household income of $75K or higher, that live within a 15 mile radius of the retail store.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nAccording to our COO, Gretchen Joyce, &ldquo;while it may not be surprising that San Francisco topped the list as having the most people interested in hot new technology, it&rsquo;s unlikely retailers and brands would have concluded that Lafayette or West Palm Beach are the number two and three most &lsquo;tech hungry&rsquo; cities. The insights we are able to provide retailers and brands allow them to take highly-relevant consumer interest data and make it actionable within minutes.&rdquo;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nTo read the full press release, click <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/online-advertising-news/new-consumer-technology-interest" target="_blank">here</a>.</p>\r\n	t	2012-03-13 14:22:04	\N	2012-03-13 14:22:04	2013-10-01 15:19:25.286142	54	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, interest data, OnPoint, indexing study, MaxPoint interest index, iPad, Apple, technology, consumer technology, data, Digital Zip, neighborhoods, San Francisco, Gretchen Joyce, press release
737	1	15	optimizing-campaigns-in-months-of-high-online-clutter	Optimizing Campaigns in Months of High Online Clutter 	<p>What do the Super Bowl, March Madness and upcoming holidays like Easter and Memorial Day have in common? Lots of planning, parties and most importantly high online chatter. And, what does this have to do with you?</p>\r\n	<p>What do the Super Bowl, March Madness and upcoming holidays like Easter and Memorial Day have in common? Lots of planning, parties and most importantly high online chatter. And, what does this have to do with you? <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nOn Twitter, for example, famous celebrities or songs of the week are overshadowed by holiday events as the upcoming holiday becomes the trending topic. Holiday hashtags are used, holiday blog posts are written, holiday/party recipes are pinned on Pinterest &ndash; the list goes on. Fortunately for advertisers, this is a great time to reach consumers because online traffic is high. However, these months can also cause an increase in high online clutter (aka chatter) and potentially distract consumers from normal online browsing habits. No matter what time of year, advertisers can re-focus their efforts and stay visible and relevant by leveraging these three tips:<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Leverage video</strong>. Display or banner ads can be very effective at reaching your audience but may not stand out to the distracted consumer. Video advertising is catchy and less-likely to get missed. In addition, online habits as far as what is tweeted about and browsed for may change during these times, but many consumers still maintain other habits such as catching up on shows online. Reach shoppers with online video advertising when they tune-in to these shows. And, one thing&rsquo;s for sure &ndash; consumers watch their video. For instance, did you know consumers are watching more than 21 hours of online video per month (on average) across a variety of connected devices?<br />\r\n<br />\r\nFor more stats on video consumption and video ad growth, click <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/onpoint-blog/2012/2/27/what-is-contributing-to-the-rapid-growth-of-digital-video-ad-spending" target="_blank">here</a>. For more information on online video advertising solutions, click <a href="http://www.maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-solutions" target="_blank">here</a>.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Revise messaging</strong>. To help avoid getting drowned out, cut through the clutter and join the conversation around a big holiday event in your advertising creative. Use keywords or messaging related to the holiday/event to catch the attention of those consumers browsing and talking about it online. If you are launching a new product or promoting a special offer, tie the holiday/event to that messaging to make it relevant.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Provide incentives</strong>. If there is one way to catch someone&rsquo;s attention, it&rsquo;s through incentives. During major holidays and national events like March Madness, people are headed to stores and looking for the best deals. Party planners like to buy in bulk, so entice consumers to engage with ads by offering in-store coupons on bulk items or buy one get one free items.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nKeep the above in mind and you can reach relevant consumers and drive in-store traffic no matter what time of year it is. Get creative, get digital and drive in-store traffic.</p>\r\n	t	2012-03-12 15:43:26	\N	2012-03-12 15:43:26	2013-10-01 15:21:59.54986	51	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, campaigns, clutter, online, online campaigns, digital campaigns, digital, advertisers, video, video advertising
732	1	15	youve-started-reaching-the-right-shoppers-online-now-what	You've Started Reaching the Right Shoppers Online, Now What?	<p>You&rsquo;ve launched a strategic online advertising campaign to drive traffic to your store and you start seeing an increase of shoppers in the store &ndash; but it doesn&rsquo;t end there, right? You have to also apply in-store marketing strategies and tactics to ensure they not only stay in the store, but that they make purchases.</p>\r\n	<p>You&rsquo;ve launched a strategic online advertising campaign to drive traffic to your store and you start seeing an increase of shoppers in the store &ndash; but it doesn&rsquo;t end there, right? You have to also apply in-store marketing strategies and tactics to ensure they not only stay in the store, but that they make purchases. <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nAccording to an interview in Wall Street Journal with Dina Howell, Chief Executive of Saatchi &amp; Saatchi X, strategic marketing in its purest form is figuring out what the consumer need is, developing an idea of meeting that need, and then getting into people&rsquo;s heads online and in the store. And, retailers and brands can achieve this by having one consistent message across different mediums.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn-store marketing, specifically the use of in-store displays, is a great addition to ensure a strong marketing mix. Continue the messaging used to reach shoppers online with the same, consistent messaging in-store. In-store displays stand-out and make it easy for shoppers to find and quickly grab a product. In addition, digital displays can also help reinforce what shoppers already think they know about a product.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nFor example, Best Buy stores have digital display centers with useful and informative content on their Kinect demo. Shoppers can browse for more information on the product and also test out the demo live. Not only is this informative but lets the shopper get a real feel for the product themselves. Other stores, like Walmart, also use in-store displays that tie together the ad and creative space used to reach shoppers online.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn-store displays can truly make or break a shopping experience. But remember, this is not enough alone. Pair in-store display or marketing efforts with digital advertising before shoppers head in store to ensure that you are getting the most out of your advertising efforts. In-store displays are great but ineffective if your messaging and creative aren&rsquo;t consistent with your online advertising campaign you launched to help drive them to your store.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhat are some creative displays you&rsquo;ve seen? Tweet us a picture <a href="https://twitter.com/maxpoint_int" target="_blank">@maxpoint_int</a> with the hashtag #onpoint.</p>\r\n	t	2012-03-05 16:35:19	\N	2012-03-05 16:35:19	2013-10-01 18:32:32.195634	50	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, retail, digital, in-store, in-store displays, digital advertising, in-store marketing, Wall Street Journal, Dina Howell, Saatchi & Saatchi X, @maxpoint_int 
