747	1	15	strategies-to-reduce-long-waiting-lines-for-shoppers	Strategies to Reduce Long Waiting Lines for Shoppers	<p>To help combat long waiting lines, more and more retailers are trying new strategies to get shoppers&nbsp; through checkout faster and create a pleasant experience as they exit the store. Let&rsquo;s take a look at what some retailers are doing to improve waiting lines.</p>\r\n	<p>Did you know the average person waits about an hour per day in line? By the time a shopper has spent two or three minutes in line, the perceived wait time is multiplied by each passing minute according to a study by Envirosell. Shoppers get impatient quickly and choose their own line based on key indicators around them such as age of people in line, number of kids, and size of basket. Some of you may think waiting lines are only long during the holidays, but retailers know the checkout line can be long any time of the year.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nTo help combat long waiting lines, more and more retailers are trying new strategies to get shoppers&nbsp; through checkout faster and create a pleasant experience as they exit the store. Let&rsquo;s take a look at what some retailers are doing to improve waiting lines.<span id="cke_bm_100C" style="display:none">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>Installing electronic devices:</strong> Apple sets a great example by using hand-held devices to ring up purchases anywhere in the store, while Whole Foods and Home Depot implemented a mobile checkout. We all know self-checkout lanes are popular in grocery chains but more and more big-box retailers are adding them to help prevent long lines too.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Entertaining customers:</strong> Walt Disney stores distract customers in line, at peak traffic times, by entertaining customers with Disney trivia until they get to the register. &ldquo;Once they get to the register, it&rsquo;s about ensuring they have everything they need, do they need more than one bag, do they need a gift receipt, a gift certificate,&rdquo; says Paul Gainer, senior vice president of retail for Disney Store.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Placing cashiers front and center:</strong> To help shoppers tell which checkout lanes are open, Home Depot instructs cashiers to stand at the front of their registers.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Pre-scanning items:</strong> Home Depot also deploys what they call &ldquo;line busters&rdquo; as soon as they see three or more people waiting in line. Employees simply pre-scan shopping cart products before customers reach the cashier. Disney uses this approach too, which has helped their stores maintain a single-file line. By doing so, shoppers perceive the checkout process as less stressful.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nTo further demonstrate the checkout experience to retailers, The Wall Street Journal&nbsp; shared a graphic a few months ago called, &ldquo;The Science of Lines: What&rsquo;s really happening at checkout&rdquo;. See image below.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<a href="http://www.maxpointinteractive.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/ReduceWaitingLines.jpg" target="_blank"><img alt="" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-2103" src="http://www.maxpointinteractive.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/ReduceWaitingLines-300x256.jpg" style="height:256px; width:300px" title="ReduceWaitingLines" /></a><br />\r\n<br />\r\nSource: Wall Street Journal<br />\r\n<br />\r\nHow are you reducing waiting times for your shoppers? Share with us below or tweet us <a href="https://twitter.com/maxpoint_int" target="_blank">@maxpoint_int</a> with the hashtag #onpoint.</p>\r\n	t	2012-03-27 15:01:48	\N	2012-03-27 15:01:48	2013-09-29 18:56:26.832906	50	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, Onpoint, shoppers, retail, waiting lines, checkout, shopper marketing, Wall Street Journal, Apple, Walt Disney, Home Depot 
746	1	15	retailing-for-the-educated-consumer	Retailing for the Educated Consumer 	<p>Educated consumers spend time completing research and utilizing multiple resources to find the best deals to get the most out of their shopping experience. They are receptive to messaging and willing to learn what you have to offer. So, how can you continue to engage and inform the educated consumer?</p>\r\n	<p><a href="http://online.wsj.com/article/SB125859990358854959.html" target="_blank">Sy Syms</a>, an American businessman, entrepreneur and philanthropist, who founded the SYMS off-price clothing chain in New York City, once said, &ldquo;An educated consumer is our best customer.&rdquo;<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nAccording to a Deloitte&rsquo;s American Pantry study, 75% of shoppers believe they are smarter shoppers than they were a year ago. Educated consumers spend time completing research and utilizing multiple resources to find the best deals to get the most out of their shopping experience. They are receptive to messaging and willing to learn what you have to offer.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSo, how can you continue to engage and inform the educated consumer? We&rsquo;ve compiled a few tips:<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Educate online.</strong> With vast online resources available, more consumers are searching and completing online research before heading in-store. Savvy shoppers will make it their business to know what they want before heading in-store.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nTailor online advertising messaging to inform shoppers about how a new product or offer is beneficial to them or provide tips on how to use a certain product. Then prompt shoppers to head in-store to learn more.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Educate in-store.</strong> Shoppers may have completed online research before heading in-store but that doesn&rsquo;t mean they don&rsquo;t want to learn more once in the store. This is where customer service and effective in-store messaging is key.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMake sure all employees on the floor are ready to handle customer questions and have the resources to search for answers that they may not know off-hand &ndash; for instance, if a competitor has the same product for less. In addition, use in-store displays to give shoppers tips on how to use a product or recommend products that would fit similar needs. Some in-store displays can be equipped with QR codes to direct shoppers to an online site that will answer more questions or provide an interactive element to let the shoppers get a real feel for the product. More recently, retailers are setting up displays that have an employee demonstrate how a product can be used. For example, some grocers cook for shoppers that are in-store using some of the featured aisle items.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Get to know shoppers.</strong>&nbsp; Shoppers become repeat customers because they feel that a certain retailer or brand understands what they want out of a product and appeals to their shopper needs in messaging.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nPay attention to customer reviews and conversations they are having with other customers online. If they are asking questions, provide answers. Based on what you hear, you can tailor your messaging to suit their needs.</p>\r\n	t	2012-03-26 14:39:13	\N	2012-03-26 14:39:13	2013-09-29 18:58:10.331409	49	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, retail,  retailing, educated consumers, customer service, online advertising
