744	1	16	technology-standards-vs-innovation	Technology Standards vs. Innovation	<p>A few months back, when it was announced that the Interactive Advertising Bureau (IAB) took over the Open RTB initiative, it got me thinking. When is a good time to implement technology standards?</p>\r\n	<p>A few months back, when it was announced that the Interactive Advertising Bureau (IAB) took over the Open RTB initiative, it got me thinking. When is a good time to implement technology standards?<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nMaybe there&rsquo;s a &ldquo;too soon&rdquo; to be standardizing within a technology. There&rsquo;s definitely a balance to maintain, but I think attempting to standardize too early on can come at the cost of threatening, or even stifling, innovation. I think there needs to be a careful balance between letting things evolve naturally, versus standardizing.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAs a long-time developer, I have a healthy respect for technological standards. There are definitely merits to having them&mdash;they can allow technologies to interact and work together, they can grow systems, and they can certainly make development faster, even easier at times. On the other hand, standards can limit the pace at which innovation can occur. Because committees get involved in standard setting, this opens the door to various agendas dictating the specifications. The process of setting standards can introduce politics into the mix, which can put artificial limits on innovation.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThere&rsquo;s no right or wrong answer. We just need to remember that as technologies grow and decisions are made, it&rsquo;s a tradeoff. Stay aware of this, and try to make the best decision for the technology.</p>\r\n	t	2012-03-21 14:14:37	\N	2012-03-21 14:14:37	2013-09-29 18:59:49.60912	52	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, technology, technology standards, IAB, Interactive Advertising Bureau
743	1	15	creating-campaigns-that-speak-to-shoppers	Creating Campaigns that Speak to Shoppers	<p>When launching a campaign, one of the keys to success is making sure the message &ldquo;speaks&rdquo; to your target audience.&nbsp; How do you do this?</p>\r\n	<p>When launching a campaign, one of the keys to success is making sure the message &ldquo;speaks&rdquo; to your target audience.&nbsp; How do you do this? Motivate shoppers to take action after seeing your campaign by creating visuals and messages that are relevant and have value to them. Below are a few examples of campaigns that paid close attention to their target audience&rsquo;s needs when developing their campaigns.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Coke&rsquo;s cause campaign:</strong> A few months ago, Coca-Cola launched a campaign with the World Wildlife Fund to produce an all-white limited-edition can for its winter &ldquo;Artic Home&rdquo; campaign that draws attention to how the climate change has impacted the Artic habitat. Knowing that supporting causes is important to its soft drinkers, Coca-Cola appealed to its audience by raising awareness and funds (in addition to selling soft drinks) to help protect the polar bear population.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Kellogg&rsquo;s &ldquo;Just Dance&rdquo; campaign:</strong> Many shoppers shop together, specifically families. And one of the reasons for this is that family&rsquo;s value the time they spend together. By understanding their audience, Kellogg&rsquo;s launched a campaign where specifically marked boxes of cereal, Pop-Tarts, and Rice Krispies Treats included codes that unlocked exclusive content in the &ldquo;Just Dance 3&rdquo; video game &ndash; a game families frequently play together. Family friendly and unity were key focuses here for this campaign.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>French&rsquo;s mom campaign:</strong> According to a post in the March 2012 issue of Shopper Marketing Magazine, &ldquo;historically, mom is the hero during the holiday season when she uses French fried onions to make green bean casserole.&rdquo; French&rsquo;s rolled out a campaign that redesigned packaging to attract attention and started calling out recipe ideas providing mom with more French&rsquo;s coupons. For this campaign, the focus was all about mom and providing a solution for an easier, faster way to leverage French&rsquo;s during the holiday seasons.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSo, what do all of the above have in common? These brands considered what mattered to their target audience and tailored messaging to meet their needs. Your audience wants to know you care about what they care about. Take some of the marketing elements above and pair with digital advertising to target the right audience online and you&rsquo;ll be on your way to campaign success!<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhat are some creative ways you&rsquo;ve let your audience know you care? Share with us below or tweet <a href="https://twitter.com/maxpoint_int" target="_blank">@maxpoint_int</a> with the hashtag #onpoint.</p>\r\n	t	2012-03-20 15:56:28	\N	2012-03-20 15:56:28	2013-09-29 19:00:55.589793	49	creative advertising campaign 2012, creative campaigns, campaigns, MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, digital advertising
742	1	15	understanding-the-hispanic-shopper-part-ii-hispanic-identity	Understanding the Hispanic Shopper Part II: Hispanic Identity 	<p>The U.S. Hispanic shopper is part of a rapidly growing consumer group with tremendous buying power that requires close attention from retailers and brands in 2012. And, if you want part of the $1.3 trillion Hispanics are predicted to spend by 2015, you must first understand the Hispanic shopper.</p>\r\n	<p>The U.S. Hispanic shopper is part of a rapidly growing consumer group with tremendous buying power that requires close attention from retailers and brands in 2012. And, if you want part of the $1.3 trillion Hispanics are predicted to spend by 2015, you must first understand the Hispanic shopper. <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/onpoint-blog/2012/1/9/understanding-the-hispanic-shopper" target="_blank">Part 1</a> of Understanding the Hispanic Shopper, we discussed some things to keep in mind when targeting the Hispanic shopper this year &ndash;including insights into their high technology adoption, strong buying power and their receptiveness to digital messaging. For part II, we will dig a little deeper and explore how Hispanics identify themselves. Why? Once you understand this, you can better tailor your digital campaign messaging and advertising efforts.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAccording to a recent post written by David Morse, author at Advertising Age, &ldquo;multicultural marketers need to be mindful that race and ethnicity are, and always have been, fluid concepts&hellip;To be successful, we will need to remove our cultural blinders and anachronistic conceptions and speak the language of whatever new America is evolving.&rdquo; In other words, marketing to Hispanics five years ago should not reflect the marketing efforts being made today. Here are a few take aways from the research study on Spanish and Latin Americans referenced in Morse&rsquo;s article:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>Today, only 2% of foreign-born Hispanics indicate they are non-Hispanic vs. the 12% of U.S. born Hispanics who indicate they are non-Hispanic.</li>\r\n\t<li>Intermarriage with non-Hispanics will affect how Hispanics identify or are receptive to multi-cultural messaging in years to come.</li>\r\n\t<li>There is a loss of Spanish as a primary language among U.S. born Hispanics, and non-Spanish speakers are significantly less likely to call themselves Hispanic.</li>\r\n\t<li>Respondents of Latin American/Spanish ancestry who identified their race as white, black or Asian were several times more likely to identify as non-Hispanic than those who said that their race was mixed or &quot;some other race&rdquo;.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nWhy is this important to know? Given that the majority of future growth in the Hispanic market will be driven by U.S. born Hispanics, it is important to understand that they will relate to their heritage differently than their parents and grandparents. According to the research referenced, Hispanics will begin to assimilate into the mainstream as future generations of Hispanics will be more likely to identify with their race vs. their Hispanic heritage. Understanding this will help you tailor your advertising messaging and make sure your marketing efforts are as effective as possible. To read the full article on what&rsquo;s to become of the Hispanic identity at Advertising Age, click <a href="http://adage.com/article/the-big-tent/hispanics-a-distinct-race/231992/" target="_blank">here</a>.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nShare your thoughts on how to best market to Hispanics by leaving your comments below.</p>\r\n	t	2012-03-19 13:52:12	\N	2012-03-19 13:52:12	2013-09-17 14:23:13.314719	49	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, Hispanics, Hispanic shopper, Hispanic identity, David Morse, Advertising Age, multi-cultural advertising, multi-cultural messaging, digital advertising
753	1	15	gaming-a-new-way-to-engage-with-shoppers	Gaming: A New Way to Engage With Shoppers	<p>In 2012, consumers are looking to retailers to continue to find new ways to get and keep them engaged. Cue &ndash; &ldquo;gamification&rdquo;. According to a recent post in Retail TouchPoints &ndash; Gamification Goes Mainstream &ndash; games and competition are proving to be successful ways to engage shoppers.</p>\r\n	<p>In 2012, consumers are looking to retailers to continue to find new ways to get and keep them engaged. Cue &ndash; &ldquo;gamification&rdquo;.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAccording to a recent post in Retail TouchPoints &ndash; <a href="http://www.retailtouchpoints.com/datapoints-of-the-week/1450-gamification-goes-mainstream-infographic#.T1-D_UIPJPs.twitter" target="_blank">Gamification Goes Mainstream</a> &ndash; games and competition are proving to be successful ways to engage shoppers. Below are some highlights and a snapshot of an infographic shared in this article.<!--more--><span id="cke_bm_99C" style="display:none">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>Companies will spend about $2.8B on gamification by 2015. Brands getting gamified in upcoming years include Coke, Nike, Nissan and Pepsi.</li>\r\n\t<li>Leveraging games to engage with shoppers can increase loyalty and drive traffic. For instance, Walmart recently <a href="http://www.chainstoreage.com/article/walmart-launch-retail-gaming-store-experience-angry-birds">announced</a> that it will partner with Angry Birds to allow Walmart customers to access special &ldquo;golden eggsteroid&rdquo; clues. These clues will unlock bonus levels and Angry Bird merchandise available in Walmart stores.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="http://www.maxpointinteractive.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/Gamification1.jpg"><img alt="" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-2167" src="http://www.maxpointinteractive.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/Gamification1-148x300.jpg" style="height:300px; width:148px" title="Gamification" /></a><br />\r\n<br />\r\nSource: Big Door Graphic, 2011<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIt&rsquo;s exciting to see retailers and brands continually use creative and unique ways to engage shoppers. However, don&rsquo;t forget to optimize on all levels. Engage with shoppers online with <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/onpoint-blog/2012/1/11/why-local-should-be-part-of-your-2012-advertising-strategy" target="_blank">localized digital advertising</a> and continue to engage in-store with digital displays and in-store messaging.</p>\r\n	t	2012-04-04 14:46:42	\N	2012-04-04 14:46:42	2013-09-27 03:16:08.730619	49	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, gamification, brand loyalty, localized digital advertising 
752	1	15	retailers-trends-to-keep-you-ahead	Retailers: Trends to Keep You Ahead	<p>An Interbrand report recently revealed its list of the top 50 U.S. retail brands, with Walmart, Target and The Home Depot coming out on top. And while these retail brands lead the pack financially, other efforts such as their role in the purchase decision process and brand loyalty helped too. So, how can you start to become a leading retailer if you&rsquo;re not already?</p>\r\n	<p>An Interbrand <a href="http://www.interbrand.com/en/BestRetailBrands/2012-Best-Retail-Brands.aspx" target="_blank">report</a> recently revealed its list of the top 50 U.S. retail brands, with Walmart, Target and The Home Depot coming out on top. And while these retail brands lead the pack financially, other efforts such as their role in the purchase decision process and brand loyalty helped too. So, how can you start to become a leading retailer if you&rsquo;re not already?<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nAccording to Lorna Pappas, contributing writer for Retail TouchPoints, there are five prominent global retail trends that retailers should keep in mind to build their brand: the need to be agile, a focus on the path to purchase, brand theme, brand value with design and the promise of omni-channel retail. Below we&rsquo;ve expanded on a few of the trends we think are important.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Advertise where your customers are:</strong> Shoppers today have more opportunities to decide where and when they choose to receive and interact with retailers. For instance, with the emergence of new technology, shoppers can head online via their laptop or smart devices to receive advertisements and search for retailer reviews. According to Pappas, &ldquo;the only location for retail is where the customers are.&rdquo;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAnd, how can you advertise where your customers are? Deliver relevant advertising to shoppers who match your shopper profile and live within a specific mile radius of your store location using localized digital advertising. More on localized digital advertising <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/onpoint-blog/2012/1/26/local-matters-to-retailers-in-2012">here</a>.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Focus on the path to purchase:</strong> By paying attention to the way consumers make purchase decisions, retailers can anticipate shoppers&rsquo; moves and find new opportunities to be innovative and build relationships at every touch point.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nTips for reaching shoppers along the path to purchase <a href="http://maxpointinteractive.com/onpoint-blog/2012/03/14/when-planning-a-shopper-http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/onpoint-blog/2012/3/14/when-planning-a-shopper-marketing-strategy-keep-local-in-mind" target="_blank">here</a>.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Create a strong brand:</strong> When creating a brand, retailers must keep in mind what speaks to their shoppers &ndash; expanding beyond the shopper&rsquo;s need for function and identity to adding emotion and dimension. Continually re-evaluate your brand message to make sure that your messages appeal to shoppers. For instance, if your shoppers are moms, focus on tailoring your message to moms and how your products can be beneficial to them.</p>\r\n	t	2012-04-03 13:00:38	\N	2012-04-03 13:00:38	2013-09-27 03:19:22.043878	49	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, retail trends, global retail trends, localized digital advertising, digital advertising
751	1	15	consumers-look-to-retailers-to-keep-easter-baskets-full	Consumers Look to Retailers to Keep Easter Baskets Full	<p>Like Halloween, Christmas and Valentine&rsquo;s Day, Easter is another sweet holiday where consumers ignore their budgets and dietary restrictions and open their arms and wallets to chocolate, candy and new purchases. So, what&rsquo;s in-store for retailers this Easter holiday?</p>\r\n	<p>Like Halloween, Christmas and Valentine&rsquo;s Day, Easter is another sweet holiday where consumers ignore their budgets and dietary restrictions and open their arms and wallets to chocolate, candy and new purchases. According to Matthew Shay, NRF President and CEO, &ldquo;Easter is one of the few holidays some consumers are willing to stretch their budgets, especially because many children look forward to treats and new outfits on Easter morning.&rdquo; So, what&rsquo;s in-store for retailers this Easter holiday? Let&rsquo;s take a look.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nA recent NRF Easter spending <a href="http://www.nrf.com/modules.php?name=News&amp;op=viewlive&amp;sp_id=1331" target="_blank">survey</a>, conducted by BIGinsight, revealed that Americans will shell out an average of $145.28 for Easter this year &ndash; up 11% from last year &ndash; total spending expected to reach $16.8B. They also revealed some other interesting results:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>Nearly half of Americans will head to stores to take advantage of retailers&rsquo; spring sales on apparel and accessories &ndash; total spending on these items expected to reach $3.0B.</li>\r\n\t<li>89.3% of Americans will head straight to the candy aisles, spending more than $2M on items such as chocolate eggs and jelly beans.</li>\r\n\t<li>42.6% will shop at department stores for gifts and other Easter items while 63.5% will shop at local discount stores.</li>\r\n\t<li>More than half of tablet owners celebrating Easter will use their tablet to research merchandise before heading in-store.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nHow can you make sure you are doing your job to keep the Easter baskets full?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>Offer plenty of promotions and discounts on candy, decorations and apparel.</li>\r\n\t<li>Use localized digital advertising <a href="http://www.maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-solutions">solutions</a> to promote your featured Easter items and help drive shoppers in-store.</li>\r\n\t<li>Use in-store digital signage to drive shoppers to featured product displays &ndash; more <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/onpoint-blog/2012/3/5/youve-started-reaching-the-right-shoppers-online-now-what" target="_blank">here</a>.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>From the MaxPoint team, we hope everyone has a happy and safe Easter holiday!</p>\r\n	t	2012-04-02 14:34:00	\N	2012-04-02 14:34:00	2013-09-27 03:22:26.571313	49	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, Easter, Easter retail spending statistics, localized digital advertising
748	1	29	guest-blogger-anupam-gupta-ceo-mixpo-inc-win-elections-best-practices-in-using-online-video-advertising-for-your-2012-campaign	Guest Blogger: Win Elections-Best Practices in Using Online Video Advertising for Your 2012 Campaign	<p>By: Anupam Gupta, CEO, Mixpo, Inc.&nbsp; The top 10 Super PACs in the US have spent over $50 million in advertising on behalf of 2012 campaign efforts.&nbsp; It remains to be seen how much of total campaign spending will be devoted to online, but rest assured it will eclipse the percentages spent in 2008 when allocations were in the sub-10% range.&nbsp; Video ads were in their infancy in 2008. Today the story is wildly different.</p>\r\n	<p>By: Anupam Gupta, CEO, Mixpo, Inc.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<a href="http://www.maxpointinteractive.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/Mixpo.jpg"><img alt="" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-2108" src="http://www.maxpointinteractive.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/Mixpo.jpg" style="height:134px; width:136px" title="Mixpo" /></a><br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe top 10 Super PACs in the US have spent over $50 million in advertising on behalf of 2012 campaign efforts.&nbsp; It remains to be seen how much of total campaign spending will be devoted to online, but rest assured it will eclipse the percentages spent in 2008 when allocations were in the sub-10% range.&nbsp; Video ads were in their infancy in 2008. Today the story is wildly different. <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn December (2011), the US internet audience watched 23.2 hours of video online on average representing 43.5 billion video views.&nbsp; Meanwhile, one of every 5 American adults now owns a tablet computer, and 40% use it while watching TV (by the way, multi-screen exposure increases recall).&nbsp; If broadcasters and programmers want to reach and engage with current and potential viewers, their program promotions have no choice but to be online &ndash; it&rsquo;s where audiences live.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAt the end of the day, online video advertising doesn&rsquo;t have to be a drag on campaign resources.&nbsp; Campaigns and Super PAC operations are often harried, particularly as elections draw near.&nbsp; That said, campaigns can keep it simple, easy, and not stressful.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn its most basic form, online video advertising simply means taking a :15 or :30 TV spot and putting it online.&nbsp; Take it up one level and it means adding interactivity on top of the video ad that appears as the ad plays like forms for volunteer sign ups, links to Facebook, additional video clips, and polling.&nbsp; Sound like a lot of work?&nbsp; It&rsquo;s not.&nbsp; Today&rsquo;s video ad platforms can enable campaigns to add compelling interactivity in a matter of minutes.&nbsp; Video ad creation can also be outsourced to broadcasters, publishers, and platform vendors that can provide superfast turnarounds.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIf your campaign (or Super PAC) is going to invest in online video advertising, here are seven key tips to keep in mind:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>It&rsquo;s easier than you think.</strong>&nbsp; There are plug-and-play web-based platforms out there that can help you ramp your video ad initiatives overnight and take advantage of best practices &ndash; all without incurring hassle.</li>\r\n\t<br />\r\n\t<li><strong>Make sure you can measure campaign impact.</strong>&nbsp; Every video ad network and portal as well as Facebook provides campaign reporting.&nbsp; Clicks, percentage of video watched, etc.&nbsp; But, campaign personnel need to be able to wake up in the morning and have one unified view of campaign performance across all campaigns media buys - aka &ldquo;site by site performance.&rdquo;&nbsp; If a campaign is getting five different reports from five different media placements, it&rsquo;s not easy to gauge performance.&nbsp; Be sure to use a video ad platform that will give you all the reporting you need, all in one place, and in a way that will inform decision making.&nbsp; It&rsquo;s also important to have detailed reporting such as whether or not the interactive elements in the video ad are resonating or not.&nbsp; Are viewers clicking on your Facebook link?&nbsp; Good video ad platforms provide this level of detail.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ul><br />\r\n\t<li><strong>Don&rsquo;t forget about mobile.</strong>&nbsp; 7% of all web traffic occurs on mobile devices whether its smartphones or tablets.&nbsp; Some video ads will &ldquo;break&rdquo; on devices, including the iPad.&nbsp; It&rsquo;s important to use a video ad platform that will avoid breakage; that will run the same ad successfully on any screen or OS.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ul><br />\r\n\t<li><strong>Target, target, target.</strong>&nbsp; Best in class video ad platforms, like MaxPoint Interactive, can enable you to target your impressions down to the neighborhood-level so that you&rsquo;re not wasting impressions.&nbsp; Some platforms can even change the message in your video &ndash; or even show different videos &ndash; based on who is watching and from where, what their political affiliation is, their gender, their age, and so forth.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ul><br />\r\n\t<li><strong>Buy early.</strong>&nbsp; In-stream video ad inventory can run tight at key election inflection points as can inventory on local sites where the amount of available impressions is less than on national sites.&nbsp; Also, consider not only purchasing in-stream video inventory but also in-banner video inventory.&nbsp; 250x300 in-banner video ads are particularly effective, and a good video ad platform can take a single video ad and run it simultaneously as either in-stream or in-banner just like it should be able to run the same video ad on any screen.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>Buy local.</strong>&nbsp; Premium local media sites &ndash; such as local newspapers, TV stations, Cable, and Radio station sites &ndash; drive higher engagement than national sites targeted to the same geographic area.&nbsp; Consider a mix of national and local.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="http://www.maxpointinteractive.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/MixpoGBImg1.jpg"><img alt="" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-2111" src="http://www.maxpointinteractive.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/MixpoGBImg1-300x273.jpg" style="height:273px; width:300px" title="MixpoGBImg1" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>Less is more. </strong>To achieve highest average percentage of the video viewed, keeping the video ad&#39;s length shorter vs. longer is good - ideally no more than :30. Include links to additional videos for voters who want to dig in further.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="http://www.maxpointinteractive.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/MixpoGBImg2.png"><img alt="" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-2112" src="http://www.maxpointinteractive.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/MixpoGBImg2-300x272.png" style="height:272px; width:300px" title="MixpoGBImg2" /></a></p>\r\n	t	2012-03-28 13:59:16	\N	2012-03-28 13:59:16	2013-09-27 03:27:37.486911	53	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, Mixpo, video advertising platforms, political advertising campaigns, online video advertising
