767	1	16	do-you-speak-language-x	Do You Speak Language X?	<p>Recently, as I was searching online for something completely unrelated, I stumbled upon a programming language I&rsquo;d never heard of. It reminded me that there are programming languages out there of which I&rsquo;m yet unaware, and this led me to wonder how often organizations limit themselves by staying within their programming &ldquo;comfort zones.&rdquo;</p>\r\n	<p>Recently, as I was searching online for something completely unrelated, I stumbled upon a programming language I&rsquo;d never heard of. It reminded me that there are programming languages out there of which I&rsquo;m yet unaware, and this led me to wonder how often organizations limit themselves by staying within their programming &ldquo;comfort zones.&rdquo;<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nTake recruiting, for example. I know that some organizations discard candidates based solely on the programming languages listed on their resumes. This is short-sighted. If you&rsquo;re hiring top talent, they can learn a new language easily. Get them a syntax book and a project, and watch them go. I&rsquo;ve yet to be proven wrong on this.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThis limited view of language often extends further into the organization. Shouldn&rsquo;t it be about getting maximum productivity, and not just about programming in one language? Don&rsquo;t you want to pick the best tools for the job, versus saying I&rsquo;m only a Language X shop? Especially given the fact that programming languages are relatively transient, evolving over time. Fifteen years ago, C++ was considered cutting edge and a default language choice for a wide range of programming tasks. Now, it&rsquo;s only used when there is a real reason to do so, because other languages are easier and more productive. There is a reason most websites&rsquo; back ends are written in languages like PHP, Ruby on Rails, Java, or ASP.NET, and not C++. I think this is how we should look at all languages.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nHow do you know you&rsquo;re making a good tradeoff, if you don&rsquo;t know what the other languages can do, what their strengths are? Is something else more efficient? Think of the reason there are so many container classes in languages. It&rsquo;s because there are tradeoffs. You need to know what&rsquo;s out there, and keep an open mind. By artificially limiting your work to one language, you&rsquo;re limiting your ability to innovate and expand your products.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThis isn&rsquo;t to say that your organization should add languages into your products just because you can&mdash;rather, choose a set that works for your situations, then evaluate if there are real reasons and justifications for adding others. At Maxpoint Interactive, our primary programming languages are Java, C#, and Python. But we use other languages, like C++ and Clojure, for specific parts of our system when it makes sense.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe bottom line is, use what will best promote productivity. Languages change and you must be able to evolve&mdash;that includes your workforce. How do you get your product implemented and out the door faster, quicker, better? That&rsquo;s what it&rsquo;s all about at the end of the day. So, why artificially limit yourself?</p>\r\n	t	2012-04-30 14:57:47	\N	2012-04-30 14:57:47	2013-09-27 02:47:24.342447	52	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, technology 
