762	1	20	conagra-targets-latino-population-to-drive-in-store-sales	ConAgra Targets Latino Population to Drive In-store Sales	<p>Every culture has different tastes in food, from bland to spicy and vegetarian to carnivore.&nbsp; Sure, some stores have small areas of ethnic foods, but retailers are learning that by expanding these selections, it opens a huge opportunity to improve shopper loyalty and in-store sales.&nbsp;</p>\r\n	<p>Every culture has different tastes in food, from bland to spicy and vegetarian to carnivore.&nbsp; Sure, some stores have small areas of ethnic foods, but retailers are learning that by expanding these selections, it opens a huge opportunity to improve shopper loyalty and in-store sales.&nbsp; <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nFor example, Whole Foods Market was very successful when they tried it with the Muslim population during Ramadan by partnering with Saffron Road Foods, a halal-friendly food manufacturer. So, why limit ethnic-specific marketing to one group?&nbsp; This is where marketing is wide-open for a new way to drive in-store sales.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nConAgra threw their hat into the ring by simply adding some spice to their already popular Act II microwave popcorn and Slim Jim meat snacks.&nbsp; ConAgra looked at U.S. census data showing a rapid increase in Latino population, particularly those under 18.&nbsp; It also pulled its own data showing Latina women as a fast growth area in snack purchases among mothers of children under 18.&nbsp; So to attract these growing markets, ConAgra added Queso Jalepeno and Salsa Valentina pour over sauces to Act II popcorn and created a Dare line of Slim Jims that include whimsical flavors such as&nbsp; &ldquo;kinda hot chili pepper,&rdquo; &ldquo;freakin&rsquo; hot jalepeno&rdquo; and &ldquo;really freakin&rsquo; hot jalepeno.&rdquo;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nTo kick off the campaign, ConAgra targeted three heavily Latino populated markets of Texas, Arizona and California, by dropping over 3 million F