764	1	15	washington-d-c-ranks-most-environmentally-conscious-city-in-u-s	Washington, D.C. Ranks Most Environmentally Conscious City in U.S.	<p>In honor of this past Earth Day, we analyzed billions of data points for our April indexing study to determine the U.S. neighborhoods that are the most eco-friendly.</p>\r\n	<p>Throughout the month of April, we start to focus on green initiatives and invest in more eco-friendly products as Earth Day reminds us to take care of the planet we live on. In honor of this past Earth Day, we analyzed billions of data points for our <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/online-advertising-news/environmental-interest" target="_blank">April indexing study</a> to determine the U.S. neighborhoods that are the most eco-friendly. <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe top ten cities that showed the greatest interest in eco-friendly products and issues include:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>Washington DC</li>\r\n\t<li>Austin, TX</li>\r\n\t<li>Honolulu, HI</li>\r\n\t<li>San Francisco, CA</li>\r\n\t<li>Medford, OR</li>\r\n\t<li>Portland, ME</li>\r\n\t<li>Tampa, FL</li>\r\n\t<li>Burlington, VT</li>\r\n\t<li>Milwaukee, WI</li>\r\n\t<li>Columbus, OH</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nIn addition to determining the most eco-friendly U.S. neighborhoods, this indexing study discovered that there are two very distinct neighborhood types when it comes to going &ldquo;green&rdquo; &ndash; those who demonstrate interest by reading and discussing environmental issues (the &ldquo;talkers&rdquo;) and those who make purchasing decisions to support environmentally friendly products (the &ldquo;walkers&rdquo;).<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>The &ldquo;Talkers&rdquo;</strong><br />\r\nAccording to our research, neighborhoods in Washington, D.C. - specifically Adams Morgan, Dupont Circle and North Old Town - are passionate about eco-friendly products and services. These neighborhoods trended high on research and discussion topics such as energy efficiency, alternative fuels, hybrid cards and organic food. The research also revealed that the demographic of these consumers were high income, college educated young adults.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>The &ldquo;Walkers&rdquo;</strong><br />\r\nAustin, TX residents &ndash; particularly those residing in Cedar Park, Round Rock and Rosedale &ndash; were more likely to act on purchasing eco-friendly products like household cleaners, biodegradable products and hybrid cars. The demographic of this group were primarily middle-class, married homeowners with children.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAccording to our COO, Gretchen Joyce, &ldquo; The results of this Interest Index were particularly surprising because we found that we have clusters of consumers who are &lsquo;talking the talk&rsquo; and some that are &lsquo;walking the walk&rsquo; when it comes to acting in an environmentally friendly way, yet both groups are important to advertisers.&rdquo;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nUsing the data gleaned from this index, we implemented highly targeted neighborhood-level digital ad campaigns for a variety of eco-friendly retailers and brands:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>A major luxury car dealer was looking to increase overall brand awareness of its new hybrid vehicle and drive sales in areas where near-term purchases were most likely. MaxPoint helped the company drive traffic to specific dealerships by targeting like-minded, environmentally conscious drivers with the disposable income available to purchase such a high-end eco-friendly vehicle.</li>\r\n\t<li>A major solar solutions company was interested in targeting the neighborhoods across the U.S.&nbsp; most likely to purchase a solar panel to power their homes. As a result of a focused digital advertising campaign, the company was able to target consumers passionate about the environment, who own homes, have good credit and have an average household income of $60K or higher.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n&ldquo;Many retailers and brands are interested in building brand awareness with a captive audience and focusing in on the consumers that are interested in buying the product right away. The results of this index provide a very real snapshot of the behaviors, demographics and locations of these groups, which makes it easy for us to create highly effective advertising campaigns that help advertisers achieve both branding and revenue goals,&rdquo; says Joyce.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nInterested in our other indexing studies? Read last month&#39;s Interest Index on cities most interested in new consumer technology <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/online-advertising-news/new-consumer-technology-interest" target="_blank">here</a>.</p>\r\n	t	2012-04-24 15:33:40	\N	2012-04-24 15:33:40	2013-09-27 02:53:58.415402	54	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, data, interest index 
759	1	15	retailers-insights-into-increasing-brand-loyalty-among-the-hispanic-shopper-group	Retailers: Insights Into Increasing Brand Loyalty Among the Hispanic Shopper Group	<p>The Hispanic shopper is part of a rapidly growing consumer group with tremendous buying power &ndash; Hispanics are predicted to spend $1.3 trillion by 2015. Knowing this, retailers are starting to pay particularly close attention to this group and how to effectively market to the Hispanic shopper.</p>\r\n	<p>The Hispanic shopper is part of a rapidly growing consumer group with tremendous buying power &ndash; Hispanics are predicted to spend $1.3 trillion by 2015. Knowing this, retailers are starting to pay particularly close attention to this group and how to effectively market to the Hispanic shopper.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nA recent article in the 2012 April issue of Shopper Marketing Magazine discussed how to effectively market to the Hispanic shopper, paying close attention to insights into what drives brand loyalty. Before, Hispanics were thought of as only loyal to a small niche of national brands. Deborah Garbato, contributor to Shopper Marketing Magazine, says, &ldquo;Spanish-dominant Hispanics will try new brands&hellip;according to Mercury Mambo&rsquo;s &lsquo;Hispanic Shopper &amp; Retail Study&rsquo;&hellip;this erodes the notion that Hispanics are fervently loyal to a small cadre of national brands.&rdquo; So, what drives Hispanics to try new brands and become loyal customers? Here are a few insights:<span id="cke_bm_98C" style="display:none">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>70% of Latinos surveyed in the Hispanic Shopper &amp; Retail Study have participated in supermarket price promotions or samplings over the past six months. 84% had never bought the item previously, and 84% had not planned on buying it.</li>\r\n\t<li>The most loyal shoppers are Spanish-dominant Latinos, however, they are hesitant to buy something they do not understand. This reinforces the importance of refining messaging and paying attention to any language barriers when marketing to this consumer group.</li>\r\n\t<li>Saving money is important to the Spanish-dominant Latinos. According to the Hispanic Shopper &amp; Retail Study, 64% of Hispanic shoppers embrace discounts, coupons and offers, and 78% of Hispanic shoppers wait to purchase a product after a promotion is over.</li>\r\n\t<li>Circulars and cause marketing also drive traffic from the Hispanic shopper. If a circular includes lifestyle content and not just pricing, Hispanics have more reason to read it. According to Garbato, &ldquo;the most relevant topics are baby care/families (39%), health (37%) and cooking (32%). As for cause marketing, 52% of Hispanics are &ldquo;very likely&rdquo; to buy a brand that supports the community.&rdquo;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nWhat can we take away from this? In 2012, pay close attention to how you market to the Hispanic shopper group. Utilize offers and cause messaging to attract shoppers and gain loyalty, and make sure messaging is easily understood by the Spanish-dominant Latino. For more insight on the Hispanic shopper, click <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/onpoint-blog/2012/3/19/understanding-the-hispanic-shopper-part-ii-hispanic-identity" target="_blank">here</a>.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhat insights do you have about marketing to the Hispanic shopper? Share with us below.</p>\r\n	t	2012-04-16 15:49:27	\N	2012-04-16 15:49:27	2013-09-27 03:04:38.97914	49	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, Hispanics, Hispanic shoppers, brand loyalty, Shopper Marketing Magazine
763	1	15	digital-trends-impact-grocery-shopper-behavior-in-2012	Digital Trends Impact Grocery Shopper Behavior in 2012 	<p>In the past, grocers leveraged print and in-store marketing to engage shoppers and drive in-store sales. Today, grocers are realizing while print and in-store marketing does lend a hand in shopper engagement, online is driving more consumer interaction and shoppers to the stores.</p>\r\n	<p>In the past, grocers leveraged print and in-store marketing to engage shoppers and drive in-store sales. Today, grocers are realizing while print and in-store marketing does lend a hand in shopper engagement, online is driving more consumer interaction and shoppers to the stores.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nAccording to Bill Bishop, chief architect of Brick Meets Click, &ldquo;Grocery shoppers are blending new and old media to make food purchasing decisions.&rdquo; We live in a digital age and most of what we do today is completed online. For instance, shoppers go online to research grocers, download coupons/offers, find reviews, and prepare shopping lists.&nbsp; More grocery shoppers are online and engaging digitally, so grocers are pushing to learn more to effectively engage with these shoppers.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nTo help identify how digital trends are impacting shopping behavior, Brick Meets Clicks <a href="http://www.progressivegrocer.com/top-stories/headlines/technology/id35156/online-tools-increasingly-drive-in-store-engagement-study/" target="_blank">surveyed</a> over 23,000 shoppers. Here are some of the findings:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>70% of shoppers report that they find online ads helpful</li>\r\n\t<li>Shoppers head to retailer websites to scan recipes and build online shopping lists</li>\r\n\t<li>Digitally engaged shoppers are more likely to add grocery shopping apps to their mobile phones &ndash; 21% currently use a grocery shopping application</li>\r\n\t<li>76% of shoppers prepare a shopping list before heading in-store</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;The study confirms that today&rsquo;s shopper is combining online planning with in-store visits to make their grocery shopping more informed, cost-effective and enjoyable,&rdquo; says Scott Lutz, CEO and president of Minneapolis-based GSN.&nbsp; Therefore, with the opportunities that exist for retailers online today, and the increase in shoppers going online, grocers should make sure they are effectively reaching the right shoppers before they head in-store and make purchase decisions.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nFor instance, reach shoppers that are preparing for grocery trips online with localized digital advertising. Targeted campaigns result in more engaging and relevant experiences for customers. The shoppers are there, so reach them and serve relevant ads to drive in-store traffic and sales. More on localized digital advertising <a href="http://www.maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-solutions" target="_blank">here</a>.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nFor more information on how to reach grocery shoppers heading online before heading in-store, click <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/onpoint-blog/2012/3/7/grocers-localize-digital-campaigns-and-reach-consumers-before-shopping-lists-are-born" target="_blank">here</a>.</p>\r\n	t	2012-04-23 16:41:01	\N	2012-04-23 16:41:01	2013-09-27 02:58:32.474874	49	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, digital, localized digital advertising, grocers
758	1	15	retailers-drive-brand-awareness-with-visuals-not-words	Retailers: Drive Brand Awareness with Visuals, Not Words	<p>&quot;The best way into the mind of a consumer is with visuals, not words,&quot; according to&nbsp; Laura Ries, Advertising Age contributor, in a recent Advertising Age article - &quot;Repositioning &#39;Positioning&#39;: The best way into the consumer&#39;s mind is not with verbal nails, but with a visual hammer.&quot;</p>\r\n	<p>&quot;The best way into the mind of a consumer is with visuals, not words,&quot; according to&nbsp; Laura Ries, Advertising Age contributor, in a recent Advertising Age article - &quot;Repositioning &#39;Positioning&#39;: The best way into the consumer&#39;s mind is not with verbal nails, but with a visual hammer.&quot;<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhen designing advertising creative in 2012, focus on the visual element. Visuals play an important role in advertising because they appeal to a consumer&#39;s emotions and tend to be more recognizable. For example, Reis referenced a research study in 1973 where Professor Lionel Standing asked subjects to look at 10,000 images over a five day period (each image only shown for 5 seconds). When the subjects were then shown pairs of images together (images they were already shown and images yet to be seen), subjects recalled 70% of the images they had seen before. The point?<br />\r\n<br />\r\nConsumers read text all throughout the day and lines of text has no identifiers that separate it from one another. Reis points out that in 2010, Coca-Cola spent $267 million advertising its brand, but no one could recall the slogan. What people do remember is the &ldquo;contour&rdquo; bottle, a visual that is strongly identified with the brand to this day.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWith all the clutter online to distract a consumer, advertisements need to be able to catch their attention quickly. You may only have a few seconds to catch the consumer&rsquo;s eye, so make you&rsquo;re your creative is optimized to its fullest. Read more on creating catchy campaigns <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/onpoint-blog/2012/3/20/creating-campaigns-that-speak-to-shoppers" target="_blank">here</a>.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nVisuals, if designed right, can have a lasting impact and are easier to differentiate and recall. For instance, retailers and brands like Target, Nike and Apple use strong visuals to create powerful and recognizable logos.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nHowever, a visual image, while visually appealing, will have no lasting impact if it is not constantly introduced to a consumer or paired with powerful messaging. Optimize your advertising campaign on all levels by pairing strong visuals with powerful messaging. Soon enough, the visual may be able to stand alone.</p>\r\n	t	2012-04-12 17:53:55	\N	2012-04-12 17:53:55	2013-09-27 03:06:50.56089	49	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, brand awareness, advertising campaigns, Advertising Age, powerful logos
756	1	20	walmart-using-exclusive-deals-to-woo-shoppers-and-boost-in-store-sales	Walmart Using Exclusive Deals to Woo Shoppers and Boost In-store Sales	<p>Retailer exclusives are not new, but can be highly effective if launched correctly and push the creative envelope.&nbsp; What retailer wouldn&rsquo;t like an exclusive deal or promotion?&nbsp; You move a larger than normal amount of inventory and it guarantees that your competitors won&rsquo;t be undercutting your efforts.&nbsp; The problem with some exclusive deals is the lack of planning.&nbsp;</p>\r\n	<p>Retailer exclusives are not new, but can be highly effective if launched correctly and push the creative envelope.&nbsp; What retailer wouldn&rsquo;t like an exclusive deal or promotion?&nbsp; You move a larger than normal amount of inventory and it guarantees that your competitors won&rsquo;t be undercutting your efforts.&nbsp; The problem with some exclusive deals is the lack of planning.&nbsp; <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nJust because you cut a deal with manufacturer X to sell their widgets in an exclusive promo pack doesn&rsquo;t guarantee you&rsquo;ll see demand flourish, especially if you just plop it on the shelf and expect the widget to sell itself.&nbsp; Success comes from creativity, planning and most importantly, promotion to the right audience.&nbsp; I see it all of the time.&nbsp; Blind mass mailings and campaigns costing tens of thousands of dollars or more that only reach a small percentage of the intended or interested market.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nA good example of creative and well-planned exclusive marketing comes from <a href="http://www.walmart.com/" target="_blank">Walmart</a>.&nbsp; The retailer seems to be stepping up its efforts to woo shoppers to their stores and boost sales of special promotional inventory.&nbsp; By partnering with <a href="http://www.hormelfoods.com/" target="_blank">Hormel Foods</a>, the duo set out to show chili lovers that the traditional winter comfort food could also be a great summer meal booster.&nbsp; Nobody wants to slave in the kitchen when summer hits, and a hot dog or hamburger with traditional toppings only last so long on the crave-o-meter.&nbsp; So Hormel and Walmart urged shoppers to &ldquo;savor the summer&rdquo; and boost their plain dogs and burgers with a chili topping.&nbsp; Very simple to do and adds a healthy boost to summer grilling.&nbsp; Though the two companies did a great job and had above average results from print ads, social media, banner ads on Walmart.com, e-wire blasts, and a combination of in-store display marketing, I am surprised to see the omission of highly targeted digital ad campaigns that reach beyond just one site.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nA second example of Walmart&rsquo;s success in exclusive partnerships was a campaign with <a href="http://www.kelloggs.com/en_US/home.html" target="_blank">Kellogg&rsquo;s</a> and <a href="http://www.ubi.com/US/" target="_blank">Ubisoft</a>.&nbsp; Imagine the difficulty coordinating marketing efforts across three large corporations, but they pulled it off.&nbsp; Walmart sold specially marked Kellogg&rsquo;s products such as cereal, Pop-tarts and Rice Krispies Treats that included an unlock code for exclusive video game content for Ubisoft-created &ldquo;Just Dance 3.&rdquo;&nbsp; What kid can resist cool snack food and cereal with a code that gives them access to video game content?&nbsp; What a creative campaign.&nbsp; I can only imagine how the metrics and traffic could skyrocket, again, through some highly targeted <a href="http://www.maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-solutions" target="_blank">neighborhood-level digital advertising</a> -- something all parties should consider for the next campaign.</p>\r\n	t	2012-04-10 14:11:55	\N	2012-04-10 14:11:55	2013-09-27 03:10:58.434058	50	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, Walmart, OnPoint, retailer exclusives, neighborhood-level digital advertising, digital advertising 
750	1	30	event-recap-stratconn-business-meeting-series	Event Recap: StratConn Business Meeting Series	<p>Last week, MaxPoint&rsquo;s Shopper Marketing team participated in the StratConn event hosted by the Path to Purchase Institute in Rosemont, IL. With participation from over 20 companies, the event was a great way to qualify, meet and engage with other attendees.</p>\r\n	<p>Last week, MaxPoint&rsquo;s Shopper Marketing team participated in the StratConn event hosted by the Path to Purchase Institute in Rosemont, IL. With participation from over 20 companies, the event was a great way to qualify, meet and engage with other attendees. Below are some of the event highlights. <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nTaking a &lsquo;speed-dating&rsquo; approach to marketing, StratConn is set up to pair vendors and clients in 30-minute meetings to discuss new ways of doing business. With many challenges facing the industry and a rapidly changing environment, there was a lot of discussion regarding the place of digital in Shopper Marketing.&nbsp; The opportunity digital extends for advertisers to reach customers online and drive them to specific retail stores resonated well with the attendees.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nReaching customers online is new to Shopper Marketers and finding the right digital fit was definitely of interest to the participants. As digital continues to take off in 2012, it is evident that more Shopper Marketers are looking to supplement their offline marketing vehicles with digital solutions.&nbsp; More on digital advertising solutions <a href="http://www.maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-solutions" target="_blank">here</a>.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAs always, the Path to Purchase Institute put on a strong event and MaxPoint is really looking forward to participating in the Shopper Marketing Summit in April! If you are attending the Summit, be sure to celebrate at MaxPoint&rsquo;s After Effie&rsquo;s party!&nbsp; More on the upcoming event <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/advertising-events">here</a>.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nHow important do you think digital advertising is to driving in-store traffic? Join the discussion <a href="http://www.linkedin.com/groupItem?view=&amp;gid=50329&amp;type=member&amp;item=98883547&amp;qid=39d75b70-3ecf-45ad-be87-572f81c10e6d&amp;trk=group_most_popular-0-b-ttl&amp;goback=.gmp_50329" target="_blank">here</a>.</p>\r\n	t	2012-03-30 15:35:19	\N	2012-03-30 15:35:19	2013-09-27 03:24:26.498401	49	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, StratConn, shopper marketing, Path to Purchase Institute
769	1	15	a-look-back-the-best-latino-advertising-campaigns	A Look Back: The Best Latino Advertising Campaigns	<p>Target Latino, a popular Hispanic marketing blog collected feedback from viewers and compiled the best Latino advertising campaigns over the past year.</p>\r\n	<p>The U.S. Hispanic shopper is part of a fast growing consumer group for many retailers and brands, with tremendous buying power. Recognizing the importance of marketing to the Hispanic shopper, retailers and brands have focused on Hispanic specific messaging and advertising campaigns. Target Latino, a popular Hispanic marketing blog collected feedback from viewers and compiled the best Latino advertising campaigns over the past year.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe below advertisements are effective because the product and messaging appealed to the Hispanic consumer. However, advertisers also leveraged video advertising to get their ads in front of the target audience. Why? In 2011, Hispanics appeared less responsive to in-store messaging (messaging at shelf or in-store TV) than non-Hispanics. In order to reach Hispanic shoppers effectively, brands and retailers needed to move beyond these methods and find the right marketing for these consumers.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nH2oh! &quot;Braids&quot;<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<iframe width="420" height="315" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/xdOoJjvr0GM?rel=0" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAxe &quot;Premature Perspiration&quot;<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<iframe width="560" height="315" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/2qD_PiZAz6k?rel=0" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nGiven online ad spending predictions and consumer preference, the digital advertising route is becoming the more effective way to reach the Hispanic audience. And, this is clear as these video advertising campaigns were received well by the Hispanic consumer group. Check out this blog post on why digital advertising makes sense for Hispanic shoppers this year.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nHispanic marketers have a lot to live up to in 2012. What creative advertisements will we see for the Hispanic consumer group this year? Only time will tell.</p>\r\n	t	2012-05-02 14:13:54	\N	2012-05-02 14:13:54	2013-09-27 02:43:49.584228	51	MaxPoint, OnPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, Hispanics, video, video advertising, campaigns
770	1	15	an-interview-with-peter-hoyt-ceo-path-to-purchase-institute	An Interview with Peter Hoyt, CEO, Path to Purchase Institute 	<p>MaxPoint interviewed Peter Hoyt, CEO, Path to Purchase Institute, recently on the shopper marketing industry and how it is changing with the emergence of new technology. The interview focuses on the change in the shopper marketing path-to-purchase and recommendations for how to reach shoppers at every touch point &ndash; highlighting digital advertising.</p>\r\n	<p><a href="http://www.maxpointinteractive.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/phoytblog1.jpg"><img alt="" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-2385" src="http://www.maxpointinteractive.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/phoytblog1.jpg" style="height:150px; width:150px" title="phoytblog" /></a><br />\r\n<br />\r\nMaxPoint interviewed Peter Hoyt, CEO, Path to Purchase Institute, recently on the shopper marketing industry and how it is changing with the emergence of new technology. The interview focuses on the change in the shopper marketing path-to-purchase and recommendations for how to reach shoppers at every touch point &ndash; highlighting digital advertising. Check out the full interview below.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>MaxPoint</strong>: With more technology, resources and information available to shoppers these days, the shopper pathway is moving away from a simple, linear model to a highly complex, non-linear model. Retailers and Brands are now challenged with new and expanded touch points to reach and build relationships with shoppers. What are your thoughts on how marketing strategies need to change in order to reach shoppers at every touch point?<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Hoyt:</strong> It&rsquo;s easy to over complicate the challenge. Like anything else, if you break it down into smaller pieces, it&rsquo;s pretty straightforward. One of the big differences between traditional marketing and shopper marketing is that with shopper marketing one targets a segment of shoppers (people who want or need diapers, shampoo, a refrigerator, etc.). So instead of trying to blanket a demographic by harvesting ever greater reach or GRPs, shopper marketers hone in on the path their prospective customer is most likely to take and seek to intercept her, as often as possible with a relevant appropriate message.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nProcter and Gamble likes to work with a framework that I think helps a lot. They call it &ldquo;Store-Back&rdquo;. Think about your shopper&rsquo;s journey backwards, so to speak. Start where she would encounter your product in-store&hellip; at the shelf (Packaging? Signage? P-O-P?), then move out to when she is &ldquo;on the go&rdquo; (mobile? OOH?), or at home or pre-shopping (Search? Social? Strategically placed banner ads?).<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMore traditional vehicles can be incorporated as well. We&rsquo;re seeing more and more consumer magazines and other media begin to describe their audiences in terms of being comprised of shopper segments and their media as offering meaningful touch points on the path to purchase. Just bear in mind, the further you get from her mission, the less direct impact your messaging will have on the ultimate purchase decision.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>MaxPoint:</strong> What marketing channels do you see being the most impactful in reaching shoppers on the path to purchase?<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Hoyt:</strong> I should probably stop holding them up as the paragon of marketing virtue but again, I would point anyone who is thinking about this to consider the approaches being taken by P&amp;G. P&amp;G pretty much coined shopper marketing in its current form. They fight hard to get their messaging in-store. But retail communications is very hard to scale. If one chain is accepting and responsible about merchandising compliance, the next will be less so. P&amp;G&rsquo;s approach is to &ldquo;control what you can control&rdquo;. So they&rsquo;ve been investing very heavily in all things digital. They are successfully engaging shoppers on-line, through search, social, well-placed banners. Anywhere and everywhere she might be looking for answers or resources, they want a P&amp;G product to appear with the appropriate message.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nA lot of what P&amp;G sells is targeted to younger women, often younger mothers. In this case digital is especially important. Millenials, the 18-35 year old set, use the web to find answers twice as often as Baby Boomers, and when she has her first baby, her use doubles again. Across all age groups, she is going on-line for up to 45 minutes before she goes shopping. Whether she&rsquo;s looking for value or assortment, the fact is that the primary target for most messaging directed at shoppers can be effectively reached on-line.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>MaxPoint:</strong> Do you see digital advertising as an impactful way to reach these consumers? If so, would you recommend more shopper marketing dollars being budgeted towards digital advertising methods to reach shoppers before heading in-store?<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Hoyt:</strong> I recommend that folks fish where the fish are. If your target audience is using the web to gather information, find answers, decide where to shop or what to buy, then, by all means, you should invest in a more robust digital presence. Ask a lot of questions of your customers. Only do so with a &ldquo;Store-Back&rdquo; mentality and the path will reveal itself.</p>\r\n	t	2012-05-03 13:45:34	\N	2012-05-03 13:45:34	2013-09-21 02:04:27.721681	53	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, path-to-purchase, shopper marketing, path to purchase
773	1	15	shoppers-make-room-on-budget-and-head-in-store-for-mothers-day	Shoppers Make Room on Budget and Head In-Store for Mother's Day	<p>From brightly colored flowers to new gardening gear, shoppers are making room in their budget this Mother&rsquo;s Day to make the holiday as special as possible.</p>\r\n	<p>From brightly colored flowers to new gardening gear, shoppers are making room in their budget this Mother&rsquo;s Day to make the holiday as special as possible. According to a National Retail Federation (NRF) <a href="http://www.nrf.com/modules.php?name=News&amp;op=viewlive&amp;sp_id=1350" target="_blank">survey</a>, the average consumer celebrating the holiday is expected to spend $152.52 on gifts (up from $140.73 last year), with total spending expected to reach $18.6B. So, how are &ldquo;celebrants&rdquo; spending their money and preparing for Mother&rsquo;s Day? Let&rsquo;s take a look. <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Expected Mother&rsquo;s Day Shopping Behavior</strong><br />\r\n&ldquo;Americans will look for sentimental and unique ways to shower mom with affection this year,&rdquo; said NRF President and CEO Matthew Shay. When it comes to items to purchase and where/how to shop, consumers are well prepared.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Popular items chosen for purchase:</strong> This year, consumers will spend on special meals/outings, clothing, flowers, electronics and more. According to the NRF survey, two-thirds (66.4%) will buy flowers, spending a total of $2.2B, and nearly one-third (32.8%) will treat mom to a new blouse or sweater, spending $1.6B on clothing and accessories. Those buying electronics (12.7%) will shell out a total or $1.6B, and over half (54.3%) will treat mom to a nice meal. Last but not least, consumers will spend $1.8B on gift cards and $1.3B on personal services (trip to the spa).<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Where people will shop:</strong> Department stores will be packed up until Mother&rsquo;s Day as more than one-third (35.6%) of consumers will shop at a department store. If the perfect gift for mom is not found at a department store, however, consumers will head to discount and specialty stores. While shoppers will still also shop online, in-store shopping is still the most preferred way to get gifts for mom.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>How people will shop:</strong> With all of the new technology available to consumers today, more are headed online to complete research and prepare lists before heading in-store. Nearly 39.3% of smartphone owners and 51.2% of tablet owners plan to use their devices to research products/compare prices, redeem coupons, look up retailer information and search for the perfect gift.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nRetailers &ndash; expect crowds this Mother&rsquo;s Day as shoppers make room in their budget for that special gift for mom. Since shoppers are already heading online before heading in-store, make sure the ads you serve are reaching the right audience, use relevant messaging, provide Mother&rsquo;s Day shoppers with coupons, stock up on popular items, and continue to reach and cater to shoppers once in-store this Mother&#39;s Day weekend.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nFrom everyone at MaxPoint, we wish you a safe and Happy Mother&rsquo;s Day!</p>\r\n	t	2012-05-10 16:48:43	\N	2012-05-10 16:48:43	2013-09-21 02:00:04.021152	49	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, retail, consumers, holiday shopping, holiday, consumer spending
771	1	20	whole-foods-sets-creative-example-for-precision-marketing-to-ethnic-audiences	Whole Foods Sets Creative Example for Precision Marketing to Ethnic Audiences	<p>America is one big melting pot of culture that is constantly adding new ingredients to the mix.&nbsp; Gone are the days retailers solely target the usual holidays like Christmas, Thanksgiving, Easter, Fourth of July and Halloween.&nbsp; With so many different cultures, religions and lifestyles being welcomed in the U.S., the opportunity to target these groups is tremendous.</p>\r\n	<p>America is one big melting pot of culture that is constantly adding new ingredients to the mix.&nbsp; Gone are the days retailers solely target the usual holidays like Christmas, Thanksgiving, Easter, Fourth of July and Halloween.&nbsp; With so many different cultures, religions and lifestyles being welcomed in the U.S., the opportunity to target these groups is tremendous.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nTake for example, <a href="http://www.wholefoodsmarket.com/" target="_blank">Whole Foods Market</a>.&nbsp; The national retailer launched a shopper marketing campaign last summer specific to American-Muslims in time for Ramadan, a significant holiday for Muslims requiring daily fasts broken by a daily meal called &ldquo;iftar.&rdquo;&nbsp; The catch is that foods consumed during Ramadan must be halal-certified (foods allowed under Islamic dietary guidelines.)&nbsp; Finding halal-friendly foods can be difficult or at best limited to small, local ethnic markets.&nbsp; Prior to the 2011 Ramadan holiday, Whole Foods partnered with <a href="http://www.saffronroadfood.com/" target="_blank">Saffron Road Foods</a>, maker of halal-friendly cuisine and products.&nbsp; Together, they hit the social media machine and found that Muslims were overwhelmingly excited about the accessibility of halal-certified foods provided by a large retailer like Whole Foods.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWith American-Muslim support combined with cause marketing, price-promotion components and the utilization of social media channels such as bloggers like Yvonne Maffei&rsquo;s &ldquo;My Halal Kitchen,&rdquo; Whole Foods was able to reach Muslim consumers online where halal conversations were already taking place.&nbsp; Through these efforts, Whole Foods was able to drive significant in-store traffic and played a major role in increasing Saffron Road&rsquo;s sales in August by 300%.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThis was a win-win for everyone.&nbsp; Saffron Road gained significant exposure and increased sales while Whole Foods gained market share among the American-Muslim population. Marketing with a broader view on global and social diversity will prove to be the next generation of successful shopper marketing strategies.&nbsp; Imagine how complementing this social media strategy with targeted digital display or video advertising to ethnicities could further enhance the effectiveness.</p>\r\n	t	2012-05-07 14:18:35	\N	2012-05-07 14:18:35	2013-09-21 02:03:21.795641	50	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, multi-cultural marketing, shopper marketing, digital advertising, digital, retail
768	1	19	giving-national-campaigns-a-local-edge	Giving National Campaigns a Local Edge	<p>As new technology provides more opportunities for retailers and brands to expand advertising solutions across channels, they look for innovative ways to effectively target the right consumers with their marketing messages. And, for every challenge there is an opportunity, and this year it&rsquo;s all about working &ldquo;local&rdquo; into your marketing strategy.</p>\r\n	<p>As new technology provides more opportunities for retailers and brands to expand advertising solutions across channels, they look for innovative ways to effectively target the right consumers with their marketing messages. And, for every challenge there is an opportunity, and this year it&rsquo;s all about working &ldquo;local&rdquo; into your marketing strategy.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nTo clarify, when we talk about local, we don&rsquo;t mean corner stores or local brands. We&rsquo;re talking about national campaigns that pinpoint consumers at the neighborhood level. For example, a car maker wants to create targeted awareness of their brand for all their buyers. Not everyone in the country is an intended buyer so the car maker needs to find a way to target a lot of people, but be smart about it. Cue a better, more efficient and more effective way to target existing and prospective customers.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn order to achieve this level of precision, companies are turning to &ldquo;big data&rdquo; solutions. These solutions analyze billions of data points consumed by neighborhoods across the U.S. such as offline point-of-sale data, social media, videos, music, local Web pages and online magazines.&nbsp; This data can be used to score each neighborhood and determine its interests &mdash; perhaps it&rsquo;s neighborhoods across the country with residents most interested in a healthier lifestyle, in the market for a new car or who currently use your competitor&rsquo;s product. By analyzing these data sets, companies can look at clusters of people who are most likely to be interested in their products or services.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn many cases, brands will use this local approach to complement an existing campaign. Targeting at the neighborhood level across the entire nation helps to curb that wasteful ad spending. By finding a relevant audience at a national level, brands can combine reach with efficiency and serve the right ads to the right potential buyers at the exact right time to create demand for a product. While most advertising programs require brands to create campaigns weeks or months in advance of when they&rsquo;d like to drive interest in their product or services based on the time of year or a special event, highly-localized digital campaigns of any size can easily be created in a matter of hours by reusing digital assets to drive consumers into stores.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nBy developing a highly-customized local digital advertising strategy that complements existing campaigns, retailers and brands can consistently and effectively drive sales that help to increase revenue and create a more personal relationship with customers. More on localized advertising solutions <a href="http://www.maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-solutions" target="_blank">here</a>.</p>\r\n	t	2012-05-01 13:00:43	\N	2012-05-01 13:00:43	2013-09-27 02:45:19.288517	49	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, localized advertising, local, localized digital advertising, data, campaigns, consumers
897	1	51	maxpoint-vp-of-marketing-adds-hyperlocal-flavor-to-tima-ebook	MaxPoint’s VP of Marketing Adds Hyperlocal Flavor to TIMA eBook	<p>MaxPoint&rsquo;s VP of Marketing, Lynn Vitello, contributed several hyperlocal digital advertising tips to the latest eBook from TIMA. Take a look at the advice she offered.</p>\r\n	<p><a href="http://www.triangleinteractive.org/blog/tima-tips-free-ebook" target="_blank"><img alt="TIMA eBook cover" src="/system/editor/W1siZiIsIjIwMTQvMDEvMTMvMTNfNDNfNDVfNjA3X1RJTUFfZUJvb2tfYmxvZ18zNjB4MjcwLnBuZyJdLFsicCIsInRodW1iIiwiODAweDgwMD4iXV0/TIMA-eBook-blog_360x270.png" style="float:right; height:270px; margin:5px; width:360px" /></a>The Triangle enjoys a vibrant business community encompassing the areas of Chapel Hill, Durham, and Raleigh, North Carolina. Home to hundreds of global companies and startups alike, the region holds a wealth of marketing talent across a variety of industries. Triangle Interactive Marketing Association (TIMA) recently compiled the wisdom of local digital marketing experts in an eBook, <a href="http://www.triangleinteractive.org/blog/tima-tips-free-ebook" target="_blank"><em>Triangle&rsquo;s 101 Innovative Digital Marketing Tips</em></a><em>. </em>MaxPoint&rsquo;s VP of Marketing, Lynn Vitello, contributed several hyperlocal digital advertising tips to help marketers boost in-store sales:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Drive the Right Shoppers to Your Store&nbsp; </strong><br />\r\nSkip the DMA- and city-level targeting&mdash;it&rsquo;s too broad. Instead, eliminate wasted ad impressions by targeting the most interested customers in the right neighborhoods close to your local stores.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Go Easy on Geofencing</strong><br />\r\nGeofencing targets a handful of customers only when they are near a store. On the other hand, a hyperlocal digital campaign targets crowds of ideal customers at the right time. This provides precise targeting with the scale that geofencing lacks.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Match Your Ads to Real-Time Weather Conditions </strong><br />\r\nProvide relevance to your ads by dynamically turning them on or off in response to weather conditions. By being highly relevant in your ad timing, and targeting the right customers, you can predict and influence what shoppers will buy in the moment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Take Advantage of the Full Mobile Experience</strong><br />\r\nMobile is about convenience. Make it easy for customers to interact with your local business by providing click-to-call and click-to-map functionality in your ads and on your mobile-responsive site.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The TIMA eBook offers many other insights to improve your digital marketing, but the most powerful strategy of all is hyperlocal. Hyperlocal digital advertising gives you the precision and scale you need to effectively drive in-store sales.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>What else did the experts say? Get all the tips from Lynn and her fellow Triangle digital marketers by </em><a href="http://www.triangleinteractive.org/blog/tima-tips-free-ebook" target="_blank"><em>downloading the eBook</em></a><em> today.</em></p>\r\n	t	2014-01-13 19:40:04	\N	2014-01-13 19:43:26.516522	2014-01-13 19:45:52.80653	47	\N
780	1	15	new-york-neighborhoods-most-interested-in-asthma-and-allergy-remedies	New York Neighborhoods Most Interested in Asthma and Allergy Remedies 	<p>In honor of National Asthma and Allergy Awareness Month, we analyzed billions of data points to determine the U.S. neighborhoods most interested in allergy and asthma remedies.</p>\r\n	<p>In honor of National Asthma and Allergy Awareness Month, we analyzed billions of data points to determine the U.S. neighborhoods most interested in allergy and asthma remedies. What did this reveal? According to our Interest Index report, New York ranked the highest of all U.S. cities, and its Bay Shore and Smithtown neighborhoods were most interested in purchasing brand name and generic drugs, respectively. <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe top 10 cities that showed the greatest interest in asthma and allergy remedies include:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>New York, NY</li>\r\n\t<li>Columbus, OH</li>\r\n\t<li>Casper-Riverton, WY</li>\r\n\t<li>Charlotte, NC</li>\r\n\t<li>Hartford and New Haven, CT</li>\r\n\t<li>Hattiesburg-Laurel, MS</li>\r\n\t<li>Lafayette, LA</li>\r\n\t<li>Miami-Ft. Lauderdale, FL</li>\r\n\t<li>Philadelphia, PA</li>\r\n\t<li>Providence et al, RI-MA</li>\r\n\t<li>Rockford, IL</li>\r\n\t<li>Victoria, TX</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nAccording to our COO, Gretchen Joyce, &ldquo;Pharmaceutical companies are faced with a significant challenge when it comes to identifying and marketing to consumers, due to privacy concerns.&rdquo; Due to privacy issues highly discouraging the use of cookies in the healthcare industry, this data is often difficult to determine or access. However, our technology, which is not reliant on cookies, makes this data accessible and actionable to brands and retailers without violating consumer privacy concerns.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn addition, unlike traditional DMA targeting, brands and retailers can now target specific neighborhoods within the same DMA. For example, brands can identify neighborhoods of consumers who prefer generic versus brand name medications and tailor their message accordingly.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nUsing the data gleamed from this index, we implemented highly targeted neighborhood-level digital advertising campaigns for both pharmaceutical brands and retailers. For example:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>A major pharmaceutical brand was looking to increase awareness and participation in its asthma patient program by targeting areas with a high concentration of asthma sufferers. By combining DMA and interest data, MaxPoint was able to target women age 25-54 showing an interest in asthma for themselves and their families &ndash; ultimately doubling the number of program participants.</li>\r\n\t<li>A major consumer packaged goods company was interested in generating awareness and driving in-store sales of its over-the-counter cold medication. As a result of a highly targeted online video campaign, the CPG company was able to reach households with adults ages 25-54, who were interested in flu and cold remedies, and purchased competitive brands and products in the past.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nFor more information on this Interest Index report, click <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/online-advertising-news/asthma-and-allergy-remedy-interest" target="_blank">here</a>.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nTo check out last month&rsquo;s Interest Index report on the most environmentally conscious cities, click <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/online-advertising-news/environmental-interest" target="_blank">here</a>.</p>\r\n	t	2012-05-30 14:10:16	\N	2012-05-30 14:10:16	2013-11-01 21:33:53.044309	54	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, Interest Index, Digital Zip, OnPoint, data, neighborhood-level advertising, digital advertising
