781	1	15	advertisers-leverage-the-2012-olympic-games-to-engage-audiences	Advertisers Leverage the 2012 Olympic Games to Engage Audiences	<p>The summer of 2012 is finally here, marking the arrival of the London Olympic Games. And, with millions of people tuning in and heading online to watch/read about the games coming this July, advertisers are taking advantage and launching campaigns that are sure to reach their target audiences.</p>\r\n	<p>The summer of 2012 is finally here, marking the arrival of the London Olympic Games. And, with millions of people tuning in and heading online to watch/read about the games coming this July, advertisers are taking advantage and launching campaigns that are sure to reach their target audiences.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nFor example, Coca-Cola and Visa are just two of the brands that have already started leveraging the Olympic Games and launched campaigns of Olympic size. According to Thomas Pardee, editorial/production coordinator at Advertising Age, &ldquo;Both play on the general spirit of excitement and competition while careful skirting of the international politics of games.&rdquo; Here are a few details around these campaigns:<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Coca-Cola &ldquo;Move to the Beat of London 2012&rdquo; &ndash;</strong> Coca-Cola&rsquo;s campaign takes a music-based approach as Mark Ronson and singer, Katy B, are moving to the beat of the fast-paced Olympic spectacle. Aimed to engage a teenage audience and create hype around the Olympic Games, the unveiling of the campaign marks the launch of a &ldquo;Track the Beat&rdquo; Facebook app, online video spots and a &ldquo;Move to the Beat&rdquo; television commercial. In addition, the soundtrack for the campaign will play across digital/mobile platforms, during Coca-Cola events and will be available for purchase later on this year. Already, number five on the viral video chart, with over a million views, this campaign is rapidly working its way into the minds of viewers everywhere. Watch <a href="http://youtu.be/HjPHjtZ5cIk" target="_blank">here</a>. The agency behind this campaign is Mother London.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Visa &ldquo;Go World 2012&rdquo; &ndash;</strong> Visa recently unleashed its largest campaign in its 25-year history as a sponsor of the Olympic Games &ndash; leveraging TV, print and digital. The campaign features stories of Olympic athletes (Michael Phelps and Li Na for example) that highlight past glory moments, with the tagline, &ldquo;Join our global cheer.&rdquo; Already racking in more than 2.7 million video views, the campaign has generated significant social buzz across the 70 countries it&rsquo;s been released to. For the first time, Visa is leveraging social media to encourage consumer/fan participation. Watch <a href="http://www.youtube.com/visabrand" target="_blank">here</a>. The agency behind this campaign is TBWA/Chiat/Day Los Angeles.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nBoth of these brands are leveraging online video, as well as traditional methods to deliver a strong cross-channel campaign. In addition, each of these brands speaks to an audience&rsquo;s emotion, as they are focused on an event that many people have grown up with over the years. It&rsquo;s a powerful marketing mix that is expected to create a strong return on investment.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOther brands launching campaigns of Olympic size to watch out for are Gap, Rovio, Old Spice and Volvo (to name a few).</p>\r\n	t	2012-05-31 13:49:05	\N	2012-05-31 13:49:05	2013-09-20 00:54:57.860979	49	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, campaigns, online video, advertising  
775	1	15	new-research-reveals-behaviors-of-todays-cost-conscious-grocery-shoppers	New Research Reveals Behaviors of Today's Cost-Conscious Grocery Shoppers 	<p>Today, we&rsquo;ve released a new research report, conducted by BIGinsight&trade; that reveals the changing behavior among cost-conscious grocery shoppers as they move through the path to purchase in today&rsquo;s post-recession economy.</p>\r\n	<p>When it comes to making a budget for shopping, consumers are mindful of how the economy has affected their lifestyle and spending habits. As a result of the post-recession economy, consumers have tried to find the best ways to maximize their monthly spend, specifically, they have become more cost-conscious grocery shoppers. Today, we&rsquo;ve released a new research report, conducted by BIGinsight&trade; that reveals the changing behavior among cost-conscious grocery shoppers as they move through the path to purchase in today&rsquo;s post-recession economy. <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe Grocery Industry Pulse titled, &ldquo;Reaching Today&rsquo;s Cost-Conscious Consumer,&rdquo; reveals that the average monthly spend on groceries has steadily increased among the general population from pre- to post-recession. While spending continues to climb, nearly three in four respondents have made changes to their grocery shopping habits within the last year, becoming more cost-conscious before and during their trips. Some of the ways cost-conscious grocery shoppers have changed their behavior include:<span id="cke_bm_98C" style="display:none">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>Shopping closer to home and shopping at multiple grocery stores</li>\r\n\t<li>Leveraging coupons and sales more</li>\r\n\t<li>Preparing lists before shopping</li>\r\n\t<li>Using more resources such as digital channels to prepare for shopping trips</li>\r\n\t<li>Heading to recipe-specific destination sites to prepare for shopping</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nOther Key findings include:<span id="cke_bm_99C" style="display:none">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>Average monthly spend on groceries has steadily increased among the general population from pre-to post-recession from $250.94 in August 2007 to $277.00 in August 2011. Among moms, it has steadily increased from $311.95 to $341.14 during the same timeframe.</li>\r\n\t<li>Two in five respondents indicate they are purchasing more store brand or generic items now than compared with this time last year. 53.4% are purchasing the same amount.</li>\r\n\t<li>Three in 10 respondents have cut back on purchasing bakery items, candy, dessert items and magazines/books/DVDs over the past year. One in four have cut back on prime cuts of meats/seafood.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nAs a result of the changing economy, it is clear that consumers are shifting shopping behaviors to get more for their money. According to our COO, Gretchen Joyce, &ldquo;Digital is reshaping the grocery shopping experience in the post-recession economy, as consumers turn to new channels to help plan their shopping trips. By understanding what motivates today&rsquo;s consumer, brands can tailor their shopper marketing strategies to ensure they are gaining mindshare and winning at the shelf-level.&rdquo;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nFor a copy of the full research brief, please click <a href="http://offers.maxpoint.com/GroceryShopperInsights.html" target="_blank">here</a>.</p>\r\n	t	2012-05-15 14:57:01	\N	2012-05-15 14:57:01	2013-09-21 01:51:32.586696	49	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, retail, shoppers, grocery sales, path to purchase
777	1	15	top-5-ways-to-optimize-your-holiday-campaigns	Top 5 Ways to Optimize Your Holiday Campaigns	<p>For many brands and retailers, holiday planning begins early in the year. Why do you think you see advertisements for Christmas in July? It&rsquo;s never too early to start preparing for holidays that can rack in the largest retail sales of the year.</p>\r\n	<p>For many brands and retailers, holiday planning begins early in the year. Why do you think you see advertisements for Christmas in July? It&rsquo;s never too early to start preparing for holidays that can rack in the largest retail sales of the year.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nAccording to the International Council of Shopping Centers, holiday sales in November and December can amount up to 40% of a retailer&rsquo;s annual sales. And, with this much riding on the line, retailers need to do everything they can to come out on top. Below are our top five ways to optimize your holiday campaigns this year.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Use relevant messaging:</strong> Holiday campaigns are typically not intended for all audiences. The product or offer being advertised is intended for a specific audience that has buying power during the holiday shopping season. Make sure messaging is relevant and speaks to your intended audience. Messaging towards parents would be much different than messaging towards teenagers, where parents may be more concerned with holiday sales and teens focused on new trends.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Pair campaigns with offers/coupons:</strong> Knowing consumers will be spending a lot on different holiday decorations and gifts, it is important to keep their budget in mind. Attract shoppers in-store by offering coupons or specials in your digital holiday ads that they can download and take in-store.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Leverage localized digital advertising solutions:</strong> Above, we touched on the importance of using relevant messaging for specific audiences. However, this will not matter if your intended audience does not receive the advertisement. Leverage localized digital advertising solutions to target and serve advertisements to the relevant audience for maximum ROI. More on localized digital ad solutions <a href="http://www.maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-solutions" target="_blank">here</a>.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Create cross-platform campaigns:</strong> Traditional advertising methods alone cannot deliver maximum reach, so marketers are exploring new and multiple channels to advertise on. Take creative intended for TV and repurpose it online &nbsp;such as pre/mid-roll video ads. By creating cross-platform campaigns, you can reach a wider audience and deliver on a strong marketing mix. More on cross-platform campaigns <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/onpoint-blog/2012/5/9/creating-cross-platform-campaigns-what-works-what-to-avoid" target="_blank">here</a>.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Continue to reach shoppers in-store:</strong> Once you successfully leverage online efforts and drive shopper&rsquo;s in-store, also make sure they are engaged once they get there. For instance, provide digital displays that direct shoppers to certain products seen in advertisements. This way your campaign can reach shoppers at all touchpoints on the path to purchase.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIt&rsquo;s a season that defines retailers and brands, so make sure your holiday campaign is optimized to its fullest. We would love to hear your feedback on tips for optimizing holiday campaigns. Leave a comment below or tweet <a href="https://twitter.com/maxpoint_int">@maxpoint_int</a> with the #onpoint.</p>\r\n	t	2012-05-21 14:15:42	\N	2012-05-21 14:15:42	2013-09-21 01:48:41.418955	49	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, campaigns, holiday campaigns, cross-platform
776	1	15	maxpoint-asks-fmi-attendees-how-have-you-seen-consumer-grocery-shopping-habits-change	MaxPoint Asks FMI Attendees: How Have You Seen Consumer Grocery Shopping Habits Change?	<p>MaxPoint headed to Dallas, TX for FMI 2012, the food retail show of the year, and hit the show floor to survey over 100 food retail industry executives. We wanted to know how the changing economy has affected consumers, specifically when it comes to grocery shopping habits. This is what FMI attendees had to say.</p>\r\n	<p>MaxPoint headed to Dallas, TX for FMI 2012, the food retail show of the year, and hit the show floor to survey over 100 food retail industry executives. We wanted to know how the changing economy has affected consumers, specifically when it comes to grocery shopping habits. This is what FMI attendees had to say:<!--more--><span id="cke_bm_98C" style="display:none">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>Shopping multiple stores:</strong> Thirty-five percent of food retail industry executives indicated that more shoppers today are heading in-store but shopping at multiple stores in order to find the best prices and deals. In addition, approximately 15 percent of survey respondents said that consumers are more frequently shopping at discount stores and club stores like Costco and Sam&rsquo;s Club.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Shopping closer to home:</strong> Local is becoming important to shoppers in 2012 as the survey also revealed that 30 percent of retail industry executives believe consumers are shopping closer to home.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Using coupons/loyalty cards:</strong> According to the survey, 32 percent of respondents said that shoppers are using more print coupons and 31 percent of respondents said that shoppers are using more digital coupons. FMI attendees (20 percent) also believe that grocery shoppers are increasing their use of store loyalty cards.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Buying more generic/private label brands:</strong> Twenty-one percent of survey respondents noted when surveyed that consumers are dealing with the changing economy by focusing purchases on buying more generic/private label brand items.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Cut back on splurging and shopping for sales:</strong> Twenty percent of respondents shared that &ldquo;splurging&rdquo; on items at the grocery store has been cut back. They said consumers are just buying what is needed. Seventeen percent believe that consumers are shopping more sales days.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Completing online research:</strong> Twenty percent of FMI attendees surveyed indicated that more shoppers are heading online to plan their trips.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Sticking to shopping lists:</strong> Seven percent of respondents believe that consumers will stick to shopping lists created before heading in-store.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>No change at all:</strong> For the most part, it is evident to food retail executives that consumer grocery shopping habits have changed as a result of the changing economy. However, 2 percent have indicated that they have not noticed a change in shopping behavior in the past year.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nInterested in finding out if what FMI attendees had to say matches what consumers say about the change in their grocery shopping habits?<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOn the heels of BIGinsight&rsquo;s research report released yesterday titled &ldquo;Reaching Today&rsquo;s Cost-Conscious Consumer,&rdquo; we compared what consumers had to say to industry executives. Interestingly enough, there are discrepancies between grocery executives&rsquo; insights around digital advertising and consumer behavior.&nbsp; For instance, we found that only 20 percent of respondents think consumers use digital mediums to prepare for their shopping trips. However, BIGinsight&rsquo;s research found that 90 percent of consumers regularly research products online before purchasing them in-store.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAccording to our COO, Gretchen Joyce, &ldquo;The combination of our research and BIGinsight&rsquo;s report provide great insights into how consumers are now making purchasing decisions and the role that digital plays in those decisions.&rdquo; Click <a href="http://offers.maxpoint.com/GroceryShopperInsights.html" target="_blank">here</a> and get your copy of the FREE research report on reaching today&rsquo;s cost conscious consumer and how the changing economy has affected consumers&rsquo; grocery shopping habits.</p>\r\n	t	2012-05-16 12:00:19	\N	2012-05-16 12:00:19	2013-09-21 01:50:16.832651	49	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, grocery, shoppers, retail, path to purchase, consumers, digital
881	1	15	measuring-your-digital-ad-campaigns-closing-the-loop-on-sales-part-2	Measuring Your Digital Ad Campaigns: Closing the Loop on Sales—Part 2	<p>There&#39;s more than one way to measure sales. This week&#39;s post covers two types of studies that measure sales lift, while being more budget-friendly than panel studies.</p>\r\n	<p><img alt="" src="/system/editor/W1siZiIsIjIwMTMvMDkvMjkvMTBfMDdfMTlfNDI5X0Jsb2dfTWVhc3VyZW1lbnRfU2VyaWVzXzMucG5nIl0sWyJwIiwidGh1bWIiLCI4MDB4ODAwPiJdXQ/Blog%20Measurement%20Series_3.png" style="float:right; height:290px; margin:0px 15px; width:300px" />In our last post, we covered <a href="http://staging.maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/onpoint-blog/2013/9/18/measuring-your-digital-ad-campaigns-closing-the-loop-on-sales-part-1" target="_blank">panel-based sales lift studies</a>. They&rsquo;re expensive and work on only the largest of campaigns. But they do provide excellent insights to the advertiser. They aren&rsquo;t your only option, however, for measuring sales lift. Today, we&rsquo;ll cover the two major alternatives&mdash;third-party point-of-sale studies and retail-partner studies. They both provide excellent data, yet are easier on your budget.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Just to recap, each of the sales lift study methods include the following steps:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n\t<li>Run a campaign to a specific test group, in an area or over a specific time frame.</li>\r\n\t<li>Collect data on both the test group and the control group.</li>\r\n\t<li>Compare the difference in sales between both groups.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nThe general process is always the same&mdash;it&rsquo;s the data collection step that changes. This affects both the price and the results. And that&rsquo;s where today&rsquo;s studies come in.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Point-of-Sale Studies</strong><br />\r\nMany stores provide research firms access to sales data in exchange for either monetary compensation or access to general industry data from the research firm. In turn, the research firm can use this data as input for sales lift studies. This relationship benefits all sides&mdash;the stores get data (or financial compensation) that they wouldn&rsquo;t get otherwise, and the firms get access to sales data that helps them complete different studies.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>These studies are less expensive than those involving panel data. Because the data comes from stores rather than directly from consumers, however, you won&rsquo;t receive any extra information about the audience. Panel studies provide additional insights about consumers because the researchers know the exact makeup of the audience. Although you can&rsquo;t get the same insights from point-of-sale studies, they still provide accurate sales data at a decent price.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Retail-Partner Studies</strong><br />\r\nRetail-partner studies are the least expensive type of sales lift study. These studies involve collecting data from your retail partners in both test stores and control stores, then comparing the lift between the two. For example, if you work with a major national retailer, you can compare the increase in sales in one region against another. Alternatively, you could compare sales during a campaign&rsquo;s run dates against a control time period.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Retail-partner studies are great options when you want to put a dollar figure on your ad campaigns, but don&rsquo;t have the budget to spend on a study from a research firm. However, there are two major flaws with them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>First, these studies can be skewed. Research firms typically run algorithms to correct for any over- or under-representation among their panels or store samples. For example, if young male professionals are underrepresented in a panel when compared to the ratio of the nation at large, then the third-party firm will typically count this group&rsquo;s purchases with a little more weight to compensate. Retail-partner studies don&rsquo;t necessarily correct for any demographic imbalances, making them at risk for heavy skew.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Second, these studies aren&rsquo;t always an available option. They require that your retail partners are willing to share data with you in a timely manner. This isn&rsquo;t always the case. Additionally, you may end up picking a retail chain that has drastically skewed sales, making your results suspect.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, if you have the data available, the numbers from these studies can be an excellent ballpark for your sales figures, even if they&rsquo;re not perfect.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Sales Lift in Action</strong><br />\r\nSo, what kind of results can you expect? MaxPoint helped a major food CPG brand promote in-store sales at one of its big-box retail partners. Because the brand typically sells a high volume of products and has a fairly high measurement budget, it decided to run a panel-based sales lift study with a third-party research firm. Over three months, MaxPoint ran ads to targeted audiences in key neighborhoods around the big-box stores. After the campaign, the research firm compiled sales data from a panel to uncover the sales lift. According to the research firm&rsquo;s findings, the campaign produced a 17% increase in sales at the big-box store and a 13% increase in product sales at other retail stores. While sales lift numbers can vary widely based on the product and the industry, a 17% sales lift was a great result for this campaign.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>What&rsquo;s Next?</strong><br />\r\nThis concludes our discussion of sales lift studies. We hope you learned a lot, and now realize that you don&rsquo;t always need a huge budget to test your sales lift.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But what if your goal is to produce an effect at a higher spot in the sales funnel? Next, we&rsquo;ll tackle that topic by introducing you to <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/onpoint-blog/2013/10/15/measuring-your-digital-ad-campaigns-brand-lift-and-engagement" target="_blank">brand engagement studies</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Don&rsquo;t Want to Wait?</strong><br />\r\n<a href="http://offers.maxpoint.com/measurement" target="_blank">Download our measurement guide</a> now to learn more about putting your digital campaigns to the measurement test.</p>\r\n	t	2013-09-30 15:02:58	\N	2013-09-29 15:03:41.658653	2013-10-15 13:06:28.26011	62	\N
900	1	37	do-not-panic-dealing-with-the-unforeseen-in-advertising	Don’t Panic: Dealing with the Unforeseen in Advertising	<p>Advertisers frequently have to change course mid-campaign. Today&#39;s post covers some tips on how to deal with the unforeseen in digital advertising.</p>\r\n	<p><img alt="Skiing" src="/system/editor/W1siZiIsIjIwMTQvMDEvMjgvMTFfNDhfMzJfNjQ3X2lTdG9ja18wMDAwMDU5Nzg3MDBTbWFsbC5qcGciXSxbInAiLCJ0aHVtYiIsIjgwMHg4MDA%2BIl1d/iStock_000005978700Small.jpg" style="float:right; height:232px; margin:5px; width:350px" />When I heard that Lindsey Vonn wouldn&rsquo;t be able to compete in this year&rsquo;s Olympics, I had two reactions. First, I felt terrible for Lindsey. Imagine training for your entire life, being the best in your sport, and then having an injury sideline you when you reach the Olympics. It has to be tough, so I feel for Lindsey.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My second reaction was concern for the retailers and brands that would have to pull some of their ads. Imagine that you&rsquo;ve invested in campaigns featuring an Olympic athlete, only to see your main spokesperson injured for the event. Of course, many Lindsey ads will still work, but the brands will have to make judgment calls on which ads they&rsquo;ll need to pull. Regardless, this situation will likely cause some headaches.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This sort of thing happens more often than it should. The problem goes beyond celebrity endorsement issues&mdash;it could include a brand-sponsored event that gets rained out, or it could be that a brand partner for a joint venture gets bad press. Frankly, I&rsquo;d bet good money that these situations are the leading causes of insomnia among agency employees.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But when I started to think about it, I realized that maybe hiccups like these don&rsquo;t have to completely torpedo a campaign. There are a few preventive steps agencies can take to keep a campaign from completely collapsing:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n\t<li><strong>Foster a Responsive Agency Culture&mdash;</strong>It often starts with office culture. Do you encourage employees to deal well with rapid changes? And if problems arise, do cooler heads prevail? In the real-time era, it&rsquo;s paramount that agency employees feel comfortable dealing with quick changes. Encourage them now, and you&rsquo;ll have a good foundation to cushion you when you fall.<br />\r\n\t&nbsp;</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Always Have a Plan B&mdash;</strong>You will breathe easier if you have a good backup plan. In Lindsey&rsquo;s case, you could switch your client&rsquo;s campaign to cheer on all of Team USA. This keeps the campaign relevant to the Olympics, but doesn&rsquo;t focus on any single athlete.<br />\r\n\t&nbsp;</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Advertise Digitally&mdash;</strong>Digital channels provide a lot of breathing room for advertisers. Instead of scrambling to pull a print ad from a magazine issue or letting an out-of-date direct mail package reach recipients, you can swap out the creative for campaigns within 24 hours (or less).<br />\r\n\t&nbsp;</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Consider Adaptive Campaigns&mdash;</strong>Problems frequently arise outside of issues with endorsements or bad press. Sometimes, an ad campaign can fall flat due to real-time local conditions. That&rsquo;s when a good ad technology partner can help. For example, MaxPoint runs hyperlocal digital campaigns that adapt to changing weather conditions, which means iced coffee ads on warm days and hot latte ads on frigid days. In short, smart technology leads to agile advertising campaigns.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nUltimately, unforeseen events can push you off course, but they don&rsquo;t have to completely sink your campaigns. If you lay the groundwork and take a few precautions, setbacks like these will require only a few tweaks in order to right the ship.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Do you know the best audience for your Olympic-themed campaigns? Find out by reading our recent <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/advertising-tips-and-strategies/advertising-insights/bring-home-the-advertising-gold-this-winter" target="_blank">Interest Index</a>.</em></p>\r\n	t	2014-01-28 17:38:38	\N	2014-01-28 17:41:39.825949	2014-01-28 18:11:00.802603	63	\N
898	1	33	big-data-brings-rewards-for-those-seeking-advertising-jobs	Big Data Brings Big Rewards for Those Seeking Advertising Jobs	<p>Is big data at the top of your career development list? Find out why it should be if you are pursuing advertising jobs.</p>\r\n	<p><em><img alt="" src="/system/editor/W1siZiIsIjIwMTQvMDEvMjEvMTFfNDJfMDlfOTI5X2lTdG9ja18wMDAwMTc0NTI2ODlNZWRpdW0uanBnIl0sWyJwIiwidGh1bWIiLCI4MDB4ODAwPiJdXQ/iStock_000017452689Medium.jpg" style="float:right; height:200px; margin:5px; width:300px" />Will it play in Peoria?</em> That&rsquo;s the question advertisers have asked for years to determine whether a product, promotion, or event will appeal to mainstream America. For advertisers today, big data makes it easier than ever to answer that question. Brands are staffing their teams with professionals who know how to use the powerful insights from big data to predict if a product will play in Peoria &hellip; or Bakersfield &hellip; or Chicago &hellip; or anywhere else across the nation. So if you&rsquo;re looking to advance your career in advertising, big data should be at the top of your career development list.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Why Brands Like General Mills Use Big Data</strong><br />\r\nGeneral Mills&rsquo; brand pages and social channels, such as Facebook and Twitter, generate millions of customer interactions annually. Each of those interactions connects back to a consumer with a real mouth and stomach who makes decisions several times per day about what they and their family will eat. For a brand like General Mills, tapping into the insights learned from these interactions through a social media listening center provides incredible opportunity for the brand. When General Mills ties a consumer trend to product innovation faster than its competitors, it wins big in the form of greater in-store sales.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With this in mind, brands like General Mills are hiring experts and implementing tools to instantly aggregate and analyze data. With the right resources, they can act on microtrends related to food combinations and flavor movements extracted from online conversations. By simply listening to their consumers, brands can calculate indexes on emerging topics and tie them to sentiments. For General Mills, this means the brand can understand and act when users are excited or turned off by some product or flavor, from Cinnamon Toast Crunch to Toaster Strudels, and everything in between.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>How Big Data Is Changing the Advertising Job Market</strong><br />\r\nNever before have brands and retailers been able to chase trends and test new ideas with the same confidence and expediency. Big data is driving major disruptions in distribution, warehousing, pricing, product presentation, and more.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This disruption does not end in the warehouse or the retail shelves; it also affects job creation and recruitment. <a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/forbesinsights/2013/08/02/analysis-shows-jump-in-marketing-analytics-jobs/" target="_blank">According to Forbes</a>, sources predict that big data will create 1.9 million new jobs in the United States by 2015.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For college students and other job seekers who embrace big data and the study of analytics, there is considerable career potential in the advertising industry. These are just a few of the roles:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>Analytics and Data Processing</strong> &ndash; Strict data-mining roles are among the faster growing positions at digital agencies, manufacturers, retailers, and data vendors.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Media Planning and Buying</strong> &ndash; Digital agencies, manufacturers, and retailers are filling these roles with professionals who are familiar with big data and who can ensure media buys capitalize on user demands, trends, and segments.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Design and Development</strong> &ndash; Quite often these roles at digital agencies, consultancies, and brand-orientated design shops work in tandem with those familiar with the big data trends driving ad placement and targeting. An understanding of analytics is critical to ensuring campaigns are valuable.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Sales and Consultation</strong> &ndash; Publishers, aggregators, data management firms, research companies, and analytics groups need not only your pitch skills but also your deeper understanding of the big data ecosystem and how it affects the advertising industry.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nThe future of advertising belongs to people with big data skills. Whether you&rsquo;re a student exploring careers or you&rsquo;re a seasoned veteran wanting to further your development, mastering the basics of big data and analysis will put you light-years ahead of others in the job market.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>At MaxPoint, we know a lot about big data. Every day, we use rich insights and proprietary data to help retailers and brands make smarter digital advertising decisions at the hyperlocal level. If you think you&rsquo;d be a good fit for our team, we want to hear from you. </em><a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/online-advertising-careers/online-advertising-jobs" target="_blank"><em>Check out our current job postings now</em></a><em>.</em></p>\r\n	t	2014-01-21 16:57:18	\N	2014-01-21 17:01:53.833469	2014-01-21 17:53:59.51413	47	\N
736	1	16	why-big-data-matters	Why Big Data Matters	<p>Now, &ldquo;big data&rdquo; is something we&rsquo;re hearing a lot about. But why does it matter?</p>\r\n	<p>Recently, I was thinking of a conversation I had with one of our analysts a few years ago, in which we were discussing a problem in design, related to the sample sets modeled for analysis. I remember thinking, well, just run all the data. Of course at the time, access to that kind of data-crunching power wasn&rsquo;t as common as it is today. The tools weren&rsquo;t as well known, and people weren&rsquo;t in that mode of thinking. Analysts were still trained to run samples.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nNow, &ldquo;big data&rdquo; is something we&rsquo;re hearing a lot about. But why does it matter? Well, it matters because of what it enables. Technologies&mdash;Hadoop, Hive, Mahout&mdash;have unlocked access to growing amounts of data. This big data now seems smaller, more manageable, more useful&mdash;more actionable. And while these tools have helped unlock these capabilities, there is a definite learning curve. You still have to know how to use it and apply it.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nToday, these tools enable companies of varying sizes to use big data to innovate in new and interesting ways. Access to all this data unlocks lots of potential and opens the door for more creativity. It&rsquo;s going to be exciting to watch the innovation that comes of it.</p>\r\n	t	2012-03-09 14:00:34	\N	2012-03-09 14:00:34	2013-10-01 15:24:41.114925	52	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, data analysis, OnPoint, Kurt Carlson, big data, data, analysts, technology, Hadoop, Hive, Mahout 
728	1	15	what-is-contributing-to-the-rapid-growth-of-digital-video-ad-spending	What is Contributing to the Rapid Growth of Digital Video Ad Spending?	<p>Did you know consumers are watching more than 21 hours of online video per month (on average) across a variety of connected devices? With a lot of eyeballs focused on online video, marketers must start following the trends and move more advertising dollars to online video to adapt to this consumer behavior.</p>\r\n	<p>Did you know consumers are watching more than 21 hours of online video per month (on average) across a variety of connected devices? With a lot of eyeballs focused on online video, marketers must start following the trends and move more advertising dollars to online video to adapt to this consumer behavior. With digital video ad spending growing by more than 25% from 2011 to 2016, what is driving all of this growth? <a href="http://www.forrester.com/rb/research/" target="_blank">Forrester</a> revealed some reasons for this growth in a recent report. Let&rsquo;s take a look at what they had to say:<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Digital video content is maturing from user generated to premium content.</strong> It wasn&rsquo;t long ago, when consumers watched digital video to see stupid human tricks, cool pet tricks and even cute baby tricks, but online video is evolving today to the point where digital media companies like Hulu are producing premium original content that brands can partner with.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Devices and platforms for video consumption are on the rise.</strong> Remember the days when we just watched video on a TV screen? Now it seems like devices multiplied overnight and consumers are watching digital video on computers, smartphones, and tablets. Consumers can also use new devices like Apple TV and Internet connected TVs to watch digital video. To make sure consumers can access TV content at all times, content providers are working extra hard to make this happen on a variety of devices, as long as consumers are willing to pay their cable bill.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Young consumers point to a &ldquo;video my way&rdquo; future.</strong> I&rsquo;m sure you aren&rsquo;t surprised to hear that a big part of this digital video growth is due to young consumers &ndash; they are leading the way in online viewing. According to Forrester, 37 million US households own a connected device that enables them to watch digital video on their TV screen. Of these households, young consumers lead the way by outpacing the overall population in adoption by almost 20 percentage points. By 2016, there will be even more opportunities for video consumption options.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIt&#39;s clear that digital is becoming an increasingly important part of our culture and more consumers are headed online every day. And, as consumer habits change so must advertising. So...the question remains - are you leveraging this growth and using digital video as part of your marketing strategies in 2012?</p>\r\n	t	2012-02-27 15:57:25	\N	2012-02-27 15:57:25	2013-10-01 19:05:18.219013	51	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, Alicia Johston, video, online advertising, advertising budgets, Forrester, digital video ad growth, advertising statistics, consumption, consumers
