787	1	15	fathers-day-marketing	Father's Day Marketing	<p>As Father&rsquo;s Day approaches, retailers and brands focus on serving advertisements with Father&rsquo;s Day specific messaging and target shoppers that are looking for a special gift for dad. And, to compete with the other clutter this time of year (graduations, weddings and the launch of summer), retailers and brands need to make sure their advertising reaches and engages the right audience.</p>\r\n	<p>As Father&rsquo;s Day approaches, retailers and brands focus on serving advertisements with Father&rsquo;s Day specific messaging and target shoppers that are looking for a special gift for dad. And, to compete with the other clutter this time of year (graduations, weddings and the launch of summer), retailers and brands need to make sure their advertising reaches and engages the right audience.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn a recent article on Luxury Daily, &ldquo;How Father&rsquo;s Day marketing differs from Mother&rsquo;s Day campaigns,&rdquo; associate reporter, Rachel Lamb, talks about how labels eyeing Father&rsquo;s Day may prefer to appeal to shoppers on the grounds of practicality and the needs and wants of the gift recipient. It is a very strategic marketing process as retailers and brands must focus on marketing gifts that appeal to dad while also getting through to moms and children - key purchasers behind Father&rsquo;s Day gifts.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nHere are a few tips to reach and engage shoppers this Father&rsquo;s Day:<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Think about the female shopper.</strong> While dads may head in-store to take advantage of Father&rsquo;s Day deals, it is most likely women who are shopping for fathers or husbands. In the article, Lamb notes that women shopping for fathers or husbands are more likely to be more creative with their purchases. Women seek out gifts for Father&rsquo;s Day that will create memories and become a keepsake. Knowing this, marketing around Father&rsquo;s Day products can highlight a product dad will enjoy but appeal to the woman receiving the ad. For instance, in your ad, be sure to talk about how the product will create a memory for dad.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Understand what dad wants.</strong> This year, retailers and brands are hitting dads with luxury items, including: nice watches, cufflinks, suits and high end vehicles. Gifts around golf and other sports-related items are welcomed by dad too. Retailers and brands should be mindful of product placement around popular Father&rsquo;s Day gifts and deals making it easy for the in-store shopper to find.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Leverage online advertising.</strong> Retailers and brands will be using multi-channel strategies as part of their overall Father&rsquo;s Day advertising this year. According to Lamb, &ldquo;social media and email are expected to take the reins for Father&rsquo;s Day marketing this year, but brands should consider a multi-channel attack for maximum exposure.&rdquo; Consumers are always connected and most shoppers head online to research a product or retailer/brand before heading in-store. Make sure online ads are served to the right audience when that audience begins their decision making process. With shoppers turning to digital closer to the beginning of the path to purchase, retailers and brands can leverage online advertising to make sure campaigns are delivered early and have influence. Then retailers and brands can continue to deliver advertisements and consistent messaging all the way in-store.</p>\r\n	t	2012-06-13 14:22:50	\N	2012-06-13 14:22:50	2013-09-20 00:39:09.587404	49	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, campaigns, advertising, multi-channel
786	1	15	digitals-impact-on-in-store-marketing	Impact of Digital on In-Store Marketing 	<p>Over the past few years, we have seen major advancements in new technology and in the opportunities they present us. In the advertising industry, the advancement of new technology has opened up more channels for advertisers to leverage and market on &ndash; creating new ways to reach shoppers.</p>\r\n	<p>Over the past few years, we have seen major advancements in new technology and in the opportunities they present us. In the advertising industry, the advancement of new technology has opened up more channels for advertisers to leverage and market on &ndash; creating new ways to reach shoppers.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn the grocery world, the rise of digital and new technology has impacted the way retailers and brands can reach shoppers. More specifically, in addition to opening up more avenues to reach shoppers along the path to purchase, digital is causing retailers and brands to re-think and ramp up their in-store marketing.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn a recent article in Progressive Grocer, &ldquo;What&rsquo;s Next For the Supermarket Circular?,&rdquo; Jason Brennan, founder of Stream Cos., discusses how in a world where everything is going digital, the printed supermarket circular is becoming counter-intuitive. According to Brennan, &ldquo;the retail circular is not necessarily dead. It just needs to be re-evaluated in the changing world of integrated, digital, mobile, and social marketing.&rdquo;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhat does this mean? In-store marketing is still an important step in the path to purchase but marketers need to make sure the in-store marketing incorporates digital strategies. To execute a clean marketing strategy from digital to in-store, retailers and brands should keep consistent with digital messaging and leverage digital in-store. Here are a couple things to keep in mind:<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Incorporate digital messaging:</strong> Today, most shoppers head online to complete grocery research before they go in-store, and it can be one of the first places shoppers see an ad. Keep consistent with digital messaging on in-store displays and signage to deliver a seamless brand experience. In addition, if shoppers have seen and responded to ads online, in-store signs that incorporate digital messaging will reinforce and remind shoppers of the message. To read more on consumer grocery shopping habits, click <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/onpoint-blog/2012/5/15/new-research-reveals-behaviors-of-todays-cost-conscious-grocery-shoppers" target="_blank">here</a>.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Leverage digital devices</strong>: The digital experience does not have to end online. With the advancement of new technology, devices like smart phones and tablets, allow shoppers to access mobile shopping apps. and bring digital in-store. For instance, place QR codes on in-store displays and shoppers can easily scan and access more information on a certain product. Shoppers can also access coupons or reference digital in-store floor maps from mobile devices for easier store navigation.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nBy reaching shoppers at the beginning of the path to purchase with digital and continuing to reach them once in-store, retailers and brands can deliver a strong marketing strategy that drives in-store traffic and sales.</p>\r\n	t	2012-06-11 15:12:02	\N	2012-06-11 15:12:02	2013-09-20 00:44:54.740008	49	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, retail, in-store marketing, digital, digital advertising
783	1	15	graduation-means-retail-sales	Graduation Means Retail Sales	<p>As graduates rush around to finalize last minute details, such as gown orders and over-due book returns, parents and loved ones are equally as rushed searching for that special graduation gift. And, just like the holiday season, graduation is always expected to rack in sales for retailers.</p>\r\n	<p>As graduates rush around to finalize last minute details, such as gown orders and over-due book returns, parents and loved ones are equally as rushed searching for that special graduation gift. And, just like the holiday season, graduation is always expected to rack in sales for retailers. <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nAccording to the National Retail Federation&rsquo;s (NRF) 2012 <a href="http://blog.nrf.com/2012/05/24/graduation-gift-giving-to-top-4-7-billion-in-2012/" target="_blank">Graduation Survey</a>, one-third of Americans will buy graduation gifts this year, a rise from 30.7 percent in 2011. Here are some key takeaways from the survey:<span id="cke_bm_337C" style="display:none">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>Over one-third intend to give gift cards &ndash; 5 percent increase from last year. According to Kathy Grannis, NRF spokesperson, &ldquo;the flexibility, convenience, and ease of purchasing gift cards makes this type of gift the ideal way for consumers to show their appreciation while also letting the graduate choose the perfect gift for them.&rdquo;</li>\r\n\t<li>Apparel, greeting cards, and electronics are also other popular items that have increased retail sales and continue to grow as people share their &ldquo;congratulations.&quot;</li>\r\n\t<li>U.S. consumers are predicted to spend $99.94 on graduation gifts this year &ndash; total spending predicted to hit $4.7 billion.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nGraduation certainly brings in retail traffic for brands and retailers and the push to buy special gifts for graduates is on the rise. Retailers and brands can make sure