784	1	15	how-to-engage-consumers-and-keep-advertising-fresh-with-changing-seasons	How to Engage Consumers and Keep Advertising Fresh with Changing Seasons 	<p>As the seasons change, so do consumers. They adapt to climate changes and begin shopping for season deals on home decorating, clothing and other &ldquo;must-have&rdquo; seasonal goods. With summer around the corner, here are a few tips to drive heightened awareness around your brand and summer deals in and out of the store to keep up with seasonal consumer needs.</p>\r\n	<p>As the seasons change, so do consumers. They adapt to climate changes and begin shopping for season deals on home decorating, clothing and other &ldquo;must-have&rdquo; seasonal goods. With summer around the corner, here are a few tips to drive heightened awareness around your brand and summer deals in and out of the store to keep up with seasonal consumer needs.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Driving attention around summer deals outside of the store:</strong><br />\r\nTo engage with consumers and grab a little extra attention from your target audience this summer, give campaigns a seasonal edge and really speak to consumers seasonal needs. For example, in a <a href="http://www.progressivegrocer.com/top-stories/headlines/beverages/id35495/mikes-hard-lemonade-aims-to-do-summer-different/" target="_blank">new campaign</a> around Mike&rsquo;s Hard Lemonade, the brand recently launched a series of TV commercials that shows guys interacting in popular summer drinking occasions such as golf and fishing outings. But it doesn&rsquo;t stop there &ndash; while TV ads show viewers how to &ldquo;Do Summer Different,&rdquo; a series of unique digital initiatives (video, mobile and social media) encourage consumers to decide how the promotion will play out. In addition, knowing that summer pulls in large movie crowds, Mike&rsquo;s Hard will be rolling out 15-second ad spots in more than 750 movie theaters.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhat can you take from the above example? Speak to consumers&rsquo; seasonal mindset by tailoring campaigns with seasonal messaging, as Mike&rsquo;s Hard launched campaigns associating their product with popular summer outings. These kinds of campaigns speak to consumers emotions and create a connection with the brand.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Driving attention around summer deals in-store:</strong><br />\r\nWhile it is vital to reach shoppers before they head in-store to influence purchasing decisions, it is also important to continue to reach consumers once in-store. Tie in campaign messaging with in-store displays and signage. Highlight summer deals with store-front displays that showcase the product and let shoppers know why it is a &ldquo;must have&rdquo; this summer. For instance, Mike&rsquo;s Hard could provide free samples or provide shoppers with fun summer meal ideas the drink compliments at check-out or on in-store signage.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAnd remember, as always, it&rsquo;s important to know that your campaigns will reach and be received by the target audience. Leverage localized digital advertising to target those consumers who meet your shopper profile and drive in-store traffic this summer. More on localized digital advertising <a href="http://www.maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-solutions" target="_blank">here</a>.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n	t	2012-06-06 15:30:04	\N	2012-06-06 15:30:04	2013-09-20 15:29:09.709944	49	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, campaigns, advertising, retail
899	1	28	four-digital-shopper-marketing-trends-you-will-see-in-2014	Bring on the Crystal Ball: Four Digital Shopper Marketing Trends You’ll See in 2014	<p>Since the digital age put shoppers in the power seat, retailers and CPGs must now work harder than ever to win them over. See our predictions for the biggest digital shopper marketing trends you&rsquo;ll see this year.</p>\r\n	<p><img alt="" src="/system/editor/W1siZiIsIjIwMTQvMDEvMjIvMTZfNTBfNDhfODMyX2lTdG9ja18wMDAwMjIwNzMwMTlYU21hbGwuanBnIl0sWyJwIiwidGh1bWIiLCI4MDB4ODAwPiJdXQ/iStock_000022073019XSmall.jpg" style="float:right; height:200px; margin:0px 25px; width:180px" />Shopper marketing has seen a sea change over the past few years, as the digital age put shoppers in the power seat, and retailers and CPGs must now work harder than ever to win them over. But one thing has not shifted: That is, the need for retailers and CPGs to get shoppers into stores and down the aisles in order to boost sales and category leadership.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Digital tools, from e-commerce and social media to mobile, give consumers the freedom to shop how they choose&mdash;but smart shopper marketers are also using the latest in digital options to influence shopper behavior and engage them at home, on the go, and in the store.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Here are my predictions for the four biggest digital shopper marketing trends you&rsquo;ll see in 2014:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>1. Webrooming will beat out showrooming. </strong><br />\r\nIf this past holiday season is any indication, webrooming&mdash;researching a product online before purchasing the actual item in-store&mdash;will see a boom in 2014 and virtually cancel out problems of showrooming&mdash;checking out products in the store before buying online. A <a href="http://www.upi.com/Business_News/Consumer-Corner/2013/12/08/Webrooming-beats-showrooming-this-holiday-season/UPI-41461386500460/" target="_blank">December 2013 Harris Poll</a> found that nearly half of US consumers (46%) said they have showroomed, but more than two-thirds (69%) said they have webroomed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>2. Hyperlocal digital advertising will hit the target.</strong><br />\r\nAll of those webroomers will influence a massive amount of sales this year: According to <a href="http://www.forrester.com/Forrester+US+CrossChannel+Retail+Sales+To+Reach+18+Trillion+By+2017/-/E-PRE6324" target="_blank">Forrester Research</a>, in-store transactions that are influenced by the web will continue to grow in 2014 and in years to come, reaching $1.8 trillion by 2017. Retailers and CPGs will be able to take full advantage of this trend through hyperlocal digital advertising, which pinpoints the right target audience with precision and at scale and delivers ads that drive purchases at the checkout counter.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>3. Mobile analytics will become even more essential.</strong><br />\r\nAccording to <a href="http://www.comscore.com/Insights/Press_Releases/2013/11/comScore_Reports_September_2013_U.S._Smartphone_Subscriber_Market_Share" target="_blank">comScore</a>, nearly half of Americans now own smartphones. And with most consumers using smartphones while in the store, mobile has moved from an experimental shopper tool to one that is nearly status quo. In 2014, digital shopper marketers will focus heavily on mobile analytics&mdash;whether within apps or on the mobile web&mdash;to increasingly identify who customers are and provide them with targeted, personalized offers that engage them, enhance loyalty programs, and boost sales.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>4. Retailers and CPGs will work to provide seamless shopping experiences. </strong><br />\r\nIt&rsquo;s a word that&rsquo;s been floating around for the last few years, but <em>omnichannel</em> may prove to be the digital shopper marketing term of 2014 as, more than ever, consumers demand a shopping journey that is easy and consistent no matter what channel they choose&mdash;smartphone, desktop, or in-store. According to a <a href="http://money.msn.com/saving-money-tips/post.aspx?post=341fc645-31ed-4468-bd06-11c1b74bf372" target="_blank">recent study by Accenture</a>, consumer expectations may still be higher than retail capabilities in this regard, but forward-thinking retailers are testing new technologies and engagement methods that may bring the shopper&rsquo;s wish for a truly omnichannel experience to fruition.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Digital shopper marketing has long proven that it can leverage the latest in data-driven solutions and technologies to go far beyond traditional print inserts, circulars, and in-store displays to influence and drive positive shopper behavior. I believe 2014 is going to be the year when digital and brick-and-mortar begin to truly merge and evolve into the omnichannel, personalized, targeted experience that consumers want and retailers and brands need to provide.</p>\r\n	t	2014-01-22 22:44:11	\N	2014-01-22 22:49:37.962709	2014-01-23 14:23:21.386958	50	\N
902	1	42	a-powerful-one-two-punch-digital-circulars-hyperlocal-ads	A Powerful One-Two Punch: Digital Circulars + Hyperlocal Ads	<p>Want to make the most of your investment in print circulars? Digitize your deals and promote them with hyperlocal rich media ads&mdash;a can&#39;t-miss combination that boosts ROI.&nbsp;</p>\r\n	<p>We all know consumers have changed&mdash;for good. These days, customers spend more of their time online and fewer hours watching TV ads. (<a href="http://www.emarketer.com/Article/Digital-Set-Surpass-TV-Time-Spent-with-US-Media/1010096#IMCWrGAtqtk2zegx.99" target="_blank">According to eMarketer</a>, the average time spent with digital media surpassed TV viewing for the first time in 2013&mdash;more than five hours per day.)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>These fundamental behavioral changes have also affected the world of traditional retail circulars. It is no longer enough for retailers to offer weekly deals in print at the store entrance, tucked in newspapers, or sticking out of shopper mailboxes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Instead, top retailers, such as CVS, Walgreens, Safeway, and Target, are all leading the way with the latest in digital circular offerings that are smartphone- and tablet-friendly, and tied to data-driven loyalty programs. In addition, a variety of vendors are serving up platforms and apps that pluck the original print circular out of the mailbox and send it into the digital universe.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="Grocery Shoppers" src="/system/editor/W1siZiIsIjIwMTQvMDIvMTcvMDhfMTNfMzdfMzU2X0dyb2NlcnlfU2hvcHBpbmdfNjAweDQwMC5wbmciXSxbInAiLCJ0aHVtYiIsIjgwMHg4MDA%2BIl1d/Grocery-Shopping_600x400.png" style="float:left; height:200px; margin:5px; width:300px" />But <a href="http://www.mediapost.com/publications/article/208063/" target="_blank">according to Catalina</a>, grocery stores still spend upward of 70% of their ad budgets on print, even though print circulars are not nearly as effective as they used to be (the study found that two-thirds of Memorial Day transactions, for example, contained nearly zero items promoted in the holiday circular).<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Making the Most of Your Circulars</strong><br />\r\nSo how can you fully leverage the retail circular data in a much more impactful way? The answer is a powerful one-two punch: digital circulars and hyperlocal, rich media ads.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>By digitizing your weekly circulars, you can bring your promotions to online users who prefer to check out deals on retailer websites using their desktops, laptops, tablets, or smartphones. Then, by running hyperlocal digital ads in your target neighborhoods, you can dynamically pull those promotions that are best suited for each neighborhood&mdash;meaning you&rsquo;ll reach only the audience most likely to buy and ensure that every impression contributes to in-store sales. In addition, your ads can include everything from prices and item-specific content to store locators, localized callouts, and calls to action.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This dynamic combo is particularly compelling because it hits three best practices for today&rsquo;s marketers:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n\t<li><strong>Relevancy: </strong>One circular doesn&rsquo;t fit the needs of all consumers. By running ads that respond to specific neighborhood-level interests, whether it is an offer for paper products or a discount on high-end electronics or clothing, you can know with certainty that your ads are reaching the right audience with the right offer.<br />\r\n\t&nbsp;</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Scale:</strong> It&rsquo;s one thing to find the right local neighborhoods interested in your promotions, but what about scaling an entire national campaign around specific buying attributes? Now, the technology exists to find neighborhoods across regions and around the nation that share similar purchasing attributes or behavior, so your hyperlocal campaign works in a larger, yet still highly targeted way.<br />\r\n\t&nbsp;</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Efficiency:</strong> One thing is certain about traditional circulars&mdash;they are inefficient in reaching the right shoppers and expensive to produce. With digital circulars and hyperlocal rich media ads, you minimize waste by running ads for deals in only those neighborhoods that are ready, willing, and able to buy.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<em>Are you getting the most out of your circular? Tell us more about your digital circular experience by leaving a comment below.</em></p>\r\n	t	2014-02-13 12:48:23	\N	2014-02-13 12:53:32.373231	2014-02-17 14:14:01.312195	50	\N
806	1	15	neighborhoods-in-seattle-named-barbeque-kings-by-maxpoint-interactive-interest-index-3	Neighborhoods in Seattle Named Barbeque Kings by MaxPoint Interactive Interest Index	We are in the heart of summer and enjoying the swimming pool, playing outside activities and grilling our favorite summer foods. With all of this summer fun, we decided to find the U.S. neighborhoods that are most interested in barbeque foods. Today we issued the results of an indexing study that analyzed billions of data points to determine the U.S. neighborhoods that are the most interested in barbeque foods.	We are in the heart of summer and enjoying the swimming pool, playing outside activities and grilling our favorite summer foods. With all of this summer fun, we decided to find the U.S. neighborhoods that are most interested in barbeque foods. Today we issued the results of an indexing study that analyzed billions of data points to determine the U.S. neighborhoods that are the most interested in barbeque foods.<!--more--><br/>\n<br/>\nSeattle – specifically the Wallingford and International District neighborhoods – ranked the highest, but varied in their preference for pork vs. chicken, respectively. Surprisingly, the Interest Index found the cities with neighborhoods most interested in barbeque foods are located in the Pacific Northwest, with Portland, Oregon falling right behind Seattle. Spokane, Washington ranked third.<br/>\n<br/>\nThe top 10 cities that showed the greatest interest in barbeque food include:<br/>\n<br/>\n1. Seattle, WA<br/>\n2. Portland, OR<br/>\n3. Spokane, WA<br/>\n4. Missoula, MT<br/>\n5. Idaho Falls, ID<br/>\n6. Topeka, KS<br/>\n7. Phoenix, AZ<br/>\n8. Ft. Smith, AR<br/>\n9. Green Bay, WI<br/>\n10. Lubbock, TX<br/>\n<br/>\nTo find these cities, MaxPoint went beyond traditional DMA targeting and analyzed billions of data points consumed by neighborhoods across the U.S. such as offline point-of-sale data, social media, videos, music, local Web pages, and online magazines and recipes related to barbeque foods. MaxPoint discovered that although the demographics of the neighborhoods were identical (consumers ages 25-34 with a household income of $60,000-80,000), there are two very distinct neighborhood types when it comes to barbequing — those that prefer chicken and those that prefer pork. This information is invaluable to advertisers looking to effectively reach consumers with the right message, in the right place at the right time.<br/>\nUsing the data gleaned from this index, MaxPoint implemented highly targeted neighborhood-level digital ad campaigns for a variety of retailers and brands:<br/>\n<ul><br/>\n\t<li>A major chicken brand wanted to drive awareness of its chicken breast patties in 18 different markets. MaxPoint helped the company drive in-store traffic by targeting women ages 25-54, who have children ages 7-17, and who have purchased competitive chicken brands.</li>\n\t<li>A national pork brand needed to generate brand awareness and drive sales of its pork products at targeted store locations. As a result of a focused digital advertising campaign, the company was able to drive in-store sales by targeting consumers ages 35-64 who live within an 8-mile radius of each store location and who are interested in competitive brands.</li>\n</ul>\n“The results of this Interest Index were unexpected to say the least. Not only were we surprised to find the biggest barbeque food fans in the Pacific Northwest, but the data showing their strong preferences toward particular meats is both interesting and incredibly valuable to advertisers looking to market specific products,” said Gretchen Joyce, chief operating officer of MaxPoint Interactive. “This data shows that to reach the right consumers, advertisers need to go beyond traditional DMA targeting and understand the preferences, interests, lifestyle, purchasing habits, demographics and locations – right down to the neighborhood level – of prospective customers to increase brand awareness and drive in-store sales.”<a href="http://maxpointinteractive.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/MaxPointInteractive_July_Infographic_BLOG-JPG.jpg" target="_blank"><img class="alignright size-medium wp-image-3022" title="MaxPointInteractive_July_Infographic_R6" src="http://maxpointinteractive.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/MaxPointInteractive_July_Infographic_BLOG-JPG-95x300.jpg" alt="" width="95" height="300" /></a><br/>\n<br/>\nTo check out last month’s Interest Index report, <a href="http://maxpointinteractive.com/onpoint-blog/2012/06/28/madison-wisconsin-is-the-u-s-city-most-excited-for-the-2012-summer-olympic-games/">click here</a>.<br/>\n<br/>\nThank you for visiting the OnPoint blog! If you have any questions, comments or inquiries, please contact <a href="mailto:OnPoint@maxpointinteractive.com">OnPoint@maxpointinteractive.com</a>.	t	2012-07-31 13:29:39	\N	2012-07-31 13:29:39	2013-05-24 02:44:09.254665	54	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, Interest Index, Barbeque, neighborhoods, digital zip
807	1	20	teen-vogue-driving-national-back-to-school-shopping-day	Teen Vogue Driving National Back to School Shopping Day	It takes a big publication with a huge readership to pull off the launch of a national holiday, officially or unofficially.  First there was Black Friday, then Cyber Monday, followed by State Tax Holidays and now, August 11, 2012 has been deemed by Teen Vogue magazine as a national day for back to school shopping.  	It takes a big publication with a huge readership to pull off the launch of a national holiday, officially or unofficially.  First there was Black Friday, then Cyber Monday, followed by State Tax Holidays and now, August 11, 2012 has been deemed by Teen Vogue magazine as a national day for back to school shopping.  <!--more--><br/>\n<br/>\nWhat better of a target market for such an event than teenage girls filled with the angst of building a new back-to-school wardrobe that will be the envy of her groupies.  Back-to-School Saturday will offer young shoppers — and the parents who often pay the bills — sales, free samples and events in stores and malls.<br/>\n<br/>\nTeen Vogue has two dozen advertisers taking part, all of them reliant on the back-to-school season for revenue. The participants will include Aéropostale, American Eagle Outfitters, Express, Guess, H&amp;M, Maybelline New York, Pacific Sunwear of California, Quiksilver, Staples and Vans.  Additionally, four brands sold by Procter &amp; Gamble, the nation’s largest advertiser, will be involved: Cover Girl, Olay, Pantene and Tampax.<br/>\n<br/>\nBack-to-School Saturday will be promoted in the typically enthusiastic Teen Vogue tone of voice. For instance, ads and posters will exhort, “Get ready, get set, get shopping!” And social media will, of course, play a big role; Teen Vogue has already called dibs on a hashtag, #btss.<br/>\n<br/>\n“We’re trying to create a moment of imagination and motivation,” said Jason Wagenheim, vice president and publisher of Teen Vogue, part of the Condé Nast Publications division of Advance Publications. “We saw it as a real opportunity, because for our girls, back-to-school is as important as the Christmas shopping season,” he added.<br/>\n<br/>\nMr. Wagenheim acknowledged that the back-to-school shopping period “is a very random 8 to 12 weeks that starts early in the South and later in the North.” But research suggested that shopping for school supplies, clothing and other merchandise “seems to peak in the second and third week of August,” he said, so the Aug. 11 date was selected as one that could be turned into “a galvanizing moment.”<br/>\n<br/>\nConsumers are becoming “increasingly interested in event-based shopping,” said Gary H. Schoenfeld, chief executive at Pacific Sunwear, who recalled how he was “up all night on Black Friday in three or four of our stores, and customers were having a blast.”<br/>\n<br/>\n“Three o’clock in the morning felt like 8 o’clock at night, as people were with friends and having a great time shopping,” Mr. Schoenfeld said. “The idea of Teen Vogue trying to introduce something like that for back-to-school is a fun idea; why not be a part of it?”<br/>\n<br/>\nWell said Mr. Schoenfeld – why not be a part of it?  You’d be truly missing out on a huge opportunity to drive in-store sales if you’re not a part of it.  Many advertisers will also use hyperlocal digital advertising targeting their customers who live within a certain mile radius of their stores across the country. With increasing pressure for companies to boost sales and profits during the back-to-school season, smart marketers will look for opportunities like this to gain that extra edge on the competition.<br/>\n<br/>\nThank you for visiting the OnPoint blog! If you have any questions, comments or inquiries, please contact <a href="mailto:OnPoint@maxpointinteractive.com">OnPoint@maxpointinteractive.com</a>.	t	2012-08-03 12:07:45	\N	2012-08-03 12:07:45	2013-05-24 02:44:09.273938	58	back-to-school, in-store shopping, teens, MaxPoint, OnPoint
