796	1	15	landing-page-optimization	Landing Page Optimization 	<p>By: Rob Humphreys, Founder &amp; CEO, iDriveROI, LLC<br />\r\nIncreasing ROI (Return on Investment) is the Holy Grail for every digital marketer.&nbsp; Mathematically speaking, increasing ROI can be achieved by any of the following means: (1) decrease the investment (2) increase the return (3) a combination of 1 and 2. For the purposes of this post, we will focus on increasing returns (specifically - conversions and landing pages).</p>\r\n	<p><strong>By: Rob Humphreys, Founder &amp; CEO, iDriveROI, LLC</strong><br />\r\n<br />\r\nIncreasing ROI (Return on Investment) is the Holy Grail for every digital marketer.&nbsp; Mathematically speaking, increasing ROI can be achieved by any of the following means: (1) decrease the investment (2) increase the return (3) a combination of 1 and 2. For the purposes of this post, we will focus on increasing returns (specifically - conversions and landing pages).<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nOptimizing your landing pages for conversions (i.e., purchasing products, downloading a white paper, signing up for a newsletter, filling out a form, clicking on some button, etc.) will ensure your marketing goals are headed in the right direction. Even seemingly &ldquo;non-conversion&rdquo; type of pages, like contact or press page, should have some underlying call to action.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSo how do you optimize landing pages to ensure they are converting as best they can?<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn order to transform your website into a well-optimized conversion machine, below is the basic playbook to follow:<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Define your conversion events &amp; goals:</strong> Are you selling tangible or intangible products on your site? Are you offering a webinar, downloadable white paper or e-book? It is important to figure out what you are offering and what it is worth to you.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Select the right tools for multivariate testing and learning:</strong> Now that you&rsquo;ve defined your conversion events and the values of these events, you can select the tool(s) that best suit your needs. For large Internet Retailers or enterprise level companies, <a href="http://www.omniture.com/en/products/conversion/test-and-target" target="_blank">Adobe Test and Target</a> is hands-down the best solution. Test and Target allows marketers to optimize their websites by performing continuous testing based on any number of variables within the marketing mix matrix. For smaller companies that wish to do multivariate landing page split tests, the two popular tools are <a href="https://accounts.google.com/ServiceLogin?service=websiteoptimizer&amp;continue=http://www.google.com/analytics/siteopt/%3Fhl%3Den&amp;hl=en" target="_blank">Google Website Optimizer</a> and <a href="http://visualwebsiteoptimizer.com/" target="_blank">Visual Website Optimizer</a>.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Map your site pages to your conversion funnel:</strong> This process is fairly straightforward. Every page on a website should be assigned to one phase of your conversion funnel.&nbsp; The most basic phases of a conversion funnel are: Awareness, Decision, and Action.&nbsp; Once you do this you can then refine the messaging pages based on the funnel stage and decide which content assets should be integrated into the page content or sidebar of the site.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Develop and assign media assets for each funnel stage (and pages):</strong> Most media assets will exist in some shape or form as a natural build out of the site. Typical assets range from call-to-action graphics/buttons to white papers/e-books and videos/webinars. Defining what types of assets are used for a particular stage of the funnel and assigning existing media assets allows marketers to increase engagement and facilitate movement towards a specific conversion event.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Create a testing calendar:</strong> Creating a testing calendar is simple block-and-tackling marketing. Basically, a testing calendar provides a visual of what is being tested and the duration. Laying this out in calendar format will also allow you to compare this to other concurrent activities within the company.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Conduct continuous testing and learning:</strong> Too many times, site owners will test too many things on given page and for too short a period of time.&nbsp; A common test is to test the placement and/or color of a call-to-action button.&nbsp; Additionally, common tests involve the wording of an offer (e.g., short bullet-listed copy versus narrative).&nbsp; There are a number of tools available that will help figure out your statistical significance.&nbsp; For example, <a href="http://splittester.com/" target="_blank">Split Tester</a> is a free tool that will report how certain you can be that two ads will perform differently over time.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nLanding page optimization is a mercurial process and one that cannot be done without the proper methodology AND tools. Regardless of what your site is selling or offering, following this playbook will help you better organize your plan and allow you to focus on execution and learning.</p>\r\n	t	2012-07-03 13:00:46	\N	2012-07-03 13:00:46	2013-09-19 23:54:34.378168	53	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, landing pages
792	1	15	cannes-reveals-the-most-popular-online-ads	Cannes Reveals: The Most Popular Online Ads 	<p>It&rsquo;s no secret online video advertising is becoming an effective and vital tool for retailers and brands to reach their target audiences. According to Forrester Research, U.S. online video ad spend will reach $5.4 billion by 2016 and is becoming a rising digital force that advertisers are allocating more dollars to. And, brands and retailers are catching on as they leverage online video ads that create buzz and engagement fast.</p>\r\n	<p>It&rsquo;s no secret online video advertising is becoming an effective and vital tool for retailers and brands to reach their target audiences. According to Forrester Research, U.S. online video ad spend will reach $5.4 billion by 2016 and is becoming a rising digital force that advertisers are allocating more dollars to. And, brands and retailers are catching on as they leverage online video ads that create buzz and engagement fast.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nFor example, in light of the recent Cannes festival, scores of TV commercials and online films were submitted to compete for the Film Grand Prix. While the winners are determined by the official judges, a few of the online video submissions from brands have already been noticed for their &ldquo;viralness&rdquo; and ability to engage online viewers.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe top three online advertisements are: Carlsberg&rsquo;s &ldquo;Bikers&rdquo;; Sony&rsquo;s &ldquo;Michael&rdquo;; Chipotle&rsquo;s &ldquo;Back to Start&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, what&rsquo;s the secret behind these ads? Like Coca-Cola&rsquo;s success in building viral <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/onpoint-blog/2012/6/21/building-a-viral-brand" target="_blank">online videos</a>, these brands understand their consumer base, developing advertisements that will appeal to the consumer&rsquo;s interests and emotions.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWatch the videos here:<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Carlsberg &quot;Bikers&quot;</strong><br />\r\n<iframe width="560" height="315" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/RS3iB47nQ6E?rel=0" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Sony &quot;Michael&quot;</strong><br />\r\n<iframe width="560" height="315" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/fj96XYhwTFI?rel=0" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Chipotle &quot;Back to the Start&quot;</strong><br />\r\n<iframe width="560" height="315" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/aMfSGt6rHos?rel=0" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nHowever, while these videos have gone viral, they are only effective if reached and received by the right audience.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nFor more information on tapping online video advertising&#39;s potential, click <a href="http://maxpointinteractive.com/onpoint-blog/2012/04/26/how-to-tap-video-advertisings-potential/">here</a>.</p>\r\n	t	2012-06-25 14:51:11	\N	2012-06-25 14:51:11	2013-09-20 00:12:36.877048	51	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, online video, advertising, digital 
794	1	15	madison-wisconsin-is-the-u-s-city-most-excited-for-the-2012-summer-olympic-games	Madison, Wisconsin is the U.S. City Most Excited for the 2012 Summer Olympic Games	<p>Summer 2012 has finally arrived and with it comes the Summer Olympic Games. Interested in the buzz generated every 4 years around this event, we wanted to find the cities most interested in the Olympic Games.</p>\r\n	<p>Summer 2012 has finally arrived and with it comes the Summer Olympic Games. Interested in the buzz generated every 4 years around this event, we wanted to find the cities most interested in the Olympic Games. <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nToday we released the results of our June Interest Index and after analyzing billions of data points, we found that Madison, Wisconsin &ndash; specifically neighborhoods within its Middleton suburb &ndash; have the highest interest in the Olympics of all neighborhoods in the U.S.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe top 10 cities with neighborhoods that showed the greatest interest in the Olympics include:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>Madison, WI</li>\r\n\t<li>Lansing, MI</li>\r\n\t<li>Knoxville, TN</li>\r\n\t<li>St. Louis, MO</li>\r\n\t<li>Peoria-Bloomington, IL</li>\r\n\t<li>Rochester, MN</li>\r\n\t<li>Des Moines, IA</li>\r\n\t<li>Washington, DC</li>\r\n\t<li>San Francisco, CA</li>\r\n\t<li>Rochester, NY</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nTo find these cities, we analyzed data consumed by neighborhoods throughout the U.S., such as offline point of sale data, social media, videos, music, local Web pages and online magazines. The company then scored each neighborhood across hundreds of topics, which cluster together indicating broader interest trends over a period of time. We used a composite score that consisted of a variety of Olympic interests including &ldquo;Team USA 2012,&rdquo; &ldquo;Michael Phelps&rdquo; and &ldquo;Olympic gymnastics,&rdquo; among a number of other specific athletes, events and related terms to compile the top 10 list.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWith billions of dollars in advertising spend expected around the Olympic Games this year, the results of this Interest Index go beyond the capabilities of traditional DMA targeting to reveal those U.S. neighborhoods that are most receptive to Olympic-themed campaigns. This data is invaluable for brands and retailers looking to avoid the wasted ad dollars associated with blanketed campaigns.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAccording to the research, the neighborhoods with the most Olympic spirit tend to have higher income and are well educated compared with the rest of the nation.&nbsp; Residents of the highest ranking cities typically had an average income of $80,000 per year and college educations.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nUsing the data from this index, we implemented highly targeted neighborhood-level digital advertising campaigns for both brands and retailers. For example:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>A major skincare brand was looking to drive in-store sales by increasing coupon downloads of its product using an Olympic athlete as its spokesperson in their creative. Using MaxPoint&rsquo;s Digital Zip<sup>&reg;</sup> technology, the brand was able to drive participation by targeting neighborhoods with women aged 25-54, with a household income of $50k or higher, an active sports lifestyle and an interest in skin care.</li>\r\n\t<li>A marquee consumer packaged goods company was interested in increasing coupon downloads for its newest cereal brand. As a result of a highly targeted online video campaign featuring famous athletes, the CPG manufacturer was able to increase sales in all four of its markets by reaching neighborhoods showing a high interest in sports.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nAccording to our COO, Gretchen Joyce, &ldquo;This index proves that even with the events of national interest, there are specific neighborhoods across the country that are more attractive advertising targets than others based on their location, demographics, interests and lifestyle. This is the type of information that is crucial to retailers and brands looking to target specific consumer segments with special deals or products.&rdquo;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nTo check out last month&rsquo;s Interest Index report, click <a href="http://maxpointinteractive.com/company/news/?news_id=2699" target="_blank">here</a>.</p>\r\n	t	2012-06-28 16:01:31	\N	2012-06-28 16:01:31	2013-09-19 23:58:13.767026	54	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, Interest Index, data, Digital Zip, neighborhoods
901	1	10	move-over-showrooming-webrooming-is-here	Move Over Showrooming: Webrooming Is Here	<p>Find out how retailers can draw more webrooming consumers into stores with hyperlocal digital ads.</p>\r\n	<p>With the explosion in mobile device usage, brick-and-mortar stores have become concerned about showrooming&mdash;when consumers visit a store to research a product but subsequently buy that product online, often from a lower-priced competitor and sometimes while still in the store. It&#39;s become such an irritant that one Australian retailer <a href="http://news.cnet.com/8301-17938_105-57576395-1/store-charges-$5-showrooming-fee-to-looky-loos/" target="_blank">began charging a $5 fee</a> to consumers who came into the store and claimed to be &quot;just looking.&quot; Other retailers have countered showrooming by beefing up store-brand products, trying to make it difficult for consumers to compare private-label products to branded products online.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Hope for Retailers</strong><br />\r\n<img alt="woman browsing on the computer" src="/system/editor/W1siZiIsIjIwMTQvMDIvMDUvMTVfMzVfMTNfNzYyX1dlYnJvb21pbmdfYmxvZ183MjB4NzIwLnBuZyJdLFsicCIsInRodW1iIiwiODAweDgwMD4iXV0/Webrooming-blog_720x720.png" style="float:right; height:200px; margin:5px; width:200px" />Although showrooming has historically given brick-and-mortar stores cause for concern, a new survey indicates that all is not lost. A November 2013 <a href="http://www.harrisinteractive.com/NewsRoom/HarrisPolls/tabid/447/ctl/ReadCustom%20Default/mid/1508/ArticleId/1339/Default.aspx" target="_blank">Harris Poll</a> showed that while 46% of shoppers admit to showrooming, a greater percent said that they do just the opposite: 69% percent of shoppers research a product online first and then purchase the item in the store (also known as <em>webrooming)</em>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Does that mean retailers should be having a conversation about webrooming rather than showrooming? Definitely. The increasingly popular pattern of researching online and then buying in-store indicates consumers&#39; ongoing need for retailers to provide a positive in-store environment as well as a seamless omnichannel experience.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Hyperlocal Digital Ads and Today&rsquo;s Consumers</strong><br />\r\nBy 2017, <a href="http://mashable.com/2013/03/12/forrester-u-s-ecommerce-forecast-2017" target="_blank">e-commerce is expected to account for just 10% of all retail sales in the United States</a>, which means the bulk of sales will continue to occur in brick-and-mortar stores. Between these retail sales predictions and the rise in webrooming, it&rsquo;s clear that consumers will continue to buy in stores, even after first researching products online. Add to that the fact that they shop close to home (with very few exceptions) and have similar purchase patterns as their neighbors, and you have a set of consumer truths that can guide you to effective advertising strategies.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>One of those strategies is hyperlocal digital advertising. By using a combination of sophisticated analytics and powerful technology, hyperlocal digital advertising helps retailers seamlessly drive consumers from the online content consumption experience to the in-store purchase experience.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This advanced technology pinpoints the neighborhoods most likely to contain a retailer&rsquo;s ideal audience based on the content the consumers are viewing online, their demographics, their purchase histories, and more. Because consumers see the hyperlocal digital ads best matched to their interests and location, they are more likely to click on a retailer&rsquo;s website for more information, and ultimately visit the store. And it&rsquo;s once consumers come in that the transition from the online experience to the in-store experience can begin.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Showrooming is not quite the big bad beast we&rsquo;ve all made it out to be for the retail experience. Brick-and-mortar stores are here to stay. So, let&rsquo;s spend more time implementing the strategies that work for today&rsquo;s webrooming consumer&mdash;hyperlocal digital advertising, for example&mdash;and less time talking about showrooming, which is stacking up to be a simple distraction from the real retail story.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Are you using hyperlocal digital advertising to reach the consumers most likely to buy in your stores? Tell us more in the comments below.</em></p>\r\n	t	2014-02-04 17:44:32	\N	2014-02-04 17:53:42.765207	2014-02-05 21:45:34.535688	49	\N
