801	1	15	an-interview-with-jim-mercado-principal-co-owner-sicem-advertising	An Interview with Jim Mercado, Principal & Co-Owner, Sic’Em Advertising	<p>MaxPoint recently interviewed Jim Mercado, Principal &amp; Co-Owner, Sic&rsquo;Em Advertising, on the digital advertising industry and some of the challenges advertisers face today. The interview focuses on how to optimize ad campaigns, effective audience targeting and how to address certain industry challenges.</p>\r\n	<p>MaxPoint recently interviewed Jim Mercado, Principal &amp; Co-Owner, <a href="http://www.sic-em.com/" target="_blank">Sic&rsquo;Em Advertising</a>, on the digital advertising industry and some of the challenges advertisers face today. The interview focuses on how to optimize ad campaigns, effective audience targeting and how to address certain industry challenges.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>MaxPoint:</strong> Online advertising campaigns can either be very effective or ineffective at reaching and engaging with the right audience. What do you feel are the main elements an advertising campaign needs to include to achieve the campaign goal?<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Mercado</strong>: In order to be effective, campaigns need an integrated approach &ndash; a central message that is being distributed through a variety of channels whether that be through social media, online advertising, traditional advertising or a combination of all. However, the challenge is to develop interesting content that will be received well by a target audience and then be able to deliver that message to the target audience. Determining the right creative and the right message is a process &ndash; it is a process of elimination and process of testing.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn addition, with the growth of new technology, advertisers can take their integrated message and then leverage targeting technology to distribute content to the relevant audience and return a strong marketing mix. If all goes well, the same message is delivered across all channels and ideally elicits a response &ndash; that means we did our job right. You also need a call to action or some sort of offer to prompt action.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>MaxPoint:</strong> What are some of the biggest challenges online advertisers face? What are some ways advertisers can address these obstacles?<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Mercado:</strong> Targeting - getting the right message to the right person at the right time. That is the biggest challenge. If we serve the right message, at the right time to the right audience we should see higher results. Many of our clients want to reach a specific audience and we are forced to continuously look for more and more targeted ways.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAnd, in order to find the right targeting technology, we have to keep up with and evaluate new technology. New technology is evolving and coming at us all the time, bringing new ways of finding people. We are all trying to get the right message to the right audience at the right time &ndash; that is the biggest challenge right now.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>MaxPoint:</strong> How can advertisers effectively reach their target audience? Do you believe hyper-local targeting has an impact on reaching the right audience?<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Mercado:</strong> Advertisers can effectively reach their target audience by leveraging hyper-local targeting solutions. AM radio and magazines can reach a lot of people but are not very targeted which is why more people are turning to digital solutions today. However, advertisers also need to create compelling messages that will engage their target audience, once reached.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWe get a check mark because of our creative but we also provide a very interesting mix of media to go after a target audience. In order to effectively reach an audience, there are various stages to complete. For instance, first we need to develop the creative. Then we have to put a forecast together &ndash; how many people are going to see this, what is the CTR, guestimates on past work, past products and then try to formulate some sort of return on investment with the client.</p>\r\n	t	2012-07-16 12:21:22	\N	2012-07-16 12:21:22	2013-09-17 14:14:59.523246	58	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, online advertising, targeting
805	1	20	part-i-the-growth-of-multicultural-advertising	PART I -The Growth of Multicultural Advertising	<p>With the large influx of different races, religions and nationalities flooding into the US melting pot, things are starting to change.</p>\r\n	<p>For decades, advertisers sought to target the perfect audience with ads that piqued the interest of the largest group possible.&nbsp; Back when ads were first placed on TV, it was simple; advertise to the Caucasian consumer.&nbsp; It was a time when very few minorities owned a TV, or even had the income to purchase many of the advertised goods.&nbsp; True, today, Caucasians still hold the majority of buying power.&nbsp; But with the large influx of different races, religions and nationalities flooding into the US melting pot, things are starting to change.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nAccording to a 2007 study by the Selig Center for Economic Growth at the University of Georgia, Caucasians still hold most of the economic clout in the United States &mdash; 85.5 percent of the nation&#39;s annual buying power of $10 trillion.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn recent years, though, marketers have been revising old assumptions and campaigns in anticipation of profound shifts in the nation&#39;s demographics, and in reaction to changes already under way in what the Selig Center describes as &quot;The Multicultural Economy.&quot;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThey note that:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>African-American buying power has risen from $318 billion in 1990 to $845 billion in 2007 &mdash; a 166 percent gain. Caucasians&rsquo; buying power rose 124 percent during that period.</li>\r\n\t<li>The combined buying power of African-Americans, Asians and Native Americans was $1.4 trillion in 2007, a gain of 201 percent since 1990. Meanwhile, the economic clout of Latinos rose by 307 percent, to $862 billion, over that span.</li>\r\n\t<li>The number of African-American-owned companies rose 45 percent from 1997 to 2002 &mdash; 4 1/2 times faster than the national average &mdash; and their receipts grew slightly faster than all others. Native American-owned businesses increased by 67 percent, Asian firms 24 percent, Latino companies 31 percent.</li>\r\n\t<li>The African-American population grew 27 percent from 1990 to 2007, compared to 15 percent for Caucasians and 21 percent overall. And the percentage of multiracial citizens, though just 1.6 percent of America&#39;s 302 million people, is swelling at 10 times the rate of Caucasian population growth.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nIf current trends continue, demographers say, nonwhites will be in the majority in America by 2042 &mdash; a prospect not lost on advertisers, says Melanie Shreffler, editor of Marketing to the Emerging Majorities, an industry newsletter.&nbsp; Marketers &quot;aren&#39;t turning out multicultural ads for the good of society,&quot; says Shreffler. &quot;They recognize there is money involved. If you skip out on a group that is going to be half the population by 2042 &mdash; good heavens, who are you marketing to?&quot;</p>\r\n	t	2012-07-30 13:00:30	\N	2012-07-30 13:00:30	2013-09-17 14:20:39.729293	58	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, multicultural, latino marketing
804	1	20	multicultural-advertising-favorably-works-its-way-into-latino-market-but-not-asian-market	Multicultural Advertising Favorably Works Its Way Into Latino Market But Not Asian Market	<p>&nbsp;With ever-growing Latino, Asian and Indian populations in the U.S., advertising needs to grow with them, not only culturally, but also socially.</p>\r\n	<p>It&rsquo;s a new revolution in advertising that, in a year or two, a multicultural focus will be mainstream in all advertising.&nbsp; Advertising professionals knew it was coming&mdash;the need to appeal to the rapidly changing cultural demographics in the United States.&nbsp; With ever-growing Latino, Asian and Indian populations in the U.S., advertising needs to grow with them, not only culturally, but also socially.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nSo far, the Spanish dominant Hispanics are most pleased with advertisers&rsquo; efforts to include them. According to the Horowitz Associates&#39; 13th annual State of Cable and Digital Media: Multicultural Edition study, Caucasian, African American, Hispanic, and Asian urban consumers were asked how well TV represents racial and ethnic groups in terms of quality (accuracy in comparison with reality) and quantity (proportionate with reality). One-third (32%) said TV does a good job with quality, but a comparable number (27%) gave unfavorable ratings; two in five (40%) gave favorable ratings for quantity and one-quarter (23%) gave unfavorable ratings. Across total multicultural consumers, neutral ratings fell between 37% (quantity) and 41% (quality).<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe study also showed there is much work to be done in appealing to the Asian market.&nbsp; According to the study, Asians are the least satisfied with multicultural representation, giving the lowest favorable ratings for quantity (24%; 31% unfavorable) and quality (22%; 27% unfavorable). Asians are the only segment that gave higher unfavorable ratings than favorable ratings for both quantity and quality.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&quot;Multicultural audiences have always been the best customers for television and entertainment. Tokenism and stereotypical representation of ethnicities in the media will not pass muster among this new general market for media,&quot; notes Adriana Waterston, Horowitz&#39;s VP of Marketing and Business Development. &quot;Our findings, particularly the dramatic differences between key segments of the Hispanic market, help underscore the value viewers place in seeing themselves represented in the stories, voices, and faces they watch on TV.&quot;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nNo longer can an advertiser bombard an audience with smiling Caucasian families eating around a dinner table with a view of a white picket fence outside of the window.&nbsp; Times have changed and so has the family dinner.&nbsp; People want to look into a mirror when being advertised to.&nbsp; They want the ads to relate to them as a person mentally, physically and emotionally. With that said, advertising needs to be more lifestyle focused.&nbsp; Targeting groups of individuals with commonalities across activities, income level, values and interests is now more important than ethnicity alone.&nbsp; A more holistic approach in connecting with your audience will help drive successful campaigns.</p>\r\n	t	2012-07-27 12:50:15	\N	2012-07-27 12:50:15	2013-09-17 14:24:46.779394	58	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, Latino Marketing, Hispanic Marketing, Multicultural
