803	1	15	re-evaluating-customer-service-in-2012	Re-Evaluating Customer Service in 2012 	<p>While digital advertising has given retailers a great opportunity to reach and engage with shoppers before they head in-store, it&rsquo;s still important to make sure a shopper has a good experience once in-store.</p>\r\n	<p>While digital advertising has given retailers a great opportunity to reach and engage with shoppers before they head in-store, it&rsquo;s still important to make sure a shopper has a good experience once in-store. Shoppers may have prepared lists and made decisions before heading to the physical store location but things like poor customer service and other in-store experiences can still affect a final purchase. <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nAccording to a recent post in Chain Store Age, &ldquo;customer service is critical to survival.&rdquo; In fact, surveyors in a recent Consumer Reports&rsquo; annual supermarket survey indicated that they have left stores due to rude employees, long check-out lines and crowds. Here are more stats supporting the push for improving customer service:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>82 percent of retail executives said improving customer service is a priority in 2012.</li>\r\n\t<li>67 percent of companies rank customer satisfaction as the top strategic initiative for 2012. Retailers have indicated 2012 is all about the customer.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nAnd to improve customer service strategies, retailers have isolated reoccurring problems to focus on improving this year. These include: Long checkout lines; idle cashiers; long transaction service times.&nbsp; Here are some tips for addressing and improving these issues:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>Retailers can now use an integrated system of thermal technology to count customers and automatically manage checkout that will help determine how to boost customer loyalty and improve functioning.</li>\r\n\t<li>Sensors above checkout lanes can monitor customer numbers as well as checkout behavior to future aid staff development.</li>\r\n\t<li>Many shoppers enter the store in groups and are often considered a single unit. Treat each shopper as an individual purchaser and tailor customer service to meet each individual&rsquo;s needs.</li>\r\n\t<li>Equip floor personnel with new technology so they can effectively answer customer questions. For instance, employees can use smart phones to compare prices for customers at other store locations and use apps to help shoppers navigate through the store.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nConsumers will determine the outcome of their experience with a retailer after making the final purchase in-store. Make sure shoppers walk away with a positive experience to ensure that they will become repeat customers and encourage friends to shop at a certain store as well.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nTo read more on the importance of customer service, click <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/onpoint-blog/2011/10/7/poor-customer-service-can-undo-retailers-efforts-to-drive-in-store-sales-2" target="_blank">here</a>.</p>\r\n	t	2012-07-25 13:25:28	\N	2012-07-25 13:25:28	2013-09-17 14:27:54.739678	58	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, customer service, in-store
