818	1	20	back-to-school-yeah-theres-an-app-for-that	Back to School: Yeah, there’s an app for that!	<p>It&rsquo;s back to school time. The time when your credit card gets so hot from swiping you need an insulated purse to carry it. I forgot that back to school shopping is more than new shoes, clothes and classroom supplies. Perhaps the summer spoiled me when it came to lunches&mdash;hot food, cold food, fast food&mdash;the choices were endless.&nbsp;</p>\r\n	<p>It&rsquo;s back to school time.&nbsp; The time when your credit card gets so hot from swiping you need an insulated purse to carry it.&nbsp; I forgot that back to school shopping is more than new shoes, clothes and classroom supplies.&nbsp; Perhaps the summer spoiled me when it came to lunches&mdash;hot food, cold food, fast food&mdash;the choices were endless.&nbsp; <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nBut now, the back to school grocery shopping begins!&nbsp; Finding nutritional lunches that do not need to be heated, that won&rsquo;t spoil or get soggy and of course will be eaten and not thrown away or traded.&nbsp; I spent plenty of time seeking the best deals and bargains on clothing and school supplies but forgot about school lunches!<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThank goodness for coupon apps.&nbsp; According to new research by <em>The NPD Group</em>, coupon apps are used by about 25 million Americans each month.&nbsp; Many people don&rsquo;t have time to sort through and cut coupons for back to school food items (and who receives a newspaper anymore?), so they rely on their local grocery stores to provide them with a shopping and coupon app.&nbsp; They give a list of your most commonly purchased items, the coupons associated with them (or incentives for competing brands), a place to create a shopping list sorted by store layout and meal ideas.&nbsp; The only thing shoppers need to do is go to the store, get their groceries and burn up that credit card.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMore and more, consumers are turning to the Internet to prepare for their grocery shopping trips.&nbsp; In fact, according to a <a href="http://offers.maxpoint.com/GroceryShopperInsights.html" target="_blank">BIGinsight grocery survey</a>, Moms and those in the 25-54 age group, are more likely than adults 18+ to use the Internet to prepare for grocery shopping trips. &nbsp;A simple search for &ldquo;back to school lunch ideas&rdquo; returns an enormous amount of ideas, and much to the pleasure of marketers, it also returns brand preferences.&nbsp; Users prepare for their shopping experience at home and then go to the store to purchase their goods.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWith increased online usage, brands and retailers should take advantage of local store apps as well as hyperlocal digital advertising to target specific neighborhoods with specific products at specific stores.&nbsp; Now that&rsquo;s smart marketing!</p>\r\n	t	2012-08-29 12:20:03	\N	2012-08-29 12:20:03	2013-09-17 13:59:58.454745	58	back-to-school, retail, BIGinsight, grocery shopping, MaxPoint, OnPoint
817	1	20	back-to-school-spending-up-retailers-vie-for-the-lead-with-smart-targeted-advertising	Back to School Spending Up: Retailers Vie For the Lead with Smart, Targeted Advertising	<p>It&rsquo;s been a rough couple of years for the U.S.&nbsp; People are stretching their dollars amidst the murky economy.&nbsp; It appears the worst is behind us, and it is time for back-to-school shoppers to catch up after last year&rsquo;s cautious spending.&nbsp; According to the National Retail Federation (NRF), parents are still worried about the weak economy but feel the need to restock school supplies after cutting back last year.</p>\r\n	<p>It&rsquo;s been a rough couple of years for the U.S.&nbsp; People are stretching their dollars amidst the murky economy.&nbsp; It appears the worst is behind us, and it is time for back-to-school shoppers to catch up after last year&rsquo;s cautious spending.&nbsp; According to the National Retail Federation (NRF), parents are still worried about the weak economy but feel the need to restock school supplies after cutting back last year.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nProving that spending is increasing this year, families with children in kindergarten through 12th grade are expected to spend $688.62 on average for back-to-school items, up from $603.63 last year, according to NRF&#39;s 2012 back-to-school survey.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&quot;People have put some of these things off as long as they can,&quot; NRF President and CEO Matthew Shay told Reuters, adding that back-to-school sales have been flat in the past couple of years.&nbsp; &quot;This is not discretionary, this is really mandatory,&quot; Shay said. &quot;Parents are going to do whatever they need to.&quot;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe expected spending bump will give some solace to U.S. retailers counting on the second-biggest selling season of the year for a much-needed sales boost after months of lackluster sales in the stagnant U.S. economy.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nEven though American shoppers intend to spend more, stores will still have to work to woo them, since parents plan to shop for discounts and cut back on children&#39;s extracurricular activities.&nbsp; That means retailers and brands will need to spend their advertising budgets wisely and target their audience carefully to gain strong market share in the crowded back-to-school market.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nParents estimate they will spend an average of $246.10 on clothes and $217.88 on electronics this year, up from estimates of $220.60 on clothes and $189.51 on electronics last year.&nbsp; Parents are spending on older children as well. College students and their families will spend an average of $907.22 on everything from dorm furniture to electronics to personal care items, up from $808.71 last year, according to NRF&#39;s 2012 back-to-college survey.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nTotal back-to-college spending is expected to reach $53.5 billion, while total back-to-school spending is expected to touch $30.3 billion.&nbsp; All told, the return to school serves as the second biggest consumer spending event for retailers behind the winter holidays. That is a significant increase for any retailer in terms of potentially increasing their bottom line.&nbsp; That said, to do so means smart, targeted advertising.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAdvertisers should focus on hyperlocal neighborhood targeting as a way to efficiently use their ad dollars.&nbsp; Digital neighborhood-level targeting effectively finds your specific audience before they go to the store.&nbsp; Further, only the neighborhoods most interested in purchasing your specific product will be shown a digital ad, efficiently driving these shoppers to specific retail locations.</p>\r\n	t	2012-08-28 10:00:17	\N	2012-08-28 10:00:17	2013-09-17 14:00:50.084274	58	back-to-school, NRF, retail, in-store, MaxPoint, OnPoint
815	1	35	how-data-affects-back-to-school-shoppers	How Data Affects Back To School Shoppers	<p>In the advertising market, many companies keep gathering more information and building more detailed profiles. If that information is not current, it is often worse than having no information at all.</p>\r\n	<p>Recently I was visiting with another dad Thom as we sent our kids off on a summer mission project. We talked about what else we did for the summer: family trips, household projects, sports, etc. Somehow this summer seemed to be the bucket where every activity that could not possibly fit in the last nine months is getting shoved. It will be a relief when school starts back and the kids are in one place from 8am to 3pm.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhen the conversation turned to where we worked, I mentioned working for an online advertising company, and Thom told me about his recent experience online. After several searches, he started to see specific ads for an SUV he wanted. Everywhere he went online, ads would show up exactly on target for what he was looking for. The stores were just around the corner from his house in San Francisco. Companies had built an incredible profile of his shopping habits. The only issue is that he bought that SUV more than a year ago. On top of that, Thom moved to Austin from San Francisco more than 10 years ago. Here was a profile of Thom&rsquo;s life and interests that was accurate, detailed and actionable except it was out of date. These advertisers were spending money targeting a specific customer who was no longer relevant. No amount of advertising was going to get Thom back in those stores for back-to-school clothes.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMy experience has been similar. I went to a site that shows the information collected in my digital footprint. It had interesting details on my life like the fact that I have a kid under two and another under five. Now I understand why I get ads for diapers every now and then even though it has been a while since my son (now in college) and daughter (in high school) have needed them. Incredibly detailed, actionable data that is stale and irrelevant. By the time school starts, I will be buying a new laptop for Patrick and clothes, school supplies and probably a car for Rebecca (she loves the Toyota Matrix). Pampers are not high on that list.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn the advertising market, many companies keep gathering more information and building more detailed profiles. If that information is not current, it is often worse than having no information at all. These ads, most likely, were cookie-based campaigns. According to comScore, only 20% of the intended audience is typically found with a cookie-based campaign, and 30% of computers delete their ad server cookies more than four times every month. With cookie-based campaigns, you&rsquo;ll never find enough of your customers. Advertisers should focus on a combination of multiple robust data sources, such as demographics data, retail purchase data, health data and lifestyle data, to better define and locate the right audience. Make sure any information you use for your back-to-school campaigns this summer is current as well as actionable.</p>\r\n	t	2012-08-23 13:47:24	\N	2012-08-23 13:47:24	2013-09-17 14:04:53.098339	58	back-to-school, data, digital advertising, MaxPoint, OnPoint 
814	1	20	staples-refreshes-offers-incentives-to-get-a-jump-on-back-to-school-shopping	Staples Refreshes Offers, Incentives to Get a Jump On Back-to-School Shopping	<p>No one likes stale inventory, especially when it comes to kids and teens.&nbsp; Having the newest, latest and greatest is all part of the back-to-school season and retailers like Staples<sup>&reg;</sup> know it.</p>\r\n	<p>No one likes stale inventory, especially when it comes to kids and teens.&nbsp; Having the newest, latest and greatest is all part of the back-to-school season and retailers like Staples<sup>&reg;</sup> know it. From binders in vibrant candy-colored hues to shag carpeting and LED chandeliers for lockers, Staples launches the back-to-school season in style with the hottest new product trends and guaranteed savings on essential supplies. <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nStaples, one of the top retail destinations for back to school, offers an amazing assortment of designs and essentials throughout the season to fit students&rsquo; needs from kindergarten to college.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&ldquo;Students want to personalize back-to-school supplies to reflect their personality without spending a small fortune,&rdquo; said Alison Corcoran, senior vice president of retail marketing, Staples. &ldquo;Staples makes it easy for parents and students to shop and save for back to school with the latest technology offerings, exclusive designs and must-have supplies at great values.&rdquo;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nStaples further sweetens the pot with a 15% back-to-school savings pass, which is a great deal as long as you plan on spending more than $100 in supplies to cover the $10 fee for the pass and reap some savings.&nbsp; The Pass is valid until Sept. 15 for use once a day on supplies including pens, pencils, paper, notebooks and backpacks. The savings pass is not applicable on technology such as computers and calculators.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nBack-to-school shoppers are always looking for heavy incentives to stretch their dollar, so retailers that lack the discounts and special offers will certainly feel the hit on their bottom line.&nbsp; Furthermore, originality, refreshed inventory and quality products are a must to bolster the customer loyalty that keeps them coming back year after year.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSome of the cool trends to drive back to school sales include new binder designs, magnetic locker wallpaper, shag rug squares to line your locker shelves, Reebok Z-series backpacks and a Martha Stewart Home Office&trade; line of products.&nbsp; A full list of trends that Staples is launching this year can be found at BTS Trends.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAnd, with the latest advertising technology out there today, smart marketers are leveraging hyperlocal digital advertising to drive in-store traffic to specific local stores to buy all of these cool new product lines this back to school shopping season.</p>\r\n	t	2012-08-21 11:41:56	\N	2012-08-21 11:41:56	2013-09-17 14:06:10.512408	58	back-to-school, digital advertising, in-store, MaxPoint, OnPoint
813	1	20	major-advertisers-grabbing-at-the-chance-to-reach-latino-market-with-mundofox	Major Advertisers Grabbing at the Chance to Reach Latino Market With MundoFox	<p>The Latino market in the U.S. is exploding, so it is no wonder we are witness to increased prominence of bi-lingual signage, multicultural advertising and now an increase in the number of Spanish-speaking TV networks, like MundoFox, which launched this week.&nbsp;</p>\r\n	<p>The Latino market in the U.S. is exploding, so it is no wonder we are witness to increased prominence of bi-lingual signage, multicultural advertising and now an increase in the number of Spanish-speaking TV networks, like MundoFox, which <a href="http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20120812005029/en/MundoFox-Live-Network-Launches-Latino-Audiences-U.S." target="_blank">launched this week</a>.&nbsp; <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhat&rsquo;s the big deal?&nbsp; New networks are launched all of the time.&nbsp; The difference is, this Spanish-speaking network has caught the eye of some major advertisers in an attempt to bolster their multicultural marketing initiatives, particularly to the Hispanic market.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMundoFox has already secured L&#39;Oreal USA, Toyota Motor Sales, U.S.A., Inc. and T-Mobile USA as major advertisers and charter sponsors for the network&#39;s debut.&nbsp;&nbsp; Notice that they are all the USA divisions of each corporation.&nbsp; This speaks volumes to the importance of reaching the Latino market in the US and securing their shopper loyalty ahead of the competition.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&quot;MundoFox wants to challenge and revolutionize the status quo by giving media buyers and advertisers more innovative options,&quot; said Tom Maney, Senior Vice President of Advertising Sales, Fox Hispanic Media. &quot;Smart marketers believe there is a new Latino mindset. They are asking for more choices and they will be given just that from MundoFox.&quot;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAdvertisers with MundoFox will also enjoy the benefits of cross-promotion with the other networks within the Fox Hispanic Media portfolio, such as Utilisima, Nat Geo Mundo and FOX Deportes.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&quot;This exclusive partnership with MundoFox is extremely important for our consumer products brands,&quot; stated Marc Speichert, Chief Marketing Officer, L&#39;Oreal USA. &quot;It furthers our strategy of reaching Hispanic consumers while providing us with a new platform on which to share relevant content that resonates with this important group.&quot;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nLikewise, Toyota Motor Sales, U.S.A., Inc. and T-Mobile USA seized this new opportunity to partner with a game changer like MundoFox. &quot;The launch of MundoFox greatly expands the options for consumers to experience quality Spanish content and represents a tremendous opportunity for marketers to take part in delivering that content,&quot; said Brett Dennis, Chief Media Communications Officer of Conill, the multicultural advertising agency representing Toyota Motor Sales, U.S.A., Inc. and T-Mobile USA. &quot;Our clients compete in fiercely aggressive categories and we are constantly looking for ways to engage people that go beyond simple air-time. MundoFox&#39;s programming strategy, innovative approach to creating advertising within that content and geographic penetration at launch were the overarching factors in bringing our clients on board as charter partners.&quot;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMundoFox is a joint venture between Fox International Channels (FIC), News Corporation&#39;s international multi-media business, and RCN, the leading Latin American television network and production company belonging to Organizacion Ardila Lulle (OAL). Together, FIC and RCN currently reach over 1.2 billion households worldwide with primetime comedies, dramas and daytime series, as well as factual, sports and lifestyle programming. Additionally, both operate and program cable networks and twenty-four-hour global news channels. The new