811	1	33	local-advertising-budgets-go-online	Local Advertising Budgets Go Online	<p>According to US Census data, 75 percent of consumer spending occurs within 15 miles of the average American&rsquo;s front door, meaning 50 percent of the nation&rsquo;s GDP is dependent on consumers buying locally. It&rsquo;s more important than ever for brick-and-mortar businesses&mdash;and the brands that sell within them&mdash;to connect with consumers (especially in the popular 18&ndash;54 age range) to drive them into stores.</p>\r\n	<p>According to US Census data, 75 percent of consumer spending occurs within 15 miles of the average American&rsquo;s front door, meaning 50 percent of the nation&rsquo;s GDP is dependent on consumers buying locally. It&rsquo;s more important than ever for brick-and-mortar businesses&mdash;and the brands that sell within them&mdash;to connect with consumers (especially in the popular 18&ndash;54 age range) to drive them into stores. <!--more--></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Over the last six decades, traditional channels, such as TV, radio and direct mail, were the primary avenues for reaching and serving ads to a target audience. More recently, advertisers have recognized the importance of digital advertising and have been putting local advertising dollars online. According to a report by media research company BIA/Kelsey, the rate of digital ad growth outstrips total local media expenditures and is expected to rise 2.6 percent annually through 2016 to $151.3 billion.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAs you allocate more of your local advertising budget online, there are a few things you&rsquo;ll want to keep in mind:<span id="cke_bm_99C" style="display:none">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>The scale and reach, cost-effectiveness, speed and flexibility of digital are what enable advertisers to efficiently drive in-store traffic. Digital intrinsically offers greater flexibility for your campaigns, and localized digital advertising solutions let you target different ads to different neighborhoods around the country.</li>\r\n\t<li>Not every consumer lives within close proximity of a retail store. National retailers waste a lot of national ad spend each year on ads that touch consumers who live outside a store&rsquo;s retail trade area. Your budget is better spent on a localized advertising solution that can guarantee that only consumers who match your shopper profile and who live within a specific radius of a retail location will see your ad.</li>\r\n\t<li>Although most advertising programs require you to create campaigns weeks or even months in advance of when you&rsquo;d like to generate interest in a product or service, highly localized digital campaigns of any size can launch within a matter of hours because you can leverage existing creative assets.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nAs soon as you properly target digital ads on a neighborhood level, you should see a lift in sales, increased brand engagement and more traffic at specific retail locations.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nFor more on giving digital campaigns a local edge, <a href="http://streetfightmag.com/2012/04/26/giving-national-campaigns-a-local-edge/" target="_blank">click here</a>.</p>\r\n	t	2012-08-14 12:00:09	\N	2012-08-14 12:00:09	2013-09-17 14:09:09.871506	58	local, digital advertising, MaxPoint, OnPoint, in-store
809	1	20	more-spending-for-back-to-school-shoppers-according-to-pricegrabber-survey	More Spending For Back-to-School Shoppers, According to PriceGrabber Survey	<p>The talk of a slowly improving economy just gained more support with the release of a recent PriceGrabber<sup>&reg;</sup> survey. The results of its first Back-to-School Shopping Forecast survey, revealing that nearly half (46 percent) of consumers are planning to spend more this back-to-school shopping season than in 2011.</p>\r\n	<p>The talk of a slowly improving economy just gained more support with the release of a recent PriceGrabber&reg; survey. The results of its first Back-to-School Shopping Forecast survey, revealing that nearly half (46 percent) of consumers are planning to spend more this back-to-school shopping season than in 2011. <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn comparison, only 13 percent of shoppers planned to spend more last year, and this data was reflected in an overall disappointing back-to-school season for retailers in 2011. Conducted from to May 22 to June 5, 2012, the survey includes responses from 4,450 U.S. shopping consumers, with 1,509 of the respondents planning to shop this back-to-school season.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhile almost half of the surveyed shoppers said they plan to spend more this back-to-school season, 35 percent of respondents plan to spend the same amount of money, and 19 percent of shoppers plan to spend less this year. In 2011, 52 percent of PriceGrabber survey respondents said they would spend the same amount of money on back-to-school shopping, and 35 percent said they would spend less.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAccording to PriceGrabber survey data, 17 percent of consumers plan to start their back-to-school shopping in June, 35 percent plan to start shopping in July, 44 percent noted August, and only 3 percent cited September. In 2011, respondents planned to shop a little later in the summer with only 13 percent planning to start their shopping in June, 31 percent in July, 49 percent in August, and 7 percent in September.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&quot;From last year&#39;s holiday shopping season through the middle of 2012, we have seen consumers starting to shop earlier surrounding major shopping seasons and holidays, and we expect this trend to continue this back-to-school shopping season,&quot; stated Graham Jones, general manager of PriceGrabber. &quot;While PriceGrabber survey data reveals that many consumers are planning to spend more money this back-to-school shopping season, a few are still hesitant about spending, leading shoppers to search for deals even earlier to take advantage of retailer incentives and discounts such as free shipping, coupons and sales.&quot;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSimilar to last year, shoppers still plan to spread out their back-to-school purchases in order to distribute the cost over a longer time period. According to PriceGrabber survey data, 55 percent of consumers plan to spread out their back-to-school purchases this year.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&quot;Back-to-school shopping can quickly become expensive,&quot; added Jones. &quot;In today&#39;s challenging economic climate, it&#39;s important for families and students to save on back-to-school items.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThis is also in alignment with what a recent BIGinsight grocery research&nbsp; revealed: consumers are more cost conscious now than in 2007.&nbsp; They are leveraging coupons and sales and are also shopping closer to home.&nbsp; Shoppers are also increasingly using digital resources to prepare for their shopping trips and in fact, 90% of shoppers research online before they go to the store.&nbsp; Now, more than ever, advertisers are realizing the importance of hyperlocal digital advertising to drive in-store traffic and sales.</p>\r\n	t	2012-08-09 12:11:57	\N	2012-08-09 12:11:57	2013-09-17 14:16:33.323846	58	MaxPoint, OnPoint, back-to-school, retail, PriceGrabber
810	1	20	marketing-to-a-hispanic-market-examples-of-advertisers-heading-in-the-right-direction-2	Marketing to a Hispanic Market: Examples of Advertisers Heading in the Right Direction	<p>Retailers aren&#39;t the only ones trying to become more relevant to Hispanic and other multicultural shoppers.&nbsp; Across almost all product categories, manufacturers are creating targeted campaigns, too. Below are some good examples shared in a Progressive Grocer article of companies marketing to a multicultural nation.</p>\r\n	<p>Retailers aren&#39;t the only ones trying to become more relevant to Hispanic and other multicultural shoppers.&nbsp; Across almost all product categories, manufacturers are creating targeted campaigns, too. Below are some good examples shared in a Progressive Grocer article of companies marketing to a multicultural nation.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nCoca-Cola Co. said it views three groups as &quot;key Hispanic shoppers&quot; for its brands: moms, teens and blue-collar males. To reach these groups &mdash; and ultimately drive traffic to retail locations &mdash; the Atlanta-based beverage company builds its marketing efforts around &quot;connection points&quot; such as functional/body, emotional/mind and cultural/spirit.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhen it comes to attracting Latina moms, Coca-Cola&#39;s messaging has previously centered predominantly on pairing its products with meal occasions. However, the company decided instead to talk about pairing its products with home entertainment occasions.&nbsp; This is a testament to a company&rsquo;s ability to change and rapidly modify their efforts to what is most timely and relevant.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nLatina moms love watching telenovelas, or Spanish-language soaps, so the company created the &quot;Coca-Cola Telenovela Club,&quot; and recruited two popular serial stars to be the club&#39;s spokespeople. The program incorporates a digital platform and in-store displays.&nbsp; Within two months, the website generated more than 30 million impressions and retail outlets with the displays were reporting a 22 percent increase in Coca-Cola sales.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nLatina moms are General Mills&#39; target as well. The company&#39;s &quot;Que Rica Vida&quot; program, which bundles many of its iconic American brands, strives to establish an emotional connection with Latinas, in turn making the products more relevant to them and their families, said Rodolfo Rodriguez, the Minneapolis-based company&#39;s director of multicultural marketing.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&quot;Que Rica Vida&quot; launched in 2007 with a direct-mail magazine printed four times a year, and has grown to include grassroots promotions, a Univision media partnership, digital efforts and other strategic partnerships. The magazine continues to be a highly successful piece, with households receiving the publication generating 10 percent higher sales, Rodriguez said.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nRather than segment by gender, Chicago-based MillerCoors focuses its initiatives on bicultural Hispanic consumers, those who &quot;feel like a Latino, but think and dress like an American,&quot; according to Roger Garcia, brand manager for the Coors Family of Brands, Hispanic.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe brewer uses the acronym SLICE to describe its Hispanic market approach:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>Sponsorships (ex. entertainment venues, New York&#39;s Puerto Rican Day Parade)</li>\r\n\t<li>Local markets</li>\r\n\t<li>Innovations (its newest product is aluminum pints)</li>\r\n\t<li>Culturally relevant advertising and programming</li>\r\n\t<li>Execution</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nGarcia said retail activation is vital to bringing all of these pieces together to reach the consumer. &quot;If we don&#39;t have retail displays that resonate, all of this can get lost,&quot; he noted.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThis point was also echoed by Marla Rappaport of Dallas-based Kimberly-Clark Corp., who said engaging consumers at retail is a key aim of her company&#39;s Hispanic program for its Scott brand of paper products.&nbsp; The Scott program is built around &quot;dichos,&quot; folksy sayings used by Hispanics in their everyday conversations. In its recent campaign, Scott asked consumers how they apply &quot;dichos&quot; in their own lives.&nbsp; The campaign was called &quot;Buen Rollo,&quot; which translated means &quot;the good roll.&quot; The company teamed with retailers such as Walmart, Kroger, Family Dollar and ShopRite, driving consumers to the stores for in-store demonstrations, samplings, a free gift with purchase, and giveaways. &quot;Buen Rollo&quot; community events also were held in various markets.&nbsp; The company saw 9 percent growth in measured markets and made 141 million impressions, exceeding its goal.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAutumn Dawn McDonald, director, consumer insight &amp; strategy for Kraft, and Roberto Ruiz, VP, brand solutions at Univision, teamed together on using in-market testing for growth in the Hispanic market.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMcDonald and Ruiz showed how a campaign based on Hispanic-specific insights helped increase sales of Kraft Singles cheese by 12 percent in the Hispanic market. &quot;The general market campaign was geared to bringing back grilled cheese sandwiches &mdash; but that message doesn&#39;t resonate with Hispanics,&quot; said Ruiz. Switching to a Hispanic message focused on &quot;made from milk&quot; spoke more directly to Hispanic moms, he said.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMulticultural campaigns do not necessarily need to be complicated. In this case, a simple three-word phrase made grilled cheese resonate in the Hispanic market.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n*General Mills, MillerCoors and Kimberly Clark all executed their programs bilingually.</p>\r\n	t	2012-08-10 14:29:59	\N	2012-08-10 14:29:59	2013-09-17 14:13:02.955637	58	MaxPoint, OnPoint, multicultural, hispanic marketing, coca-cola
808	1	20	part-ii-multi-cultural-advertising-becomes-more-about-interests-over-race	PART II – Multi-Cultural Advertising Becomes More About Interests Over Race	<p>It is no longer black or white in the advertising world, literally.&nbsp; The rapidly growing populations of Latinos, Indians and Asian are rapidly changing the way advertisers target specific markets.&nbsp;</p>\r\n	<p>It is no longer black or white in the advertising world, literally.&nbsp; The rapidly growing populations of Latinos, Indians and Asian are rapidly changing the way advertisers target specific markets.&nbsp; <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nThis phenomenon may explain a couple of ads: a black-and-white commercial produced by Spike Lee for Gatorade Mission G features close-ups of Caucasian, African-American and multiracial athletes, staring straight into the camera to tell viewers about heart, hustle and soul; a spot promoting Cash4Gold.com has two famously bankrupt celebrity pitchmen of different races, Ed McMahon and rap artist MC Hammer, explaining how easy it is to liquidate gold cufflinks, golf clubs and the like.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nKarl Carter, chief executive of the Atlanta marketing agency GTM Inc. (Guerrilla Tactics Media), calls this the &quot;Benetton Approach&quot; since it echoes a 1980s campaign by United Colors of Benetton that pictured interracial close-ups, such as a Caucasian woman and an African-American woman hugging an Asian baby.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSuch ads often depict, Carter says, &quot;a bunch of different races playing along, side by side, Kumbaya.&quot; The ads may play well now, but Carter wonders how long they will be effective &mdash; particularly as America &quot;beiges&quot; and race becomes less essential to how individuals self-identify. Over the long run, advertisers would do better, he says, to focus on a cultural approach with versatile images and campaigns easily adapted to highly individualized tastes and interests. Put another way: How do hip-hoppers feel? What are the common desires of surfers, or skateboarders, or kayakers?<br />\r\n<br />\r\nPepsi appears to have digested the message. Though its &quot;Refresh Everything&quot; ads include people of multiple races, &quot;We&#39;re targeting anyone who embodies optimism and the spirit of youth,&quot; says Nicole Bradley, a Pepsi spokeswoman. &quot;It&#39;s more about a mind-set than a demographic. With young people who&#39;ve grown up in a biracially or surrounded by different cultures and races, it&#39;s more about what connects them.&quot;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nCommon connections and interests rather than race, give credence to the old adage &ldquo;birds of a feather flock together.&rdquo;&nbsp; It is not necessarily true any longer in the US that races alone flock together.&nbsp; Rather, people and groups with similar views, tastes, beliefs, income, culture, activities and interests flock together independent of race.&nbsp; If advertisers are really serious about getting highly targeted campaigns, interest &amp; lifestyle data should be used along with a combination of other powerful data sources like consumer demographics data, health data, and retail purchase data.</p>\r\n	t	2012-08-06 23:58:17	\N	2012-08-06 23:58:17	2013-09-17 14:19:24.509944	58	MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, multicultural, latino marketing, asian marketing, aftrican american marketing
724	1	15	what-is-the-state-of-localized-advertising-in-retail	What is the State of Localized Advertising in Retail?	<p>Retailers and brands are continually focused on ways they can re-think their marketing strategy to drive in-store traffic to different retail locations. In 2012, localization (specifically, localized digital advertising) is becoming a key part of&nbsp; brand strategies,&nbsp; but it&rsquo;s still a small percentage of the overall budget to drive traffic to stores.</p>\r\n	<p>Retailers and brands are continually focused on ways they can re-think their marketing strategy to drive in-store traffic to different retail locations. In 2012, localization (specifically, localized digital advertising) is becoming a key part of&nbsp; brand strategies,&nbsp; but it&rsquo;s still a small percentage of the overall budget to drive traffic to stores. <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nListen to our video on &ldquo;What is the State of Localized Advertising in Retail?&rdquo; and hear MaxPoint&rsquo;s COO, Gretchen Joyce, discuss why localization is important to brands and why brands and retailers should take advantage of local digital advertising. She discusses highlights from Retail Systems Research&rsquo;s (RSR) <a href="http://maxpoint.com/rsrreport" target="_blank">research study</a> on how retailers use digital experiences to drive local store traffic.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWatch here:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<iframe width="560" height="315" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/6Fccw1y0aC4?rel=0" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n\r\n<p><!--This is the embed code for the video, notice the 2 src parameters you need to update--></p>\r\n	t	2012-02-22 12:30:45	\N	2012-02-22 12:30:45	2013-10-01 19:10:23.318132	51	MaxPoint Interactive, MaxPoint, OnPoint, Gretchen Joyce, local, localized advertising, retail, brands, video, in-store traffic, marketing strategies, Retail Systems Research, local
825	1	18	how-hyper-local-can-play-in-holiday-marketing	How Hyper-Local Can Play in Holiday Marketing	<p>It&rsquo;s natural for brands and retailers to assume that holidays and seasonal events like back-to-school are revenue-generators, but it&rsquo;s not always that simple with variable inventory, shifting digital media consumption patterns and an economy still in the doldrums.</p>\r\n	<p>It&rsquo;s natural for brands and retailers to assume that holidays and seasonal events like back-to-school are revenue-generators, but it&rsquo;s not always that simple with variable inventory, shifting digital media consumption patterns and an economy still in the doldrums.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nThere are steps every brand and retailer can take to ensure their products move off the shelf at the right time to avoid having to sell them for half-price in mid-September. It starts by getting local. Hyperlocal, that is.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOne of the biggest concerns for brands and retailers is the idea of having to liquidate seasonal events and holidays that typically spur excess sales. In an ideal world, stores have enough of a product during the high-traffic times and an appropriately adjusted amount of inventory left in the months to follow. The supply side knows the &ldquo;just-in-time&rdquo; model well, but it is imperative that stores understand how to create just-in-time demand as well.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nEvaluating local digital advertising strategies will help determine the best way to drive foot traffic to nearby stores. It is an incredibly effective way to create just-in-time demand for specific products at the first signs of inventory imbalance.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nTraditional advertising programs require brands and retailers to create campaigns weeks or months in advance of when they&rsquo;d like to drive traffic to stores. Digital changes all that. Now, brands can &mdash; and should &mdash; reuse campaign assets to launch hyper-local digital campaigns in a matter of hours. This gives marketers incredible power &mdash; no longer do campaigns need to be planned far in advance. Now, marketers can supplement planned promotions with those that drive demand at the individual store level, based on the inventory at any given location.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhile targeting consumers within a certain demographic in a specific DMA is common practice, retailers should be targeting consumers with specific interests within a certain mile radius from stores with excess inventory, to take that targeting technique to a far more advanced level. This requires leveraging technology that analyzes both online and offline data points and making this data actionable in a matter of milliseconds. This data is incredibly valuable, revealing the attributes of neighborhoods across the country so brands and retailers can drill down to target only those neighborhoods with residents that are a fit for their products and services, driving real traffic to specific stores, with the ability to scale nationwide.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOnce <a href="www.maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-solutions" target="_blank">neighborhood data</a> is determined, national campaign assets can be easily customized with localized messages and the address of the nearest store location. Not only does this create a more personalized ad experience, it creates consistency across all ad elements on various media, and contributes to the ROI on the money spent on campaign creative. This is key for brands looking to maximize their ad investments.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nFor instance, a national craft store chain wanted to drive awareness of its back-to-school products to consumers within a 10-mile radius of specific store locations. By using demographic, point-of-sale and geographic data, the chain was able to target consumers on a hyperlocal level. It hit either a.) only female teachers, ages 25-55, with a bachelor&rsquo;s degree or higher, and a household income of less than $60,000; or b.) mothers, ages 35-55, with a household income of less than $100,000, and frequent purchasers of craft products based on past data.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nHyperlocal precision takes incentives and offers to a whole new level. If in-store sales are slow for a particular item, brands and retailers can create campaigns that incentivize local consumers to come in and make purchases of that specific item.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThose companies that solely run carpet-bombing national campaigns need to rethink their digital ad strategy. If building awareness is the goal, this strategy works. But if you want to move products off shelves, carpet-bombing can be irrelevant, too broad and just plain expensive. Instead, they should complement national campaigns with hyperlocal campaigns. Get local, and you will move seasonal items off-the-shelf, where and when you want.</p>\r\n	t	2012-09-17 10:45:45	\N	2012-09-17 10:45:45	2013-09-16 22:37:01.240188	58	hyper-local, neighborhoods, digital advertising, holiday marketing
822	1	20	diversity-inclusion-add-to-marketing-breadth	Diversity, Inclusion Add to Marketing Breadth	<p>Today&rsquo;s marketers and advertisers need to look beyond the typical target markets in order to survive and gain precious market share, not only from their tried and true audience, but audiences that are quickly gaining momentum.&nbsp; If you are not thinking ahead to the next big market, your competitors may leave you in the dust.</p>\r\n	<p>Today&rsquo;s marketers and advertisers need to look beyond the typical target markets in order to survive and gain precious market share, not only from their tried and true audience, but audiences that are quickly gaining momentum.&nbsp; If you are not thinking ahead to the next big market, your competitors may leave you in the dust.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nOne of those groups, the LGBT (Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, Transgender) is rapidly gaining acceptance and will soon become an everyday acronym in advertising.&nbsp; &quot;The dollars are there,&quot; said Brian Stout, senior strategist who heads the GLBT marketing division at Leo Burnett. &quot;This is an enormously large group in terms of buying power.&quot; The GLBT audience is the minority in the U.S. with the third-most overall buying power after Hispanics and African-Americans, he said, &quot;bigger than Asian and American Indian combined.&quot;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nForward thinking groups such as Marriott International, Inc. have embraced this group and began a campaign targeted and customized directly to them.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe &quot;Be You, With Us&quot; campaign launches in celebration of Pride Season (often observed from June through September) in cities around the world that host gay pride parades and festivals to celebrate the LGBT community. The campaign is filled with imagery and messages that welcome all guests to be themselves when staying with Marriott.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&quot;We are proud of this campaign and of our long-standing reputation for our commitment to diversity and inclusion,&quot; says Joanna Todd, vice president, segment strategy. &quot;Our core strength lies in our ability to embrace differences and make everyone feel respected and valued when they visit and stay in our hotels. Later this year, we will also launch new campaigns to reach African American and Latino audiences.&quot;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOther reputable names throwing their hats into the GLBT market include JC Penney, who included in their catalog a pair of gay dads playing with their kids in a Fathers Day ad. &nbsp;But Marriott International, Inc and JC Penney aren&rsquo;t alone in seeing this audience as ripe for business: Allstate Insurance and American Airlines last week announced new marketing campaigns aimed at the GLBT audience as well.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThis is a new generation of thinking.&nbsp; A time when diversity, culture, inclusion and acceptance blur the line in our society, thus challenging marketers and advertisers to drastically change the way they think about new markets, present and future.</p>\r\n	t	2012-09-11 12:04:50	\N	2012-09-11 12:04:50	2013-09-16 22:43:57.131819	58	LGBT, diversity, culture, agencies
821	1	20	top-retailers-prepared-with-incentives-but-are-they-reaching-their-target-market-effectively	Top Retailers Prepared with Incentives but are they Reaching their Target Market Effectively?	<p>Kids love back-to-school shopping.&nbsp; So much so, they start earlier each year.&nbsp; Even the teachers are preparing their class lists well in advance of the first day.&nbsp; So what is a retailer to do?&nbsp; Advertise earlier, promote earlier and find some killer promotion to guide young consumers (and their parents) to their stores. &nbsp;</p>\r\n	<p>Kids love back-to-school shopping.&nbsp; So much so, they start earlier each year.&nbsp; Even the teachers are preparing their class lists well in advance of the first day.&nbsp; So what is a retailer to do?&nbsp; Advertise earlier, promote earlier and find some killer promotion to guide young consumers (and their parents) to their stores. &nbsp;<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nNearly 20 percent of consumers say they started their back-to-school buying in June, a month when many schools were just letting out, according to a survey by PriceGrabber. Last year, 13 percent were shopping in June.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&quot;Retailers simply cannot afford to have consumers spend a dollar somewhere else, so they start earlier and earlier with back-to-school,&quot; said Richard Feinberg, a retail professor at Purdue University. &quot;They are aggressive because they have to be.&quot;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nFor others, it&#39;s a way to spread out spending.&nbsp; In fact, the PriceGrabber survey showed 55 percent of shoppers said they have budgeted to do just that.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&quot;In terms of spreading out purchases? Yes. Many customers make multiple trips during back-to-school,&quot; said Karen Pevenstein, a spokeswoman for Staples. &quot;This way they can stock up all season long.&quot;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nNearly $70 billion was spent on back-to-school purchases in 2011, according to the National Retail Federation. That&#39;s second only to the holiday season, which pulls in $471 billion.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWith offers of deeper discounts and incentives to capture precious market share, retailers are left with thinner bottom lines and advertising budgets that need to stretch for longer back-to-school season.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOne way to stretch advertising budgets is to focus on neighborhood-level advertising.&nbsp; Instead of purchasing an entire DMA, advertisers can now pinpoint specific neighborhoods where your specific shoppers live, within a certain mile radius of your store.&nbsp; Neighborhood-level targeting drives traffic to specific stores while also eliminating waste on a national, regional or local scale &ndash; further stretching those advertising dollars.</p>\r\n	t	2012-09-07 15:21:15	\N	2012-09-07 15:21:15	2013-09-16 22:44:27.713641	58	back-to-school, in-store, shoppers, retailers, MaxPoint, OnPoint
820	1	20	major-retailers-look-to-drive-more-in-store-sales-with-extended-back-to-school-deals	Major Retailers Look to Drive More In-store Sales With Extended Back-to-school Deals	<p>I never remember back to school shopping as a kid being the next closest thing to an Olympic event. Nor do I remember retailers having huge sales on everything in the store that might even remotely be associated with back-to-school. Now, as a parent, I too am seeking the gold medal for savings on all things scholastic. Like many other parents, there are a handful of retailers that come to mind for a one-stop shop for back-to-school supplies, apparel and food.</p>\r\n	<p>I never remember back to school shopping as a kid being the next closest thing to an Olympic event.&nbsp; Nor do I remember retailers having huge sales on everything in the store that might even remotely be associated with back-to-school.&nbsp; Now, as a parent, I too am seeking the gold medal for savings on all things scholastic.&nbsp; Like many other parents, there are a handful of retailers that come to mind for a one-stop shop for back-to-school supplies, apparel and food.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nFor example, Target Corporation is extending its summer &ldquo;Bonus Black Friday&rdquo; to a Friday and Saturday sales event.&nbsp; Target said customers will find &ldquo;Black Friday-like&rdquo; deals on more than 2,000 items including toys, movies, and apparel.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe big box retailer&rsquo;s move comes as many companies are searching for ways to boost sales amid the lagging economy.&nbsp; Several stores have started back-to-school sales and introduced fall lines early, while some&mdash;like Target&mdash;have pushed &ldquo;Christmas in July&rdquo; sales to expand the spending season beyond the November and December deluge.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWal-Mart has taken the direct approach by letting teachers post their school supply lists on the retailer&rsquo;s website &ndash;effectively driving both online and offline sales.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhat&rsquo;s at stake?&nbsp; According to an NRF report, the average family of K-12 students will rack up a back-to-school receipt of $688.&nbsp; Multiply that by the number of families with children in grades K-12 (which also grew according to the report &ndash;to the tune of 3 in 10 Americans having children between ages 6 and 17) and retailers will be vying for billions of back-to-school dollars.&nbsp; Aside from the K-12 market, there is yet another chunk of the market&mdash;higher education.&nbsp; The NRF report found that 15% of college shoppers will purchase their back-to-school items via catalog &ndash; a stat that has tripled since 2003.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAs stores seek more market share in a slow-to-recover economy, extending sales and drawing consumers to the store is key to survival.&nbsp; Also in the NRF report, chain department stores find themselves in with the popular crowd this year as 6 in 10 shoppers plan to shop that category &ndash; the most in survey history. These retailers and the brands that sell within them can grab more of the market through smart hyperlocal advertising.&nbsp; It&rsquo;s this simple:&nbsp; use neighborhood targeting to drill down to specific customer segments for more precise and effective campaigns with scale.</p>\r\n	t	2012-09-05 23:33:46	\N	2012-09-05 23:33:46	2013-09-16 22:45:34.579854	58	back-to-school, retailers, shoppers, in-store, MaxPoint, OnPoint
723	1	15	imedia-brand-summit-event-recap-iconic-brand-strategies-unleashed	iMedia Brand Summit Event Recap: Iconic Brand Strategies Unleashed	<p>Last week, MaxPoint headed to Bonita Springs, Florida for the 2012 iMedia Brand Summit to join the conversation on the secrets in digital that define the world&rsquo;s most iconic brands. Below is a brief recap of the event.</p>\r\n	<p>Last week, MaxPoint headed to Bonita Springs, Florida for the 2012 <a href="http://www.imediaconnection.com/summits/29552.asp" target="_blank">iMedia Brand Summit</a> to join the conversation on the secrets in digital that define the world&rsquo;s most iconic brands. Below is a brief recap of the event. <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nAs spending shifts from traditional to digital, more are realizing the importance of digital&rsquo;s role and the impact it can have on an advertising campaign. At this past iMedia Brand Summit, attendees dove into learning and discussing the role digital plays in delivering a lasting brand impact and deeper audience engagement.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nTo stress how brands can help shape how consumers feel about their lives and themselves through rich brand experiences, the summit focused on three main topics:<span id="cke_bm_337C" style="display:none">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>What branding works in different digital environments</li>\r\n\t<li>How to become iconic with memorable digital branding</li>\r\n\t<li>How to leverage multiple digital platforms like video, mobile, social, etc., for big branding bang</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nPresentations ranged from unique brand digital strategies to social media campaigns and how to leverage new technology in high retail traffic seasons. Keynote speakers included <a href="http://www.linkedin.com/pub/scott-roen/5/283/7b8" target="_blank">Scott Roen</a>, VP Digital Marketing &amp; Innovation for American Express and <a href="http://blogs.imediaconnection.com/blog/2012/02/07/how-dockers-got-its-manhood-back