es to accurately target an audience online, reaching and influencing them before they decide what to buy or where to shop? In this session, audience members will learn:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>How brands and retailers can work together to create a beneficial, consumer-driven relationship and drive in-store traffic and product sales by precisely targeting shoppers online</li>\r\n\t<li>Which specific strategies can eliminate the problem of advertising waste by efficiently and effectively targeting shoppers at the neighborhood level on a national scale</li>\r\n\t<li>How retailers can implement targeted digital experiences to complement their existing offline and in-store efforts</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nWe look forward to seeing you at Navy Pier!</p>\r\n	t	2012-10-15 20:58:32	\N	2012-10-15 20:58:32	2013-09-10 16:39:36.223013	58	shopper marketing expo, shopper marketing, retailers, brands
831	1	15	top-10-infographic-design-tips	Top 10 Infographic Design Tips	<p>Everywhere you look these days, there are infographics. According to an article in Mashable, &ldquo;infographics are graphic visual representations of information, data or knowledge. These graphics represent complex information quickly and clearly, such as in signs, maps, journalism, technical writing, and education.&rdquo;</p>\r\n	<p>Everywhere you look these days, there are infographics. According to an article in <a href="http://mashable.com/" target="_blank">Mashable</a>, &ldquo;infographics are graphic visual representations of information, data or knowledge. These graphics represent complex information quickly and clearly, such as in signs, maps, journalism, technical writing, and education.&rdquo;<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nSo how do you get started? Well, if you&rsquo;re an advertiser thinking about creating an infographic, here are some tips to keep in mind to ensure your infographic stands out from the rest:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n\t<li><strong>Gather your data:</strong> Obviously, it all starts with data. Make sure you have enough data to tell your story in the form of an infographic, and don&rsquo;t lose sight of the data as you begin your design.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Keep the design simple:</strong> Don&rsquo;t overthink the design and make it too complicated. You want to lure your viewers in, so be sure to use a simple design that&rsquo;s easy to interpret.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Choose one topic:</strong> Be sure the story you&rsquo;re trying to tell focuses on one topic. Otherwise, you&rsquo;ll end up with too many confusing visualizations.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Tell a story:</strong> Think about taking your data and turning it into a narrative. Maybe you&rsquo;ll explain a process, highlight trends on a given topic, or support some type of debate. Whatever it is, your infographic will stand out when you take a storytelling approach.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Check your facts:</strong> You will lose immediate credibility if you publish an infographic with incorrect data. It may seem obvious, but it happens. Be sure to double-check your facts and proofread, proofread, proofread!</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Consider visual approaches:</strong> Effective infographics use attractive colors, proper typography, and hierarchy techniques to keep viewers engaged.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Make sure it can stand alone:</strong> A good infographic should be able to stand on its own, especially in this world of sharing online.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Cite your data:</strong> With infographics containing so much data, don&rsquo;t forget to cite your sources for not only the data points but also your photos and illustrations.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Avoid using too many words:</strong> Even though you should be telling a story through the use of visuals and short phrases, don&rsquo;t write a novel. Keep your information short and to the point.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Create a small file:</strong> You want readers to be able to share and download your infographic easily, so keep the size of the file small while not compromising the quality of your imagery.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nThese tips will help you create an effective infographic. To see which infographics made the biggest splash in 2011, check out <a href="http://mashable.com/2011/10/23/top-mashable-infographics/" target="_blank">these infographics from Mashable</a>.</p>\r\n	t	2012-10-18 15:45:46	\N	2012-10-18 15:45:46	2013-09-10 16:39:57.844958	58	infographics, creative campaigns, mashable, 2011
833	1	15	a-look-at-the-four-es-of-luxury-brand-success	A Look at the Four E’s of Luxury Brand Success	<p>Believe it or not, consumers are staying loyal to luxury brands even during our challenging economic times. Why? Lower brands aren&rsquo;t offering the quality consumers are finding in luxury brands.</p>\r\n	<p>Believe it or not, consumers are staying loyal to luxury brands even during our challenging economic times. Why? Lower brands aren&rsquo;t offering the quality consumers are finding in luxury brands. <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nAccording to a Global 500 study by Brand Finance, &ldquo;consumers turn to these alphabrands because they are keen to cast aside their worries about the economic downturn and allow themselves an indulgence in a brand which they know, trust and admire.&rdquo; So what are these luxury brands doing right to keep these consumers coming back for more?<br />\r\n<br />\r\nLuxury brands follow not only the classic four P&rsquo;s of marketing but also the four E&rsquo;s &ndash; experience, exclusivity, engagement, and emotion.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>Experience:</strong> Consumers are still buying the luxury brands, but they&rsquo;re being extra selective and are asking themselves &ldquo;Is it worth it?&rdquo; Luxury brands answer this question by offering consumers an &ldquo;experience.&rdquo; For example, Burberry saw a 29% increase in revenue by switching most of its marketing budget to digital experiences. And the Ritz-Carlton has proved that investing in a quality experience will set you aside from your competition.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Exclusivity:</strong> We all know one key to a luxury brand&rsquo;s success is the exclusivity it offers, which the brand can transfer to its digital marketing. For example, the St. Regis offers an e-butler app, and Chanel offers an interactive culture microsite. It&rsquo;s this high-tech marketing that makes these luxury brands appear exclusive and on the cutting edge.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Engagement:</strong> In the luxury brand world, engagement means one thing &ndash; a story. We&rsquo;ve all cried while watching a diamond commercial that tells an engaging story, right? An appealing story that evokes emotion from consumers is key to a successful luxury brand. Tiffany &amp; Co. saw a 20% uptick in sales after its launch of the &ldquo;What Makes Love True&rdquo; microsite and &ldquo;Engagement Ring Finder&rdquo; mobile app &ndash; both of which communicate the story of realizing true love.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Emotion:</strong> The final element is emotion. Speaking to consumers&rsquo; wants is key for a luxury brand. Consumers who want to feel authentic and timeless stay loyal to brands like Burberry. They shop at Tiffany&rsquo;s to feel love, and they stay at the Ritz-Carlton to feel admired.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nLuxury brands have proved that following the four E&rsquo;s is critical to their success in a slowing economy, when consumers have so many more affordable options. Marketers who are seeking to improve loyalty to their brands may want to apply the four E&rsquo;s to their strategies.</p>\r\n	t	2012-09-27 10:00:57	\N	2012-09-27 10:00:57	2013-09-16 22:31:34.240694	58	luxury, brands, marketing, advertising
832	1	15	understanding-the-brain-of-a-boomer	Understanding the Brain of a Boomer	<p>When it comes to marketing to baby boomers, it is best to keep it simple. As boomers age, it becomes more challenging for their brains to handle complex visuals and verbiage.</p>\r\n	<p>When it comes to marketing to baby boomers, it is best to keep it simple. As boomers age, it becomes more challenging for their brains to handle complex visuals and verbiage.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<a href="http://gaia.adage.com/images/bin/image/rightrail/0910p28-targeting-tips-side.jpg?1347043305"><img alt="" src="data:image/png;base64," style="border:0pt none; float:left; height:864px; margin-left:10px; margin-right:10px; padding-bottom:10px; padding-left:10px; width:181px" /></a>The positive side of this is that their brains tend to filter out negative messaging and images (and focus on the positive) thanks to the amygdala &ndash; the emotional center in the brain.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nCaroline Winnett, chief marketing officer of Nielsen Neurofocus, says &ldquo;the brain is far more adaptable than we thought. So the old paradigm that you get old and your brain and all your neurons die is completely getting shot down by new research.&rdquo;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAccording to a recent article in <a href="http://adage.com/" target="_blank"><em>Advertising Age</em></a>, research shows that &ldquo;while boomers have more trouble seeing the forest through the trees and often ignore busy ads or information in borders around ads, that&#39;s just because they&#39;re more easily distracted than younger folks. And that&#39;s a problem, it turns out, that a little &lsquo;World of Warcraft&rsquo; might cure.&rdquo; A recent study even showed that those over 55 saw immediate structural brain changes after exposure to a series of video games.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhy is this important? Well, many advertisers focus on the millennial group and tend to forget boomers, who according to Nielsen make up 25% of the US population and control 70% of the net worth of American households. <em>Advertising Age</em> recognizes the importance of marketing to boomers and recently shared some tips on understanding the differences between the boomer brain and the millennial brain. Read through these tips from Nielsen Neurofocus, and let us know your thoughts on marketing to boomers.</p>\r\n	t	2012-10-11 18:36:22	\N	2012-10-11 18:36:22	2013-09-10 16:44:52.363163	58	advertising age, nielsen, advertising, creative campaigns
