n a Nobel Peace Prize. She is also the <em>New York Times</em> bestselling author of <em>Reality is Broken: Why Games Make Us Better and How They Can Change the World</em> (Penguin Press, 2011). She also currently serves as the creative director for Social Chocolate, where she makes games powered by the science of positive emotion and social connection.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWe look forward to seeing you at the conference!</p>\r\n	t	2012-10-08 19:05:38	\N	2012-10-08 19:05:38	2013-09-10 16:45:56.452957	58	MIMA Summit, interactive, digital advertising, marketing
716	1	15	super-bowl-xlvi-its-all-about-the-advertising	Super Bowl XLVI - It's All About the Advertising	<p>Almost as exciting (if not more exciting for some) as the Super Bowl game itself, fans anticipate the select group of new advertisements shown. This year, advertisers are stepping it up, creating viral campaigns, buying selective spots and adding digital elements.</p>\r\n	<p>As Super Bowl XLVI draws near (February 5!), smells of chili, brew and talks of Super Bowl parties are in the air - but the chatter doesn&rsquo;t stop there. Almost as exciting (if not more exciting for some) as the Super Bowl game itself, fans anticipate the select group of new advertisements shown. This year, advertisers are stepping it up, creating viral campaigns, buying selective spots and adding digital elements. Below is a preview of who&rsquo;s buying what and a look at how advertisers are using digital to reach consumers.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Who&rsquo;s buying what?</strong><br />\r\nWith 30-second spots quickly going for as much as $3.5 million, retailers and brands are stepping up, dishing out the dollars and grabbing the spots before others can take their place. Who&rsquo;s buying what? Here&rsquo;s a sneak peak:<span id="cke_bm_98C" style="display:none">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>Skechers: This popular retailer has secured one spot to run just before the two-minute warning in the first half of the game. Entrepreneur, Mark Cuban will promote Skechers&rsquo; GoRun shoe line alongside a bulldog named &ldquo;Mr. Quigley.&rdquo; Watch the preview <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=j87Y-NS7Evk&amp;feature=player_embedded" target="_blank">here</a>.</li>\r\n\t<li>Volkswagen: For this year&rsquo;s Super Bowl, Volkswagen grabs a 60-second spot that will air in the third quarter of the game. A minute-long teaser for its 2012 entry features dogs in &ldquo;Star Wars&rdquo; accessories barking the movie&rsquo;s &ldquo;Imperial March.&rdquo; Watch the preview <a href="http://www.thehdroom.com/news/The-Bark-Side-2012-Volkswagen-Super-Bowl-Commercial-Teaser-/10106" target="_blank">here</a>.</li>\r\n\t<li>Bridgestone: In addition to sponsoring the half-time show this year, Bridgestone will air two related commercials about their tire performance. Watch the preview <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6NjDDFIV7Z8&amp;feature=player_embedded#!" target="_blank">here</a>.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nSee the full list <a href="http://adage.com/article/special-report-super-bowl/buying-super-bowl-2012/231122/" target="_blank">here</a>.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>The Super Bowl embraces digital</strong><br />\r\nWe all know TV is the main channel for Super Bowl advertisements, but more advertisers are incorporating digital elements and using digital to make the ads go viral -extending beyond viewers who are simply watching during the game. With over 60% of the U.S. population using the Internet, it has proved to be an effective medium to reach and engage with consumers.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nLast year, consumers and advertisers shared Super Bowl ads over YouTube &ndash; making them more viral than if they had just left it up to traditional advertising. This year, retailers and brands incorporate digital elements by adding mobile apps for consumers to interact with a campaign or play a game that ties back to the advertised product. For example, PepsiCo &ldquo;<a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2012/01/03/business/media/to-promote-brisk-tea-pepsi-enlists-the-aid-of-yoda.html?_r=1" target="_blank">Star Wars</a>&rdquo; campaign has limited edition bottles and a &ldquo;Star Wars&rdquo; mobile game. Others use social media channels and online contests to create hype around a Super Bowl campaign, such as Doritos &ldquo;<a href="http://www.crashthesuperbowl.com/" target="_blank">Crash the Super Bowl</a>.&rdquo;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn addition, Super Bowl advertisers &ndash; leverage your high priced TV creative after the Super Bowl with online vi