842	1	20	men-and-the-zen-of-mobile-shopping	Men and the Zen of Mobile Shopping	<p>For years, women ruled the shopping world, far surpassing men in virtually all categories. The trend seemed to follow the rules of the universe, maintaining the yin and yang of the advertising and consumer worlds. Enter smartphones and tablets.</p>\r\n	<p>For years, women ruled the shopping world, far surpassing men in virtually all categories. The trend seemed to follow the rules of the universe, maintaining the yin and yang of the advertising and consumer worlds.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nEnter smartphones and tablets.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThese mobile devices single-handedly rocked the advertising world by converting men into shopping gurus! That&rsquo;s right; according to a September 2012 study conducted by online market research company <a href="http://www.usamp.com" target="_blank">uSamp</a>, women in the United States trail men in terms of mobile purchases. Men out-shop women in the consumer electronics category by nearly 20% and have significant leads in digital content, movie and event tickets, computer equipment, and luxury goods. Women, however, still hold the lead for health and beauty by a 6% margin when it comes to mobile purchases.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMen also over-index for most mobile shopping activities, not just buying. The study by uSamp indicates that 91% of male mobile device users have scanned a mobile barcode, compared to 85% of female US mobile users. Moreover, almost half of male mobile users have used their mobile devices to make a payment, compared to just over one-third of females. However, female mobile users do beat out their male counterparts when it comes to the use of mobile coupons: 44% to 35%.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nA mobile shopping study by digital ad agency <a href="http://www.moosylvania.com/" target="_blank">Moosylvania</a> also points to women as heavy mobile coupon users. According to its findings, 44% of female US smartphone users redeemed an online coupon via mobile in November 2011, compared to 34% of men.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe same Moosylvania study also found that 32% of female US smartphone users have opted in to receive location-based mobile coupons, compared to only 26% of men.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAs more men become one with their mobile devices, the opportunities for advertising increase significantly. It&rsquo;s important to keep in mind, however, that men&rsquo;s advertising preferences and shopping behavior are very different from that of women. According to an <a href="http://www.iprospect.com/digital-anatomy-of-the-affluent-male" target="_blank">iProspect report</a>, for example, males show a preference for video ads over banner ads. Marketers should take note of gender differences when launching any mobile commerce-related campaigns and offers.</p>\r\n	t	2012-11-28 21:01:58	\N	2012-11-28 21:01:58	2013-09-04 15:25:22.222477	59	mobile, mobile advertising, retailers, brands, MaxPoint
841	1	20	target-customers-online-and-to-the-store-they-will-come-with-some-help-from-stylish-actors	Target Customers Online and to the Store They Will Come—With Some Help from Stylish Actors	<p>It is pretty obvious by now that if you don&rsquo;t have an online component in one form or another to your advertising campaign, the likelihood of effectively reaching your target audience is slim to none. With the rise of hyperlocal targeting and companies that can serve your ads online directly to a specific market, merchandisers have a golden opportunity to spend their dollars on the exact people they wish to reach.</p>\r\n	<p>It is pretty obvious by now that if you don&rsquo;t have an online component in one form or another to your advertising campaign, the likelihood of effectively reaching your target audience is slim to none. With the rise of hyperlocal targeting and companies that can serve your ads online directly to a specific market, merchandisers have a golden opportunity to spend their dollars on the exact people they wish to reach.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nBefore the hyperlocal movement, placing ads was like fishing with a trawling net. Since trawling nets are fairly indiscriminate in what they catch, you usually end up catching fish that are too small to keep or a noncommercial species that you dispose of. Sure, you&rsquo;ll get a few of the specific fish you want to catch, but the majority will be waste you throw back in, some even slipping through the holes. In fact, according to Greenpeace, trawlers frequently throw away over 30% of the fish they catch, and as much as 70% of trawl catches are wastefully dumped overboard. Today, brands that use the latest in hyperlocal targeting are catching exactly what they want with the right tools and bait for a specific audience&mdash;with very few getting away.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMarketing to shoppers is difficult. Marketing to male shoppers is even more so because men tend to see shopping as a tactical strike rather than a drawn-out process. Procter &amp; Gamble&rsquo;s Gillette Fusion line is no exception to a targeted strategy aimed at men. The ProGuide Styler, designed to enhance facial hair to create an individual look, is a favorite among North American men, particularly those under 30 years old. What is the best way to reach a 20-something male? Digitally. Combine that with happy customers, and you have an online, viral campaign driving young men to snatch up the latest tool in the facial fashion trend. According to Procter &amp; Gamble&rsquo;s research on the campaign, 70% of men who have already used the ProGlide Styler said it is better than the grooming tools they&rsquo;ve used previously.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nTo round out its digital advertising and social media efforts, Gillette also leverages television, print advertising, and in-store merchandising. The integrated effort features rapper and actor Andr&eacute; Benjamin (AKA Andr&eacute; 3000), Mexican actor Gael Garc&iacute;a Bernal, and American actor and director Adrien Brody. Procter &amp; Gamble chose the three because of their stylish, individually sculpted facial hair as well as their strong sense of self and authentic style, all of which appeal to younger males.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSo whether you are targeting moms, young men, dads, or kids, old-school trawl net methods of reaching your audience are a thing of the past. Savvy marketers will hit their targets with laser focus through hyperlocal digital advertising.</p>\r\n	t	2012-11-20 13:49:04	\N	2012-11-20 13:49:04	2013-09-04 16:27:00.440648	50	shopper marketing, brands, Procter & Gamble, hyperlocal targeting, MaxPoint Interactive
840	1	15	five-ways-to-avoid-getting-cooked-by-the-competition-this-thanksgiving	Five Ways to Avoid Getting Cooked by the Competition This Thanksgiving	<p>Thanksgiving is less than a week away, but it&rsquo;s not too late for digital advertisers to make a final online push for their holiday-friendly food, beverages, decorations, and more.</p>\r\n	<p>Thanksgiving is less than a week away, but it&rsquo;s not too late for digital advertisers to make a final online push for their holiday-friendly food, beverages, decorations, and more. Here are five tips for making sure no money is left on the table come Thursday:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n\t<li><strong>Keep It Local</strong> &ndash; Last-minute shoppers scrambling for a turkey next week will opt for convenience above all else, choosing to shop local for their final Thanksgiving items. Drive the most traffic to your stores by targeting your ads to customers within just a few miles of your locations instead of blanketing an entire DMA.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Connect with Shoppers Interested in Your Business </strong>&ndash; The best way to maximize your ad spend this season is to reach interested shoppers online before they head to the store. In addition to targeting local Thanksgiving diners, reach shoppers who you know are interested in what you have to offer&mdash;<a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/advertising-tips-and-strategies/advertising-insights/gourmet-and-comfort-food-interest" target="_blank">whether that&rsquo;s a modern twist on a traditional Thanksgiving item or a good old-fashioned classic</a>.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Don&rsquo;t Underestimate the Need for Good Creative</strong> &ndash; Online advertising for the winter holidays is in full swing, which means you&rsquo;ll be up against countless brands and retailers vying for the attention of consumers. With just days until Thanksgiving, however, you don&rsquo;t have the luxury of getting lost in the crowd. Use simple, bold creative with a clear call to action and solid, honest copy.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Leverage Your TV Ads </strong>&ndash; You don&rsquo;t have to reinvent the wheel for your Thanksgiving digital advertising push. Take your existing TV advertising spots, for example, and repurpose them as pre-roll video spots online.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Think Multichannel </strong>&ndash; Thanksgiving shoppers will be consuming content in a variety of ways leading up to the holiday&mdash;from browsing for recipes and checking out football schedules on their laptops to monitoring flight delays and tracking the latest weather developments from their smartphones. Maximize your ROI by implementing a multichannel advertising campaign that takes advantage of display, video, and mobile.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nOne of the great benefits of digital advertising is that online ads can be up and running within as few as 24 hours. With this and the tips above in mind, every advertiser can make the most of the days leading up to Thanksgiving.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<em>Like this post? Get more tips for the holiday advertising season in our </em><a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/advertising-tips-and-strategies/advertising-guides-and-reports/guide-to-holiday-advertsing" target="_blank"><em>Guide to Holiday Advertising</em></a><em>. </em></p>\r\n	t	2012-11-16 14:52:16	\N	2012-11-16 14:52:16	2013-09-04 16:29:43.465135	58	holiday advertising, digital advertising, Thanksgiving, MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive
839	1	20	you-dont-have-to-be-big-to-be-successful-but-you-need-to-know-your-audience	You Don’t Have to Be Big to Be Successful, But You Need to Know Your Audience!	<p>Huge retailers have huge budgets and giant corporate partnerships to market new products. But a large budget doesn&rsquo;t necessarily translate into big sales results. One small company is turning to online channels to drive in-store sales, but most important, it&rsquo;s hitting its target market on the head.</p>\r\n	<p>Huge retailers have huge budgets and giant corporate partnerships to market new products. But a large budget doesn&rsquo;t necessarily translate into big sales results. One small company is turning to online channels to drive in-store sales, but most important, it&rsquo;s hitting its target market on the head.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Brain-Twist Inc. launched a Slap brand frozen energy drink in April. The first priority? Making sure the target audience was aware of the product. Aimed primarily at college students, Slap relied heavily on social marketing and convenience store placement.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&ldquo;College kids aren&rsquo;t listening to the radio. These kids live online, and if you want to reach them, you have to live online as well,&rdquo; says Mike Oringer, president of Brain-Twist. &ldquo;If you look at a convenience store, that&rsquo;s our target. The average college student is not shopping at the grocery store. Their daily shopping is at the c-store.&rdquo;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nLeading up to the launch, Brain-Twist partnered with midwestern c-store chain Casey&rsquo;s General Stores for a &ldquo;Frozen Ticket&rdquo; promotion that encouraged Casey&rsquo;s shoppers to register on Slap&rsquo;s Facebook page to receive a BOGO coupon via regular mail. In-store signage supported the promotion.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nLike any good college product, the frozen drink, like a Slurpee, is charged with caffeine, B vitamins and the amino acid taurine. In marketing materials, Brain-Twist is using a &ldquo;Freeze it. Squeeze it. Get Slap&rsquo;d&rdquo; tagline.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn addition to extensive Facebook and Twitter promotions to drive students to c-stores, Brain-Twist developed a &ldquo;Freeze Yourself&rdquo; app at Slapfrozen.com, where users can insert their image into virtual blocks of ice in easily sharable photographs. Viral marketing at its best!<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe big coup of Brain-Twist was a negotiated placement of Slap energy drinks in Walmart stores in addition to sampling events in areas frequented by students, including campuses, beaches, and amusement parks.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe company is also offering an on-pack promotional sweepstakes through which customers can submit a picture of themselves with a Slap beverage for a chance to win a trip to the Snow Village Ice Hotel in Montreal. &ldquo;College kids love dealing with things on a bucket list,&rdquo; Oringer says. &ldquo;An ice hotel is something very cool. This is a clever way of appealing to them and reinforces our brand attributes.&rdquo;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe moral of this story is to know what your audience likes, know how they act, and know how to reach them. The rest will fall in place.</p>\r\n	t	2012-11-07 20:54:31	\N	2012-11-07 20:54:31	2013-09-04 16:31:04.026042	50	brand promotions, brands, shopper marketing
838	1	20	better-than-a-rebate-loyalty-gets-shoppers-major-league-soccer-merchandise-tickets	Better Than a Rebate: Loyalty Gets Shoppers Major League Soccer Merchandise, Tickets	<p>Marketers need to continually up their game when it comes to originality and innovative ways to drive customers to their products. The status quo simply won&rsquo;t cut it anymore as smart consumers look to get the most value out of a product, whether it&rsquo;s from price or promotion.</p>\r\n	<p>Marketers need to continually up their game when it comes to originality and innovative ways to drive customers to their products. The status quo simply won&rsquo;t cut it anymore as smart consumers look to get the most value out of a product, whether it&rsquo;s from price or promotion.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nPepsiCo subsidiary The Quaker Oats Co. launched a multiyear partnership with the Chicago Fire, a Major League Soccer (MLS) club. The summer/fall promotions target loyalty card customers at Jewel-Osco, the Chicago-based Supervalu chain. Shoppers can purchase three Quaker products at various participating supermarkets and receive a free ticket to one of the Fire&rsquo;s regular-season matches. In addition, shoppers who purchase any Quaker product with their loyalty card automatically receive an entry into a sweepstakes to win a trip to Harrison, New Jersey, to watch the Fire play in person. Additional prizes include tickets to home games, jerseys, T-shirts, scarves, and Jewel gift cards.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nShelley Pisarra, senior director of shopper insights and marketing at Quaker Foods &amp; Snacks says this of the promotion: &ldquo;[We] want consumers, especially mothers with kids in the household, to be aware that Quaker has healthy products to start the day. Additionally, we want to reach both current soccer fans and engage new fans who may have never attended a game.&rdquo;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe program is a four-way win among consumers, Quaker, Jewel, and MLS, where customers get rewarded for their loyalty, Jewel enjoys more traffic in its stores, Quaker sells more healthy products, and MLS increases its fan base.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWith the Jewel offer, the onus was on the giveaway. &ldquo;We wanted shoppers and the Fire fans to know this was a one-of-a-kind prize that only Quaker could provide,&rdquo; Pisarra said. Everyone loves an exclusive, until a copycat comes along. But as they say, copying is the best form of flattery.</p>\r\n	t	2012-11-01 17:23:10	\N	2012-11-01 17:23:10	2013-09-04 16:32:10.860298	50	brands, shopper marketing, Quaker, Major League Soccer
837	1	20	kimberly-clark-aims-to-grab-attention-of-kids-and-moms	Kimberly-Clark Aims to Grab Attention of Kids and Moms	<p>You know that when shopping with your children, you would love to have special child blinders that keep them focused on the aisle ahead and not on what&rsquo;s on the shelves. Smart marketers know that will never happen and use kids as vehicles to attract moms&rsquo; attention to certain products.</p>\r\n	<p>You know that when shopping with your children, you would love to have special child blinders that keep them focused on the aisle ahead and not on what&rsquo;s on the shelves. Smart marketers know that will never happen and use kids as vehicles to attract moms&rsquo; attention to certain products. <!--more-->Cereal has done it for years with the promise of &ldquo;a prize in every box.&rdquo; Regardless of whether their kids actually like the cereal or not, most of the time, moms purchase the product.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nGoing beyond the edible consumables, Kimberly-Clark is grabbing kids&rsquo; attention in the aisles with Tinker Bell and Spider-Man on nighttime underwear brand GoodNites. According to Dave Caputo, senior brand manager for GoodNites, his team is &ldquo;targeting moms of kids age 4&ndash;6 who are still using training pants to help manage bedwetting.&rdquo;<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&ldquo;Spidey&rdquo; for boys and &ldquo;Tink&rdquo; for girls are targeting more than moms; they&rsquo;re catching the eyes of moms&rsquo; younger shopping companions. Why Spider-Man and Tinker Bell? According to Caputo, his team selected them based on research of character appeal by the entertainment firms of Walt Disney Co. (Tinker Bell) and Marvel Entertainment (Spider-Man). &ldquo;We relied on our partners at Marvel and Disney to help us come up with the right characters for the age range, and we think we hit a home run.&rdquo;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nI can almost bet with certainty that they will hit that home run. Smart partnerships with kid-centric brands can accelerate awareness and ultimately, sales. Appealing to shoppers at two very different ages for a single product is extremely difficult, but as Kimberly-Clark has shown, not impossible.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe advertising and promotion is wide-ranging, including traditional print advertising in mom and parent magazines, free-standing inserts, and public relations. More important, there is a huge digital component, including parenting websites, retailer microsites, social media, and mommy bloggers.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWith measured success, I have a feeling that more CPG advertisers will be looking toward popular characters for future campaigns&mdash;likely coinciding with the next children&rsquo;s blockbuster hit. Smart!</p>\r\n	t	2012-10-26 14:47:14	\N	2012-10-26 14:47:14	2013-09-10 16:40:37.114509	50	Kimberly-Clark, CPG, Spider-Man, Tinker Bell, GoodNites
835	1	15	consumers-expected-to-spend-8-billion-this-halloween	Consumers Expected to Spend $8 Billion This Halloween	<p>With the fall season finally here, it&rsquo;s time to start thinking about planning for Halloween. According to the National Retail Federation&rsquo;s (NRF&#39;s) 2012 Halloween consumer spending survey by BIGinsight, 170 million people plan to celebrate Halloween this season.</p>\r\n	<p>With the fall season finally here, it&rsquo;s time to start thinking about planning for Halloween. According to the National Retail Federation&rsquo;s (NRF&#39;s) 2012 Halloween consumer spending survey by BIGinsight, 170 million people plan to celebrate Halloween this season.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nWith that many people celebrating Halloween, more shoppers will be heading in-store to purchase decorations, costumes, and candy. In fact, the average person will spend $79.82 on all these items with total Halloween spending expected to reach $8 billion. &ldquo;Retailers know that when it comes to Halloween, new costume ideas for children, adults and pets, and the latest in home and yard d&eacute;cor top people&rsquo;s shopping lists,&rdquo; said NRF President and CEO Matthew Shay. &ldquo;We expect retailers to stock their shelves well ahead of time to capture the attention of eager holiday shoppers.&rdquo;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nEven though there are record spending figures for this year&rsquo;s Halloween, almost 26% say the state of the economy will affect their Halloween plans. To compensate, most say they will spend less overall (83.5%), while others will make their own costume and over one-third will buy less candy.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Here are more survey highlights:</strong>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>35.7% will look for new costume ideas in a store, and 23.7% will turn to their friends and family.</li>\r\n\t<li>15.2% will turn to Facebook for costume inspiration, and 7.1% will eye Pinterest.</li>\r\n\t<li>33.3% will get their costume inspiration via