715	1	15	maxpoint-interactive-interest-index-helps-advertisers-pinpoint-neighborhoods-most-interested-in-a-healthier-lifestyle-in-2012	MaxPoint Interactive Interest Index Helps Advertisers Pinpoint Neighborhoods Most Interested in a Healthier Lifestyle in 2012	<p>Did you know that one of the most popular resolutions to make in the New Year is to lead a healthier lifestyle? Knowing how important leading a healthy lifestyle is to us and others around us, we were curious in knowing what neighborhoods are the most motivated when it comes to making a change for a healthier lifestyle in 2012.</p>\r\n	<p>Did you know that one of the most popular resolutions to make in the New Year is to lead a healthier lifestyle? Here at MaxPoint, our employees are encouraged to take weekly walks, join local runs, shop for healthy recipes and we even have a monthly gym stipend! Knowing how important leading a healthy lifestyle is to us and others around us, we were curious in knowing what neighborhoods are the most motivated when it comes to making a change for a healthier lifestyle in 2012. <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nToday, we&rsquo;re happy to announce the release of our indexing study that analyzed billions of data points to determine the U.S. neighborhoods most interested in establishing healthier lifestyles in 2012. With the start of a new year and most fitness-focused resolutions still unbroken, we conducted the research to provide advertisers seeking to sell health-related products with the neighborhoods most likely to respond to them. The cities that indexed the highest for looking to make a change for a healthier lifestyle in 2012 are:<span id="cke_bm_98C" style="display:none">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>Johnstown, PA</li>\r\n\t<li>Burlington, VT</li>\r\n\t<li>Fresno, CA</li>\r\n\t<li>Gainesville, FL</li>\r\n\t<li>Marquette, MI</li>\r\n\t<li>Panama City, FL</li>\r\n\t<li>Wheeling, WI</li>\r\n\t<li>Charlotte, NC</li>\r\n\t<li>Billings, MT</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nUsing the data from this indexing study, we implemented highly-targeted neighborhood-level digital campaigns for:<span id="cke_bm_100C" style="display:none">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>An athletics shoe retailer, who was able to identify and target neighborhoods that indexed highest around interests in jogging or running</li>\r\n\t<li>A high-end organic yogurt brand&rsquo;s introduction into neighborhoods that indexed high for healthy eating and fitness</li>\r\n\t<li>A large retailer, who used this information to drive participation for free health screenings and information on quitting smoking</li>\r\n\t<li>A national retail chain, who announced the redesign of its produce section to carry more fresh fruits and vegetables to the neighborhoods that would be most receptive to this information</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nAccording to our COO, Gretchen Joyce, &ldquo;too often, retailers and brands are wasting spend on advertising that is very broadly focused or not relevant to the audience they are reaching. By leveraging digital solutions that are very targeted, retailers and brands can execute more effective campaigns.&rdquo; This Interest Index is just one of many examples of how it&rsquo;s possible to get the critical and highly-accurate information advertisers&rsquo; need to reach a specific audience to drive in-store traffic.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nRead the full release on our indexing study <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/advertising-tips-and-strategies/advertising-insights/neighborhoods-healthier-lifestyle" target="_blank">here</a>.</p>\r\n	t	2012-01-31 14:54:43	\N	2012-01-31 14:54:43	2013-10-01 19:59:14.655373	54	MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, press release, MaxPoint, interest index, indexing study, health, healthy lifestyle, 2012, data, retail, advertising, digital campaigns, Gretchen Joyce 
707	1	20	social-inventor-community-quirky-a-retailers-dream-to-increase-offline-online-traffic	Social Inventor Community, Quirky, A Retailer's Dream to Increase Offline & Online Traffic	<p>We&rsquo;ve all had that idea in our heads for the next big product.&nbsp; The &ldquo;as seen on TV&rdquo; ideas that we see and say, &ldquo;why didn&rsquo;t I think of that!&rdquo;&nbsp; Maybe you have, but didn&rsquo;t want to go through the effort to file patents, hire designers, create business models, develop marketing strategies, build sales teams and source manufacturing.&nbsp; Enter Quirky.&nbsp;</p>\r\n	<p>We&rsquo;ve all had that idea in our heads for the next big product.&nbsp; The &ldquo;as seen on TV&rdquo; ideas that we see and say, &ldquo;why didn&rsquo;t I think of that!&rdquo;&nbsp; Maybe you have, but didn&rsquo;t want to go through the effort to file patents, hire designers, create business models, develop marketing strategies, build sales teams and source manufacturing.&nbsp; Enter <a href="http://www.quirky.com/" target="_blank">Quirky</a>.&nbsp; A social inventor community that allows someone to post their invention, gain real time feedback, and potentially be chosen by peers and Quirky employees as that week&rsquo;s best new idea.&nbsp; That&rsquo;s right, each week a new design is chosen for development.&nbsp; At that point, your idea is on the fast track to manufacturing and you make money on royalties.&nbsp; Granted, there is a point where Quirky owns your idea, but you still get paid based on sales.&nbsp; The benefit:&nbsp; you get to invent and not deal with the costs of marketing, sales and manufacturing.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nRetailer <a href="http://www.bedbathandbeyond.com/default.asp?" target="_blank">Bed, Bath &amp; Beyond</a> jumped at a chance to partner with Quirky, seeing the huge impact potential all of these new products could have on in-store and online traffic.&nbsp; This is another great example of pushing the limits of creativity to gain market share.&nbsp; This leap of faith seems to be working well for Bed, Bath &amp; Beyond as several products developed through Quirky inventors are selling across the retailer&rsquo;s nationwide stores.&nbsp; The products are even featured in their advertising free standing inserts (fsi&rsquo;s) and online ads, inviting others to join in and invent new products.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhile not exclusive to Bed, Bath &amp; Beyond, many products sell for the same price on another Quirky partner, Home Shopping Network (HSN).&nbsp; But, who doesn&rsquo;t have a 20% off coupon from Bed, Bath &amp; Beyond that makes it a no brainer to head to your closest neighborhood store and pick up the newest Quirky invention.&nbsp; Speaking of those great coupons, they are not valid online &ndash; what a perfect way to drive in-store traffic!&nbsp; With forward thinking like this from Bed, Bath &amp; Beyond, their position in the offline market share race is up in front!</p>\r\n	t	2012-01-12 14:43:36	\N	2012-01-12 14:43:36	2013-10-02 14:24:49.608383	49	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, Lynn Vitello, Quirky, Bed, Bath & Beyond, in-store traffic, retailers, market share   
855	1	15	how-to-select-the-right-creative-agency-for-your-company	How to Select the Right Creative Agency for Your Company	<p>Optimizing and launching your digital ads is only half the battle. It&rsquo;s often ad creative that ultimately makes or breaks a campaign.&nbsp;Unfortunately, too many marketers shortcut the process of finding the right creative agency.&nbsp;If you have ever had to select an agency, you understand why; it can be a time-consuming and labor-intensive task. But in the end, the stakes are high, which means the process is well worth your time and attention.</p>\r\n	<p>Optimizing and launching your digital ads is only half the battle. It&rsquo;s often ad creative that ultimately makes or breaks a campaign.&nbsp;Unfortunately, too many marketers shortcut the process of finding the right creative agency.&nbsp;If you have ever had to select an agency, you understand why; it can be a time-consuming and labor-intensive task. But in the end, the stakes are high, which means the process is well worth your time and attention.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nHere are a few tips to consider as you start your creative agency search:<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Look for an agency with a portfolio of diverse clients, including some in your industry.</strong><br />\r\nDon&rsquo;t underestimate the value of working with an agency that understands the broader market landscape and industry terminology.<strong> </strong>Companies that shy away from agencies that have worked with a competitor fail to see the value in the situation. An agency that has worked with a competitor probably understands the nuances and challenges of the market. It has likely done a fair amount of focus-group testing to understand the messages and themes that resonate with customers and prospects and can share those lessons learned. There is also far less ramp-up time for an agency like this, which means you can stay focused on the creative aspect of design and execution and worry less about the agency &ldquo;getting it.&rdquo;<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Make sure the agency has experience designing for digital channels.</strong><br />\r\nThere are still a number of agencies out there that focus solely on print or traditional channels, or that &ldquo;dabble&rdquo; in&mdash;or even outsource&mdash;digital work. Although that may fit your need for the short term, it&rsquo;s best to work with an agency that has experience working across various digital platforms. As the world moves further away from print and more toward digital, you will want your ideas to translate in every medium. If the agency does not have the experience, but you really want to work with it, ensure that the agency has a strong partner network of digital experts.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Remember that chemistry is important.</strong><br />\r\nFrom start to finish, a creative process can take months and even years to complete. In short, you&rsquo;re going to be with these guys for a while. It is important that you like your team. Sure, there will be creative differences and some bumps in the road, but you have to have a mutual respect and understanding that you are all working toward the greater end. One component of chemistry to consider is location. Many of the world&rsquo;s most creative minds reside in Chicago, New York, and Los Angeles. If your company doesn&rsquo;t mind paying for travel or is comfortable with videoconferencing, it may not matter where your agency of record is headquartered. If your past experiences with vendors have shown you that local contacts equal better relationships with your team, narrow your search to those agencies that are close.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Find an agency that can clearly define the project process for you.</strong><br />\r\nYou should feel comfortable knowing how your project will progress.<strong> </strong>If you have ever been through the process, you know that everyone will have something to say about your creative campaign when all is said and done. Some good, some bad, some complaints, some praise. That is why it is critical that any agency you work with clearly define the project process before you start. If you are far along a path of design and your stakeholder changes his mind, what happens? How far does that set you back? You want to make sure you set a series of check-ins and tests along the way and that everyone (on both sides) remains committed to the process. Setting an anticipated timeline of deliverables up front saves a lot of heartache in the long run.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<em>Have your own tips for selecting a creative agency? Leave a comment below.</em></p>\r\n	t	2013-03-14 17:19:36	\N	2013-03-14 17:19:36	2013-09-04 14:56:00.679633	58	digital advertising, creative agency, digital channels
853	1	15	same-old-song-you-give-hyperlocal-a-bad-name	Same Old Song: You Give Hyperlocal a Bad Name	<p>Recently, we learned that NBC News shut down EveryBlock, its hyperlocal news site. The intent of the site was to provide a collective view of local news, reviews, photos, videos, etc., for people at the town or city level. However, the company found that its business model was just not sustainable for the future. Does this mean doom and gloom for other hyperlocal business models?</p>\r\n	<p>Recently, we learned that NBC News <a href="http://edition.cnn.com/2013/02/07/tech/innovation/everyblock-closed/?hpt=hp_t3" target="_blank">shut down EveryBlock, its hyperlocal news site</a>. The intent of the site was to provide a collective view of local news, reviews, photos, videos, etc., for people at the town or city level. However, the company found that its business model was just not sustainable for the future. Does this mean doom and gloom for other hyperlocal business models?<br />\r\n<br />\r\nNo&mdash;and here&rsquo;s why.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<em>Hyperlocal</em> has been an overused, poorly defined term for years, especially in the context of advertising. Some view direct mail as hyperlocal. Others see placing an ad on a local newspaper&rsquo;s site as hyperlocal. Yet, both of these models (much like EveryBlock) have failed to capture the essence and long-term value of customer acquisition and retention.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhy?<br />\r\n<br />\r\nBecause they take a one-size-fits-all approach. For the most part, they consider everyone within a certain radius to be interested in the same thing. Does the 20-year-old student care about the same products, services, and content as her 80-year-old grandfather who lives in the same town? It&rsquo;s highly unlikely. There is no precision or science to this approach. It is not customized to a very specific audience. It is also a waste of valuable resources and dollars, which many small local businesses don&rsquo;t have to spend.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nHyperlocal should be about understanding and catering to an individual&rsquo;s (or close group of individuals&rsquo;) interests, preferences, and propensities. Herein lies the advantage of hyperlocal when it comes to advertising. Imagine a world in which the new martini bar in town can tailor and execute a digital advertising campaign to its key demographic: women ages 25&ndash;50, making $100,000 or more a year and living within a five-mile radius of the bar. Had that bar advertised in a local paper or even on a local news site, it&rsquo;s very unlikely it would have hit even a fraction of its intended audience. With a truly hyperlocal ad campaign, a restaurant (or retailer or brand) has the power to reach only the audience it believes is most likely to come into its establishment and drive sales.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSo, although the intentions have been good, we believe that the term hyperlocal has been given a bad name in the industry. An advertiser needs much more than a zip code or DMA (designated market area) to truly get hyperlocal. Seventy-five percent of all US consumer spending occurs at retail locations within 15 miles of consumers&rsquo; homes&mdash;an area smaller than most DMAs.<sup>1</sup> By targeting the most relevant consumers at the neighborhood level instead of the entire DMA, businesses can serve digital ads to only the most qualified prospects, thereby reducing wasteful ad spend.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nLet&rsquo;s take a look at regional businesses, such as restaurant chains and franchises. These businesses now have the ability to leverage technology that analyzes and combines offline and online data, enabling them to learn more about their target guests. Using these data, business owners can get hyperlocal by pinpointing the neighborhoods where their ideal customers most likely live. To give a real-world example, a national restaurant chain franchisee who owns more than 100 East Coast locations evaluated what is ordered throughout the day, every day, at each location. By analyzing guest traffic patterns, typical orders, etc., the franchisee was able to identify trends and serve up relevant, online advertising campaigns based on that data and specific to each location.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThis is just the tip of the iceberg. Although those who fail to capitalize on what hyperlocal has to offer will continue to fall by the wayside (EveryBlock, for example), there is still tremendous opportunity in the market for those companies that take full advantage of the technology and data available to get it right.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<sup>Sources:<br />\r\n1. US Census Data, 2009</sup></p>\r\n	t	2013-02-19 16:35:13	\N	2013-02-19 16:35:13	2013-09-04 14:59:06.283899	58	EveryBlock, hyperlocal, hyperlocal advertising
854	1	15	fifteen-percent-of-tv-ad-spend-moving-to-digital	Fifteen Percent of TV Ad Spend Moving to Digital?	<p>Recently, the Interactive Advertising Bureau commissioned a study with Nielsen that looked at how the movement of advertising dollars from TV to digital affects the reach and cost of campaigns. The study concluded that a 15% shift in media spend to digital drives a distinct increase in advertiser reach across verticals.</p>\r\n	<p>Recently, the Interactive Advertising Bureau <a href="http://www.iab.net/about_the_iab/recent_press_releases/press_release_archive/press_release/pr-022513_dvresearch" target="_blank">commissioned a study with Nielsen</a> that looked at how the movement of advertising dollars from TV to digital affects the reach and cost of campaigns. The study concluded that a 15% shift in media spend to digital drives a distinct increase in advertiser reach across verticals.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nNielsen examined 18 real TV schedules across key advertiser verticals. Categories included CPG (specifically health and beauty aids, food, and beverages), technology, automotive, retail, finance, and telecom.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe study provided a number of compelling insights that brands should consider as they determine how to divvy up their ad spend. We&rsquo;ve included a few snippets from the findings that we think are most interesting:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>Planning and running online ads first can boost how well both the online and TV portions of a campaign work.</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nOne of the largest risks associated with TV advertising is cost. Nailing a spot during primetime or a big event like the Super Bowl can cost advertisers quite a chunk of change, and there is often little insight into what impact the ad will have. Many national spots are minimally effective because there&rsquo;s no opportunity to target likely purchasers with localized, relevant messaging. For instance, a luxury car brand is more likely to have success if it targets a neighborhood of wealthy consumers with disposable income, rather than targeting a lower-income neighborhood or one that relies heavily on public transportation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The study notes these limitations of TV advertising, finding that message recall from an online ad is 40%, double that of what TV (broadcast and cable) nets (20%). General recall from online ads is 64%, and brand recall is 50%; TV advertising teeters at 46% and 27%, respectively.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Planning and running video ads online prior to running the same ads on TV, however, boosted brand recall by 33%. Similarly, viewers of an online display ad were 25% more likely to remember the brand if they had seen the ad online before viewing the ad on TV.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Combined, digital and TV advertising can be a powerful mix, more powerful than either channel is alone.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>Online viewers watch more online video content for longer.</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nThe study found that traditional TV viewing numbers are somewhat flat while total monthly online streaming numbers continue to rise. The average viewer now watches about six hours of streamed content per month. The demographic most affected by the switch from traditional TV to online streaming is 18- to 34-year-olds. Women tend to stream more content than men, while men tend to spend more time viewing the content (with the exception of long-form content).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>These insights are a goldmine for brands. Brands not only know where to target their key audience, but also how long is too long before they lose an audience. For instance, if men are more likely to view for longer periods, then brand advertisers can wait a bit longer for the call to action to appear in their videos. On the other hand, ads targeted primarily at women must cut to the chase sooner.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>Reallocating dollars to online channels builds higher quality, more effective reach at a lower cost.</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nBoth CPG and non-CPG brands can greatly enhance their effectiveness by allocating some of their overall ad spend to digital. The report indicates that by shifting to digital, advertisers see a 4% increase in overall reach. The most effective approach is a blend of TV and online advertising. CPG advertisers can reach 17% of their audience on both platforms by shifting 15% of spend to digital.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Overall, the importance of digital in the advertising ecosystem continues to gain traction. Within our own customer base, we&rsquo;ve found that the national brands that focus on a hybrid of national TV and local online campaigns have had the most success. However, we also continue to see a great deal of traction for small and midsize companies that commit a majority of their budgets to online channels.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIt will be interesting to continue to watch this shift, especially as the 18&ndash;34 demographic continues to mature and rely on digital as its primary channel for information and entertainment.</p>\r\n	t	2013-03-07 19:10:35	\N	2013-03-07 19:10:35	2013-09-04 14:57:51.074973	58	TV advertising, video ads, digital advertising, media spend
852	1	15	three-ways-digital-advertisers-should-use-big-data	Three Ways Digital Advertisers Should Use Big Data	<p>Big data is extremely valuable when it comes to affecting the outcomes of advertising campaigns. But there are three often overlooked ways big data can be used more effectively in digital advertising for campaign precision and scale: audience discovery, cross-correlation, and dynamic decision-making.</p>\r\n	<p>Big data is extremely valuable when it comes to affecting the outcomes of advertising campaigns. But there are three often overlooked ways big data can be used more effectively in digital advertising for campaign precision and scale: audience discovery, cross-correlation, and dynamic decision-making.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Audience Discovery:</strong> Until now, big data has been somewhat static in providing insights on consumers (where they live, what they buy, what their demographics are, etc.). Much of this data is outdated by the time it reaches an advertiser. Consumer preferences change in real time, and so should the information you&rsquo;re using to drive your advertising decisions.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<a href="http://www.maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-solutions" target="_blank">By analyzing billions (and sometimes trillions) of data points in real time</a> on everything ranging from social media discussions to point-of-sale (POS) data, advertisers get a clearer picture of exactly who their consumers are, what they are interested in, and when and why they buy. For instance, just because Sally makes $100,000 a year, has two kids, and is 35 years old, that doesn&rsquo;t mean she is going to buy a minivan. It&rsquo;s more important to know where Sally lives, how she buys, what she has purchased recently, what she is interested in on social networks, what her lifestyle preferences are, and where and when she shops. Taking these data points and providing a real-time snapshot of habits and preferences is much more specific and targeted to Sally&mdash;and empowers an advertiser to act in real time.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Cross-Correlation: </strong>Cross-correlation is critical to gaining that deeper level of consumer insight. For instance, an advertiser should not just want to understand that Sally buys BrandX jeans, but rather what that purchase says about what she will buy at the grocery store (for example, that she&rsquo;ll buy BrandY olive oil). Or perhaps a neighborhood is indexing high for searches and POS data on heart medication. The natural cross-correlation there may mean that consumers in that neighborhood are also looking to purchase aspirin as a treatment to lower the risk of a heart attack. At first glance, this may not have been a neighborhood the advertiser would have naturally targeted for heart medication, but the cross-correlation of data points makes it a solid case for an advertising campaign&mdash;and one with enormous scale.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Dynamic Decision-Making: </strong>By leveraging information and making it actionable in real time, advertisers can glean immediate results from campaigns. For example, an allergy drug manufacturer would typically drop an ad campaign in April or May, when spring allergies kick into high gear across the United States. <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/online-advertising-news/most-concerned-cities-about-flu" target="_blank">Now, they can use big data to cross-analyze weather patterns, consumer purchase data, and social media postings, among other data sets, at the moment they are happening.</a> This means they can access the precise time (right down to the day) and city where allergies are affecting consumers and hit &ldquo;go&rdquo; on a digital campaign that targets this specific group of consumers. Depending on the severity of the allergy season, they can scale the campaign up and down as needed. This precision and ability to scale will radically change the way advertising decisions are made in the future.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn all, big data is now in the grasp of everyone and is making advertisers smarter and campaigns far more precise and effective. By combining audience discovery, cross-correlation, and dynamic data, advertisers can make smarter decisions and experience immediate results.</p>\r\n	t	2013-02-15 14:32:55	\N	2013-02-15 14:32:55	2013-09-04 15:02:36.67818	58	big data, audience discovery, digital advertising, cross-correlation
850	1	15	super-bowl-ads-for-branding-or-buying	Super Bowl Ads: For Branding or Buying?	<p>When the 49ers and Ravens square off on Sunday to earn the coveted Vince Lombardi trophy (that&rsquo;s the Super Bowl trophy for you non&ndash;sports fans), many consumers will be keeping tabs on the most entertaining and unique Super Bowl ads that play throughout the game.</p>\r\n	<p>When the 49ers and Ravens square off on Sunday to earn the coveted Vince Lombardi trophy (that&rsquo;s the Super Bowl trophy for you non&ndash;sports fans), many consumers will be keeping tabs on the most entertaining and unique Super Bowl ads that play throughout the game.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhether it&rsquo;s <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PpBarEAicbo" target="_blank">Go Daddy pushing the limits</a> of its domain branding service with scantily clad women or <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9H0xPWAtaa8" target="_blank">Volkswagen playing off a Jamaican vibe</a> to promote its new Beetle, brands spend a lot of money and need a lot of creativity to make their ads noticeable during the Super Bowl. But what happens after the game? Does brand awareness spike? Do sales increase? How can brands carry that momentum forward to actually drive sales?<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<a href="http://maxpointinteractive.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/iStock_000020890275XSmall.jpg"><img alt="Get more from your Super Bowl ads with a hyperlocal online advertising campaign" src="http://maxpointinteractive.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/iStock_000020890275XSmall.jpg" style="border:0pt none; float:right; height:226px; padding-bottom:10px; padding-left:10px; width:340px" title="Get more from your Super Bowl ads with a hyperlocal online advertising campaign" /></a>One of the most effective ways to continue to drive value from the big investment of the Super Bowl ad blitz is to execute a <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/onpoint-blog/2013/1/11/taking-hyperlocal-campaigns-to-a-national-level" target="_blank">hyperlocal advertising campaign</a> to further the momentum started by the humorous or creative commercial. By using all the assets available from the national campaign, brands can quickly and cost-effectively execute a hyperlocal campaign to drive sales in regions across the country. As a result, brands can turn that buzzing into buying.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nFor instance, Volkswagen could create an online advertising campaign that targets only specific neighborhoods in the &ldquo;yuppie&rdquo; sections of major towns near their dealerships, based on the data and interest level of consumers in that area. They could also add a call-to-action that entices those consumers to go to their local dealership to check out the car. This approach helps brands get highly targeted, with little investment.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<a href="http://www.maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-solutions" target="_blank">Technology like ours</a> helps these brands identify the<strong><em> neighborhoods</em></strong> that are most interested in a brand (based on demographics, POS data, and social media chatter, among billions of other data sources.) As we shift away from direct mailers and local newspaper ads, hyperlocal advertising becomes an even more critical ingredient of turning brand awareness into sales in a timely and effective fashion.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIt&rsquo;s also an effective method for understanding cross-selling opportunities. For instance, if we measure an uptick in interest around a new flavor of spicy Doritos throughout certain neighborhoods in the United States, it&rsquo;s likely that data can be used to identify people who like spicy foods. That information can then be used to help a Mexican restaurant chain with new menu items drive sales, or even help a brand of salsa make inroads in new markets. The opportunities are endless.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSo who wins the Super Bowl trophy when it comes to brands? We believe it&rsquo;s those who think national AND 