851	1	15	selling-generic-drugs-and-remedies-during-the-flu-season	Selling Generic Drugs and Remedies During the Flu Season	<p>With the cold months here, we can count on one thing: the flu. This season is one of the toughest flu seasons in years. In fact, it has been such a rough season that the flu has frequently been one of the top stories in the major news outlets.</p>\r\n	<p>With the cold months here, we can count on one thing: the flu. This season is one of the toughest flu seasons in years. In fact, it has been such a rough season that the flu has frequently been one of the top stories in the major news outlets.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAlthough you may not enjoy having to beat the sniffles, you have to be happy if you sell products to help others beat them. In fact, Ad<em> </em>Age <a href="http://maxpointinteractive.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/iStock_000015547443XSmall.jpg" target="_blank"><img alt="Now is a great time to sell your store-brand flu products" src="http://maxpointinteractive.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/iStock_000015547443XSmall.jpg" style="border:0pt none; float:right; height:147px; padding-bottom:10px; padding-left:10px; width:217px" title="Now is a great time to sell your store-brand flu products" /></a>recently posted <a href="http://adage.com/article/news/flu-reckitt-johnson-johnson-a-shot-arm/239156/" target="_blank">an article</a> talking about big increases in sales for companies that promote and sell cold and flu remedies. And it&rsquo;s not only flu shots and brand-name medicines that are boosting profits&mdash;many generic products, including cleaning solutions and disinfectants, are flying off the shelves as well.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIf you&rsquo;re in the business of selling flu products, this can be a great time to move your store-brand items. Here are a few tips:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>Offer Coupons and Discounts for Generic Products &ndash;</strong> Generic products are often already priced lower than their brand counterparts, but offering additional promotions and discounts can bring people into your store and push them over the edge on switching from the big brands to your store brand.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ul><br />\r\n\t<li><strong>Look at Store Sales Data to Target the Right Locations &ndash; </strong>MaxPoint has run many campaigns for pharmacies and stores trying to sell generic products. Our experience has shown that you cannot make universal assumptions about which customers will be likely to switch from brand-name items to generics. For example, although generics are less expensive than their brand equivalents, having a lower income does not always indicate that the customer will switch to generics. Instead, you must look at sales data to see which of your locations have a track record of customers switching from brands to generics. Once you select the right stores, you can reliably target the best neighborhoods for your campaign.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ul><br />\r\n\t<li><strong>Don&rsquo;t Forget Supporting Products &ndash;</strong> The season is not just about flu shots and cold medicine. According to MaxPoint&rsquo;s <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/online-advertising-news/most-concerned-cities-about-flu" target="_blank">monthly Interest Index</a>, many shoppers are interested in supporting products, such as hand sanitizer, chicken soup, vitamin C, and orange juice. You can get a lot of mileage out of the flu by promoting in-store specials on other products and tying them into your advertisements. Even if customers buy brand-name flu medicine, you may still get them to buy store-brand hand sanitizers or thermometers.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ul><br />\r\n\t<li><strong>Keep Running Campaigns Over the Next Few Months &ndash;</strong> According to an <a href="http://www.cnn.com/2013/01/11/health/flu-dont-know/index.html" target="_blank">article on cnn.com</a>, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention claims that we still don&rsquo;t have a great idea of when the flu season officially ends (it may be as late as May). Although sickness peaks in January and February, you are likely to still see flu remedy sales in March and April.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nAlthough you may hate getting sick, the flu can be one of the biggest drivers in pharmacies and grocery stores this time of year. With more than 47 states declaring flu advisories, this year may be one of the roughest flu seasons in some time. And with top news sites covering the event, you&rsquo;ll get a major boost to your online advertising simply through the exposure. It&rsquo;s up to you to get your local store to be the go-to place for relieving those awful symptoms.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nPlease take a look at our <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/online-advertising-news/most-concerned-cities-about-flu" target="_blank">January Interest Index</a> to learn more about which areas are particularly concerned about this year&rsquo;s flu season.</p>\r\n	t	2013-02-06 15:34:01	\N	2013-02-06 15:34:01	2013-09-04 15:06:12.749917	57	flu, generic products, hyperlocal advertising, store-brand products
849	1	15	spotlight-how-naked-pizza-used-hyperlocal-online-advertising-to-boost-all-natural-pizza-sales	Spotlight: How Naked Pizza Used Hyperlocal Online Advertising to Boost All-Natural Pizza Sales	<p>MaxPoint released a case study today for Naked Pizza. Naked Pizza, a restaurant providing delicious and healthy all-natural pizza, wanted to create brand awareness, generate traffic, and increase restaurant sales at several of its New Jersey locations. The case study demonstrates how a multi-location business can effectively drive in-store sales with a hyperlocal online advertising campaign.</p>\r\n	<p>MaxPoint released a case study today for Naked Pizza. Naked Pizza, a restaurant providing delicious and healthy all-natural pizza, wanted to create brand awareness, generate traffic, and increase restaurant sales at several of its New Jersey locations. The case study demonstrates how a multi-location business can effectively drive in-store sales with a hyperlocal online advertising campaign.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe full text of the case study can be found below.<br />\r\n________________________<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>How did Naked Pizza use local online advertising to increase orders of its all-natural pizza?</strong><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Goal</strong><br />\r\nGenerate awareness, increase traffic, and drive sales at select New Jersey Naked Pizza locations.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Strategy</strong><br />\r\nMaxPoint used its Digital Zip<sup>&reg;</sup> technology to target families in the local area with an interest in maintaining a healthy lifestyle<strong>&mdash;</strong>a perfect fit for Naked Pizza, which offers a full menu of all-natural pizzas. MaxPoint also displayed the restaurant&rsquo;s ads to businesspeople who frequent area establishments during the midday lunch rush.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Results</strong><br />\r\nBy using MaxPoint&rsquo;s local online advertising solution, Naked Pizza was able to gain new insights into its customers making online orders, including their age, household income, net worth, and level of education. The restaurant was also able to get valuable data about which local neighborhoods visit its online ordering page and at what time of the day they place most orders. In all, targeted online ads have helped Naked Pizza increase sales by 19% at one New Jersey location and generate more than 600 new visits to its company website.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-solutions/digital-advertising-case-studies/naked-pizza-advertising" target="_blank"><img alt="Naked Pizza Heat Map" src="/system/editor/W1siZiIsIjIwMTMvMDkvMDQvMTBfMTRfMDFfNDMxX0hlYXRNYXBfTmFrZWRQaXp6YV9OSl82NDV4NDYwLnBuZyJdLFsicCIsInRodW1iIiwiODAweDgwMD4iXV0/HeatMap_NakedPizza_NJ_645x460.png" style="float:left; height:460px; width:645px" /></a><br />\r\n<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n	t	2013-01-24 17:39:01	\N	2013-01-24 17:39:01	2013-09-04 15:15:03.356307	61	audience insights, case study, local online advertising, Naked Pizza
848	1	37	native-advertising-an-ad-in-contents-clothing	Native Advertising: An Ad in Content’s Clothing	<p>Many advertising publications are declaring 2013 as the year of native advertising. The format has been around for a while, but it is really starting to grow. Over the next few years, advertisers will push billions into native ads. So what is native advertising, and how does it stack up to other online channels?</p>\r\n	<p>Many advertising publications are declaring 2013 as the year of native advertising. The format has been around for a while, but it is really starting to grow. Over the next few years, advertisers will push billions into native ads. So what is native advertising, and how does it stack up to other online channels?<br />\r\n<!--more--><br />\r\n<em>Native advertising</em> refers to ads displayed in context of the publication. Native ads take on the look and feel of the publishing site and fit within the flow of the user experience. For example, Facebook&rsquo;s sponsored stories use Facebook&rsquo;s blue as well as the typical font and style of a status update. Other examples of native advertisements are promoted tweets on Twitter, sponsored YouTube videos, and even Google paid ads.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOn the other end of the spectrum, online display ads retain the advertiser&rsquo;s branding rather than the publisher&rsquo;s. This makes them stand out and drive the user&rsquo;s attention toward the ad rather than their main task. Additionally, display ads are distributed across many publisher sites rather than just those individual platforms that support native publishing.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>The Tradeoffs of Native Advertising</strong><br />\r\nNative ads definitely show promise. They can drive engagement for ads placed in online publications and social media platforms, particularly when shared within social circles on the big social media platforms. But native ads are far from an online advertising silver bullet.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn order to provide a seamless user experience, native ad publishers require customized content. It can get expensive to consistently produce custom content for each separate publication. For example, the format of a Facebook sponsored story will be quite different from the shorter sponsored Tweet format. And each of these will have a different design and format than a Tumblr or BuzzFeed post. This type of customization requires time and resources that can make the effort cost-prohibitive.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong><a href="http://maxpointinteractive.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/Screen-Shot-2013-01-16-at-1.50.59-PM.png"><img alt="Example of a Facebook sponsored post" src="http://maxpointinteractive.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/Screen-Shot-2013-01-16-at-1.50.59-PM.png" style="border:0pt none; float:right; height:374px; padding-bottom:10px; padding-left:10px; width:413px" title="Example Facebook sponsored post" /></a></strong>In contrast, display ads come in fairly standardized sizes and formats, so they are a lot easier to create and distribute. Also, ad distribution technology has become very sophisticated in its ability to target the correct audience. By properly layering data from multiple online and offline sources, hyperlocal ad delivery is both cost-efficient and extremely accurate.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAdditionally, according to a survey from Solve Media<sup>1</sup>, only 14.3% of publishers are very likely to add a native advertising option. As a result, native advertising can cast a smaller net than other forms of online advertising. If you use a hyperlocal strategy for display and video, you&rsquo;ll reach a larger audience of qualified customers.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nNative ads can sometimes be <em>more</em> disruptive to users than traditional online advertisements. People are used to seeing display advertisements on the web, and they understand their purpose. But native is a relatively new format, and users are still adapting to it. If they&rsquo;re not done well, the ads can leave customers with a bad impression.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nFor example, the other day I was looking for funny posters on a blog. I had just seen a picture of a dog dressed as a banana when I noticed a video post. I clicked the video and watched for a few moments. I watched about a full minute before I noticed the &ldquo;Sponsored&rdquo; label in the upper left and realized that it wasn&rsquo;t going to be a humor video, but rather an ad for continuing education. This annoyed me because I expected it to be funny. If the advertisement had been ironic and had included a funny video of a cat, it would have made more sense in context (and I probably would have shared it with my friends). But instead, it just left me shaking my head.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOdds are good that as native advertisements become more prevalent, people will get used to them as they have display and video pre-roll. But between now and then, you run the risk of leaving a bad brand impression if your ad doesn&rsquo;t add to the experience of the publishing site.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIt takes a lot of time, effort, and money to do native advertising effectively. Native ads can&rsquo;t beat the scalability of online display and video advertising. While they offer a lot of promise, don&rsquo;t go dropping your other online and offline efforts just yet.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<sup>Sources:<br />\r\n1. <a href="http://paidcontent.org/2012/12/12/study-says-half-of-media-buyers-will-try-native-advertising-in-2013/" target="_blank">http://paidcontent.org/2012/12/12/study-says-half-of-media-buyers-will-try-native-advertising-in-2013/</a></sup></p>\r\n	t	2013-01-16 19:09:45	\N	2013-01-16 19:09:45	2013-09-04 15:16:48.537058	58	native advertising, sponsored stories, promoted tweets, MaxPoint
846	1	20	build-a-mobile-friendly-site-and-they-will-come	Build a Mobile-Friendly Site, and They Will Come	<p>The mobile revolution hit quickly, and it is necessary to be equally as quick to adapt your website, advertising, and apps for any number of devices&mdash;from smartphones to tablets&mdash;especially if you have a physical store location.</p>\r\n	<p>The mobile revolution hit quickly, and it is necessary to be equally as quick to adapt your website, advertising, and apps for any number of devices&mdash;from smartphones to tablets&mdash;especially if you have a physical store location. If mobile users can&rsquo;t find you easily, they may move on to a more user-friendly competitor. Nothing screams, &ldquo;I am stuck in the first decade of the Millennium&rdquo; like failing to have a mobile-friendly website. An app that is compatible with smartphones and tablets and that is relevant to your business can&rsquo;t hurt either.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAccording to a July 2012 survey of US adult smartphone Internet users conducted by market research and consulting firm <a href="http://www.smithgeiger.com/" target="_blank">SmithGeiger</a> and <a href="http://www.sterlingresearchgroup.com/" target="_blank">Sterling Research</a> on behalf of Google, about two-thirds of respondents said they were more likely to purchase something from a mobile-optimized site, while three-quarters said they were more likely to make a return visit to the site. That&rsquo;s pretty compelling data.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nConsumers&rsquo; desire for mobile-friendly sites stretched across pretty much all verticals, but its use was often closely tied to obtaining information about physical business locations. The first or second most important task identified by consumers in all industry categories was getting directions to a store or obtaining store hours. Of smartphone users, 74% named obtaining the location or operating hours of a physical store as their most important mobile retail task. That was followed by contacting the store (64%) and getting information about products (61%).<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIf that hasn&rsquo;t convinced you of the urgency in updating your website, Google found that failing to design sites for mobile had spillover effects, potentially damaging the reputation of the company. And consumers&rsquo; adoption of the mobile web is only going to continue. eMarketer projects that the number of US mobile Internet users will hit 198.8 million in 2016.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAnd, while you are upgrading your site, consider supercharging your mobile advertising as well. Sometimes advertisers try to be too clever with their creative, and they miss the basics. Since consumers in shopping mode are primarily using their mobile phones for getting directions and contacting the store, your mobile ad creative better include &ldquo;click to call&rdquo; with your store&rsquo;s phone number and &ldquo;click to map&rdquo; to help consumers find the location they are looking for. Don&rsquo;t miss the basics&mdash;start using mobile effectively to drive in-store traffic and sales.</p>\r\n	t	2013-01-04 17:16:52	\N	2013-01-04 17:16:52	2013-09-10 14:52:04.059402	59	mobile advertising, mobile devices, retailers, smartphones, mobile-friendly websites
754	1	15	event-recap-imedia-video-summit-2012	Event Recap: iMedia Video Summit 2012	<p>&ldquo;From bed to bus, from Los Angeles to New York, consumers are embracing all the various video platforms available to them.&rdquo; &ndash;iMedia Video Summit</p>\r\n	<p>&ldquo;From bed to bus, from Los Angeles to New York, consumers are embracing all the various video platforms available to them.&rdquo; &ndash;iMedia Video Summit<br />\r\n<br />\r\nLast week, MaxPoint headed to San Antonio, TX for the 2012 <a href="http://www.imediaconnection.com/summits/29955.asp" target="_blank">iMedia Video Summit</a>. The focus of the conference - bring awareness to the number of different topics trending in the video space right now, such as: online video measurement, the marriage of new media and old media, and the future of online content (content creators include Hulu, AOL, DBG and YouTube). <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nOnline video is hot in 2012 and attendees gathered from all over to discuss digital video consumption and how to execute smart content development. Notable companies represented at iMedia included iconic brands such as Macy&rsquo;s, True Value Hardware, H&amp;M, Dell, and Disney&hellip;to name a few. For 3 days, attendees enjoyed networking opportunities, high-caliber keynotes and speakers, breakout sessions and a variety of receptions and recreational activities.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nHere are some event highlights:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>The first day of panels involved the future of the video buying (the Upfronts) and a look at the future of technology and marketing. The panels discussed how by 2020 only 30% of video dollars will be going to online originated video content, and 70% will be going to broadcast&hellip;so, the integration of the traditional television business models with the digital business models are huge.</li>\r\n\t<li>Most attendees and expert panelists agreed that quality content is key and marketers are willing to pay for it.</li>\r\n\t<li