861	1	10	independent-retailers-dont-have-to-lose-the-local-marketing-arms-race	Independent Retailers Don’t Have to Lose the Local Marketing Arms Race	<p>The Shopper Technology Institute recently wrote a piece discussing how some large chains, such as CVS, Kroger, and Safeway, benefit from sophisticated brand-funded shopper marketing campaigns. The story, based on research from Kantar, suggests that these chains are becoming more aggressive and targeted in their reach to consumers by focusing primarily on personalization with an emphasis on &ldquo;delivering the right promotion to the right shopper at the right time and in the right place.&rdquo;</p>\r\n	<p>The Shopper Technology Institute <a href="http://www.shoppertech.org/lm032113.html" target="_blank">recently wrote a piece</a> discussing how some large chains, such as CVS, Kroger, and Safeway, benefit from sophisticated brand-funded shopper marketing campaigns. The story, based on research from Kantar, suggests that these chains are becoming more aggressive and targeted in their reach to consumers by focusing primarily on personalization with an emphasis on &ldquo;delivering the right promotion to the right shopper at the right time and in the right place.&rdquo;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe most robust loyalty card programs can track what consumers are buying, when they are buying it, and at which locations. As a result, retailers can target consumers with timely promotions, messages, and rewards while learning more about those shoppers&rsquo; interests to aid future personalized marketing efforts. These same insights are also very valuable to brands looking to sell their products in these stores.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAccording to the story, &ldquo;personalized marketing has proven its ability [to] drive increased basket size, increased shopping trips, and increased shopper retention over time. <strong>And if you&rsquo;re a top-tier retailer, you get all these benefits paid for by manufacturers funding those personalized promotions to your shoppers.</strong>&rdquo;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSo, what&rsquo;s a midsized or independent retailer to do? These retailers have neither the budget of the big guys, nor the same kind of sophisticated technology. Yet, they still need to push product and drive sales.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAdditionally, the Kantar report suggests that there will continue to be a &ldquo;more extensive collaboration between the retailer and brand, with a focus on clear objectives and performance accountability,&rdquo; a trend that clearly favors larger retail partners, especially those on which the brands have focused entire teams.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOf course, sophisticated loyalty programs are effective if you can afford them and have the resources. But equally as effective is investing shopper marketing dollars in <a href="http://maxpointinteractive.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/01/MI_SHOPPER_WEB_FINAL.pdf" target="_blank">hyperlocal digital advertising campaigns</a>. With limited budgets and a need to focus on consumers within a very tight radius, independent and midsized stores know that focus is key. What&rsquo;s more, they understand their target customers, where they live, and what they are interested in. Hyperlocal digital advertising allows them to target their ideal shoppers to drive traffic and in-store sales.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nFor instance, if an independent grocer is selling a new brand of gourmet coffee, it knows that not everyone who happens to live near the store is going to be interested. In addition to traditional advertising efforts, such as the weekly circular and local paper, the grocer can get more precise by creating a hyperlocal digital advertising campaign that focuses on shoppers ages 25&ndash;50 with an interest in more expensive coffee (maybe those without a hip cafe in the neighborhood).<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAnd to make the campaign immediately actionable, the grocer can leverage real-time interest data, such as which consumers are planning to shop within the next few hours (based on past habits and social media posts), which are looking for a local coffee shop, or which have disposable income. The campaign can go beyond simply raising awareness for the new brand by offering a coupon to incentivize consumers to come into the store and buy.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThat may sound just as difficult and expensive to pull off as the big guys&rsquo; sophisticated loyalty programs, but with a partner such as MaxPoint pulling all that data together and executing the program, both the brand and retailer can realize a big return for a relatively small investment.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe other advantage is that a digital campaign doesn&rsquo;t have to involve long-term planning. In cases when a retailer is carrying an abundance of a brand&rsquo;s product that needs to move before it expires or becomes irrelevant (think turkeys at Thanksgiving or champagne at New Year&rsquo;s), the retailer can activate a campaign within hours to help drive sales at the specific locations where it has excess inventory.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe truth is that independent and midsized retailers have a lot to offer the communities they serve. They can compete fiercely against the larger, national chains not by using the same tactics as the largest brands and retailers, but rather by teaming up with partners that focus on targeted, locally focused campaigns.</p>\r\n	t	2013-04-26 14:12:32	\N	2013-04-26 14:12:32	2013-09-04 13:47:23.183149	49	Shopper Technology Institute, personalized marketing, hyperlocal advertising, shopper marketing
862	1	15	mobile-geofencing-an-advertising-trap	Mobile Geofencing—An Advertising Trap?	<p>By now, many in the advertising industry are familiar with the term mobile geofencing, or a retailer&rsquo;s ability to target shoppers passing near its store by establishing a very narrow advertising radius (often just a few feet). Each time a consumer who has downloaded a store&rsquo;s app on their GPS-enabled mobile device enters this tight perimeter, they receive a mobile alert with a special offer from that business.</p>\r\n	<p>By now, many in the advertising industry are familiar with the term mobile geofencing, or a retailer&rsquo;s ability to target shoppers passing near its store by establishing a very narrow advertising radius (often just a few feet). Each time a consumer who has downloaded a store&rsquo;s app on their GPS-enabled mobile device enters this tight perimeter, they receive a mobile alert with a special offer from that business.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSounds brilliant, right? In theory, mobile geofencing is a smart way to reach a handful of shoppers when they are in the immediate area. But if you want to reach a large enough crowd of shoppers that really makes an impact on your business, then geofencing falls short. Some of its flaws include:<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>Lack of meaningful targeting. </strong>An effective advertising campaign draws the consumer in with messaging that speaks to their interests. Perhaps the shopper is a first-time mom in the market for her first SUV/minivan. Or maybe she&rsquo;s a local college student looking for a cool place to hang with her friends when she is home on break. An effective advertising campaign targets its message and call to action to a specific, well-defined audience&mdash;not just shoppers who happen to walk by a place of business.<br />\r\n\t<br />\r\n\tA geofencing advertising campaign, however, may not allow an advertiser to communicate in a way that&rsquo;s meaningful to a specific consumer. Rather, geofencing generally takes the &ldquo;you are in the area, you must care&rdquo; approach, which is ineffective for most campaigns. To be fair, some geofencing solutions are starting to address this by targeting both location and demographics, but it&rsquo;s important to remember that effective and meaningful targeting takes into consideration where consumers come from, not just where they are at the moment.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ul><br />\r\n\t<li><strong>Tracking can make consumers uncomfortable.</strong> Even though geofencing requires that consumers opt in, many users may not understand the full ramifications. By opting in, consumers allow advertisers to track their every move. Although advertising becomes more effective when it takes into consideration more consumer information, there are some things that people do not want to share&mdash;like how often they visit the doctor&rsquo;s office, where their child goes to preschool each day, or how many times they visit their favorite bar each week. Do you want someone to know every time you leave the house?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>Scale is missing.</strong> Geofencing focuses on a very tight radius, making it hard to scale a campaign. You can reach only a handful of consumers traveling within a limited area. By casting such a small net, geofencing limits the ability of mobile ads to generate long-term, sustainable growth and customer return.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nSo is there a better way? Yes. A hyperlocal digital or mobile campaign works much better. Geofencing targets customers when they&rsquo;re in the vicinity of the store, but how do you drive them there in the first place? A hyperlocal digital campaign helps you target crowds, rather than a handful, of ideal customers. Hyperlocal advertising goes beyond geofencing, ultimately allowing you to reach local neighborhoods full of shoppers likely to buy your products and services. In the long run, this strategy of reaching the right people at the right time with the right offer combines the precise targeting you need with the scale missing from geofencing.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMobile advertising must go beyond targeting shoppers simply because they&rsquo;re within a few feet of a business. There are many tools and technologies available today that empower advertisers to be very precise and focused while also reaching many qualified shoppers.</p>\r\n	t	2013-05-03 19:49:41	\N	2013-05-03 19:49:41	2013-10-15 13:24:07.964645	59	mobile, geofencing, advertising
856	1	15	is-big-data-a-big-deal	Is Big Data a Big Deal?	<p>By now, anyone not living under a rock has heard the term <em>big data</em>. It&rsquo;s a constant topic of debate within the business, technology, and even mainstream press, and it is starting to gain some traction in verticals like marketing, banking, retail, and human resources.</p>\r\n	<p>By now, anyone not living under a rock has heard the term <em>big data</em>. It&rsquo;s a constant topic of debate within the business, technology, and even mainstream press, and it is starting to gain some traction in verticals like marketing, banking, retail, and human resources.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nFor marketers, big data enables a more holistic view of customers, creating a unified view of all online and offline behaviors: Where do customers shop? What brands do they buy? What level of influence do they have on their friends&rsquo; purchasing decisions because they share on social media? Many companies now even have a unique and personalized docket of preferences for each customer&mdash;a gold mine for understanding what customers really want.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nA <a href="http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424127887324178904578340071261396666.html?mod=WSJ_Tech_LEADTop" target="_blank">recent <em>Wall Street Journal</em> article</a> provided a great example of how Intercontinental Hotels created a highly customized communication targeted at its Priority Club Rewards members. When referring to Intercontinental&rsquo;s new email marketing programs, the piece said, &ldquo;Where previous campaigns might have on average seven to 15 customized marketing messages, the new campaign has 1,552. The messages are rolled out in stages to an initial core of 12 customer groups, each of which is defined by 4,000 attributes.&rdquo; In the end, the new campaign generated a 35% higher conversion rate than previous campaigns.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIt may seem obvious that getting smarter about what your customers want is a more effective way to reach them, but thousands of marketing campaigns are executed every day that lack the precision that big data offers.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nNow just imagine how much more precise big data can make a marketing campaign when you&rsquo;re trying to go hyperlocal.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nNo longer do retailers and brands have to spend the time and money to roll out national campaigns to every neighborhood in the country. Instead, big data helps them understand where likely buyers actually live&mdash;all the way down to the neighborhood level&mdash;so they can effectively target that group based on preferences, purchase history, and social media tendencies. This is a radically different approach from the way national advertising campaigns used to run. Now, advertisers can run the big ad on a major network for brand exposure but then scale the campaign down to specifically target the neighborhoods in the central part of Michigan or the western part of New York, for example, where shoppers are most likely to respond to the call to action.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAs big data strategies and practices continue to evolve, marketing campaigns will only get smarter and more effective. So if you don&rsquo;t think big data is a big deal yet, just wait until your favorite hotel tells you that they know you are ready to take a vacation, just as you&rsquo;re thinking it yourself.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<em>Is your company using big data in its advertising? Tell us how below.</em></p>\r\n	t	2013-03-21 19:54:10	\N	2013-03-21 19:54:10	2013-09-04 14:55:02.552987	58	big data, digital advertising, hyperlocal advertising
860	1	15	real-time-or-bust-why-anything-short-of-real-time-in-digital-advertising-will-soon-be-passe	Real Time or Bust: Why Anything Short of Real Time in Digital Advertising Will Soon Be Passé	<p>We&rsquo;ve been talking for some time about how important real-time information is when it comes to building and executing an effective digital advertising strategy. Having insight into constantly changing consumer behaviors and how current events like the flu season are affecting buying decisions gives retailers and brands the ability to act quickly and to cater their campaigns to push supply that meets demand.</p>\r\n	<p>We&rsquo;ve been talking for some time about how important real-time information is when it comes to building and executing an effective digital advertising strategy. Having insight into constantly changing consumer behaviors and how current events like the <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/online-advertising-news/most-concerned-cities-about-flu" target="_blank">flu season</a> are affecting buying decisions gives retailers and brands the ability to act quickly and to cater their campaigns to push supply that meets demand.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nRecently, <em>Adweek</em> <a href="http://www.adweek.com/news/technology/brands-buy-real-time-mobile-ads-based-weather-148430" target="_blank">ran a piece</a> on how many retailers are tailoring their digital campaigns around factors like weather patterns. These retailers have found that contextual ads are quite effective when they encourage a consumer to take action based on the weather. For instance, ACE Hardware has started to use real-time mobile ads to target consumers with deals on shovels and de-icers in advance of big snowstorms. They plan to do the same this spring by targeting consumers with fertilizer brands and other garden products when the weather is prime for planting and maintaining one&rsquo;s yard.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThis strategy seems obvious, yet smart. The examples shared in <em>Adweek</em> just scratch the surface when it comes to where the market is going and what brands and retailers are already doing to drive real-time interest and sales. At MaxPoint, we&rsquo;ve built our business around empowering brands and retailers to target consumers with the right product at the right time, regardless of which digital medium consumers prefer.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nFor example:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>Let&rsquo;s say you run a large grocery store chain. Your store in downtown Akron, Ohio, has a surplus of holiday Pop-Tarts, and there are just seven days until Christmas. Why not target consumers within an eight-mile radius who are likely to buy Pop-Tarts (young kids, college students) with a special offer to drive traffic and demand at your store?</li>\r\n\t<li>Or perhaps your vodka brand is introducing a new flavor and would like to target consumers within a 10-mile radius of a liquor store who score highly for an interest in holiday cocktails.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nMaxPoint can identify hot spots of real-time interest and align that data with key demographics and physical locations to roll out a campaign that captures your audience when they are in the buying mind.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWith information flowing so fast and furious, and billions of data points on consumer behavior and preferences being created every day, there is no question that real-time advertising is the real deal. We will soon live in a world where traditional advertising campaigns planned well in advance of their flights will fall by the wayside.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAdvertisers are getting smarter and quicker. Are you keeping up?</p>\r\n	t	2013-04-19 19:05:28	\N	2013-04-19 19:05:28	2013-09-04 13:51:14.08592	58	big data, digital advertising, Adweek, contextual ads
844	1	15	get-last-minute-shoppers-by-going-online-with-your-advertising	Get Last-Minute Shoppers by Going Online with Your Advertising	<p>If you haven&rsquo;t started or still need to ramp up your holiday advertising, then going online with your ads is the smartest move you can make.</p>\r\n	<p>The clock is ticking on the holiday season. There are just a few more weeks until the big day is here. The Christmas music has been playing since November, or in some places even before the last Halloween candy hit the bottom of the bag, and people are in the mood to look for the perfect gift. With few shopping days, and even fewer shipping days, until Christmas, a targeted online advertising campaign can bring those last-minute shoppers right through your doors.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIf you haven&rsquo;t started or still need to ramp up your holiday advertising, then going online with your ads is the smartest move you can make. Here&rsquo;s why:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>Start Running a Campaign in a Single Day. You don&rsquo;t have to wait days or weeks to get your campaign up and running like you do with print ads. It can often take as little as 24 hours to start getting your message in front of targeted customers. And with fewer shopping days until Christmas, every moment counts.</li>\r\n\t<li>Make Inventory Changes Quickly. If you have a particularly hot item or special deal that you want to highlight, then you can make changes to your existing advertising materials mid-campaign. Unlike a print ad, you can easily update your online campaign without a ton of time or money.</li>\r\n\t<li>Reach People Where They Are. Consumers are increasingly going online for their entertainment. According to Forrester Research data cited in the Barclays Capital Internet Data Book, online has become the primary medium for people between 18 and 54. And with the added targeting power that an online campaign offers, you know you&rsquo;re reaching the right people.</li>\r\n\t<li>Save Money by Reusing Previously Successful Holiday Advertising Materials. If you ran a campaign last year that was particularly effective, then there&rsquo;s no reason you can&rsquo;t have the same kind of windfall this year.</li>\r\n\t<li>Complement Your Other Advertising Methods. Of course, online ads don&rsquo;t completely replace traditional advertising methods. But by running an online campaign in combination with more traditional advertising methods, you can increase your exposure and make both methods more effective.</li>\r\n\t<li>Take Advantage of Mobile. Mobile is growing rapidly and offers a few added benefits over other forms of advertising. With mobile ads, you can reach your customers wherever they are: in-between meetings at work, traveling on the bus or train, or even relaxing at home in the evening. And you can often use your other online display ads for mobile.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nThe window for holiday shopping is closing. Although some shoppers may buy online, many last-minute shoppers will have to step into local stores to avoid late deliveries of their gifts. A well-executed online campaign can help keep you top of mind and drive customers into your store this holiday season.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nFor tips and tricks on how to improve your holiday advertising, take a look at our <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/advertising-tips-and-strategies/advertising-guides-and-reports/guide-to-holiday-advertising" target="_blank">Guide to Holiday Advertising</a>.</p>\r\n	t	2012-12-11 15:27:43	\N	2012-12-11 15:27:43	2013-09-12 12:16:09.890814	59	holiday advertising, hyperlocal targeting, mobile advertising, MaxPoint Interactive
859	1	15	a-practical-take-on-glocal-advertising	A Practical Take on “Glocal” Advertising	<p><em>Harvard Business Review</em> recently ran a piece that looked at how global brands (or those striving to be so) must look at advertising through a new lens: the so-called<em> glocal </em>lens. Translation: a combination of <em>global</em> and <em>local</em> meaning &ldquo;locally adapting a universally embraced core idea that will resonate in any market anywhere in the world.&rdquo;</p>\r\n	<p><em>Harvard Business Review</em> recently <a href="http://blogs.hbr.org/cs/2013/03/great_advertising_is_both_loca.html" target="_blank">ran a piece</a> that looked at how global brands (or those striving to be so) must look at advertising through a new lens: the so-called<em> glocal </em>lens. Translation: a combination of <em>global</em> and <em>local</em> meaning &ldquo;locally adapting a universally embraced core idea that will resonate in any market anywhere in the world.&rdquo;<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Glocal Strategy</strong><br />\r\nThe authors of the piece&mdash;Jerry Wind (professor of marketing at the Wharton School), Stan Sthanunathan (vice president of marketing strategy and insights at the Coca-Cola Company), and Rob Malcolm (former president of global marketing at Diageo)&mdash;shared some interesting insights about brands&rsquo; successful and failed endeavors to appeal to a global audience. They said that a successful glocal strategy rests on three pillars:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n\t<li>A global concept that addresses a universal human motivation</li>\r\n\t<li>A unified brand vision with creative delivery that respects local nuances and empowered consumers in each locale</li>\r\n\t<li>An organizational architecture, including culture, technological platform, and dedicated resources, that emphasizes and facilitates dynamic and effective collaboration between the developers of global strategy and local strategists and implementers</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nThe authors note the importance of starting with a theme that appeals to a global audience but that also includes elements that would appeal to the local audiences that will see and hear the campaign. It is important to appeal to the subset of consumers and potential customers within each market. They say that the framework respects and encourages local decision-making while at the same time supporting a unified brand identity. Moreover, the organizational architecture aims to tap into the best ideas and talent, no matter where in the world they come from; this fluid process lets more innovative ideas get recognized and become the basis for a global strategy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If done strategically and with the right mix of creative and branding elements, this approach is highly successful. Brands like Coca-Cola and Johnnie Walker are just a few that have executed a glocal strategy successfully.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Nlocal Strategy</strong><br />\r\nWhat&rsquo;s more, the authors say that glocal is not strictly for global brands. With so many omniculturals (people who define themselves by their lifestyles and economic and educational attainment more so than by their race or ethnicity) living in the United States, this same approach can work at the national level. This is something we at MaxPoint have been talking about for some time. We have a unique way to identify omniculturals using our Digital Zip&reg; technology, which analyzes billions of data points for neighborhoods across the United States. Once we&rsquo;ve considered offline point-of-sale data as well as shoppers&rsquo; consumption of social media, videos, music, local Web pages, and online magazines (to name just a few), we can run digital ads for our clients targeted to the right omniculturals at the neighborhood level.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOur nlocal (national and local) approach not only allows national brands to target the right neighborhoods with the right message at the right time but also eliminates wasteful spending often associated with local marketing and advertising campaigns. We work with a lot of brands to help them repurpose their assets from a national campaign and apply them to a local market in a meaningful way.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWe strongly believe that more retailers and brands have to start thinking glocal and nlocal as they build their branding and advertising campaigns. The technology is in place to make these approaches seamless, successful, and scalable.</p>\r\n	t	2013-04-11 20:05:56	\N	2013-04-11 20:05:56	2013-09-04 13:52:05.20643	58	glocal, nlocal, local advertising, omniculturals
857	1	15	ad-age-talks-big-data	Ad Age Talks Big Data	<p>We&rsquo;ve talked a lot about big data on this blog and the impact it has on smarter and more effective digital advertising. Recently, <em>Advertising Age</em> dedicated a section of its print issue to the topic and shared a number of interesting insights.</p>\r\n	<p>We&rsquo;ve <a href="http://staging.maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/onpoint-blog/2013/3/21/is-big-data-a-big-deal" target="_blank">talked a lot about big data on this blog</a> and the impact it has on smarter and more effective digital advertising. Recently, <em>Advertising Age</em> dedicated <a href="http://adage.com/archive-date?pub=11&amp;vol=84" target="_blank">a section of its print issue</a> to the topic and shared a number of interesting insights.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe series of stories looked at the big data revolution from all angles. Is big data too Big Brother? Is the amount of data growing too quickly for advertisers to keep up with? Is big data really effective in advertising, or is it just a bunch of relatively random guesses based on previous online purchasing and browsing behaviors? Or, have some companies mastered a big data strategy, and do they hold the keys to the kingdom?<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe answer is yes and no to all the above. We&rsquo;ve extracted some interesting pieces from the stories in <em>Ad Age</em> to paint a picture of where the big data industry appears to be today&mdash;at least as it concerns the advertising world.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Data Hoarding</strong><br />\r\nIn her story &ldquo;<a href="http://adage.com/article/data-at-work/data-war-dispatch-turning-data-crude-real-revenue/240358/" target="_blank">Data War Dispatch: Turning Data Crude Into Real Revenue</a>,&rdquo; Kate Kaye wrote that &ldquo;data commoditization is a concern for the new crop of information merchants. . . . Brands are especially averse to the risk of competitors accessing their information. It&#39;s no wonder large retailers and product brands keep the bulk of their customer data locked in secure servers housed in the Fort Knox-esque facilities of data firms such as Acxiom, like so much gold bullion.&rdquo;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAlthough some retailers do opt for a more holistic view of data via data firm APIs, many are still wary of granting too much access. As a result, these retailers run the risk of missing out on more effective and precise ways of reaching customers and prospects. The one-dimensional (although very rich) data they have tells just a part of the story of consumer behavior and preferences. Because this hoarding mentality is hurting many large retailers, it&rsquo;s critical that they look beyond their fears to incorporate a broader digital data strategy.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>The Data Lifecycle</strong><br />\r\nOne of the most interesting elements of the big data issue was an <a href="http://adage.com/article/dataworks/purchase-targeted-ads-data-s/240300/" target="_blank">infographic</a> that showed the lifecycle of data associated with a single purchase. It was a compelling illustration of how one purchase sets off a chain reaction of data discovery and consumer intelligence inventory.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Standalone Data Management Platforms</strong><br />\r\nIt was Jack Neff&rsquo;s piece, however, that resonated with us the most. He discussed the trends that we are seeing within our own customer base of large brands. In his piece, &ldquo;<a href="http://adage.com/article/data-at-work/package-goods-marketers-build-private-trading-desks/240374/" target="_blank">Package-Goods Marketers Build Private Trading Desks to Hoard Data</a>,&rdquo; Neff describes how some large brands, such as Kellogg, Unilever, and Kimberly-Clark, are moving toward a model of creating their own standalone data management platforms and trading desks. This is an effort to reduce expenses associated with large multiclient trading desks and to avoid tying up data and insights in an agency-owned system that the brand may not be able to access in the future.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nYet, Forrester Research believes this approach is still rare. In a 2012 Forrester survey, the company found that although a quarter of marketers say they use agency trading desks, only 7% report using in-house trading desks.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&ldquo;My sense is that ultimately a lot of marketers aren&#39;t really set up to take execution fully in-house when they have traditionally been so reliant on external support,&quot; said Forrester analyst Joanna O&#39;Connell.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>The Endgame</strong><br />\r\nThe net/net here is that there is still a lot of shifting going on in the advertising industry when it comes to the most effective and nonintrusive way to use big data. The way brands and retailers attack a big data strategy may differ greatly, but the endgame is to provide a more successful way to reach customers and drive additional revenue.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIf you haven&rsquo;t had a chance to check out <a href="http://adage.com/archive-date?pub=11&amp;vol=84" target="_blank"><em>Ad Age</em>&#39;s big data issue</a>, and you are interested in how big data may work for your organization, it&rsquo;s a worthy read. The issue contains insights from retailers and brands that have found ways to use big data successfully to improve their understanding of customer segments, effective marketing tactics, and the quickest path to success.</p>\r\n	t	2013-03-29 13:43:43	\N	2013-03-29 13:43:43	2013-09-04 14:54:01.814104	58	Advertising Age, big data, data hoarding
858	1	10	hiding-ads-wont-cure-banner-blindness	Hiding Ads Won’t Cure Banner Blindness	<p>One of the biggest criticisms of digital advertising has long been that there are just so many irrelevant ads that consumers have developed &ldquo;banner blindness.&rdquo; One solution to banner blindness that the industry is currently buzzing about is native advertising.</p>\r\n	<p>One of the biggest criticisms of digital advertising has long been that there are just so many irrelevant ads that consumers have developed &ldquo;banner blindness.&rdquo; One solution to banner blindness that the industry is currently buzzing about is native advertising.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAccording to an <a href="http://allthingsd.com/20130320/whats-all-the-hype-about-native-ads-anyway-looking-beyond-the-buzzword/" target="_blank">article in the <em>Wall Street Journal</em>&rsquo;s AllThingsD</a>, &ldquo;Native ads are paid experiences that are complementary to the platform and content in which they are presented.&rdquo; For instance, if you are reading a publication like the <em>Huffington Post</em>, you may not realize that one of the articles in the sidebar column (which may or may not relate to the main topic on that page) is a sponsored article. In essence, native advertising is an endorsement or ad disguised as content.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOf course, not everyone is a fan. In an article he penned for Digiday, Ben Kunz of media agency Mediassociates <a href="http://www.digiday.com/publishers/native-advertising-is-bad-news/" target="_blank">took this aggressive stance</a> on native advertising:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Native advertising is a more insidious encroachment into consumer media content than any prior form of advertising. Billions of banner ad impressions may annoy readers, but they don&rsquo;t misdirect users by disguising the source of the message &mdash; and this is exactly what native does. If publishers and marketers aren&rsquo;t careful, they are going to poison the well of digital ad communications by breaking consumer trust.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And beyond whether or not native ads are deceitful, this form of digital advertising simply doesn&rsquo;t solve for the real cause of banner blindness: hundreds and thousands of irrelevant ads appear before consumers on a daily basis. After a while, consumers stop looking at the ads altogether because they just don&rsquo;t speak to their needs and interests&mdash;no matter if they&rsquo;re buried in content they like or if they take over the whole screen.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe best digital advertising has focus and is effectively targeted. If you know what a consumer needs or is interested in, you can speak her language and grab her attention in much the same way that she responds to the sound of her name, even if it&rsquo;s on the lips of a mother addressing her child of the same name in the grocery store. That&rsquo;s the kind of digital advertising that drives store traffic and increases sales.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nBut to get there, you need rich consumer data sources and advanced technology. Sneakily concealing an ad doesn&rsquo;t make it more precise. It just makes it harder to identify as an ad and gives consumers one more reason to lose trust in advertisers and publishers.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nBanner blindness? It&rsquo;s a real problem that native ads simply can&rsquo;t solve.</p>\r\n	t	2013-04-04 15:17:08	\N	2013-04-04 15:17:08	2013-09-04 13:53:08.181215	58	 digital advertising, hyperlocal advertising, native advertising, banner blindness
865	1	37	perhaps-cookies-might-not-be-so-sweet	Perhaps Cookies Might Not Be So Sweet	<p>Much of Internet advertising builds upon the basic foundation of cookies&mdash;but are they really enough?</p>\r\n	<p>Much of Internet advertising builds upon the basic foundation of cookies&mdash;but are they really enough?</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="Cookies" src="/system/editor/W1siZiIsIjIwMTMvMDcvMTUvMTJfMTRfNDRfODE3X2lTdG9ja18wMDAwMDg5MTI4NjFYU21hbGxfQ29va2llcy5qcGciXSxbInAiLCJ0aHVtYiIsIjgwMHg4MDA%2BIl1d/iStock_000008912861XSmall_Cookies.jpg" style="float:left; height:186px; width:171px" />To begin with, what do these small files, which are downloaded to a person&rsquo;s computer when they visit a website and contain personal information about a user&rsquo;s web behavior or web history, actually do? Well, they can enhance a user&rsquo;s experience with a website or make their lives easier&mdash;for instance, you can thank cookies for the ability to stay logged in to an application, so you don&rsquo;t have to keep entering your username and password every time. They help site publishers and web applications deliver a more personalized experience for their customers. And cookies are so ubiquitous on the web that many people don&rsquo;t even know when they&rsquo;re on their devices.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But cookies aren&rsquo;t just for users&mdash;cookies are also used for digital advertising targeting (or re-targeting). When used well, they can help advertisers reach some very targeted customers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ultimately, cookies are powerful and they have their uses. But cookie targeting does have its limitations. Here are just a few to consider:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>Cookies Bring Privacy Concerns&mdash;</strong>If there&rsquo;s a privacy concern on a website, chances are good that cookies are involved. While cookie data usually are anonymized, they still bring some privacy concerns. In fact, some industries, especially the pharmaceutical and health care industries, almost completely shy away from the use of cookies.<br />\r\n\t&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>Cookies Don&rsquo;t Work Well on Mobile&mdash;</strong>Many mobile devices won&rsquo;t accept third-party cookies unless a user explicitly enables them in their device settings. This limits the mobile audience dramatically. To truly target a large number of users on mobile devices, you have to go with another option such as geofencing or neighborhood-level targeting. (In fact, this isn&rsquo;t unique to mobile&mdash;it&rsquo;s more of a web browser setting. Safari doesn&rsquo;t accept third-party cookies by default, and other browsers are following Safari&rsquo;s precedent. So, this means that the audience that can be reached via cookies will continue to dwindle).<br />\r\n\t&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>Cookies Don&rsquo;t Reach Enough People&mdash;</strong>You simply can&rsquo;t get enough volume by trying to reach people via cookies. Many web users turn off cookies on their computers, making it impossible to reach them. Among those who accept cookies, many delete them on a regular basis. In fact, according to a 2012 comScore study, &ldquo;about 30% of computers have their ad-server cookies deleted in a month, with a frequency of 4+ times per month.&rdquo;<a href="#_ftn1" name="_ftnref1" title="">[1]</a> Between the number of people who don&rsquo;t accept cookies and the number of people who frequently delete them, advertisers can find it challenging to reach the number of customers that they need to reach to really move cases of products, rather than just a handful.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Do I mean to say that cookies are never helpful? No. They can be great additions to campaigns&mdash;for those users who accept and keep third-party cookies, they help advertisers target them with precisely relevant ads. However, when using cookies, be careful to make sure you give some indication to the users that you are using cookies, and give them the additional ability to opt out or turn them off. This can be covered in your ad delivery vendor&rsquo;s privacy policy or terms of use. If you are unsure whether or not you have adequately disclosed the use of cookies, ask your delivery vendor.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The truth is that cookies can help, but you shouldn&rsquo;t base your entire ad campaign around them. Your better bet is to focus on a hyperlocal digital campaign that targets users on a neighborhood level. Hyperlocal targeting that&rsquo;s not reliant on cookies can help advertisers reach multiple times the number of customers&mdash;and it does so without the privacy concerns.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="#_ftnref1" name="_ftn1" title="">[1]</a> <a href="http://www.comscore.com/Insights/Blog/When_the_Cookie_Crumbles" target="_blank">http://www.comscore.com/Insights/Blog/When_the_Cookie_Crumbles</a></p>\r\n	t	2013-07-08 17:27:58	\N	2013-07-08 17:36:31.452774	2013-11-01 21:32:21.479944	52	\N
757	1	15	walmart-target-kmart-kohls-50-years-of-retail-success	Walmart,Target, Kmart, and Kohl's: 50 Years of Retail Success 	<p>In 2012, Walmart, Target, Kmart, and Kohl&rsquo;s all turn 50 (Happy Birthday!). Below is a look back at the strides these retailers have made including details on how they continue to drive brand awareness and excellence.</p>\r\n	<p>Not only is 2012 a big year in terms of new technology launches and strides in the digital advertising industry, but it&rsquo;s a&nbsp; big year&nbsp; for four important retailers: Walmart, Target, Kmart, and Kohl&rsquo;s.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn 2012, Walmart, Target, Kmart, and Kohl&rsquo;s all turn 50 (Happy Birthday!). Below is a look back at the strides these retailers have made including details on how they continue to drive brand awareness and excellence.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Walmart:</strong> When Walmart was first introduced into the retail landscape, the retailer ran with the tagline, &ldquo;Walmart &ndash; always the low prices on the brands you trust.&nbsp; Always.&rdquo; Since then, Walmart has continued to stick true to this promise as they have unveiled similar campaigns such as the famous &ldquo;Rollback&rdquo; and &ldquo;Save money. Live better.&rdquo; campaigns.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhat makes Walmart so popular is that they listened to their customer&rsquo;s needs and understood the importance of a budget-friendly and seamless shopping experience. In 2012, the retailer continues to leverage digital advertising and in-store displays to get this message across to both current customers and new Walmart shoppers.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Target:</strong> Similar to the other retailers turning 50, Target too focuses on being budget-friendly with their famous tagline, &ldquo;Expect more. Pay Less.&rdquo;&nbsp; However, it&rsquo;s not necessarily the price that drives shoppers to Target but the way Target engages with shoppers in-store.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nLike many retailers, Target recognizes the importance of an engaging in-store experience. For example, Target uses advertising and in-store messaging to give shoppers tips on what to wear &ndash; first introduced in 1990 with the &ldquo;What to Wear&rdquo; campaign.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Kmart:</strong> Kmart has certainly had its ups and downs over the years but will always be known for its partnerships with Jaclyn Smith (to launch its apparel business) and Martha Stewart (a spokesperson for the brand in past years).<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWho will Kmart partner with next? That remains to be seen, but using celebrities to get in front of shoppers is a great way to drive traffic and awareness around a brand.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Kohl&rsquo;s:</strong> A coast-to-coast retailer, Kohl&rsquo;s also focuses on budget-friendliness, engaging in-store experiences and partnerships with famous celebrities. However, what has set aside Kohl&rsquo;s from other retailers is its ability to market to the teenage consumer group.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nTeenagers for the most part are &ldquo;fashionistas,&rdquo; always concerned with staying on top of the latest fashion trends and taking advice from fashion icons. Kohl&rsquo;s has partnered with various teen icons, such as, J. Lo and American Idol, as well as, tailored campaigns with messaging specifically targeted towards the teenage shopper.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSo, what can you take away from this? Listen to your customer, focus on an engaging in-store experience, and leverage resources (e.g. celebrity partnerships) to get in front of a specific audience. However, these are only some elements that make a strong marketing campaign. Combine these tactics with digital advertising, specifically, localized digital advertising to make sure your message and offers are seen by the right audience to continue to drive in-store traffic and retailing success.</p>\r\n	t	2012-04-11 14:37:16	\N	2012-04-11 14:37:16	2013-09-27 03:08:13.076409	49	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint