755	1	15	online-video-rtb-what-to-know-before-you-bid	Online Video RTB: What to Know Before You Bid 	<p>According to recent comScore Video Metrix service report, &ldquo;179 million U.S. Internet users watched nearly 38 billion online videos in February alone. Online video consumption is rapidly growing and advertisers are realizing the incredible reach this medium presents.</p>\r\n	<p>According to recent comScore Video Metrix service report, &ldquo;179 million U.S. Internet users watched nearly 38 billion online videos in February alone. Online video consumption is rapidly growing and advertisers are realizing the incredible reach this medium presents. <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe reason for this growth is three-fold: Publishers have taken advantage of the reduction in shooting and editing costs; viewers have responded by consuming 200+ videos per month across thousands of sites; and marketers are fueling demand by investing in the emerging format. And, as interest around online video grows, so has the real-time bidding (RTB) market.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhy? Both media buyers and publishers are becoming more comfortable with the process, as buyers on the exchange are using more advanced technology to take on more bids at a faster pace than before. This is great news because it is important for buyers to fully understand how they can make the most effective real-time bids for their brand. According to our Director of New Media, Chris Grech, &ldquo;Thus, savvy marketers need to treat this small but valuable marketing element carefully to maximize ROI by taking the following points into consideration as they plan their campaigns:&rdquo;<span id="cke_bm_99C" style="display:none">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>Reach the audience that matters most.</strong> Don&rsquo;t waste the time and money spent to create your video advertisement on the wrong online audience. Leverage data pulled from both on and offline data sets (such as point of sale, social media, videos, local web pages, music, and online magazines) to reach the right audience.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Remember this is a contextual environment.</strong> Work with a buyer to understand the content of the video your ad will be running with. Make sure the video content is not negative or does not contain information you would not want associated with your brand.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Remember the 80/20 rule.</strong> The majority of sales come from a fraction of stores, products or services and marketers are already maximizing broadcast, print and online advertising efforts. Use online video bids to deliver messaging to the most loyal consumers to increase purchase frequency.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nAs online video and the real-time bidding market continues to grow, marketers need to compile real, actionable data to create campaigns that complement offline efforts and reach the right online audience with messaging that motivates consumers to head in-store and make an offline purchase. For more on online video solutions, click <a href="http://www.maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-solutions" target="_blank">here</a>.</p>\r\n	t	2012-04-06 14:42:15	\N	2012-04-06 14:42:15	2013-09-27 03:12:12.163756	51	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, real-time bidding, rtb, campaigns, online video 
658	1	15	retailers-tips-to-keep-your-shoppers-in-store-longer	Retailers: Tips to Keep Your Shoppers In-Store Longer	<p>It&rsquo;s no secret that consumers are researching products and deals online before heading to the store. By 2014, the web will be influencing $1.4 billion worth of in-store sales, according to Forrester Research. And, about 62% of shoppers say they search for deals online for at least half of their shopping trip, according to a survey by Booz &amp; Co. and the Grocery Manufacturers Association.</p>\r\n	<p>It&rsquo;s no secret that consumers are researching products and deals online before heading to the store. By 2014, the web will be influencing $1.4 billion worth of in-store sales, according to Forrester Research. And, about 62% of shoppers say they search for deals online for at least half of their shopping trip, according to a survey by Booz &amp; Co. and the Grocery Manufacturers Association. <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nIf consumers are taking the time to research online, then imagine the time they&rsquo;ll invest shopping once they get to the stores. So this leads me to ask, what can stores do to keep these shoppers in their stores longer and lead to more purchases? Check out some of our tips below.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Offer Plenty of Shopping Carts and Baskets</strong><br />\r\nIt may seem like the obvious, but carts and baskets can slow customers down and keep them in the store longer. And, they can help increase the amount of products customers buy. Even if stores are small, they should still offer some type of basket or bag to help carry their items &ndash; customers can only fill their arms so much but a basket offers so much more room for products.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Surprise Customers</strong><br />\r\nThese days, retailers need to get creative and design their stores in a way that confronts shoppers with items that pique their interest and keep them browsing. For example, in Urban Outfitters, a shopper may come across a stack of new books while shopping for pants. Displaying signs throughout the store to advertise special deals may also help direct customers to new areas and shop longer.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Hire Great Staff</strong><br />\r\nA welcoming staff will make customers feel good and believe it or not, will help them stay longer. The key is to make sure all customers are treated the same and given equal attention whether they buy or not. Stores like Trader Joe&rsquo;s have staff walking around carrying a giant question mark so customers know where to go for questions. And Apple, has a special Genius Bar featuring experts to handle tech support and offer opinions on gadget needs.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Make Customers Comfortable</strong><br />\r\nIf customers walk into your store carrying extra bags or heavy coats, store associates should offer to put some of those items aside while they shop. This will help make customers comfortable and have free arms to buy products off shelves or racks. Stores should also consider creating a safe play area for children to help with their family shoppers.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>In-Store Demonstrations and Videos</strong><br />\r\nWhether it be a video lesson or an in-store demonstration of a new product, both tactics will help keep shoppers in stores longer. For example, Williams-Sonoma hosts cooking classes in stores, and Guitar Center offers weekly recording lessons for customers. Small businesses, like a beauty store, can even have a makeup artist come in to show customers new makeup products while they shop.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Engage Consumers&rsquo; Senses</strong><br />\r\nFree food samples, live music, light aroma sprays, and product demos can entice customers and keep them in the spending mood. Some stores refer to companies like ScentAir Technologies to spray aromas in various parts of their stores. For example, the infant apparel section may get the baby powder scent, and a swimwear section may be filled with the scent of coconut.</p>\r\n	t	2011-09-20 15:29:37	\N	2011-09-20 15:29:37	2013-08-28 16:50:12.470597	49	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, retail, Alicia Johnston, shoppers, in-store, in-store traffic, tips, in-store sales, Forrester Research, Booz & Co., Grocery Manufacturers Association
741	1	15	online-video-simplified	Online Video Simplified	<p>Consumption of online video continues to ramp dramatically every day.&nbsp; It&rsquo;s been more than one year since the number of online videos consumed eclipsed search queries!</p>\r\n	<p>Consumption of online video continues to ramp dramatically every day.&nbsp; It&rsquo;s been more than one year since the number of online videos consumed eclipsed search queries!<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe cycle creating this tremendous growth is three-fold: Publishers have taken advantage of the sharp reduction in shooting and editing costs. Viewers have responded by consuming a whopping 200+ videos per month across thousands of sites. Marketers are fueling the demand by investing in this emerging format thanks to overwhelming evidence that online video is at least as effective, if not more, than broadcast.&nbsp; Additionally, it&rsquo;s an economical way to extend broadcast reach and frequency curves among light TV viewers.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThis is great news for the entire industry! Consumers get access to more quality, on-demand content, publishers increase revenue streams, and marketers shift more budgets to online video.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nDespite all of this growth, the reality is pre-roll video only accounts for 2% of all impressions served on the web. Thus, savvy marketers need to treat this tiny, yet extremely valuable, marketing element carefully to maximize ROI. Here are three ideas to take advantage of this growing audience:<span id="cke_bm_98C" style="display:none">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>Utilize offline data to make your media decisions.</strong> Statistically, the buying power of 220MM American consumers far outweighs panel data that drives the majority of online advertising decisions. As look-a-like and cookie-based targeting continues to erode offline data sets become far more powerful.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Remember the 80/20 rule.</strong> The majority of your sales come from a fraction of your stores, products or services.&nbsp; Marketers are already blanketing the country or a market through broadcast, print and online efforts. Focused messaging to your most loyal consumers will continue to increase their purchase frequency and stay with your brand.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Make your video investment work harder for you.</strong> You&rsquo;ve already spent a great deal of money producing the beautiful commercial being shown on television and online. The Internet allows you to easily have the conversation you want to have with your consumer in the environment that makes them most comfortable. Simply adding interactive elements will drive far more viewer engagement if they choose.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nIt&#39;s time to intelligently harness the power of this growing phenomenon by complementing your broadcast, out-of-home and local print efforts with the ideas above.</p>\r\n	t	2012-03-16 13:37:54	\N	2012-03-16 13:37:54	2013-09-29 19:02:14.712403	51	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, Chris Grech, online video, video, online video advertising, digital, video consumption, offline data 
869	1	37	television-and-mobile-friends-or-foes	Television and Mobile: Friends or Foes?	<p>Many advertisers have been aware of the multi-screen advertising trend for a while. If you aren&rsquo;t already on top of it, then you&rsquo;re missing out on one of the best opportunities you have for building your brand.</p>\r\n	<p>Almost everyone in my office is obsessed with the same TV show. It&rsquo;s one of those water cooler programs that compel you to talk about the characters, the plot, and how each episode ended.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="Multi-screen usage" src="/system/editor/W1siZiIsIjIwMTMvMDgvMjEvMDhfMzZfMTRfODY4X011bHRpc2NyZWVuXzE1MHgxNTAucG5nIl0sWyJwIiwidGh1bWIiLCI4MDB4ODAwPiJdXQ/Multiscreen_150x150.png" style="float:left; height:130px; margin-left:10px; margin-right:10px; width:130px" />But despite the captivating story, most of us don&rsquo;t give it our undivided attention. I asked several coworkers, and it turns out that more than half of us had our phones or tablets fired up during the show. I&rsquo;ve personally lost multiple chess matches over the course of the series!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I admit it&rsquo;s a small, non-scientific sample size, but we&rsquo;re certainly not unique. A report from the Interactive Advertising Bureau (IAB) claims that, while watching TV, up to &ldquo;77% of tablet owners between the ages of 18-44 years old say they are likely to be multi-tasking.&rdquo;<a href="#_ftn1" name="_ftnref1" title="">[1]</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Many advertisers have been aware of this trend for a while. They call it <em>multi-screen advertising</em>, and if you aren&rsquo;t already on top of it, then you&rsquo;re missing out on one of the best opportunities you have for building your brand.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Can You Sell to a Distracted Audience?</strong><br />\r\nWhen I first thought about it, I figured multi-screen behaviors would be bad for brands. I mean, doesn&rsquo;t an advertisement need to take center stage to be effective?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It turns out the answer is &ldquo;no.&rdquo; In fact, message retention may increase due to multiple simultaneous exposures across screens. For example, imagine watching a Yankee game on TV while researching player stats on your iPad. During your research, you see an advertisement for macaroni and cheese. At the same time, you overhear a message from the same brand during the game&rsquo;s commercial break. The next time you go grocery shopping, odds are good you&rsquo;ll remember this brand.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Additionally, the convenience of mobile devices makes it easier for TV viewers to immediately research a product without having to leave their couches. The IAB report found that 47% of tablet users are likely to take subsequent action after seeing a commercial on TV. If the same macaroni and cheese advertisement is served to a customer during the game, they can immediately start searching for coupons or deals at their local store. And if they&rsquo;re hungry enough, you&rsquo;ll immediately drive them to the store to fulfill their craving.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>What About Best Practices?</strong><br />\r\nMulti-screen advertising is still fairly new, but I want to offer two key recommendations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>First, <em>make sure to integrate your campaigns tightly across channels</em>. If your mobile ads clash with your TV campaigns, you&rsquo;re likely to leave a negative impression with your customers. They might see both ads within the span of a few minutes&mdash;so it&rsquo;ll be very obvious if the messages clash.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Second, <em>design your ads to focus on the best user experience for the device</em>. For example, click-to-call and click-to-map functionality works best on mobile devices, which customers bring with them while they&rsquo;re on the go. For campaign features that require more typing, such as sign-up forms and registration pages, focus on targeting users on tablet devices.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The multi-screen trend won&rsquo;t disappear. In fact, with the rising tide of millennial shoppers who grew up using smartphones and tablets, multi-screen behaviors will only grow in importance. Whatever you do, don&rsquo;t ignore it&mdash;mobile advertising might be the biggest thing to happen to TV advertising since the Super Bowl.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="#_ftnref1" name="_ftn1" title="">[1]</a>. <a href="http://www.iab.net/media/file/The_Multiscreen_Marketer.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.iab.net/media/file/The_Multiscreen_Marketer.pdf</a></p>\r\n	t	2013-08-21 08:08:00	\N	2013-08-21 00:37:04.063009	2013-10-15 13:22:17.262393	52	\N
843	1	20	pulling-strength-from-experience-the-next-generation-of-retail-stores	Pulling Strength from Experience: The Next Generation of Retail Stores	<p>Smart retailers that are ahead of the game learn from past experiences and embrace technology rather than resist or run from it.</p>\r\n	<p>It&rsquo;s interesting how modern technology has such a huge impact on the way we shop&mdash;how it attracts us to a specific store because it is something new and different. Thirty-plus years ago, the most exciting technology in stores was talking registers, calculators on cart handles, and the catalog store concept (which allowed you to see and try a sample item that a warehouse then fulfilled and shipped to you). Twenty years ago it was in-store touch screen directory kiosks to help you find an item and the beginnings of what is now the loyalty card. Ten years ago, the self-checkout became mainstream along with ordering out-of-stock items from a computer in the store with direct-to-home shipping.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nEach decade by itself seems pretty boring compared to today&rsquo;s technology standards, which allow stores to incorporate mobile devices such as smartphones and tablets into the shopping experience. However, today&rsquo;s brick-and-mortar stores are returning to these older concepts and simply updating them with a modern flair. &ldquo;Showroomers&rdquo; want to see an item, touch it, or use it before purchasing it&mdash;paralleling the old catalog store concept&mdash;only now, they want to use their smartphones to snap the bar code, find who has the best price, read product reviews, learn the stock status, and purchase the item.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nCustomers want data at their fingertips, so brick-and-mortar stores are giving it to them. Smart retailers are posting everything you can find on your phone, in the store. Download their in-store app and you&rsquo;ll find store layout plans as well as aisle numbers to search for items. Why is this important? According to Nathan Pettyjohn, CEO of aisle411, about 20% of in-store retail sales are lost because shoppers can&rsquo;t find items.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAlso within these in-store apps, retailers have added prices, store hours, bar code scanners and even coupons as an incentive to buy in the store. Hmmm, sounds like the directory kiosks and loyalty cards of the past.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAnd who wants to wait around to check out or to find out if the item is in stock? No problem; retailers are empowering any employee to check stock availability, pull/hold inventory, ship from a different location, or process an order from their very own smartphone. That sure adds some personal attention back into the equation from the self-checkouts and self-order kiosks of the past.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhat I am trying to say is that history repeats itself in one form or another, and retailers that are ahead of the game realize this and embrace the technology rather than resist or run from it. Sure, e-commerce challenged physical stores at first, and the naysayers saw this as the apocalyptic end to brick-and-mortars. But rising from the ashes is the next generation of physical stores, revisiting old strengths, pairing them with today&rsquo;s technology, and attracting even the most avid online shoppers&mdash;if only because it is something new and different.</p>\r\n	t	2012-12-07 18:22:26	\N	2012-12-07 18:22:26	2013-09-10 14:51:01.783898	59	retailers, brick-and-mortar stores, in-store apps, smartphones
845	1	20	the-in-store-mobile-experience-a-necessary-adaptation	The In-Store Mobile Experience: A Necessary Adaptation	<p>It&rsquo;s classic Darwinism. Adapt or die. How many retailers have we seen hang up their hats in a woe-is-me surrender to the digital age? And how many retailers have we seen flourish? We&rsquo;ve seen both, and the ones who have risen from the doldrums of the e-commerce era have adapted.</p>\r\n	<p>It&rsquo;s classic Darwinism. Adapt or die. How many retailers have we seen hang up their hats in a woe-is-me surrender to the digital age? And how many retailers have we seen flourish? We&rsquo;ve seen both, and the ones who have risen from the doldrums of the e-commerce era have adapted. The ones who have crashed and burned, have not. Simple. What isn&rsquo;t simple is how the strong have survived. It&rsquo;s taken a lot of change and faith in doing things in a different way. These evolutionary superstars have seen an opportunity in the showrooming phenomenon brought on by advances in mobile technology and have used it to their advantage.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<u><a href="http://maxpointinteractive.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/iStock_000017090588_ExtraSmall.jpg"><img alt="Mobile devices bridge the digital and in-store shopping experiences" src="http://maxpointinteractive.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/iStock_000017090588_ExtraSmall.jpg" style="border:0pt none; float:right; height:258px; padding-bottom:10px; padding-left:10px; width:298px" title="Mobile devices bridge the digital and in-store shopping experiences" /></a></u>To help drive more in-store sales and combat showrooming, today&rsquo;s retailers are turning to mobile devices in hopes of bridging digital and in-store shopping experiences. According to July 2012 research from <a href="http://www.e-tailing.com/" target="_blank">the e-tailing group</a>&rsquo;s &ldquo;Mobile Mystery Shopping Study,&rdquo; certain cross-channel features may help US retailers deliver more positive shopping experiences for smartphone and tablet-toting shoppers.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe group found that in the second quarter of 2011, more than half of retailers with mobile web store locators enabled geolocation from the site. That number was up to 82% a year later, in the second quarter of 2012. Locating specific products via a mobile device before heading to a store might be even more advantageous for information-hungry, time-crunched shoppers. About half of retailers enabled that function via mobile websites as of this year.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn-store pickup is another added experience retailers are beginning to implement. The e-tailing group found that in 2011, only 22% of retailers offered the capability to purchase a product via mobile or online and then pick it up in store. By the second quarter of 2012, 34% of US retailers had enabled the pickup function.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nA June study by <a href="http://www.retailsystemsresearch.com/" target="_blank">Retail Systems Research (RSR)</a> also demonstrates that retailers are giving more thought to cross-channel activities. According to RSR data, about half of retailers worldwide enabled shoppers to buy online then pick up in store. And 63% allowed shoppers to buy in-store, and then fulfill through online or direct.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe e-tailing group lists &ldquo;implementing [mobile] site improvements&rdquo; on the checklist for meeting the needs of today&rsquo;s on-the-go shopper. Marrying mobile experiences with in-store ones might boost consumer opinions of retailers and lead to more frequent purchases.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nClearly, in-store experiences are still very important to shoppers. However, recognizing that shoppers visit many channels before they make the ultimate purchase is crucial for today&rsquo;s brick-and-mortars. In fact, a comScore and dunnhumbyUSA study showed that digital advertising lifted in-store CPG sales by 20%. And, Forrester Research predicts the web will be influencing $1.4 trillion worth of in-store sales by 2014. Smart retailers have already adapted and know that hyperlocal digital advertising incorporated into their overall mix helps drive additional in-store traffic and sales.</p>\r\n	t	2012-12-20 16:53:15	\N	2012-12-20 16:53:15	2013-09-10 14:52:54.744182	59	in-store sales, mobile advertising, retailers, showrooming, MaxPoint
