720	1	15	what-to-consider-when-measuring-online-video-ad-engagement	What to Consider When Measuring Online Video Ad Engagement	<p>According to eMarketer, online video will make up one-third of all online display advertising by 2014 and $5.71 billion is projected to be spent by 2014 as well. With such big dollars at stake, marketers need to understand video engagement to ensure they&rsquo;re getting the best bang for the buck. &nbsp;</p>\r\n	<p>According to <a href="http://www.emarketer.com/" target="_blank">eMarketer</a>, online video will make up one-third of all online display advertising by 2014 and $5.71 billion is projected to be spent by 2014 as well. With such big dollars at stake, marketers need to understand video engagement to ensure they&rsquo;re getting the best bang for the buck. &nbsp;<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nVideo ad engagement can be defined in many ways from time spent watching videos, number of clicks, number of times the video was shared, and many more, but what metrics are the most important? Based on a 2011 eMarketer webinar, below are metrics to focus on when measuring online video engagement.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Time Spent:</strong> Time spent with the video ad is the essential metric, particularly completion rates and percentage of the ad viewed.<span id="cke_bm_338C" style="display:none">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>Fifty-three percent of respondents from an eMarketer survey say they pay attention to video ads when they are of interest, meaning precise video ad targeting is essential.</li>\r\n\t<li>Shorter ads tend to increase audience involvement. For example, :15 second pre-roll ads have higher engagement rates than :30 second ads.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<strong>Interactions:</strong>&nbsp; Marketers should look at video ad interactions including mouse-overs, start rates including start rates, mouse-overs, activating a video player and expanding a video banner ad<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Sharing:</strong> If the video campaign has a viral focus, marketers will want to look at the number of times the video has been shared. Twenty-five percent of marketers who have used YouTube for viral purposes have had viral success, indicating strong engagement.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Brand Health:</strong> Advertisers can check to see if there was a lift in brand-health metrics such as purchase intent, favorability and awareness<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Post Video Activity:</strong> According to an eMarketer survey, 48% of respondents say they visit the company website after viewing the online video ad. Marketers should make sure the look/feel of the online video is on brand with the website to help make a smooth transition for the viewer.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAs you launch your video ad campaigns, keep these metrics in mind when it comes time to measuring the engagement of your campaign, specifically time spent with the video. For more on video advertising solutions click <a href="http://www.maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-solutions" target="_blank">here</a>.</p>\r\n	t	2012-02-13 15:42:46	\N	2012-02-13 15:42:46	2013-10-01 19:40:54.729325	51	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, video, Alicia Johnston, eMarketer, advertising budget, online video advertising, digital, retail, brand, campaigns 
740	1	15	forrester-predicts-changes-as-tv-and-digital-advertising-strategies-unite	Forrester Predicts Changes as TV and Digital Advertising Strategies Unite	<p>In the next few years, TV and digital video strategies will start to merge into a single media strategy. As that happens, what changes can we expect?</p>\r\n	<p>In the next few years, TV and digital video strategies will start to merge into a single media strategy. As that happens, what changes can we expect? As part of our <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/onpoint-blog/2012/3/8/why-online-video-and-tv-strategies-are-slow-to-integrate" target="_blank">blog series</a> on TV and digital video strategies, we thought it would be appropriate to end on looking into the future. Forrester predicts that by 2016, digital video ad spending will be 5% of traditional TV ad spending. Forrester further investigated what changes we can expect to see and below is a recap of their predictions.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Better response to more relevant ads.</strong> Digital ad content and timing is going to be key &ndash; meaning it&rsquo;s going to become more relevant to consumers. Why? Because marketers are going to get more and more targeted at reaching their customers. To give you an example, some sites currently has the ability to target&nbsp; subscribers by demographic information, geography, content preference, daypart, or media device (e.g., video gaming console). So just imagine what will be possible in the next few years!<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Media buying and selling systems will change dramatically.</strong> The need for new campaign and inventory management systems is going to be necessary to plan, buy, and optimize across channels. You may be aware of a recent merger of MediaBank and Donovan Data Systems into MediaOcean &ndash; this is just one example of the types of change to come in the future.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Adaptive marketers will buy audiences across platforms.</strong> According to Forrester, &ldquo;Adaptive marketers, versed in both TV and digital video vocabularies and currencies, will be able to buy and compare audiences across platforms.&rdquo;&nbsp; By using a balance of digital video impressions and linear TV spots, Forrester predicts that marketers will be able to measure their unduplicated reach across all video media against their target audiences. To learn more about adaptive marketing, you can read a recent AdAge <a href="http://adage.com/article/mediaworks/adaptive-marketing-set-big-thing/232673/" target="_blank">article</a> for more information.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Budgets focused on objectives.</strong> We can expect more objective-based budgets &ndash; this will allow marketers to focus on delivering on a single marketing objective. To give you an example, Pepsi&rsquo;s consumer engagement team has a budget that&rsquo;s only focused on building engagement across multiple media channels. They still have separate planning teams for TV and digital, but each operates with the same engagement strategy in mind. Another example comes from Delta Air Lines &ndash; they have separate marketing budgets for brand messaging and tactical objectives.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Flexible creative.</strong> We all know video advertising opportunities are spreading across other technologies such as tablets and smartphones &ndash; so what is does this mean for the future? It means advertisers will have to adapt creative to run wherever their customers are. And it means they will need to be more flexible with their advertising formats and specifications in order for ads to work across various platforms.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Media teams fluent in both TV and digital video.</strong> It&rsquo;s no surprise that most TV media planners and buyers these days aren&rsquo;t fluent in digital video and vice versa. With the rise of more integrated marketing teams, single video teams will exist that fully speak the language of both TV and digital video and can plan and buy across both without a hitch.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSome of these predictions are already taking place and you may be seeing some of these changes occurring in your marketing and media departments. As a reminder, be sure to start complementing your TV and other offline media strategies with digital video.</p>\r\n	t	2012-03-15 19:58:39	\N	2012-03-15 19:58:39	2013-10-01 15:10:41.877558	51	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, Alicia Johnston, Forrester Research, digital, digital advertising, advertising, digital video strategies, video, targeting, media buying, media selling, media stats, AdAge 
