735	1	15	why-online-video-and-tv-strategies-are-slow-to-integrate	Why Online Video and TV Strategies are Slow to Integrate	<p>Why are marketers and media agencies slow to integrate their online video and TV strategies? A recent Forrester report revealed some answers to this question &ndash; let&rsquo;s look at what their research discovered.</p>\r\n	<p>By 2015, online advertising is expected to make up nearly 28% of total US major media ad spending, compared to TV, whose share of total spending is expected to hover around 38% for the next five years, according to eMarketer. If this is the case, then why are marketers and media agencies slow to integrate their online video and TV strategies? A recent Forrester report revealed some answers to this question &ndash; let&rsquo;s look at what their research discovered:<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Old media habits and traditional thinking still controls TV budgets</strong>. Forrester interviewed marketers and ad sellers and learned many of them still stick to their traditional media habits and are &ldquo;reluctant to upset the TV advertising status quo to embrace new digital metrics, placements, and innovations.&rdquo; Nielsen data hasn&rsquo;t changed much in 30 years and TV ads are still bought and sold based on this data. And with TV still having the audiences marketers are looking for, and delivering expected decent results, it&rsquo;s easy to stick with it &ndash; however the smart strategy is to use digital video to complement traditional offline media plans.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Marketers don&rsquo;t think digital video has the scale</strong>. More and more research is validating how online video positively effects brand lift and purchase intent. However, according to a MediaPost article, marketers are still seeking tangible performance results to prove the impact of digital video. A 2011 Forrester report on marketing mix modeling states, &ldquo;Marketing mix models, the tools that marketers use to measure marketing return on investment, still lack the required data to quantify the effects of digital video on marketing key performance indicators and business goals.&rdquo;<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Media and marketing teams operate independently</strong>. Any media agency and marketing department will tell you they have channel-specific teams, and tend to work independent of one another. TV and digital each have their own budget, and there are different skill sets required to plan and buy media for each. Take a look below at a graphic from Forrester that depicts this conflict. What also tends to happen is marketers will partner with different media agencies for their TV and digital media buying needs, further separating these teams.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<a href="http://www.maxpointinteractive.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/FORBLOG2.png"><img alt="" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-2006" src="http://www.maxpointinteractive.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/FORBLOG2-300x203.png" style="height:203px; width:300px" title="FORBLOG2" /></a><br />\r\nSo if you&rsquo;ve been wondering why media agencies and marketers are still separating their TV and digital video strategies, I hope this helps you understand why, and maybe gives you some ideas on what you can do to help merge these strategies.&nbsp; Digital video strategies should complement your traditional offline media plans, not detract from them.&nbsp; For instance, take a look at this past <a href="http://maxpointinteractive.com/onpoint-blog/2012/02/07/you-just-spent-3-5-million-on-your-super-bowl-ad-now-what/" target="_blank">post</a> on what to do with your TV Super Bowl creative.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nTo learn more about how MaxPoint can help you with your digital video strategies, <a href="http://www.maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-solutions" target="_blank">click here</a>. And, don&rsquo;t forget to <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/advertising-events" target="_blank">schedule a meeting</a> with us at the iMedia Video Summit on March 25-28.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSource: Why Marketers Must Integrate TV and Video Strategies - Forrester Research, 2012</p>\r\n	t	2012-03-08 15:43:48	\N	2012-03-08 15:43:48	2013-10-01 15:28:40.901409	51	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, Alicia Johnston, video, online advertising, TV, traditional advertising, Forrester Research, media habits, eMarketer, digital video strategies, digital 
871	1	37	advice-to-financial-advertisers-target-millennials	Advice to Financial Advertisers: Target Millennials	<p>Why should financial advertisers focus on millennials? We&#39;ll show you why&mdash;and give you tips on how to reach them.</p>\r\n	<p><img alt="" src="/system/editor/W1siZiIsIjIwMTMvMDgvMjkvMTFfNDJfMTVfNDU0X0Jsb2dfb25fTWlsbGVubmlhbHMucG5nIl0sWyJwIiwidGh1bWIiLCI4MDB4ODAwPiJdXQ/Blog-on-Millennials.png" style="float:left; height:116px; margin-left:15px; margin-right:15px; width:116px" />MaxPoint&rsquo;s most recent <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/advertising-tips-and-strategies/advertising-insights/preparing-for-the-golden-years" target="_blank">Interest Index</a> presented clear profiles for both retirement planners and financial services spenders. I wasn&rsquo;t surprised by the findings&mdash;both groups are well established and have more money than younger shoppers. But as a millennial, I was curious about my generation&mdash;are we good targets for financial advertisers, too?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I think so, for a few key reasons.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For starters, our generation is massive. Often called the &ldquo;echo boomers,&rdquo; we have numbers reminiscent of the post-WWII baby boomers. It would be unwise to ignore a group that includes upward of 77 million potential customers.<a href="#_ftn1" name="_ftnref1" title="">[1]</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Second, we may be more financially conscious than previous generations. A 2012 bankrate.com survey found that millennials are more likely than boomers to have a higher share of savings than credit card debt.<a href="#_ftn2" name="_ftnref2" title="">[2]</a> I think this can be attributed to the recession&mdash;the economic situation taught my generation how important fiscal security really is. We may have less money than older Americans, but we&rsquo;ve already developed strong saving habits.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Third, we start saving for retirement earlier than other generations. According to a MediaPost report, the average age that millennials start saving for retirement is 22, but most boomers didn&rsquo;t start until 35.<a href="#_ftn3" name="_ftnref3" title="">[3]</a> In short, the moment we enter the workforce, we start saving for the golden years. &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Finally, banks and financial services firms can reach millennials while we&rsquo;re still young. Because we often don&rsquo;t have solid brand preferences yet, we&rsquo;re more receptive to your message. And once we do choose a bank, chances are good that it will be our go-to for years to come.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Tips for Reaching Millennials</strong><br />\r\nSo, banks and financial services firms need to target the younger crowds. But how do they do it successfully? Let me offer just a few words of advice, coming from a member of the millennial generation:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>Buy Mobile Placement&mdash;</strong>We&rsquo;re obsessed with our phones. Even when we&rsquo;re watching our favorite shows, we still text friends, play Candy Crush, or <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/onpoint-blog/2013/8/21/television-and-mobile-friends-or-foes" target="_blank">research something we saw on TV</a>. Every campaign should include some mobile and tablet buys, but with a millennial-focused campaign, you should devote an even larger share of your budget.<br />\r\n\t&nbsp;</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Focus on Savings and Security&mdash;</strong>We&rsquo;re fiscally cautious. Keep this insight in mind when putting together your creative&mdash;focus on promoting your brand as the safe, solid choice. Messaging about high investment returns won&rsquo;t resonate as much as ads touting the ability to securely build our nest eggs.<br />\r\n\t&nbsp;</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Target Areas That Over-Index for Young Professionals&mdash;</strong>Not all millennials are ready to start saving and investing. So, make sure to use multiple data sources to target neighborhoods that over-index for young professionals. They&rsquo;ll have both the willingness and the ability to buy. You&rsquo;ll see even higher returns if you leverage MaxPoint&rsquo;s interest data to target young professionals with an interest in finance.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nI&rsquo;m not trying to dissuade financial services advertisers from targeting more established boomers or people in Gen X. To the contrary, you should aim the bulk of your ad budget at the profiles from the recent Interest Index. But I do think it would be a mistake to avoid my generation entirely. Just remember&mdash;if you invest in us now, your company will likely profit for years to come.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="#_ftnref1" name="_ftn1" title="">[1]</a>. <a href="http://www.pewresearch.org/daily-number/the-millennial-count/" target="_blank">http://www.pewresearch.org/daily-number/the-millennial-count/</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="#_ftnref2" name="_ftn2" title="">[2]</a>. <a href="http://www.bankrate.com/finance/consumer-index/survey-shows-savings-triumphs-debt.aspx" target="_blank">http://www.bankrate.com/finance/consumer-index/survey-shows-savings-triumphs-debt.aspx</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="#_ftnref3" name="_ftn3" title="">[3]</a>. <a href="http://www.mediapost.com/publications/article/200287/careful-kids-affluent-gen-y-spend-less-invest-m.html#axzz2TMmU2Tak" target="_blank">http://www.mediapost.com/publications/article/200287/careful-kids-affluent-gen-y-spend-less-invest-m.html#axzz2TMmU2Tak</a></p>\r\n	t	2013-08-29 08:55:39	\N	2013-08-28 20:57:21.567558	2013-10-15 13:21:03.824588	54	\N
676	1	15	what-restaurants-should-consider-when-trying-to-reach-households-with-children	What Restaurants Should Consider When Trying to Reach Households with Children	<p>According to childstats.gov, there are over 75 million children in the U.S. and with the average household eating out 2 to 3 times per week, restaurants need to make sure they are appealing to families with children.&nbsp;</p>\r\n	<p>According to <a href="http://www.childstats.gov/" target="_blank">childstats.gov</a>, there are over 75 million children in the U.S. and with the average household eating out 2 to 3 times per week, restaurants need to make sure they are appealing to families with children.&nbsp; For starters, restaurants can launch a digital campaign to parents with children and offer coupons or special offers to drive traffic, but what can restaurants do to keep these families coming back? Families have so many choices these days, so let&rsquo;s take a look at what restaurants could do to increase loyalty.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Provide Quality Food</strong><br />\r\nAccording to an <a href="http://www.rmgtmagazine.com/news/changing-demographics-and-brand-appeal-put-pressure-casual-dining?page=2" target="_blank">article</a> in Restaurant Management Magazine, price is not the only factor for families. In this article, University of Louisville marketing professor Wayne Jones, states, &ldquo;It&rsquo;s more of a price/quality dynamic. If you&rsquo;re putting out good food at $12 a plate, you&rsquo;ll do better than if you charge $9 a plate for mediocre food.&rdquo;<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Create a Family Atmosphere</strong><br />\r\nYou don&rsquo;t have to turn your restaurant into an amusement park, but restaurants should consider a kid-friendly atmosphere. The Old Spaghetti Factory, which has an antique vibe to it, offers a trolley car, pasta choices served in a trolley-themed bowl, and cool &ldquo;bed booths&rdquo; build from old headboards. Red Robin has a wacky mascot and balloons for all kids, and places like Chuck E. Cheese&rsquo;s offer an arcade, games, prizes, and is decorated with bright colors and pictures.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Offer an Appealing Menu Selection</strong><br />\r\nWhen selecting a restaurant, Moms almost always choose a restaurant based on the attractiveness of a menu (albeit quality, variety, healthfulness and sophistication), according to a survey to Moms by the <a href="http://usfoodsight.purpleplanet.com/industry-insights/building-your-restaurants-family-appeal.html" target="_blank">US Food Service</a>. In this survey, 86% of Moms said it&rsquo;s important for a restaurant to have food their kids or family likes and 63% say it&rsquo;s important that healthy food choices are offered.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Consider Parents Too</strong><br />\r\nMaking parents feel comfortable is also key to keeping families coming back. Restaurants should make sure servers are well trained to be polite and patient with children, and provide children with crayons, paper, and small toys at the table. Offering something as simple as sippy cups and bibs helps parents when they may forget these items. Mimi&rsquo;s Caf&eacute; gives bibs and hand wipes to all families with young kids, and they also make sure all restrooms have changing tables. Conveniences like this will help keep parents happy and loyal.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIf restaurants consider these kid-friendly factors, they should be well on their way to keeping families coming back over and over.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nInterested to see what 10 restaurants Parents.com named as the &ldquo;Best Family Restaurants of 2011&rdquo;? Take a <a href="http://www.parents.com/recipes/nutrition/best-family-restaurants-2011/" target="_blank">look</a> and see if you agree.</p>\r\n	t	2011-10-12 13:00:17	\N	2011-10-12 13:00:17	2013-10-23 17:07:20.860439	49	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, Alicia Johnston, Wayne Jones, restaurants, restaurant sales, family restaurants, families, childstats.gov, US Food Service, Parents.com, Restaurant Management Magazine
