689	1	15	black-friday-what-will-retailers-do-to-come-out-on-top-for-in-store	Black Friday: What Will Retailers Do to Come Out on Top for In-Store?	<p>Black Friday, the day after Thanksgiving and the beginning of the Christmas shopping season, we know it all too well. For retailers and brands, it&rsquo;s a day that can significantly lift retail sales and drive high in-store traffic. And, this year, retailers are coming out full force.</p>\r\n	<p>Black Friday, the day after Thanksgiving and the beginning of the Christmas shopping season, we know it all too well. For many consumers, it&rsquo;s a day of hiding at home or rushing to stores as soon as they open, trying to grab the sweet deals offered before anyone else. For retailers and brands, it&rsquo;s a day that can significantly lift retail sales and drive high in-store traffic. And, this year, retailers are coming out full force. <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nAccording to Matthew Shay, president and CEO of the <a href="http://www.nrf.com/" target="_blank">National Retail Federation</a> (NRF), &ldquo;the <a href="http://www.retailwire.com/discussion/14897/when-black-friday-comes" target="_blank">rules for Black Friday</a> have changed significantly.&rdquo; Instead of waiting until Thanksgiving Day to announce Black Friday deals, retailers are already creating buzz around what&rsquo;s to come for their shoppers. And, why not? This year, approximately 138 billion people plan to shop over Black Friday weekend (four million more than last year).&nbsp; And, a recent <a href="http://www.retailwire.com/" target="_blank">RetailWire</a> poll found that 64% think that early promotions can be a big advantage for retailers this year.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSo, how are retailers stepping it up this year in their stores?</p>\r\n\r\n<ul><br />\r\n\t<li><strong>Early openings:</strong> Sears, Kmart, Macy&rsquo;s, Walmart, Toys &ldquo;R&rdquo; Us, Bass Pro Shops, Target and several other stores are opening some or all of their stores on Thanksgiving! Yes, that&rsquo;s right &ndash; Thanksgiving. Others pulling back opening hours to midnight.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ul><br />\r\n\t<li><strong>Charitable efforts:</strong>&nbsp; For every person who checks-in on Foursquare while in-store at <a href="http://www.jcpenney.com/jcp/default.aspx?cm_mmc=Google-_-G_JCP_Official_Site_Broad-_-G_JCP_Official_Site_Broad-_-jcp" target="_blank">J.C. Penney</a> on Black Friday, J.C. Penney will make a $25 donation to the Salvation Army. We especially like that the retailer is using creative digital banner ads to support the effort!</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ul><br />\r\n\t<li><strong>Don&rsquo;t miss deals:</strong> Retailers such as Target,<a href="http://www.kohls.com/?pfx=pfx_google_roi&amp;cid=bsolo"> </a>Kohl&rsquo;s, GameStop, Best Buy, Dick&rsquo;s Sporting Goods, Old Navy, Macy&rsquo;s (to name a few) are offering huge marked down prices for electronics, clothes and toys purchased in-store. For instance, Best Buy is offering electronics with 50% off price reductions. And, Macy&rsquo;s will offer 40% of select appliances &ndash; great sales on jewelry too!</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nThese are just some of the ways retailers are stepping it up this year to drive in-store traffic but it&rsquo;s certainly not exhaustive. Tweet <a href="http://twitter.com/maxpoint_int" target="_blank">@maxpoint_int</a> with the Black Friday # (#blackfriday) and share some of the ways you have seen retailer&rsquo;s &ldquo;step up&rdquo; for Black Friday this 2011 holiday shopping season.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nFrom everyone at MaxPoint, we wish you a happy and safe Thanksgiving holiday!</p>\r\n	t	2011-11-21 16:08:56	\N	2011-11-21 16:08:56	2013-10-08 21:48:54.177311	49	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, Black Friday, retail, brands, in-store, in-store sales, holiday shopping, consumers, Matthew Shay, NRF, RetailWire, Sears, Kmart, Macy's, Walmart, Toys "R" Us, Bass Pro Shops, Target, J. C. Penney, Kohl's, GameStop, Best Buy, Dicks's Sporting Goods, Old Navy, @maxpoint_int 
684	1	15	in-the-final-72-hours-of-the-2011-holiday-shopping-season-think-local	In the Final 72 Hours of the 2011 Holiday Shopping Season - Think Local	<p>According to the National Retail Federation (NRF), holiday sales can represent anywhere between 25-40 percent of retailers&rsquo; annual sales and US Census data indicates that approximately 75 percent of all US consumer spending occurs at retail locations within 15 miles of home.&nbsp; Not only is localization important, it is a key part of the brand strategy.</p>\r\n	<p>According to the National Retail Federation (NRF), holiday sales can represent anywhere between 25-40 percent of retailers&rsquo; annual sales and US Census data indicates that approximately&nbsp; 75 percent of all US consumer spending occurs at retail locations within 15 miles of home.&nbsp; Not only is localization important, it is a key part of the brand strategy. <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nRetail Systems Research (RSR) recently issued a <a href="http://maxpoint.com/rsrreport" target="_blank">report</a> that outlined the local advertising opportunities titled, The Local Approach: The State of Localized Advertising in Retail. The report said:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;Retailers feel the challenge the most in stores. The store is getting pinched between other selling channels that steal away transactions, while the traditional media channels that used to work best to drive traffic to stores are becoming less and less effective. However, for every challenge there is an opportunity, and for stores one of the most important is local.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Retailers should evaluate their local digital advertising strategy in order to determine new ways to drive foot traffic and sales at their physical stores. Technology now allows retailers and brands to provide central control over brand promise, while also allowing retailers and brands to bring back the local flavor to different store locations. And, retailers are noticing the importance of embracing this, with the RSR research report revealing the top five &ldquo;local&rdquo; advertisers to be Macy&rsquo;s, J.C. Penney, Sports Authority, Best Buy and Kohl&rsquo;s. By reaching potential customers at the neighborhood level with digital campaigns, retailers can get much more targeted and serve the right ads to the right customers at the right time.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAccording to a recent <a href="http://www.marketwatch.com/story/comscore-and-dunnhumbyusa-research-shows-online-advertising-lifts-in-store-cpg-brand-sales-2011-10-11" target="_blank">report</a> from comScore, online digital campaigns drive a 21 percent increase in offline store sales.&nbsp; Doing a print buy, is a very involved process, with digital it is a very quick, very scalable process to buy multiple markets in one swoop with a 15-20 percent return. However, there has not been a digital solution that allows brands or retailers to use digital to drive traffic to a specific retail store. With MaxPoint&rsquo;s digital targeting technology, we have the ability to target small areas and can do specific radiuses around the retail stores.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSo, what can we take away from this? The neighborhood matters! This holiday season, especially in the critical 72 hours before the 2011 holiday shopping season ends, think local and drive in-store sales with your digital campaign.</p>\r\n	t	2011-11-09 14:26:37	\N	2011-11-09 14:26:37	2013-10-11 16:55:14.636164	49	National Retail Federation, MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, local, retail, brand, localization, brand strategy, Retail Systems Research, local digital advertising, digital, digital advertising, Macy's, J.C. Penney, Sports Authority, Best Buy, Kohl's, digital campaigns, comScore, Gretchen Joyce
