691	1	20	captive-audiences-make-for-great-retail-sales	Captive Audiences Make for Great Retail Sales	<p>&ldquo;Ladies and Gentleman, Flight 365 to Chicago will be delayed at least an hour due to a mechanical problem with the aircraft&hellip;&rdquo; How many times has this happened to you, whether on a business trip or with your family on vacation?&nbsp; There is no way out.&nbsp; You&rsquo;ve already cleared security, grabbed a bite to eat and are ready to board your flight.&nbsp; Now what do you do for the next 1+ hours?&nbsp;&nbsp; What retailers love to hear &ndash; shop!</p>\r\n	<p>&ldquo;Ladies and Gentleman, Flight 365 to Chicago will be delayed at least an hour due to a mechanical problem with the aircraft&hellip;&rdquo; How many times has this happened to you, whether on a business trip or with your family on vacation?&nbsp; Delays can be due to weather, heavy air traffic or the most unsettling, mechanical difficulties (like I really want to get on a plane that is having mechanical issues!)&nbsp; There is no way out.&nbsp; You&rsquo;ve already cleared security, grabbed a bite to eat and are ready to board your flight.&nbsp; Now what do you do for the next 1+ hours?&nbsp;&nbsp; What retailers love to hear &ndash; shop!<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<a href="http://www.nytimes.com/" target="_blank">The New York Times</a> published an <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2011/08/02/business/the-airport-experience-now-includes-shopping-for-the-whole-family.html?_r=4" target="_blank">article</a> &ldquo;The Airport Experience Now Includes Shopping for the Family&rdquo; that talks about the huge opportunity retailers have at airports and the changes airport stores are making to adapt to changing traveler demographics.&nbsp; According to the article, until recently most shops in airports were geared toward the male business traveler.&nbsp; Not so anymore.&nbsp; Airports are becoming the new shopping mall for stranded travelers geared to attract teenagers, women and bargain shoppers.&nbsp; With the average wait time in airports for travelers at more than an hour, there is plenty of time to shop.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWith most airports offering Internet connectivity, there is ample opportunity for targeted digital advertising to travelers passing time surfing the Web.&nbsp; Some airports are huge, so awareness of the store is essential.&nbsp; Print ads throughout the airport can be costly, and since you are targeting a stranded and often bored shopper in a specific location, other traditional &amp; wide spread media channels are not as effective.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAccording to the article, sales per square foot are higher at airports than they are in malls or street locations.&nbsp; Armed with this knowledge, savvy retailers are rethinking space in a mall and piloting airport locations.&nbsp; Time will tell, but it appears this is a great opportunity to try.&nbsp; Retailers can also offer free home shipping so customers won&rsquo;t have to worry about fitting the purchases in their luggage.&nbsp; Who knows, when traveling in the future, you may actually hope for a delay so you can kick out some of those errands waiting for you at home.</p>\r\n	t	2011-11-30 14:36:15	\N	2011-11-30 14:36:15	2013-10-03 00:14:16.665034	49	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, Lynn Vitello, airports, retail, airport retail shops, travelers, digital advertising, targeting, The New York Times
886	1	15	measuring-your-digital-ad-campaigns-audience-match-studies	Measuring Your Digital Ad Campaigns: Audience Match Studies	<p>Want to know how well your digital provider reached your target audience? We&#39;ll show you how in the final installment of our digital measurement series.</p>\r\n	<p><img alt="OnPoint Measurement Series" src="/system/editor/W1siZiIsIjIwMTMvMTAvMjMvMDhfMjJfNDNfODkyX0Jsb2dfTWVhc3VyZW1lbnRfU2VyaWVzXzUucG5nIl0sWyJwIiwidGh1bWIiLCI4MDB4ODAwPiJdXQ/Blog%20Measurement%20Series_5.png" style="float:right; height:290px; margin-left:45px; margin-right:45px; width:300px" />In our most recent posts, we&rsquo;ve covered several methods for measuring the effect of a digital campaign, including <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/onpoint-blog/2013/9/18/measuring-your-digital-ad-campaigns-closing-the-loop-on-sales-part-1" target="_blank">sales lift studies</a> and <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/onpoint-blog/2013/10/15/measuring-your-digital-ad-campaigns-brand-lift-and-engagement" target="_blank">brand engagement surveys</a>. Today, we&rsquo;ll conclude our measurement series with audience match studies, which allow you to measure how efficiently you reached your audience.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Many sophisticated advertisers know that their sales will increase if they simply reach enough of their intended audience. Of course, they want to reach those consumers while keeping wasted impressions at a minimum. That&rsquo;s where audience match studies enter the picture.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Audience Match Studies </strong><br />\r\nIn an audience match study, a third-party research firm uses data from a research panel to discover the audience makeup for an ad campaign. The firm can tell how many people received the ad, how many matched the audience profile, and how many impressions were mismatched.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The research firm treats the panel as a representation of the national population. However, the researchers use a statistical model that corrects for groups that are under- or over-represented in the panel. For example, if the panel includes only 25% females, while the US population is closer to 50%, the researchers will adapt panel scores to give more weight to the female scores on the panel.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>An audience match study generally produces two key metrics:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>Percentage In-Target<strong>&mdash;</strong>This is the share of a campaign&rsquo;s total impressions delivered to the target audience. For example, if 30 impressions out of a total 100 impressions for the campaign were served to the target audience, then the percentage in-target would be 30%. Percentage in-target can vary widely depending on the industry and background of the advertiser.</li>\r\n\t<li>Target Efficiency<strong>&mdash;</strong>This measures the percentage, expressed as an index of 1, of the number of impressions served to the target audience compared to the total number of people within the target audience online. A campaign is considered efficient if the target efficiency score is higher than 1. For example, if you were focused on suburban mothers, and you reached twice the percentage of suburban mothers with your campaign than you would via general web-based targeting, then you would have a target efficiency of 2.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<strong>The Pros and Cons of Audience Match Studies</strong><br />\r\nAudience match studies provide several key benefits:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>Verify your targeting. Most digital providers offer targeting measurements in their post-campaign reports. In an audience match study, the third-party research firm verifies the results reported by your digital provider.</li>\r\n\t<li>Get an indication of sales. While the studies don&rsquo;t use direct sales data, high target efficiency scores indicate high sales.</li>\r\n\t<li>Discover results for a reasonably low price. If you don&rsquo;t have the budget for a sales lift study or a brand engagement survey, an audience match study can work as a cost-effective alternative.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nOf course, there are also drawbacks. Audience match studies:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>Provide no sales data. If you want to put dollar figures on your sales, you&rsquo;ll have to run a sales lift study. &nbsp;</li>\r\n\t<li>Give no brand engagement data. Even if you reach your perfect audience, you still need to make sure your message resonates. The best way to measure this is with a brand lift study. &nbsp;</li>\r\n\t<li>Require that you know your audience. Your target audience should be clearly defined before you run an audience match study. If you lack clear customer profiles, an audience match study will provide little benefit.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<strong>Audience Match Studies in Action</strong><br />\r\nOver the years, we&rsquo;ve run several campaigns alongside audience match studies. One example was our work with a major CPG brand that sells packaged breakfast foods. We targeted Hispanic mothers between the ages of 18 and 49. The CPG brand set a benchmark target efficiency of 1.6. With this in mind, the third-party research firm tested MaxPoint&rsquo;s targeting capabilities for the campaign. The firm found that the campaign produced a target efficiency of 3.9, which was 2.4x the CPG brand&rsquo;s benchmark score.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Which Measurement Studies Work for You?</strong><br />\r\nThis concludes our series on digital advertising measurement. We wrote this series to introduce you to all the methods you have at your disposal for measuring a digital campaign. No matter what your advertising goal or your budget, there&rsquo;s a measurement study that can meet your current needs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So now it&rsquo;s your turn&mdash;how are you currently measuring your digital ad campaigns? Let us know in the comments below.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Want to Take the Series with You?</strong><br />\r\nDownload <a href="http://www.maxpoint.com/measurement" target="_blank">our full measurement guide</a> today!</p>\r\n	t	2013-10-23 13:02:06	\N	2013-10-23 13:20:26.754378	2013-10-23 13:26:27.442986	62	\N
663	1	20	poor-customer-service-can-undo-retailers-efforts-to-drive-in-store-sales-2	Poor Customer Service Can Undo Retailers Efforts to Drive In-Store Sales	<p>As retailers push to drive in-store sales through digital advertising, their entire effort can easily be derailed by overlooking the single most important factor:&nbsp; quality customer service. And, this should not be overlooked, since great service drives in-store-sales and customer loyalty.&nbsp; &nbsp;</p>\r\n	<p>As retailers push to drive in-store sales through digital advertising, their entire effort can easily be derailed by overlooking the single most important factor:&nbsp; quality customer service. And, this should not be overlooked, since great service drives in-store-sales and customer loyalty.&nbsp; &nbsp;<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nI was recently in the market for a new tennis racquet.&nbsp; Wanting to be well informed, I did a lot of online research to determine the best racquets for my skill level and price point.&nbsp; While searching several sites, ads were continually displayed for a local tennis shop that has an indoor demo court.&nbsp; I thought, wow, they really want me to visit their store.&nbsp; This was the best-case scenario, because I could research racquets online in the comfort of my home and then have the option to try them out at the store on an indoor court.&nbsp; Perfect.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOn the other hand, I walked through the front door of this eager retailer to nearly bump into a &ldquo;greeter&rdquo; that I assumed would point me in the right direction.&nbsp; No eye contact.&nbsp; Not even a hello. So, I navigated through the large store by myself and found the indoor court in the back corner.&nbsp; No one is around to help me.&nbsp; I help myself to the court and find the exact demo racquets in which I was interested &ndash; but they have a security device attached.&nbsp; I sought out an employee from the apparel department and she reluctantly asks if I need help.&nbsp; She is not able to answer any of my questions and has no idea how to remove the security device from the racquet.&nbsp; She pages the &ldquo;tennis pro,&rdquo; who, upon his arrival, made it clear he was preoccupied with something in the back room.&nbsp; He was not only arrogant but also unwilling to give five minutes of his time to answer my questions.&nbsp; To ignore a customer in such a manner, I can only assume Andre Agassi was in the back seeking this guy&rsquo;s infinite &ldquo;pro&rdquo; wisdom.&nbsp; He did take off the security devices though &ndash;so I was able to demo the racquets.&nbsp; I found one I liked, and to my surprise, it was offered at the same price as an online tennis warehouse retailer.&nbsp; So, I could get the instant satisfaction of having my racquet the same day without waiting for it to be shipped.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWell, guess what, because I was so annoyed by the level (or absence) of service, I walked outside, pulled out my iPhone and ordered from the tennis warehouse retailer; same price, free 2-day shipping.&nbsp; Had I experienced good service, I would have certainly purchased my racquet in the local store and became a loyal customer.&nbsp; Not to mention all of the positive word-of-mouth recommendations I would have given to my friends and family.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nDespite the advanced and creative efforts of the online advertising to get me into their store, this retailer failed miserably at closing the sale -- all because of poor customer service.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAccording to a recent Consumer Reports survey asking 1,010 adults about their customer-service experiences, 64 percent of respondents said they have left a store in the past year because of poor customer service. This survey is part of a larger investigation on customer service featured in the July 2011 issue of Consumer Reports and online at <a href="http://www.consumerreports.org/cro/index.htm" target="_blank">www.ConsumerReports.org</a>.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n