819	1	15	interest-index-finds-las-vegas-moms-are-those-most-interested-in-back-to-school-lunches	Las Vegas Moms Most Interested in Back-to-School Lunches	<p>It&#39;s back-to-school season and you know what that means&mdash;moms nationwide are preparing the perfect homemade and on-the-go school lunches! To celebrate this fun time of year, we issued the results today of an indexing study that analyzed billions of data points to determine the US neighborhoods with moms most interested in back-to-school lunches.</p>\r\n	<p>It&#39;s back-to-school season and you know what that means&mdash;moms nationwide are preparing the perfect homemade and on-the-go school lunches! To celebrate this fun time of year, we issued the results today of an indexing study that analyzed billions of data points to determine the US neighborhoods with moms most interested in back-to-school lunches. <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nIt turns out Las Vegas has the highest concentration of moms looking for and purchasing back-to-school lunch products, and we also revealed that there are two distinct types of moms when it comes to preparing lunches for their children. There are those who enjoy making lunches from scratch and those who prefer quick, easy and convenient meals.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn Las Vegas, Nevada, for example, &ldquo;homemade&rdquo; moms dominate the Whitney neighborhood while the Plymouth area outside of South Bend, Indiana, has a high concentration of &ldquo;on-the-go&rdquo; moms. This information is extremely valuable to grocers, food manufacturers and CPG companies that are looking for new ways to reach moms through digital shopper marketing and advertising campaigns. By using a hyperlocal approach, these brands can reach the right audience for their products &ndash; whether they are ingredients for putting together a lunch from scratch or kid-friendly prepackaged lunches.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe top 10 cities that show the greatest interest in back-to-school lunches are:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n\t<li>Las Vegas, NV</li>\r\n\t<li>South Bend, IN</li>\r\n\t<li>Greenwood, MS</li>\r\n\t<li>Anchorage, AK</li>\r\n\t<li>Fresno, CA</li>\r\n\t<li>Chicago, IL</li>\r\n\t<li>Houston, TX</li>\r\n\t<li>Twin Falls, ID</li>\r\n\t<li>Yuma, AZ</li>\r\n\t<li>Salt Lake City, UT</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nUsing the data gleaned from this August Interest Index, we implemented hyperlocal digital ad campaigns geared toward specific moms:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>A regional restaurant chain with a line of farm-fresh food products wanted to drive coupon downloads for its premade products in grocery stores. We implemented a highly targeted video ad and coupon campaign geared toward moms with kids under the age of 12 who live within a 6&ndash;8 mile radius of the restaurant chain&rsquo;s locations.</li>\r\n\t<li>A large food production company wanted to drive awareness of its new line of on-the-go meals. We created a digital ad strategy targeting moms with kids between the ages of 9 and 17 who previously purchased competitive products within the mini sandwiches category.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n&ldquo;With school starting, moms are looking for new lunch options that fit their families&rsquo; lifestyles. By zeroing in on the neighborhoods that over-index for moms who make homemade versus on-the-go meals, we can help advertisers find the best audience for their products,&rdquo; said Gretchen Joyce, chief operating officer at MaxPoint Interactive. &ldquo;In order to drive in-store traffic, brands can target moms in different neighborhoods with ads that speak to their specific interests and past purchase behavior.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="http://maxpointinteractive.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/MaxPoint-Interactive-August-Interest-Index-Infographic.jpg"><img alt="" class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-3161" src="http://maxpointinteractive.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/MaxPoint-Interactive-August-Interest-Index-Infographic-248x1024.jpg" style="height:1024px; width:248px" title="MaxPoint Interactive August Interest Index Infographic.jpg" /></a></p>\r\n	t	2012-08-30 13:30:42	\N	2012-08-30 13:30:42	2013-09-17 13:57:46.477156	54	back-to-school, interest index, Digital Zip, neighborhoods, MaxPoint, OnPoint
874	1	15	measuring-your-digital-ad-campaigns-the-conundrum-of-clicks	Measuring Your Digital Ad Campaigns: The Conundrum of Clicks	<p>Click-through rates are the yardsticks by which many advertisers currently measure their digital campaigns. But are CTRs enough?</p>\r\n	<p><img alt="" src="/system/editor/W1siZiIsIjIwMTMvMDkvMTIvMDhfMThfMjJfNjEwX0Jsb2dfTWVhc3VyZW1lbnRfU2VyaWVzXzEucG5nIl0sWyJwIiwidGh1bWIiLCI4MDB4ODAwPiJdXQ/Blog%20Measurement%20Series_1.png" style="float:right; height:290px; margin-left:50px; margin-right:50px; width:300px" />Last week, <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/onpoint-blog/2013/9/6/measuring-your-digital-ad-campaigns" target="_blank">we kicked off our digital advertising measurement series</a> with a broad overview of the different types of measurement studies that are available. Over the next few weeks, we&rsquo;re going to talk in depth about how premium studies can help you measure the impact of your digital campaigns.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But before we pick up that discussion, we should take a closer look at click-through rates (CTRs). They&rsquo;re the yardsticks by which many advertisers currently measure their digital campaigns. But are CTRs enough?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ultimately, there are pros and cons to relying on this simple metric.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>CTRs &ndash; The Beginning of the Story</strong><br />\r\nBecause you can track an online ad easily&mdash;from the number of impressions to the number of clicks&mdash;it&rsquo;s easier to gauge the results of your digital campaigns than those of your traditional media efforts; you simply can&rsquo;t measure impressions and clicks for a roadside billboard or a print ad in the newspaper.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Just because you have some metrics, however, doesn&rsquo;t mean you have the entire story. Clicks in particular are only the beginning. In fact, there are two key pitfalls to standard CTRs:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>They Don&rsquo;t Measure Offline Sales&mdash;If you&rsquo;re selling anything offline, then you simply can&rsquo;t stop at CTRs. They can&rsquo;t measure the number of people who go to your stores, nor can they measure a direct impact on sales. CTRs are great for driving people to landing pages that allow you to track conversions, but they fall short for offline sales. For anything other than ecommerce, you have to go beyond CTRs to truly close the loop on offline sales.</li>\r\n\t<li>They Don&rsquo;t Measure Brand Impact&mdash;CTRs are really just proxies for measuring engagement. They indicate a strong brand engagement, but don&rsquo;t directly measure it. It&rsquo;s always possible that you built an advertisement with a high CTR that doesn&rsquo;t actually help your brand. Even if you get a lot of people clicking, they may not remember the message. To really get at brand impact, you need to run a brand lift survey.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nIt comes down to a simple idea&mdash;clicks aren&rsquo;t your end goal. You want sales or brand impact, not clicks.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, there are some reasons to keep tracking CTRs. First, they&rsquo;re great barometers for basic engagement. They&rsquo;re not perfect, but a campaign with a higher CTR often indicates stronger brand engagement.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Second, they&rsquo;re a better measurement option for smaller or shorter campaigns. Both sales lift studies and brand lift surveys require a large amount of impressions. Additionally, sales lift studies require that campaigns run for at least three months, preferably more. So, if you&rsquo;re running a quick campaign, perhaps to spend some extra budget to boost sales for Black Friday, then you are far better off using basic stats like CTRs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>The Final Word on CTRs</strong><br />\r\nUltimately, CTRs are better than nothing. But if you have the budget, we definitely recommend trying a premium study.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Next week, we&rsquo;ll take a closer look at <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/onpoint-blog/2013/9/18/measuring-your-digital-ad-campaigns-closing-the-loop-on-sales-part-1" target="_blank">sales lift studies</a>. These premium studies can be costly, but the data you receive is worth its weight in gold.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Don&rsquo;t Want to Wait?</strong><br />\r\n<a href="http://offers.maxpoint.com/measurement" target="_blank">Download our free measurement guide</a> now to learn more about putting your digital campaigns to the measurement test.</p>\r\n	t	2013-09-12 13:14:43	\N	2013-09-12 13:18:45.985875	2013-10-15 13:19:22.6475	62	\N
816	1	20	back-to-school-smart-retailers-use-digital-ads-to-drive-in-store-traffic	Back-to-School: Smart Retailers Use Digital Ads to Drive In-Store Traffic	<p>Back-to-school is the No. 2 spending season of the year and digital advertising will play an extremely important role for brands and retailers alike.</p>\r\n	<p>Back-to-school is the No. 2 spending season of the year and digital advertising will play an extremely important role for brands and retailers alike.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nAccording to consumer goods brand Kimberly-Clark (maker of Kleenex, Huggies and Cottonelle), brands typically start planning 18 months in advance because they need six months to plan the actual promotion and retailers need another 12 months to ensure that they can incorporate their manufacturers&rsquo; programs in their stores and online.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&ldquo;We are currently planning for back-to-school 2013,&rdquo; said Ann Jones, VP of shopper marketing at Kimberly-Clark.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThis is a testament to how serious retailers are in pulling their share of the second largest shopping season of the year.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&ldquo;Returning to school after a busy summer is a challenging time for moms,&rdquo; Jones said. &ldquo;It is almost like New Year&rsquo;s. It&rsquo;s a new year, a fresh start to new routines. That&rsquo;s how moms think about it. It is kind of a renewal period.&rdquo;&nbsp; Whether moms, dads or caregivers, they are clearly looking for the best deal.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nRetailers are finding the best way to target parents, and the most effective way is through targeted digital advertising. MaxPoint&rsquo;s hyperlocal digital solution effectively finds your specific audience before they go to the store.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAre you using digital advertising intelligently?<br />\r\n<br />\r\nToo often marketers turn to digital ads to drive ecommerce sales and use traditional ads to drive foot traffic to stores. Marketers are missing the boat on 