812	1	20	shift-to-multicultural-advertising-is-not-just-in-u-s	Shift to Multicultural Advertising Is Not Just in U.S.	<p>The U.S. is one of the world&rsquo;s largest melting pots of culture and lifestyles, so it is no wonder a shift to multicultural advertising is rapidly taking focus here.&nbsp; However, the U.S is not the only country waking to the realization that global diversity is driving the way we advertise.</p>\r\n	<p>The U.S. is one of the world&rsquo;s largest melting pots of culture and lifestyles, so it is no wonder a shift to multicultural advertising is rapidly taking focus here.&nbsp; However, the U.S is not the only country waking to the realization that global diversity is driving the way we advertise.<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nAccording to the June 22, 2012 article in B&amp;T (Australia&#39;s leading title for the advertising, marketing, media and PR industries), <a href="http://www.bandt.com.au/news/marketing/multicultural-marketing-fundamental-to-growth" target="_blank">Multicultural marketing &#39;fundamental&#39; to growth</a>, the one-size fits all approach to marketing needs to be ditched and multicultural marketing communications are now a &ldquo;necessity&rdquo;, Australia&rsquo;s Communications Council states.&nbsp; The Council&rsquo;s warning follows an earlier release of the Australian Bureau of Statistics 2011 census that shows one fourth of Australia&rsquo;s population was born overseas.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&ldquo;Multicultural communications is now a necessity that demands consideration from the highest levels of business strategy development through to the promotion of products and services,&rdquo; said Lou Petrolo, multicultural marketing chair of the Communication Council. Petrolo adds, &ldquo;Marketing that caters to the different backgrounds and languages which make up Australian society is &ldquo;fundamental&rdquo; to the growth of organisations.&rdquo;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhere the U.S.&lsquo;s current multicultural focus is on its Hispanic population, Australia is eyeing the Asian population.&nbsp; According to the census, Mandarin is now the second most common language spoken at home after English with 23.2% of Australian&rsquo;s speaking a language other than English at home.&nbsp; There has also been a 30% increase in the amount of people speaking a Chinese language from the 2006 Census.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAs the multicultural revolution pans out over the next few years, it will be interesting to see the advertising shifts made in each leading country across the world based on new immigration data.</p>\r\n	t	2012-08-15 16:26:43	\N	2012-08-15 16:26:43	2013-09-17 14:08:13.7437	58	MaxPoint, OnPoint, Multicultural Advertising, Advertising
802	1	15	u-s-grocery-retailing-trends	U.S. Grocery Retailing Trends	<p>Every year is different for grocers, as in-store traffic and sales depends on the economy and changing consumer shopping habits. Recently, the U.S. Commerce Department released insights into the current trends taking place in the grocery industry.</p>\r\n	<p>Every year is different for grocers, as in-store traffic and sales depends on the economy and changing consumer shopping habits. Recently, the U.S. Commerce Department released insights into the current trends taking place in the grocery industry. <!--more-->Here are highlights from the most recent analysis:<span id="cke_bm_99C" style="display:none">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>The U.S. grocery market grew to $645 billion last year from %568 billion in 2007 &ndash; a 14 percent increase over the four year period.</li>\r\n\t<li>Growth in high performing chains continues to increase. These chains include Harris Teeter, HEB, Kroger, Publix, Wegmans and Winco.</li>\r\n\t<li>Grocery sales increased from $343 billion in 2007 to $380 billion in 2011. While this is a below average growth rate, sales can be expected to increase in 2012.</li>\r\n\t<li>Warehouse clubs and supercenters are the key competitors to other supermarkets.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nSo, what can grocers expect this year?<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAccording to David Rogers, President of DSR Marketing Systems Inc., &ldquo;These trends reflect a dynamic, ever-changing industry in which, to survive and prosper, retailers must keep their finger on the pulse of opportunities by giving priority to market research and analysis.&rdquo;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nKnowing the importance of market research and analysis in the grocery industry, we recently released a new research report conducted by BIGinsight that reveals the changing behavior among cost-conscious grocery shoppers as the move through the path to purchase in today&rsquo;s post-recession economy. To read the full report, click here [link to landing page download].<br />\r\n<br />\r\nHighlights from our report include:<span id="cke_bm_98C" style="display:none">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>Consumers shopping closer to home and shopping at multiple grocery stores</li>\r\n\t<li>Leveraging coupons and sales more</li>\r\n\t<li>Preparing lists before shopping</li>\r\n\t<li>Using more resources such as digital channels to prepare for shopping trips</li>\r\n\t<li>Heading to recipe-specific destination sites to prepare for shopping</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n	t	2012-07-23 12:09:14	\N	2012-07-23 12:09:14	2013-09-17 14:31:29.681694	58	Maxpoint, MaxPoint Interactive, OnPoint, grocery, in-store traffic
793	1	15	an-interview-with-eric-yang-ceo-black-bag-advertising	An Interview with Eric Yang, CEO, Black Bag Advertising 	<p>MaxPoint recently interviewed Eric Yang, CEO, Black Bag Advertising, on the interactive and digital advertising industry. The interview focuses on media buying and what media buyers/planners take into consideration when developing an advertising budget. &nbsp;</p>\r\n	<p><a href="http://maxpointinteractive.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/EYangML.jpg"><img alt="" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-2831" src="http://maxpointinteractive.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/EYangML.jpg" style="height:150px; width:150px" title="EYangML" /></a><br />\r\n<br />\r\nMaxPoint recently interviewed Eric Yang, CEO, Black Bag Advertising, on the interactive and digital advertising industry. The interview focuses on media buying and what media buyers/planners take into consideration when developing an advertising budget. &nbsp;<!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>MaxPoint:</strong> As you know, the digital advertising industry has exploded with the emergence of new technology. What do media buyers/planners take into account when evaluating new technology?<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Yang:</strong> First, we evaluate if the technology solves a problem and what kind of problem it solves. Second, we ask ourselves if the technology differentiates itself from the competition and if the technology actually works. Case studies are a good indicator to see if the new technology works, as long as they are relevant to whoever is looking into the new technology. Lastly, we evaluate what the costs are and what the technology maturity is.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>MaxPoint:</strong> What do you feel is most important for media buyers/planners to take into consideration when figuring out where to allocate ad spend?<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Yang:</strong> Media buyers and planners should take into consideration how efficient the media is (on both a pricing &amp; performance level) that is being purchased. Another consideration would be the potential impact for our clients in achieving their objectives. For instance, their objectives may not be getting the lowest cost per click or highest conversion rate but maybe they want to be on the homepage of NYT. It is about assessing the true value and then how do we measure that value.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOur team would say customer service too &ndash; we work with people or publishers that we like and know will have good customer service. For instance, we consider if people or publishers are timely in responses and if they have good analytics insights ready when a campaign runs.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nI also think word of mouth plays a big component for media planners. If another media planner lets you know that a particular vendor or publisher is easy to work with and gets the job done &ndash; that makes a big difference.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>MaxPoint:</strong> What are some of the challenges media buyers/planners face when they want to execute a campaign across multiple marketing channels on a limited ad budget?<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Yang:</strong> With a limited budget, you have to make sure you are using the best channels for a client. First we assess what are the client&rsquo;s goals and what is the most efficient route for reaching the goal. If the focus is on SEM or display tactics, we leverage what we know will work and which publishers will work the best. Then we go from there.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe other challenge is spreading your budget across too many things &ndash; you don&rsquo;t want to do that. There is so much that can be touched and the market is so fragmented and there are so many different types of opportunities. Knowing what will work best for a client can be a huge challenge.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhenever we do a plan we have a pretty good idea of projected conversion rates and click through rates. We also can reference historical campaign data and what the pricing/historical performance was. That makes it easier when evaluating new campaigns.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>MaxPoint:</strong> Since most campaigns focus on a specific audience, how do media buyers/planners tackle finding solutions for effective audience targeting during the campaign planning process?<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Yang:</strong> There are a lot of different solutions out there &ndash; probably more than a dozen that claim some sort of experienced audience targeting, whether it is offline/online or a combination of both. Again it goes back to our historical experience.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWe look at performance from a clickthrough and conversion rate and we want to understand the methodology for targeting and what sort of sources they are gathering from audience targeting. To eliminate companies, it is trial and error, and figuring out what works best. Again, it&rsquo;s word of mouth, historical performance, and whether or not the publisher meets our client objectives.</p>\r\n	t	2012-06-27 13:24:08	\N	2012-06-27 13:24:08	2013-09-17 14:37:35.875495	53	MaxPoint, MaxPoint Interactive, Eric Yang, OnPoint, media buying, media planning, digital advertising, targeting 
875	1	15	measuring-your-digital-ad-campaigns-closing-the-loop-on-sales-part-1	Measuring Your Digital Ad Campaigns: Closing the Loop on Sales—Part 1	<p>Curious how much your ad campaign added to your sales? Discover how you can measure sales impact in dollars in the first of two posts on sales lift studies.</p>\r\n	<p><img alt="" src="/system/editor/W1siZiIsIjIwMTMvMDkvMTgvMDhfMzJfNDFfMzI4X0Jsb2dfTWVhc3VyZW1lbnRfU2VyaWVzXzIucG5nIl0sWyJwIiwidGh1bWIiLCI4MDB4ODAwPiJdXQ/Blog%20Measurement%20Series_2.png" style="float:right; height:290px; margin-left:45px; margin-right:45px; width:300px" />Last week, we covered <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/onpoint-blog/2013/9/12/measuring-your-digital-ad-campaigns-the-conundrum-of-clicks" target="_blank">the pros and cons of relying on click-through rates (CTRs)</a> for measuring your digital advertising campaigns. In short, they&rsquo;re a good start, but they don&rsquo;t tell the entire story for a digital ad campaign. If you want the complete picture, you&rsquo;ll have to opt for a premium measurement tool, such as a sales lift study.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sales lift studies measure campaigns using real sales data, typically comparing test and control groups over a time period or in a specific area. If your campaign&rsquo;s goal is to generate strong sales for a product, this is the study that will tell you if you reached your goal.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In a sales lift study:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n\t<li>One or more digital advertisements are served to a test group.</li>\r\n\t<li>Sales data are collected from stores or consumers in both the test group and a control group.</li>\r\n\t<li>The difference in sales between the test and control groups equals the sales lift.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nLet&rsquo;s say you&rsquo;re running a campaign promoting a brand of cola. You might decide to run ads in St. Louis as a test, but avoid advertising in Kansas City. If you see higher sales figures in St. Louis, then odds are good that your campaign played a major role in lifting sales.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Sales Lift Methods</strong><br />\r\nAlthough the process above is fairly simple, there are actually three different styles of sales lift studies. They differ in how they collect data&mdash;and that&rsquo;s also what changes their price tags. The three styles are:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n\t<li>Panel-based studies</li>\r\n\t<li>Point-of-sale studies</li>\r\n\t<li>Retail-partner studies</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nEach study type has various pros and cons. This week, we&rsquo;ll focus on the consumer panel data studies. Next week, we&rsquo;ll take a closer look at point-of-sale and retail-partner studies.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Panel-Based Studies</strong><br />\r\nWhen most people think of sales lift studies, panel-based studies come to mind. These studies provide incredibly accurate and detailed data. However, they work only for lengthier campaigns and are often costly.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In a panel-based study, a research firm maintains a research panel of consumers. To participate in the panel, the consumers answer detailed questions about their demographics and background. Additionally, the panel members have software that tracks their Internet usage, which allows the researchers to match an ad impression to a particular user. To measure sales data, each panel member scans receipts to a central database, which tracks and stores their purchases. The researchers cross-reference all three data points to discover if an advertisement moved the right consumers to buy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>These studies offer a number of interesting benefits:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>They provide an exact sales number. It&rsquo;s much easier to know the value of your campaign if you can put a dollar figure on the results.</li>\r\n\t<li>They allow you to calculate other in-depth metrics. The sales figures can be used to calculate other metrics, such as estimated customer lifetime value, upcoming sales figures, and ROI.</li>\r\n\t<li>They give insights into the audience<strong>. </strong>With data on the participants&rsquo; backgrounds, researchers can give better insights into responder profiles.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nHowever, these studies do have some drawbacks. They can be expensive due to the intensity of the data collection and the amount of research labor required. Additionally, the studies must run for a long period of time, typically at least three months.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>What About Other Sales Lift Studies?</strong><br />\r\nStay tuned for the <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/onpoint-blog/2013/9/29/measuring-your-digital-ad-campaigns-closing-the-loop-on-sales-part-2" target="_blank">next post</a>, in which we discuss some of the less expensive sales lift studies including point-of-sale and retail-partner studies.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Don&rsquo;t Want to Wait?</strong><br />\r\n<a href="http://offers.maxpoint.com/measurement" target="_blank">Download our free measurement guide</a> now to learn more about putting your digital campaigns to the measurement test.</p>\r\n	t	2013-09-18 13:26:42	\N	2013-09-18 13:30:05.541638	2013-10-15 13:18:09.170981	62	\N
