888	1	15	do-digital-ads-really-get-people-to-buy-products-offline	Do Digital Ads Really Get People to Buy Products Offline?	<p>Find out how Kimberly-Clark increased offline sales of Depend&reg; products using hyperlocal digital advertising.</p>\r\n	<p><img alt="Atlanta Heatmap" src="/system/editor/W1siZiIsIjIwMTMvMTEvMDQvMTJfNDJfMjVfNzU5X0hlYXRNYXBfRGVwZW5kc19BdGxhbnRhLnBuZyJdLFsicCIsInRodW1iIiwiODAweDgwMD4iXV0/HeatMap_Depends_Atlanta.png" style="float:right; height:300px; margin-left:2px; margin-right:2px; width:420px" />Online sales get a lot of press, but most consumer purchases still take place in the retail aisles. Even though most purchases take place in the physical world, people still spend much of their lives plugged into the Web. So this leads to a question: can online advertising drive offline sales?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The story of Kimberly-Clark&rsquo;s campaign with MaxPoint may answer this question. From personal care to health care, Kimberly-Clark&rsquo;s products improve the lives of millions. In particular, its Depend<sup>&reg;</sup> brand of adult undergarments provides protection from incontinence issues while giving customers more confidence in their daily activities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When Kimberly-Clark wanted to improve sales of Depend at one of its key retail partners, it turned to MaxPoint&rsquo;s proprietary Digital Zip<sup>&reg;</sup> technology. With MaxPoint&rsquo;s help, the brand quickly developed a strategy to target shoppers in key neighborhoods around retail locations. Additionally, Kimberly-Clark decided to test the campaign&rsquo;s results by running a sales lift study using data from its retail partner. But before we get to the results, let&rsquo;s start with the campaign strategy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Defining the Perfect Audience</strong><br />\r\nAny good advertising campaign starts with defining the audience. &nbsp;So, we started out by looking for shoppers matching the following profile:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>Age: 51&ndash;70</li>\r\n\t<li>Income: $40,000+ per year</li>\r\n\t<li>Interests: bladder health and incontinence relief</li>\r\n\t<li>Purchases: incontinence products<br />\r\n\t&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Armed with this core profile, MaxPoint could then find the right locations that would drive the most sales. To do this, we focused on neighborhoods within six and eight miles of the store. This was the perfect distance&mdash;close enough to reach shoppers who can easily drive to the store, yet large enough to reach enough shoppers to really drive enough sales. &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Testing the Sales Results</strong><br />\r\nKimberly-Clark opted to run a sales lift study to discover the sales increase produced by the campaign. It chose a <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/onpoint-blog/2013/9/30/measuring-your-digital-ad-campaigns-closing-the-loop-on-sales-part-2" target="_blank">retail-partner study</a>, which used sales data directly from retail partners&rsquo; stores. The study measured purchases of Depend at participating stores during the campaign and over the four-week period following the campaign&rsquo;s completion. Finally, we compared the sales from the study period against historical sales data from before the campaign.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As a result of the campaign, Kimberly-Clark saw a <strong>21% increase in weekly sales</strong> of Depend products in participating stores. The sales increase occurred both during the campaign and during the four-week post-campaign period. In short, Kimberly-Clark received a major sales boost from the campaign and continued to see benefits for a few weeks after the campaign.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The results speak for themselves&mdash;digital advertising boosts offline sales. When you combine the right mix of offline and online data sources to find the perfect local shoppers, you&rsquo;re pretty much guaranteed to see your sales increase.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Have you run a digital advertising campaign that boosted your offline sales? Let us know by leaving a comment below.</p>\r\n	t	2013-11-04 15:00:05	\N	2013-11-04 15:01:54.361468	2013-11-08 18:52:55.110925	61	\N
885	1	15	measuring-your-digital-ad-campaigns-brand-lift-and-engagement	Measuring Your Digital Ad Campaigns: Brand Lift and Engagement	<p>How easy is it to measure your digital advertising campaign&#39;s effect on your brand? Find out with this week&#39;s post on brand lift surveys.</p>\r\n	<p><img alt="Brand Lift Studies" src="/system/editor/W1siZiIsIjIwMTMvMTAvMTUvMDhfMDdfNTVfOTM3X0Jsb2dfTWVhc3VyZW1lbnRfU2VyaWVzXzQucG5nIl0sWyJwIiwidGh1bWIiLCI4MDB4ODAwPiJdXQ/Blog%20Measurement%20Series_4.png" style="float:right; height:290px; margin-left:30px; margin-right:30px; width:300px" />In our two most recent measurement posts, we covered <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/onpoint-blog/2013/9/18/measuring-your-digital-ad-campaigns-closing-the-loop-on-sales-part-1" target="_blank">sales lift studies</a>, which use real sales data to put an exact dollar figure on the purchases your ad campaigns generate. Sales lift studies certainly have their time and place, but what would you do if you wanted to measure something less tangible, such as the effect a campaign has on customer attitudes and perceptions?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>That&rsquo;s where brand engagement surveys, also called brand lift surveys, come in. These surveys measure engagement anywhere in the sales cycle&mdash;from early awareness to purchase intent to customer recommendation. They&rsquo;re flexible, easy to run, and cost-effective.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>How Brand Engagement Surveys Work</strong><br />\r\nMeasuring the impact your digital ads have on brand engagement is surprisingly simple. A quick one-question survey delivered to both test and control groups while your campaign runs is all it takes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For example, let&rsquo;s say you sell a brand of peanut butter. Your ad campaign promotes the brand as an organic and healthy choice. While the campaign runs, you could serve a single-question survey to both a test group (who were served your ad) and a control group (who were not served your ad). If you ask both groups to choose the healthiest brand among several peanut butters and your brand scores higher among the test group than the control group, your campaign produced a positive brand lift.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Of course, you need to tailor your survey to your campaign goal. MaxPoint uses a standard set of questions, each tailored to different stages in the sales cycle. You can get these questions by downloading our <a href="http://offers.maxpoint.com/measurement" target="_blank">free measurement guide</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>The Pros and Cons of Brand Engagement Surveys</strong><br />\r\nSo, now that you know the process, why pick a brand engagement survey?</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>Measure Intangibles&mdash;Customer attitudes are abstract and intangible, but their impact on sales is absolutely real. Brand engagement surveys measure these attitudes in ways that sales lift studies simply can&rsquo;t.</li>\r\n\t<li>Adapt Surveys to Your Objective&mdash;You can tailor surveys to your campaign goal. Simply ask the question that best captures your campaign&rsquo;s goal&mdash;whether that&rsquo;s brand awareness or brand favorability. You can even change your survey mid-campaign, although this will affect your budget and your outcome.&nbsp;</li>\r\n\t<li>Test Sales Cheaply<strong>&mdash;</strong>Although brand engagement surveys won&rsquo;t provide an exact dollar figure, they can indicate a strong possibility for sales. Simply use a purchase intent question, which asks how likely a consumer is to purchase a product or service, to discover if your ad campaign had a positive effect on sales.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nBut there are some drawbacks. In particular, brand engagement surveys:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>Require Brevity&mdash;An effective survey asks only one or two questions. This keeps responses high, but does limit the number of variables you can measure.</li>\r\n\t<li>Don&rsquo;t Provide Sales Data&mdash;Purchase intent questions hint at sales lift, but they don&rsquo;t provide a concrete sales number.</li>\r\n\t<li>Can Have Incremental Costs&mdash;You need to reach a minimum number of respondents to produce a valid result. If you don&rsquo;t reach enough customers, you may need to purchase additional impressions. This doesn&rsquo;t happen often, but it is a small risk.<br />\r\n\t&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Brand Engagement in Action</strong><br />\r\nMaxPoint recently ran a campaign for a major CPG brand. The campaign sought to produce positive awareness of its beverages in markets along the Pacific Coast of the United States. Researchers tested campaign effectiveness by asking consumers to select, from a list of the brand and its competitors, the brand whose ads they remembered seeing online. The campaign produced a 62.3% lift in brand awareness among test groups, demonstrating the effectiveness of the ad campaign.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>The Final Word on Brand Engagement Surveys</strong><br />\r\nDigital advertising does more than just produce sales&mdash;it affects the hearts and minds of a brand&rsquo;s customers. Brand engagement surveys provide a simple and cost-effective way for advertisers to measure these effects.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In our next post, we&rsquo;ll finish our measurement series with a discussion of <a href="http://maxpoint.com/us/digital-advertising-company/onpoint-blog/2013/10/23/measuring-your-digital-ad-campaigns-audience-match-studies" target="_blank">audience match studies</a>. After reading, you&rsquo;ll have all the tools you&rsquo;ll need to test and prove the value of your digital advertising campaigns.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Don&rsquo;t Want to Wait?</strong><br />\r\n<a href="http://offers.maxpoint.com/measurement" target="_blank">Download our free measurement guide</a> now to learn more about putting your digital campaigns to the measurement test. The guide covers each type of measurement study, including the standard questions we ask in our brand engagement surveys.</p>\r\n	t	2013-10-15 12:55:58	\N	2013-10-15 12:58:01.083896	2013-10-23 13:36:44.32938	62	\N
660	1	15	the-local-approach-the-state-of-localized-advertising-in-retail	The Local Approach: The State of Localized Advertising in Retail	<p>Today, RSR Research revealed the results of a new Prospective View report entitled, &ldquo;The Local Approach: The State of Localized Advertising in Retail&rdquo; to evaluate how well retailers are using digital experiences to drive in-store traffic.</p>\r\n	<p>Today, <a href="http://www.retailsystemsresearch.com/" target="_blank">RSR Research</a> revealed the results of a new Prospective View report entitled, &ldquo;The Local Approach: The State of Localized Advertising in Retail&rdquo; to evaluate how well retailers are using digital experiences to drive in-store traffic. <!--more--><br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn this independent research report, RSR evaluates 20 top retailers&rsquo; localization efforts and provides recommendations for retailers of all sizes to create cohesive local campaigns that reach consumers at every touch point throughout the purchase path. The in-depth examination includes a look at traditional and digital advertising, alternative offers and website communication in four distinct retail verticals&ndash; department/clothing stores, sporting goods, electronics and casual dining.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe findings provide great insight into how retailers are effectively using localization tactics as part of their digital campaigns, as well as how many are missing the mark. RSR found that no one retailer has fully taken advantage of this local advertising opportunity.&nbsp; For instance, department stores notably outperformed the other verticals, but can do more to bring a sense of &ldquo;local&rdquo; into their stores. In addition, electronics retailers successfully leverage social channels, but still have far to go as it relates to video, mobile and alternative social branding. To address this, RSR has provided four specific recommendations that will help retailers create more cohesive local campaigns that reach consumers at every touch point of their path to purchase.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWant to learn more about how far retailers have come in local advertising and how far they have left to go? Visit <a href="http://maxpoint.com/rsrreport" target="_blank">here</a> to read more on our sponsored RSR research report.</p>\r\n	t	2011-09-27 13:10:51	\N	2011-09-27 13:10:51	2013-10-23 17:50:31.144958	49	MaxPoint Interactive, MaxPoint, OnPoint, RSR, RSR Research, RSR study, local, retail, local campaigns, localized advertising, advertising
